\par I. The Period
\par 
\par 
\par It was the best of times,
\par it was the worst of times,
\par it was the age of wisdom,
\par it was the age of foolishness,
\par it was the epoch of belief,
\par it was the epoch of incredulity,
\par it was the season of Light,
\par it was the season of Darkness,
\par it was the spring of hope,
\par it was the winter of despair,
\par we had everything before us,
\par we had nothing before us,
\par we were all going direct to Heaven,
\par we were all going direct the other way--
\par in short, the period was so far like the present period, that some of
\par its noisiest authorities insisted on its being received, for good or for
\par evil, in the superlative degree of comparison only.
\par 
\par There were a king with a large jaw and a queen with a plain face, on the
\par throne of England; there were a king with a large jaw and a queen with
\par a fair face, on the throne of France. In both countries it was clearer
\par than crystal to the lords of the State preserves of loaves and fishes,
\par that things in general were settled for ever.
\par 
\par It was the year of Our Lord one thousand seven hundred and seventy-five.
\par Spiritual revelations were conceded to England at that favoured period,
\par as at this. Mrs. Southcott had recently attained her five-and-twentieth
\par blessed birthday, of whom a prophetic private in the Life Guards had
\par heralded the sublime appearance by announcing that arrangements were
\par made for the swallowing up of London and Westminster. Even the Cock-lane
\par ghost had been laid only a round dozen of years, after rapping out its
\par messages, as the spirits of this very year last past (supernaturally
\par deficient in originality) rapped out theirs. Mere messages in the
\par earthly order of events had lately come to the English Crown and People,
\par from a congress of British subjects in America: which, strange
\par to relate, have proved more important to the human race than any
\par communications yet received through any of the chickens of the Cock-lane
\par brood.
\par 
\par France, less favoured on the whole as to matters spiritual than her
\par sister of the shield and trident, rolled with exceeding smoothness down
\par hill, making paper money and spending it. Under the guidance of her
\par Christian pastors, she entertained herself, besides, with such humane
\par achievements as sentencing a youth to have his hands cut off, his tongue
\par torn out with pincers, and his body burned alive, because he had not
\par kneeled down in the rain to do honour to a dirty procession of monks
\par which passed within his view, at a distance of some fifty or sixty
\par yards. It is likely enough that, rooted in the woods of France and
\par Norway, there were growing trees, when that sufferer was put to death,
\par already marked by the Woodman, Fate, to come down and be sawn into
\par boards, to make a certain movable framework with a sack and a knife in
\par it, terrible in history. It is likely enough that in the rough outhouses
\par of some tillers of the heavy lands adjacent to Paris, there were
\par sheltered from the weather that very day, rude carts, bespattered with
\par rustic mire, snuffed about by pigs, and roosted in by poultry, which
\par the Farmer, Death, had already set apart to be his tumbrils of
\par the Revolution. But that Woodman and that Farmer, though they work
\par unceasingly, work silently, and no one heard them as they went about
\par with muffled tread: the rather, forasmuch as to entertain any suspicion
\par that they were awake, was to be atheistical and traitorous.
\par 
\par In England, there was scarcely an amount of order and protection to
\par justify much national boasting. Daring burglaries by armed men, and
\par highway robberies, took place in the capital itself every night;
\par families were publicly cautioned not to go out of town without removing
\par their furniture to upholsterers' warehouses for security; the highwayman
\par in the dark was a City tradesman in the light, and, being recognised and
\par challenged by his fellow-tradesman whom he stopped in his character of
\par "the Captain," gallantly shot him through the head and rode away; the
\par mail was waylaid by seven robbers, and the guard shot three dead, and
\par then got shot dead himself by the other four, "in consequence of the
\par failure of his ammunition:" after which the mail was robbed in peace;
\par that magnificent potentate, the Lord Mayor of London, was made to stand
\par and deliver on Turnham Green, by one highwayman, who despoiled the
\par illustrious creature in sight of all his retinue; prisoners in London
\par gaols fought battles with their turnkeys, and the majesty of the law
\par fired blunderbusses in among them, loaded with rounds of shot and ball;
\par thieves snipped off diamond crosses from the necks of noble lords at
\par Court drawing-rooms; musketeers went into St. Giles's, to search
\par for contraband goods, and the mob fired on the musketeers, and the
\par musketeers fired on the mob, and nobody thought any of these occurrences
\par much out of the common way. In the midst of them, the hangman, ever busy
\par and ever worse than useless, was in constant requisition; now, stringing
\par up long rows of miscellaneous criminals; now, hanging a housebreaker on
\par Saturday who had been taken on Tuesday; now, burning people in the
\par hand at Newgate by the dozen, and now burning pamphlets at the door of
\par Westminster Hall; to-day, taking the life of an atrocious murderer,
\par and to-morrow of a wretched pilferer who had robbed a farmer's boy of
\par sixpence.
\par 
\par All these things, and a thousand like them, came to pass in and close
\par upon the dear old year one thousand seven hundred and seventy-five.
\par Environed by them, while the Woodman and the Farmer worked unheeded,
\par those two of the large jaws, and those other two of the plain and the
\par fair faces, trod with stir enough, and carried their divine rights
\par with a high hand. Thus did the year one thousand seven hundred
\par and seventy-five conduct their Greatnesses, and myriads of small
\par creatures--the creatures of this chronicle among the rest--along the
\par roads that lay before them.
