\par 
\par II. The Mail
\par 
\par 
\par It was the Dover road that lay, on a Friday night late in November,
\par before the first of the persons with whom this history has business.
\par The Dover road lay, as to him, beyond the Dover mail, as it lumbered up
\par Shooter's Hill. He walked up hill in the mire by the side of the mail,
\par as the rest of the passengers did; not because they had the least relish
\par for walking exercise, under the circumstances, but because the hill,
\par and the harness, and the mud, and the mail, were all so heavy, that the
\par horses had three times already come to a stop, besides once drawing the
\par coach across the road, with the mutinous intent of taking it back
\par to Blackheath. Reins and whip and coachman and guard, however, in
\par combination, had read that article of war which forbade a purpose
\par otherwise strongly in favour of the argument, that some brute animals
\par are endued with Reason; and the team had capitulated and returned to
\par their duty.
\par 
\par With drooping heads and tremulous tails, they mashed their way through
\par the thick mud, floundering and stumbling between whiles, as if they were
\par falling to pieces at the larger joints. As often as the driver rested
\par them and brought them to a stand, with a wary "Wo-ho! so-ho-then!" the
\par near leader violently shook his head and everything upon it--like an
\par unusually emphatic horse, denying that the coach could be got up the
\par hill. Whenever the leader made this rattle, the passenger started, as a
\par nervous passenger might, and was disturbed in mind.
\par 
\par There was a steaming mist in all the hollows, and it had roamed in its
\par forlornness up the hill, like an evil spirit, seeking rest and finding
\par none. A clammy and intensely cold mist, it made its slow way through the
\par air in ripples that visibly followed and overspread one another, as the
\par waves of an unwholesome sea might do. It was dense enough to shut out
\par everything from the light of the coach-lamps but these its own workings,
\par and a few yards of road; and the reek of the labouring horses steamed
\par into it, as if they had made it all.
\par 
\par Two other passengers, besides the one, were plodding up the hill by the
\par side of the mail. All three were wrapped to the cheekbones and over the
\par ears, and wore jack-boots. Not one of the three could have said, from
\par anything he saw, what either of the other two was like; and each was
\par hidden under almost as many wrappers from the eyes of the mind, as from
\par the eyes of the body, of his two companions. In those days, travellers
\par were very shy of being confidential on a short notice, for anybody on
\par the road might be a robber or in league with robbers. As to the latter,
\par when every posting-house and ale-house could produce somebody in
\par "the Captain's" pay, ranging from the landlord to the lowest stable
\par non-descript, it was the likeliest thing upon the cards. So the guard
\par of the Dover mail thought to himself, that Friday night in November, one
\par thousand seven hundred and seventy-five, lumbering up Shooter's Hill, as
\par he stood on his own particular perch behind the mail, beating his feet,
\par and keeping an eye and a hand on the arm-chest before him, where a
\par loaded blunderbuss lay at the top of six or eight loaded horse-pistols,
\par deposited on a substratum of cutlass.
\par 
\par The Dover mail was in its usual genial position that the guard suspected
\par the passengers, the passengers suspected one another and the guard, they
\par all suspected everybody else, and the coachman was sure of nothing but
\par the horses; as to which cattle he could with a clear conscience have
\par taken his oath on the two Testaments that they were not fit for the
\par journey.
\par 
\par "Wo-ho!" said the coachman. "So, then! One more pull and you're at the
\par top and be damned to you, for I have had trouble enough to get you to
\par it!--Joe!"
\par 
\par "Halloa!" the guard replied.
\par 
\par "What o'clock do you make it, Joe?"
\par 
\par "Ten minutes, good, past eleven."
\par 
\par "My blood!" ejaculated the vexed coachman, "and not atop of Shooter's
\par yet! Tst! Yah! Get on with you!"
\par 
\par The emphatic horse, cut short by the whip in a most decided negative,
\par made a decided scramble for it, and the three other horses followed
\par suit. Once more, the Dover mail struggled on, with the jack-boots of its
\par passengers squashing along by its side. They had stopped when the coach
\par stopped, and they kept close company with it. If any one of the three
\par had had the hardihood to propose to another to walk on a little ahead
\par into the mist and darkness, he would have put himself in a fair way of
\par getting shot instantly as a highwayman.
\par 
\par The last burst carried the mail to the summit of the hill. The horses
\par stopped to breathe again, and the guard got down to skid the wheel for
\par the descent, and open the coach-door to let the passengers in.
\par 
\par "Tst! Joe!" cried the coachman in a warning voice, looking down from his
\par box.
\par 
\par "What do you say, Tom?"
\par 
\par They both listened.
\par 
\par "I say a horse at a canter coming up, Joe."
\par 
\par "_I_ say a horse at a gallop, Tom," returned the guard, leaving his hold
\par of the door, and mounting nimbly to his place. "Gentlemen! In the king's
\par name, all of you!"
\par 
\par With this hurried adjuration, he cocked his blunderbuss, and stood on
\par the offensive.
\par 
\par The passenger booked by this history, was on the coach-step, getting in;
\par the two other passengers were close behind him, and about to follow. He
\par remained on the step, half in the coach and half out of; they remained
\par in the road below him. They all looked from the coachman to the guard,
\par and from the guard to the coachman, and listened. The coachman looked
\par back and the guard looked back, and even the emphatic leader pricked up
\par his ears and looked back, without contradicting.
\par 
\par The stillness consequent on the cessation of the rumbling and labouring
\par of the coach, added to the stillness of the night, made it very quiet
\par indeed. The panting of the horses communicated a tremulous motion to
\par the coach, as if it were in a state of agitation. The hearts of the
\par passengers beat loud enough perhaps to be heard; but at any rate, the
\par quiet pause was audibly expressive of people out of breath, and holding
\par the breath, and having the pulses quickened by expectation.
\par 
\par The sound of a horse at a gallop came fast and furiously up the hill.
\par 
\par "So-ho!" the guard sang out, as loud as he could roar. "Yo there! Stand!
\par I shall fire!"
\par 
\par The pace was suddenly checked, and, with much splashing and floundering,
\par a man's voice called from the mist, "Is that the Dover mail?"
\par 
\par "Never you mind what it is!" the guard retorted. "What are you?"
\par 
\par "_Is_ that the Dover mail?"
\par 
\par "Why do you want to know?"
\par 
\par "I want a passenger, if it is."
\par 
\par "What passenger?"
\par 
\par "Mr. Jarvis Lorry."
\par 
\par Our booked passenger showed in a moment that it was his name. The guard,
\par the coachman, and the two other passengers eyed him distrustfully.
\par 
\par "Keep where you are," the guard called to the voice in the mist,
\par "because, if I should make a mistake, it could never be set right in
\par your lifetime. Gentleman of the name of Lorry answer straight."
\par 
\par "What is the matter?" asked the passenger, then, with mildly quavering
\par speech. "Who wants me? Is it Jerry?"
\par 
\par ("I don't like Jerry's voice, if it is Jerry," growled the guard to
\par himself. "He's hoarser than suits me, is Jerry.")
\par 
\par "Yes, Mr. Lorry."
\par 
\par "What is the matter?"
\par 
\par "A despatch sent after you from over yonder. T. and Co."
\par 
\par "I know this messenger, guard," said Mr. Lorry, getting down into the
\par road--assisted from behind more swiftly than politely by the other two
\par passengers, who immediately scrambled into the coach, shut the door, and
\par pulled up the window. "He may come close; there's nothing wrong."
\par 
\par "I hope there ain't, but I can't make so 'Nation sure of that," said the
\par guard, in gruff soliloquy. "Hallo you!"
\par 
\par "Well! And hallo you!" said Jerry, more hoarsely than before.
\par 
\par "Come on at a footpace! d'ye mind me? And if you've got holsters to that
\par saddle o' yourn, don't let me see your hand go nigh 'em. For I'm a devil
\par at a quick mistake, and when I make one it takes the form of Lead. So
\par now let's look at you."
\par 
\par The figures of a horse and rider came slowly through the eddying mist,
\par and came to the side of the mail, where the passenger stood. The rider
\par stooped, and, casting up his eyes at the guard, handed the passenger
\par a small folded paper. The rider's horse was blown, and both horse and
\par rider were covered with mud, from the hoofs of the horse to the hat of
\par the man.
\par 
\par "Guard!" said the passenger, in a tone of quiet business confidence.
\par 
\par The watchful guard, with his right hand at the stock of his raised
\par blunderbuss, his left at the barrel, and his eye on the horseman,
\par answered curtly, "Sir."
\par 
\par "There is nothing to apprehend. I belong to Tellson's Bank. You must
\par know Tellson's Bank in London. I am going to Paris on business. A crown
\par to drink. I may read this?"
\par 
\par "If so be as you're quick, sir."
\par 
\par He opened it in the light of the coach-lamp on that side, and
\par read--first to himself and then aloud: "'Wait at Dover for Mam'selle.'
\par It's not long, you see, guard. Jerry, say that my answer was, RECALLED
\par TO LIFE."
\par 
\par Jerry started in his saddle. "That's a Blazing strange answer, too,"
\par said he, at his hoarsest.
\par 
\par "Take that message back, and they will know that I received this, as
\par well as if I wrote. Make the best of your way. Good night."
\par 
\par With those words the passenger opened the coach-door and got in; not at
\par all assisted by his fellow-passengers, who had expeditiously secreted
\par their watches and purses in their boots, and were now making a general
\par pretence of being asleep. With no more definite purpose than to escape
\par the hazard of originating any other kind of action.
\par 
\par The coach lumbered on again, with heavier wreaths of mist closing round
\par it as it began the descent. The guard soon replaced his blunderbuss
\par in his arm-chest, and, having looked to the rest of its contents, and
\par having looked to the supplementary pistols that he wore in his belt,
\par looked to a smaller chest beneath his seat, in which there were a
\par few smith's tools, a couple of torches, and a tinder-box. For he was
\par furnished with that completeness that if the coach-lamps had been blown
\par and stormed out, which did occasionally happen, he had only to shut
\par himself up inside, keep the flint and steel sparks well off the straw,
\par and get a light with tolerable safety and ease (if he were lucky) in
\par five minutes.
\par 
\par "Tom!" softly over the coach roof.
\par 
\par "Hallo, Joe."
\par 
\par "Did you hear the message?"
\par 
\par "I did, Joe."
\par 
\par "What did you make of it, Tom?"
\par 
\par "Nothing at all, Joe."
\par 
\par "That's a coincidence, too," the guard mused, "for I made the same of it
\par myself."
\par 
\par Jerry, left alone in the mist and darkness, dismounted meanwhile, not
\par only to ease his spent horse, but to wipe the mud from his face, and
\par shake the wet out of his hat-brim, which might be capable of
\par holding about half a gallon. After standing with the bridle over his
\par heavily-splashed arm, until the wheels of the mail were no longer within
\par hearing and the night was quite still again, he turned to walk down the
\par hill.
\par 
\par "After that there gallop from Temple Bar, old lady, I won't trust your
\par fore-legs till I get you on the level," said this hoarse messenger,
\par glancing at his mare. "'Recalled to life.' That's a Blazing strange
\par message. Much of that wouldn't do for you, Jerry! I say, Jerry! You'd
\par be in a Blazing bad way, if recalling to life was to come into fashion,
\par Jerry!"
\par 
