\par 
\par III. The Night Shadows
\par 
\par 
\par A wonderful fact to reflect upon, that every human creature is
\par constituted to be that profound secret and mystery to every other. A
\par solemn consideration, when I enter a great city by night, that every
\par one of those darkly clustered houses encloses its own secret; that every
\par room in every one of them encloses its own secret; that every beating
\par heart in the hundreds of thousands of breasts there, is, in some of
\par its imaginings, a secret to the heart nearest it! Something of the
\par awfulness, even of Death itself, is referable to this. No more can I
\par turn the leaves of this dear book that I loved, and vainly hope in time
\par to read it all. No more can I look into the depths of this unfathomable
\par water, wherein, as momentary lights glanced into it, I have had glimpses
\par of buried treasure and other things submerged. It was appointed that the
\par book should shut with a spring, for ever and for ever, when I had read
\par but a page. It was appointed that the water should be locked in an
\par eternal frost, when the light was playing on its surface, and I stood
\par in ignorance on the shore. My friend is dead, my neighbour is dead,
\par my love, the darling of my soul, is dead; it is the inexorable
\par consolidation and perpetuation of the secret that was always in that
\par individuality, and which I shall carry in mine to my life's end. In
\par any of the burial-places of this city through which I pass, is there
\par a sleeper more inscrutable than its busy inhabitants are, in their
\par innermost personality, to me, or than I am to them?
\par 
\par As to this, his natural and not to be alienated inheritance, the
\par messenger on horseback had exactly the same possessions as the King, the
\par first Minister of State, or the richest merchant in London. So with the
\par three passengers shut up in the narrow compass of one lumbering old mail
\par coach; they were mysteries to one another, as complete as if each had
\par been in his own coach and six, or his own coach and sixty, with the
\par breadth of a county between him and the next.
\par 
\par The messenger rode back at an easy trot, stopping pretty often at
\par ale-houses by the way to drink, but evincing a tendency to keep his
\par own counsel, and to keep his hat cocked over his eyes. He had eyes that
\par assorted very well with that decoration, being of a surface black, with
\par no depth in the colour or form, and much too near together--as if they
\par were afraid of being found out in something, singly, if they kept too
\par far apart. They had a sinister expression, under an old cocked-hat like
\par a three-cornered spittoon, and over a great muffler for the chin and
\par throat, which descended nearly to the wearer's knees. When he stopped
\par for drink, he moved this muffler with his left hand, only while he
\par poured his liquor in with his right; as soon as that was done, he
\par muffled again.
\par 
\par "No, Jerry, no!" said the messenger, harping on one theme as he rode.
\par "It wouldn't do for you, Jerry. Jerry, you honest tradesman, it wouldn't
\par suit _your_ line of business! Recalled--! Bust me if I don't think he'd
\par been a drinking!"
\par 
\par His message perplexed his mind to that degree that he was fain, several
\par times, to take off his hat to scratch his head. Except on the crown,
\par which was raggedly bald, he had stiff, black hair, standing jaggedly all
\par over it, and growing down hill almost to his broad, blunt nose. It was
\par so like Smith's work, so much more like the top of a strongly spiked
\par wall than a head of hair, that the best of players at leap-frog might
\par have declined him, as the most dangerous man in the world to go over.
\par 
\par While he trotted back with the message he was to deliver to the night
\par watchman in his box at the door of Tellson's Bank, by Temple Bar, who
\par was to deliver it to greater authorities within, the shadows of the
\par night took such shapes to him as arose out of the message, and took such
\par shapes to the mare as arose out of _her_ private topics of uneasiness.
\par They seemed to be numerous, for she shied at every shadow on the road.
\par 
\par What time, the mail-coach lumbered, jolted, rattled, and bumped upon
\par its tedious way, with its three fellow-inscrutables inside. To whom,
\par likewise, the shadows of the night revealed themselves, in the forms
\par their dozing eyes and wandering thoughts suggested.
\par 
\par Tellson's Bank had a run upon it in the mail. As the bank
\par passenger--with an arm drawn through the leathern strap, which did what
\par lay in it to keep him from pounding against the next passenger,
\par and driving him into his corner, whenever the coach got a special
\par jolt--nodded in his place, with half-shut eyes, the little
\par coach-windows, and the coach-lamp dimly gleaming through them, and the
\par bulky bundle of opposite passenger, became the bank, and did a great
\par stroke of business. The rattle of the harness was the chink of money,
\par and more drafts were honoured in five minutes than even Tellson's, with
\par all its foreign and home connection, ever paid in thrice the time. Then
\par the strong-rooms underground, at Tellson's, with such of their valuable
\par stores and secrets as were known to the passenger (and it was not a
\par little that he knew about them), opened before him, and he went in among
\par them with the great keys and the feebly-burning candle, and found them
\par safe, and strong, and sound, and still, just as he had last seen them.
\par 
\par But, though the bank was almost always with him, and though the coach
\par (in a confused way, like the presence of pain under an opiate) was
\par always with him, there was another current of impression that never
\par ceased to run, all through the night. He was on his way to dig some one
\par out of a grave.
\par 
\par Now, which of the multitude of faces that showed themselves before him
\par was the true face of the buried person, the shadows of the night did
\par not indicate; but they were all the faces of a man of five-and-forty by
\par years, and they differed principally in the passions they expressed,
\par and in the ghastliness of their worn and wasted state. Pride, contempt,
\par defiance, stubbornness, submission, lamentation, succeeded one another;
\par so did varieties of sunken cheek, cadaverous colour, emaciated hands
\par and figures. But the face was in the main one face, and every head was
\par prematurely white. A hundred times the dozing passenger inquired of this
\par spectre:
\par 
\par "Buried how long?"
\par 
\par The answer was always the same: "Almost eighteen years."
\par 
\par "You had abandoned all hope of being dug out?"
\par 
\par "Long ago."
\par 
\par "You know that you are recalled to life?"
\par 
\par "They tell me so."
\par 
\par "I hope you care to live?"
\par 
\par "I can't say."
\par 
\par "Shall I show her to you? Will you come and see her?"
\par 
\par The answers to this question were various and contradictory. Sometimes
\par the broken reply was, "Wait! It would kill me if I saw her too soon."
\par Sometimes, it was given in a tender rain of tears, and then it was,
\par "Take me to her." Sometimes it was staring and bewildered, and then it
\par was, "I don't know her. I don't understand."
\par 
\par After such imaginary discourse, the passenger in his fancy would dig,
\par and dig, dig--now with a spade, now with a great key, now with his
\par hands--to dig this wretched creature out. Got out at last, with earth
\par hanging about his face and hair, he would suddenly fan away to dust. The
\par passenger would then start to himself, and lower the window, to get the
\par reality of mist and rain on his cheek.
\par 
\par Yet even when his eyes were opened on the mist and rain, on the moving
\par patch of light from the lamps, and the hedge at the roadside retreating
\par by jerks, the night shadows outside the coach would fall into the train
\par of the night shadows within. The real Banking-house by Temple Bar, the
\par real business of the past day, the real strong rooms, the real express
\par sent after him, and the real message returned, would all be there. Out
\par of the midst of them, the ghostly face would rise, and he would accost
\par it again.
\par 
\par "Buried how long?"
\par 
\par "Almost eighteen years."
\par 
\par "I hope you care to live?"
\par 
\par "I can't say."
\par 
\par Dig--dig--dig--until an impatient movement from one of the two
\par passengers would admonish him to pull up the window, draw his arm
\par securely through the leathern strap, and speculate upon the two
\par slumbering forms, until his mind lost its hold of them, and they again
\par slid away into the bank and the grave.
\par 
\par "Buried how long?"
\par 
\par "Almost eighteen years."
\par 
\par "You had abandoned all hope of being dug out?"
\par 
\par "Long ago."
\par 
\par The words were still in his hearing as just spoken--distinctly in
\par his hearing as ever spoken words had been in his life--when the weary
\par passenger started to the consciousness of daylight, and found that the
\par shadows of the night were gone.
\par 
\par He lowered the window, and looked out at the rising sun. There was a
\par ridge of ploughed land, with a plough upon it where it had been left
\par last night when the horses were unyoked; beyond, a quiet coppice-wood,
\par in which many leaves of burning red and golden yellow still remained
\par upon the trees. Though the earth was cold and wet, the sky was clear,
\par and the sun rose bright, placid, and beautiful.
\par 
\par "Eighteen years!" said the passenger, looking at the sun. "Gracious
\par Creator of day! To be buried alive for eighteen years!"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par IV. The Preparation
\par 
\par 
\par When the mail got successfully to Dover, in the course of the forenoon,
\par the head drawer at the Royal George Hotel opened the coach-door as his
\par custom was. He did it with some flourish of ceremony, for a mail journey
\par from London in winter was an achievement to congratulate an adventurous
\par traveller upon.
\par 
\par By that time, there was only one adventurous traveller left be
\par congratulated: for the two others had been set down at their respective
\par roadside destinations. The mildewy inside of the coach, with its damp
\par and dirty straw, its disagreeable smell, and its obscurity, was rather
\par like a larger dog-kennel. Mr. Lorry, the passenger, shaking himself out
\par of it in chains of straw, a tangle of shaggy wrapper, flapping hat, and
\par muddy legs, was rather like a larger sort of dog.
\par 
\par "There will be a packet to Calais, tomorrow, drawer?"
\par 
\par "Yes, sir, if the weather holds and the wind sets tolerable fair. The
\par tide will serve pretty nicely at about two in the afternoon, sir. Bed,
\par sir?"
\par 
\par "I shall not go to bed till night; but I want a bedroom, and a barber."
\par 
\par "And then breakfast, sir? Yes, sir. That way, sir, if you please.
\par Show Concord! Gentleman's valise and hot water to Concord. Pull off
\par gentleman's boots in Concord. (You will find a fine sea-coal fire, sir.)
\par Fetch barber to Concord. Stir about there, now, for Concord!"
\par 
\par The Concord bed-chamber being always assigned to a passenger by the
\par mail, and passengers by the mail being always heavily wrapped up from
\par head to foot, the room had the odd interest for the establishment of the
\par Royal George, that although but one kind of man was seen to go into it,
\par all kinds and varieties of men came out of it. Consequently, another
\par drawer, and two porters, and several maids and the landlady, were all
\par loitering by accident at various points of the road between the Concord
\par and the coffee-room, when a gentleman of sixty, formally dressed in a
\par brown suit of clothes, pretty well worn, but very well kept, with large
\par square cuffs and large flaps to the pockets, passed along on his way to
\par his breakfast.
\par 
\par The coffee-room had no other occupant, that forenoon, than the gentleman
\par in brown. His breakfast-table was drawn before the fire, and as he sat,
\par with its light shining on him, waiting for the meal, he sat so still,
\par that he might have been sitting for his portrait.
\par 
\par Very orderly and methodical he looked, with a hand on each knee, and a
\par loud watch ticking a sonorous sermon under his flapped waist-coat,
\par as though it pitted its gravity and longevity against the levity and
\par evanescence of the brisk fire. He had a good leg, and was a little vain
\par of it, for his brown stockings fitted sleek and close, and were of a
\par fine texture; his shoes and buckles, too, though plain, were trim. He
\par wore an odd little sleek crisp flaxen wig, setting very close to his
\par head: which wig, it is to be presumed, was made of hair, but which
\par looked far more as though it were spun from filaments of silk or glass.
\par His linen, though not of a fineness in accordance with his stockings,
\par was as white as the tops of the waves that broke upon the neighbouring
\par beach, or the specks of sail that glinted in the sunlight far at sea. A
\par face habitually suppressed and quieted, was still lighted up under the
\par quaint wig by a pair of moist bright eyes that it must have cost
\par their owner, in years gone by, some pains to drill to the composed and
\par reserved expression of Tellson's Bank. He had a healthy colour in his
\par cheeks, and his face, though lined, bore few traces of anxiety.
\par But, perhaps the confidential bachelor clerks in Tellson's Bank were
\par principally occupied with the cares of other people; and perhaps
\par second-hand cares, like second-hand clothes, come easily off and on.
\par 
\par Completing his resemblance to a man who was sitting for his portrait,
\par Mr. Lorry dropped off to sleep. The arrival of his breakfast roused him,
\par and he said to the drawer, as he moved his chair to it:
\par 
\par "I wish accommodation prepared for a young lady who may come here at any
\par time to-day. She may ask for Mr. Jarvis Lorry, or she may only ask for a
\par gentleman from Tellson's Bank. Please to let me know."
\par 
\par "Yes, sir. Tellson's Bank in London, sir?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "Yes, sir. We have oftentimes the honour to entertain your gentlemen in
\par their travelling backwards and forwards betwixt London and Paris, sir. A
\par vast deal of travelling, sir, in Tellson and Company's House."
\par 
\par "Yes. We are quite a French House, as well as an English one."
\par 
\par "Yes, sir. Not much in the habit of such travelling yourself, I think,
\par sir?"
\par 
\par "Not of late years. It is fifteen years since we--since I--came last
\par from France."
\par 
\par "Indeed, sir? That was before my time here, sir. Before our people's
\par time here, sir. The George was in other hands at that time, sir."
\par 
\par "I believe so."
\par 
\par "But I would hold a pretty wager, sir, that a House like Tellson and
\par Company was flourishing, a matter of fifty, not to speak of fifteen
\par years ago?"
\par 
\par "You might treble that, and say a hundred and fifty, yet not be far from
\par the truth."
\par 
\par "Indeed, sir!"
\par 
\par Rounding his mouth and both his eyes, as he stepped backward from the
\par table, the waiter shifted his napkin from his right arm to his left,
\par dropped into a comfortable attitude, and stood surveying the guest while
\par he ate and drank, as from an observatory or watchtower. According to the
\par immemorial usage of waiters in all ages.
\par 
\par When Mr. Lorry had finished his breakfast, he went out for a stroll on
\par the beach. The little narrow, crooked town of Dover hid itself away
\par from the beach, and ran its head into the chalk cliffs, like a marine
\par ostrich. The beach was a desert of heaps of sea and stones tumbling
\par wildly about, and the sea did what it liked, and what it liked was
\par destruction. It thundered at the town, and thundered at the cliffs, and
\par brought the coast down, madly. The air among the houses was of so strong
\par a piscatory flavour that one might have supposed sick fish went up to be
\par dipped in it, as sick people went down to be dipped in the sea. A little
\par fishing was done in the port, and a quantity of strolling about by
\par night, and looking seaward: particularly at those times when the tide
\par made, and was near flood. Small tradesmen, who did no business whatever,
\par sometimes unaccountably realised large fortunes, and it was remarkable
\par that nobody in the neighbourhood could endure a lamplighter.
\par 
\par As the day declined into the afternoon, and the air, which had been
\par at intervals clear enough to allow the French coast to be seen, became
\par again charged with mist and vapour, Mr. Lorry's thoughts seemed to cloud
\par too. When it was dark, and he sat before the coffee-room fire, awaiting
\par his dinner as he had awaited his breakfast, his mind was busily digging,
\par digging, digging, in the live red coals.
\par 
\par A bottle of good claret after dinner does a digger in the red coals no
\par harm, otherwise than as it has a tendency to throw him out of work.
\par Mr. Lorry had been idle a long time, and had just poured out his last
\par glassful of wine with as complete an appearance of satisfaction as is
\par ever to be found in an elderly gentleman of a fresh complexion who has
\par got to the end of a bottle, when a rattling of wheels came up the narrow
\par street, and rumbled into the inn-yard.
\par 
\par He set down his glass untouched. "This is Mam'selle!" said he.
\par 
\par In a very few minutes the waiter came in to announce that Miss Manette
\par had arrived from London, and would be happy to see the gentleman from
\par Tellson's.
\par 
\par "So soon?"
\par 
\par Miss Manette had taken some refreshment on the road, and required none
\par then, and was extremely anxious to see the gentleman from Tellson's
\par immediately, if it suited his pleasure and convenience.
\par 
\par The gentleman from Tellson's had nothing left for it but to empty his
\par glass with an air of stolid desperation, settle his odd little flaxen
\par wig at the ears, and follow the waiter to Miss Manette's apartment.
\par It was a large, dark room, furnished in a funereal manner with black
\par horsehair, and loaded with heavy dark tables. These had been oiled and
\par oiled, until the two tall candles on the table in the middle of the room
\par were gloomily reflected on every leaf; as if _they_ were buried, in deep
\par graves of black mahogany, and no light to speak of could be expected
\par from them until they were dug out.
\par 
\par The obscurity was so difficult to penetrate that Mr. Lorry, picking his
\par way over the well-worn Turkey carpet, supposed Miss Manette to be, for
\par the moment, in some adjacent room, until, having got past the two tall
\par candles, he saw standing to receive him by the table between them and
\par the fire, a young lady of not more than seventeen, in a riding-cloak,
\par and still holding her straw travelling-hat by its ribbon in her hand. As
\par his eyes rested on a short, slight, pretty figure, a quantity of golden
\par hair, a pair of blue eyes that met his own with an inquiring look, and
\par a forehead with a singular capacity (remembering how young and smooth
\par it was), of rifting and knitting itself into an expression that was
\par not quite one of perplexity, or wonder, or alarm, or merely of a bright
\par fixed attention, though it included all the four expressions--as his
\par eyes rested on these things, a sudden vivid likeness passed before him,
\par of a child whom he had held in his arms on the passage across that very
\par Channel, one cold time, when the hail drifted heavily and the sea ran
\par high. The likeness passed away, like a breath along the surface of
\par the gaunt pier-glass behind her, on the frame of which, a hospital
\par procession of negro cupids, several headless and all cripples, were
\par offering black baskets of Dead Sea fruit to black divinities of the
\par feminine gender--and he made his formal bow to Miss Manette.
\par 
\par "Pray take a seat, sir." In a very clear and pleasant young voice; a
\par little foreign in its accent, but a very little indeed.
\par 
\par "I kiss your hand, miss," said Mr. Lorry, with the manners of an earlier
\par date, as he made his formal bow again, and took his seat.
\par 
\par "I received a letter from the Bank, sir, yesterday, informing me that
\par some intelligence--or discovery--"
\par 
\par "The word is not material, miss; either word will do."
\par 
\par "--respecting the small property of my poor father, whom I never saw--so
\par long dead--"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry moved in his chair, and cast a troubled look towards the
\par hospital procession of negro cupids. As if _they_ had any help for
\par anybody in their absurd baskets!
\par 
\par "--rendered it necessary that I should go to Paris, there to communicate
\par with a gentleman of the Bank, so good as to be despatched to Paris for
\par the purpose."
\par 
\par "Myself."
\par 
\par "As I was prepared to hear, sir."
\par 
\par She curtseyed to him (young ladies made curtseys in those days), with a
\par pretty desire to convey to him that she felt how much older and wiser he
\par was than she. He made her another bow.
\par 
\par "I replied to the Bank, sir, that as it was considered necessary, by
\par those who know, and who are so kind as to advise me, that I should go to
\par France, and that as I am an orphan and have no friend who could go with
\par me, I should esteem it highly if I might be permitted to place myself,
\par during the journey, under that worthy gentleman's protection. The
\par gentleman had left London, but I think a messenger was sent after him to
\par beg the favour of his waiting for me here."
\par 
\par "I was happy," said Mr. Lorry, "to be entrusted with the charge. I shall
\par be more happy to execute it."
\par 
\par "Sir, I thank you indeed. I thank you very gratefully. It was told me
\par by the Bank that the gentleman would explain to me the details of the
\par business, and that I must prepare myself to find them of a surprising
\par nature. I have done my best to prepare myself, and I naturally have a
\par strong and eager interest to know what they are."
\par 
\par "Naturally," said Mr. Lorry. "Yes--I--"
\par 
\par After a pause, he added, again settling the crisp flaxen wig at the
\par ears, "It is very difficult to begin."
\par 
\par He did not begin, but, in his indecision, met her glance. The young
\par forehead lifted itself into that singular expression--but it was pretty
\par and characteristic, besides being singular--and she raised her hand,
\par as if with an involuntary action she caught at, or stayed some passing
\par shadow.
\par 
\par "Are you quite a stranger to me, sir?"
\par 
\par "Am I not?" Mr. Lorry opened his hands, and extended them outwards with
\par an argumentative smile.
\par 
\par Between the eyebrows and just over the little feminine nose, the line of
\par which was as delicate and fine as it was possible to be, the expression
\par deepened itself as she took her seat thoughtfully in the chair by which
\par she had hitherto remained standing. He watched her as she mused, and the
\par moment she raised her eyes again, went on:
\par 
\par "In your adopted country, I presume, I cannot do better than address you
\par as a young English lady, Miss Manette?"
\par 
\par "If you please, sir."
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, I am a man of business. I have a business charge to
\par acquit myself of. In your reception of it, don't heed me any more than
\par if I was a speaking machine--truly, I am not much else. I will, with
\par your leave, relate to you, miss, the story of one of our customers."
\par 
\par "Story!"
\par 
\par He seemed wilfully to mistake the word she had repeated, when he added,
\par in a hurry, "Yes, customers; in the banking business we usually call
\par our connection our customers. He was a French gentleman; a scientific
\par gentleman; a man of great acquirements--a Doctor."
\par 
\par "Not of Beauvais?"
\par 
\par "Why, yes, of Beauvais. Like Monsieur Manette, your father, the
\par gentleman was of Beauvais. Like Monsieur Manette, your father, the
\par gentleman was of repute in Paris. I had the honour of knowing him there.
\par Our relations were business relations, but confidential. I was at that
\par time in our French House, and had been--oh! twenty years."
\par 
\par "At that time--I may ask, at what time, sir?"
\par 
\par "I speak, miss, of twenty years ago. He married--an English lady--and
\par I was one of the trustees. His affairs, like the affairs of many other
\par French gentlemen and French families, were entirely in Tellson's hands.
\par In a similar way I am, or I have been, trustee of one kind or other for
\par scores of our customers. These are mere business relations, miss;
\par there is no friendship in them, no particular interest, nothing like
\par sentiment. I have passed from one to another, in the course of my
\par business life, just as I pass from one of our customers to another in
\par the course of my business day; in short, I have no feelings; I am a mere
\par machine. To go on--"
\par 
\par "But this is my father's story, sir; and I begin to think"--the
\par curiously roughened forehead was very intent upon him--"that when I was
\par left an orphan through my mother's surviving my father only two years,
\par it was you who brought me to England. I am almost sure it was you."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry took the hesitating little hand that confidingly advanced
\par to take his, and he put it with some ceremony to his lips. He then
\par conducted the young lady straightway to her chair again, and, holding
\par the chair-back with his left hand, and using his right by turns to rub
\par his chin, pull his wig at the ears, or point what he said, stood looking
\par down into her face while she sat looking up into his.
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, it _was_ I. And you will see how truly I spoke of myself
\par just now, in saying I had no feelings, and that all the relations I hold
\par with my fellow-creatures are mere business relations, when you reflect
\par that I have never seen you since. No; you have been the ward of
\par Tellson's House since, and I have been busy with the other business of
\par Tellson's House since. Feelings! I have no time for them, no chance
\par of them. I pass my whole life, miss, in turning an immense pecuniary
\par Mangle."
\par 
\par After this odd description of his daily routine of employment, Mr. Lorry
\par flattened his flaxen wig upon his head with both hands (which was most
\par unnecessary, for nothing could be flatter than its shining surface was
\par before), and resumed his former attitude.
\par 
\par "So far, miss (as you have remarked), this is the story of your
\par regretted father. Now comes the difference. If your father had not died
\par when he did--Don't be frightened! How you start!"
\par 
\par She did, indeed, start. And she caught his wrist with both her hands.
\par 
\par "Pray," said Mr. Lorry, in a soothing tone, bringing his left hand from
\par the back of the chair to lay it on the supplicatory fingers that clasped
\par him in so violent a tremble: "pray control your agitation--a matter of
\par business. As I was saying--"
\par 
\par Her look so discomposed him that he stopped, wandered, and began anew:
\par 
\par "As I was saying; if Monsieur Manette had not died; if he had suddenly
\par and silently disappeared; if he had been spirited away; if it had not
\par been difficult to guess to what dreadful place, though no art could
\par trace him; if he had an enemy in some compatriot who could exercise a
\par privilege that I in my own time have known the boldest people afraid
\par to speak of in a whisper, across the water there; for instance, the
\par privilege of filling up blank forms for the consignment of any one
\par to the oblivion of a prison for any length of time; if his wife had
\par implored the king, the queen, the court, the clergy, for any tidings of
\par him, and all quite in vain;--then the history of your father would have
\par been the history of this unfortunate gentleman, the Doctor of Beauvais."
\par 
\par "I entreat you to tell me more, sir."
\par 
\par "I will. I am going to. You can bear it?"
\par 
\par "I can bear anything but the uncertainty you leave me in at this
\par moment."
\par 
\par "You speak collectedly, and you--_are_ collected. That's good!" (Though
\par his manner was less satisfied than his words.) "A matter of business.
\par Regard it as a matter of business--business that must be done. Now
\par if this doctor's wife, though a lady of great courage and spirit,
\par had suffered so intensely from this cause before her little child was
\par born--"
\par 
\par "The little child was a daughter, sir."
\par 
\par "A daughter. A-a-matter of business--don't be distressed. Miss, if the
\par poor lady had suffered so intensely before her little child was born,
\par that she came to the determination of sparing the poor child the
\par inheritance of any part of the agony she had known the pains of, by
\par rearing her in the belief that her father was dead--No, don't kneel! In
\par Heaven's name why should you kneel to me!"
\par 
\par "For the truth. O dear, good, compassionate sir, for the truth!"
\par 
\par "A--a matter of business. You confuse me, and how can I transact
\par business if I am confused? Let us be clear-headed. If you could kindly
\par mention now, for instance, what nine times ninepence are, or how many
\par shillings in twenty guineas, it would be so encouraging. I should be so
\par much more at my ease about your state of mind."
\par 
\par Without directly answering to this appeal, she sat so still when he had
\par very gently raised her, and the hands that had not ceased to clasp
\par his wrists were so much more steady than they had been, that she
\par communicated some reassurance to Mr. Jarvis Lorry.
\par 
\par "That's right, that's right. Courage! Business! You have business before
\par you; useful business. Miss Manette, your mother took this course with
\par you. And when she died--I believe broken-hearted--having never slackened
\par her unavailing search for your father, she left you, at two years old,
\par to grow to be blooming, beautiful, and happy, without the dark cloud
\par upon you of living in uncertainty whether your father soon wore his
\par heart out in prison, or wasted there through many lingering years."
\par 
\par As he said the words he looked down, with an admiring pity, on the
\par flowing golden hair; as if he pictured to himself that it might have
\par been already tinged with grey.
\par 
\par "You know that your parents had no great possession, and that what
\par they had was secured to your mother and to you. There has been no new
\par discovery, of money, or of any other property; but--"
\par 
\par He felt his wrist held closer, and he stopped. The expression in the
\par forehead, which had so particularly attracted his notice, and which was
\par now immovable, had deepened into one of pain and horror.
\par 
\par "But he has been--been found. He is alive. Greatly changed, it is too
\par probable; almost a wreck, it is possible; though we will hope the best.
\par Still, alive. Your father has been taken to the house of an old servant
\par in Paris, and we are going there: I, to identify him if I can: you, to
\par restore him to life, love, duty, rest, comfort."
\par 
\par A shiver ran through her frame, and from it through his. She said, in a
\par low, distinct, awe-stricken voice, as if she were saying it in a dream,
\par 
\par "I am going to see his Ghost! It will be his Ghost--not him!"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry quietly chafed the hands that held his arm. "There, there,
\par there! See now, see now! The best and the worst are known to you, now.
\par You are well on your way to the poor wronged gentleman, and, with a fair
\par sea voyage, and a fair land journey, you will be soon at his dear side."
\par 
\par She repeated in the same tone, sunk to a whisper, "I have been free, I
\par have been happy, yet his Ghost has never haunted me!"
\par 
\par "Only one thing more," said Mr. Lorry, laying stress upon it as a
\par wholesome means of enforcing her attention: "he has been found under
\par another name; his own, long forgotten or long concealed. It would be
\par worse than useless now to inquire which; worse than useless to seek to
\par know whether he has been for years overlooked, or always designedly
\par held prisoner. It would be worse than useless now to make any inquiries,
\par because it would be dangerous. Better not to mention the subject,
\par anywhere or in any way, and to remove him--for a while at all
\par events--out of France. Even I, safe as an Englishman, and even
\par Tellson's, important as they are to French credit, avoid all naming of
\par the matter. I carry about me, not a scrap of writing openly referring
\par to it. This is a secret service altogether. My credentials, entries,
\par and memoranda, are all comprehended in the one line, 'Recalled to Life;'
\par which may mean anything. But what is the matter! She doesn't notice a
\par word! Miss Manette!"
\par 
\par Perfectly still and silent, and not even fallen back in her chair, she
\par sat under his hand, utterly insensible; with her eyes open and fixed
\par upon him, and with that last expression looking as if it were carved or
\par branded into her forehead. So close was her hold upon his arm, that he
\par feared to detach himself lest he should hurt her; therefore he called
\par out loudly for assistance without moving.
\par 
\par A wild-looking woman, whom even in his agitation, Mr. Lorry observed to
\par be all of a red colour, and to have red hair, and to be dressed in some
\par extraordinary tight-fitting fashion, and to have on her head a most
\par wonderful bonnet like a Grenadier wooden measure, and good measure too,
\par or a great Stilton cheese, came running into the room in advance of the
\par inn servants, and soon settled the question of his detachment from the
\par poor young lady, by laying a brawny hand upon his chest, and sending him
\par flying back against the nearest wall.
\par 
\par ("I really think this must be a man!" was Mr. Lorry's breathless
\par reflection, simultaneously with his coming against the wall.)
\par 
\par "Why, look at you all!" bawled this figure, addressing the inn servants.
\par "Why don't you go and fetch things, instead of standing there staring
\par at me? I am not so much to look at, am I? Why don't you go and fetch
\par things? I'll let you know, if you don't bring smelling-salts, cold
\par water, and vinegar, quick, I will."
\par 
\par There was an immediate dispersal for these restoratives, and she
\par softly laid the patient on a sofa, and tended her with great skill and
\par gentleness: calling her "my precious!" and "my bird!" and spreading her
\par golden hair aside over her shoulders with great pride and care.
\par 
\par "And you in brown!" she said, indignantly turning to Mr. Lorry;
\par "couldn't you tell her what you had to tell her, without frightening her
\par to death? Look at her, with her pretty pale face and her cold hands. Do
\par you call _that_ being a Banker?"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry was so exceedingly disconcerted by a question so hard to
\par answer, that he could only look on, at a distance, with much feebler
\par sympathy and humility, while the strong woman, having banished the inn
\par servants under the mysterious penalty of "letting them know" something
\par not mentioned if they stayed there, staring, recovered her charge by a
\par regular series of gradations, and coaxed her to lay her drooping head
\par upon her shoulder.
\par 
\par "I hope she will do well now," said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "No thanks to you in brown, if she does. My darling pretty!"
\par 
\par "I hope," said Mr. Lorry, after another pause of feeble sympathy and
\par humility, "that you accompany Miss Manette to France?"
\par 
\par "A likely thing, too!" replied the strong woman. "If it was ever
\par intended that I should go across salt water, do you suppose Providence
\par would have cast my lot in an island?"
\par 
\par This being another question hard to answer, Mr. Jarvis Lorry withdrew to
\par consider it.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par V. The Wine-shop
\par 
\par 
\par A large cask of wine had been dropped and broken, in the street. The
\par accident had happened in getting it out of a cart; the cask had tumbled
\par out with a run, the hoops had burst, and it lay on the stones just
\par outside the door of the wine-shop, shattered like a walnut-shell.
\par 
\par All the people within reach had suspended their business, or their
\par idleness, to run to the spot and drink the wine. The rough, irregular
\par stones of the street, pointing every way, and designed, one might have
\par thought, expressly to lame all living creatures that approached them,
\par had dammed it into little pools; these were surrounded, each by its own
\par jostling group or crowd, according to its size. Some men kneeled down,
\par made scoops of their two hands joined, and sipped, or tried to help
\par women, who bent over their shoulders, to sip, before the wine had all
\par run out between their fingers. Others, men and women, dipped in
\par the puddles with little mugs of mutilated earthenware, or even with
\par handkerchiefs from women's heads, which were squeezed dry into infants'
\par mouths; others made small mud-embankments, to stem the wine as it ran;
\par others, directed by lookers-on up at high windows, darted here and
\par there, to cut off little streams of wine that started away in new
\par directions; others devoted themselves to the sodden and lee-dyed
\par pieces of the cask, licking, and even champing the moister wine-rotted
\par fragments with eager relish. There was no drainage to carry off the
\par wine, and not only did it all get taken up, but so much mud got taken up
\par along with it, that there might have been a scavenger in the street,
\par if anybody acquainted with it could have believed in such a miraculous
\par presence.
\par 
\par A shrill sound of laughter and of amused voices--voices of men, women,
\par and children--resounded in the street while this wine game lasted. There
\par was little roughness in the sport, and much playfulness. There was a
\par special companionship in it, an observable inclination on the part
\par of every one to join some other one, which led, especially among the
\par luckier or lighter-hearted, to frolicsome embraces, drinking of healths,
\par shaking of hands, and even joining of hands and dancing, a dozen
\par together. When the wine was gone, and the places where it had been
\par most abundant were raked into a gridiron-pattern by fingers, these
\par demonstrations ceased, as suddenly as they had broken out. The man who
\par had left his saw sticking in the firewood he was cutting, set it in
\par motion again; the women who had left on a door-step the little pot of
\par hot ashes, at which she had been trying to soften the pain in her own
\par starved fingers and toes, or in those of her child, returned to it; men
\par with bare arms, matted locks, and cadaverous faces, who had emerged into
\par the winter light from cellars, moved away, to descend again; and a gloom
\par gathered on the scene that appeared more natural to it than sunshine.
\par 
\par The wine was red wine, and had stained the ground of the narrow street
\par in the suburb of Saint Antoine, in Paris, where it was spilled. It had
\par stained many hands, too, and many faces, and many naked feet, and many
\par wooden shoes. The hands of the man who sawed the wood, left red marks
\par on the billets; and the forehead of the woman who nursed her baby, was
\par stained with the stain of the old rag she wound about her head again.
\par Those who had been greedy with the staves of the cask, had acquired a
\par tigerish smear about the mouth; and one tall joker so besmirched, his
\par head more out of a long squalid bag of a nightcap than in it, scrawled
\par upon a wall with his finger dipped in muddy wine-lees--BLOOD.
\par 
\par The time was to come, when that wine too would be spilled on the
\par street-stones, and when the stain of it would be red upon many there.
\par 
\par And now that the cloud settled on Saint Antoine, which a momentary
\par gleam had driven from his sacred countenance, the darkness of it was
\par heavy--cold, dirt, sickness, ignorance, and want, were the lords in
\par waiting on the saintly presence--nobles of great power all of them;
\par but, most especially the last. Samples of a people that had undergone a
\par terrible grinding and regrinding in the mill, and certainly not in the
\par fabulous mill which ground old people young, shivered at every corner,
\par passed in and out at every doorway, looked from every window, fluttered
\par in every vestige of a garment that the wind shook. The mill which
\par had worked them down, was the mill that grinds young people old; the
\par children had ancient faces and grave voices; and upon them, and upon the
\par grown faces, and ploughed into every furrow of age and coming up afresh,
\par was the sigh, Hunger. It was prevalent everywhere. Hunger was pushed out
\par of the tall houses, in the wretched clothing that hung upon poles and
\par lines; Hunger was patched into them with straw and rag and wood and
\par paper; Hunger was repeated in every fragment of the small modicum of
\par firewood that the man sawed off; Hunger stared down from the smokeless
\par chimneys, and started up from the filthy street that had no offal,
\par among its refuse, of anything to eat. Hunger was the inscription on the
\par baker's shelves, written in every small loaf of his scanty stock of
\par bad bread; at the sausage-shop, in every dead-dog preparation that
\par was offered for sale. Hunger rattled its dry bones among the roasting
\par chestnuts in the turned cylinder; Hunger was shred into atomics in every
\par farthing porringer of husky chips of potato, fried with some reluctant
\par drops of oil.
\par 
\par Its abiding place was in all things fitted to it. A narrow winding
\par street, full of offence and stench, with other narrow winding streets
\par diverging, all peopled by rags and nightcaps, and all smelling of rags
\par and nightcaps, and all visible things with a brooding look upon them
\par that looked ill. In the hunted air of the people there was yet some
\par wild-beast thought of the possibility of turning at bay. Depressed and
\par slinking though they were, eyes of fire were not wanting among them; nor
\par compressed lips, white with what they suppressed; nor foreheads knitted
\par into the likeness of the gallows-rope they mused about enduring, or
\par inflicting. The trade signs (and they were almost as many as the shops)
\par were, all, grim illustrations of Want. The butcher and the porkman
\par painted up, only the leanest scrags of meat; the baker, the coarsest of
\par meagre loaves. The people rudely pictured as drinking in the wine-shops,
\par croaked over their scanty measures of thin wine and beer, and were
\par gloweringly confidential together. Nothing was represented in a
\par flourishing condition, save tools and weapons; but, the cutler's knives
\par and axes were sharp and bright, the smith's hammers were heavy, and the
\par gunmaker's stock was murderous. The crippling stones of the pavement,
\par with their many little reservoirs of mud and water, had no footways, but
\par broke off abruptly at the doors. The kennel, to make amends, ran down
\par the middle of the street--when it ran at all: which was only after heavy
\par rains, and then it ran, by many eccentric fits, into the houses. Across
\par the streets, at wide intervals, one clumsy lamp was slung by a rope and
\par pulley; at night, when the lamplighter had let these down, and lighted,
\par and hoisted them again, a feeble grove of dim wicks swung in a sickly
\par manner overhead, as if they were at sea. Indeed they were at sea, and
\par the ship and crew were in peril of tempest.
\par 
\par For, the time was to come, when the gaunt scarecrows of that region
\par should have watched the lamplighter, in their idleness and hunger, so
\par long, as to conceive the idea of improving on his method, and hauling
\par up men by those ropes and pulleys, to flare upon the darkness of their
\par condition. But, the time was not come yet; and every wind that blew over
\par France shook the rags of the scarecrows in vain, for the birds, fine of
\par song and feather, took no warning.
\par 
\par The wine-shop was a corner shop, better than most others in its
\par appearance and degree, and the master of the wine-shop had stood outside
\par it, in a yellow waistcoat and green breeches, looking on at the struggle
\par for the lost wine. "It's not my affair," said he, with a final shrug
\par of the shoulders. "The people from the market did it. Let them bring
\par another."
\par 
\par There, his eyes happening to catch the tall joker writing up his joke,
\par he called to him across the way:
\par 
\par "Say, then, my Gaspard, what do you do there?"
\par 
\par The fellow pointed to his joke with immense significance, as is often
\par the way with his tribe. It missed its mark, and completely failed, as is
\par often the way with his tribe too.
\par 
\par "What now? Are you a subject for the mad hospital?" said the wine-shop
\par keeper, crossing the road, and obliterating the jest with a handful of
\par mud, picked up for the purpose, and smeared over it. "Why do you write
\par in the public streets? Is there--tell me thou--is there no other place
\par to write such words in?"
\par 
\par In his expostulation he dropped his cleaner hand (perhaps accidentally,
\par perhaps not) upon the joker's heart. The joker rapped it with his
\par own, took a nimble spring upward, and came down in a fantastic dancing
\par attitude, with one of his stained shoes jerked off his foot into his
\par hand, and held out. A joker of an extremely, not to say wolfishly
\par practical character, he looked, under those circumstances.
\par 
\par "Put it on, put it on," said the other. "Call wine, wine; and finish
\par there." With that advice, he wiped his soiled hand upon the joker's
\par dress, such as it was--quite deliberately, as having dirtied the hand on
\par his account; and then recrossed the road and entered the wine-shop.
\par 
\par This wine-shop keeper was a bull-necked, martial-looking man of thirty,
\par and he should have been of a hot temperament, for, although it was a
\par bitter day, he wore no coat, but carried one slung over his shoulder.
\par His shirt-sleeves were rolled up, too, and his brown arms were bare to
\par the elbows. Neither did he wear anything more on his head than his own
\par crisply-curling short dark hair. He was a dark man altogether, with good
\par eyes and a good bold breadth between them. Good-humoured looking on
\par the whole, but implacable-looking, too; evidently a man of a strong
\par resolution and a set purpose; a man not desirable to be met, rushing
\par down a narrow pass with a gulf on either side, for nothing would turn
\par the man.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge, his wife, sat in the shop behind the counter as he
\par came in. Madame Defarge was a stout woman of about his own age, with
\par a watchful eye that seldom seemed to look at anything, a large hand
\par heavily ringed, a steady face, strong features, and great composure of
\par manner. There was a character about Madame Defarge, from which one might
\par have predicated that she did not often make mistakes against herself
\par in any of the reckonings over which she presided. Madame Defarge being
\par sensitive to cold, was wrapped in fur, and had a quantity of bright
\par shawl twined about her head, though not to the concealment of her large
\par earrings. Her knitting was before her, but she had laid it down to pick
\par her teeth with a toothpick. Thus engaged, with her right elbow supported
\par by her left hand, Madame Defarge said nothing when her lord came in, but
\par coughed just one grain of cough. This, in combination with the lifting
\par of her darkly defined eyebrows over her toothpick by the breadth of a
\par line, suggested to her husband that he would do well to look round the
\par shop among the customers, for any new customer who had dropped in while
\par he stepped over the way.
\par 
\par The wine-shop keeper accordingly rolled his eyes about, until they
\par rested upon an elderly gentleman and a young lady, who were seated in
\par a corner. Other company were there: two playing cards, two playing
\par dominoes, three standing by the counter lengthening out a short supply
\par of wine. As he passed behind the counter, he took notice that the
\par elderly gentleman said in a look to the young lady, "This is our man."
\par 
\par "What the devil do _you_ do in that galley there?" said Monsieur Defarge
\par to himself; "I don't know you."
\par 
\par But, he feigned not to notice the two strangers, and fell into discourse
\par with the triumvirate of customers who were drinking at the counter.
\par 
\par "How goes it, Jacques?" said one of these three to Monsieur Defarge. "Is
\par all the spilt wine swallowed?"
\par 
\par "Every drop, Jacques," answered Monsieur Defarge.
\par 
\par When this interchange of Christian name was effected, Madame Defarge,
\par picking her teeth with her toothpick, coughed another grain of cough,
\par and raised her eyebrows by the breadth of another line.
\par 
\par "It is not often," said the second of the three, addressing Monsieur
\par Defarge, "that many of these miserable beasts know the taste of wine, or
\par of anything but black bread and death. Is it not so, Jacques?"
\par 
\par "It is so, Jacques," Monsieur Defarge returned.
\par 
\par At this second interchange of the Christian name, Madame Defarge, still
\par using her toothpick with profound composure, coughed another grain of
\par cough, and raised her eyebrows by the breadth of another line.
\par 
\par The last of the three now said his say, as he put down his empty
\par drinking vessel and smacked his lips.
\par 
\par "Ah! So much the worse! A bitter taste it is that such poor cattle
\par always have in their mouths, and hard lives they live, Jacques. Am I
\par right, Jacques?"
\par 
\par "You are right, Jacques," was the response of Monsieur Defarge.
\par 
\par This third interchange of the Christian name was completed at the moment
\par when Madame Defarge put her toothpick by, kept her eyebrows up, and
\par slightly rustled in her seat.
\par 
\par "Hold then! True!" muttered her husband. "Gentlemen--my wife!"
\par 
\par The three customers pulled off their hats to Madame Defarge, with three
\par flourishes. She acknowledged their homage by bending her head, and
\par giving them a quick look. Then she glanced in a casual manner round the
\par wine-shop, took up her knitting with great apparent calmness and repose
\par of spirit, and became absorbed in it.
\par 
\par "Gentlemen," said her husband, who had kept his bright eye observantly
\par upon her, "good day. The chamber, furnished bachelor-fashion, that you
\par wished to see, and were inquiring for when I stepped out, is on the
\par fifth floor. The doorway of the staircase gives on the little courtyard
\par close to the left here," pointing with his hand, "near to the window of
\par my establishment. But, now that I remember, one of you has already been
\par there, and can show the way. Gentlemen, adieu!"
\par 
\par They paid for their wine, and left the place. The eyes of Monsieur
\par Defarge were studying his wife at her knitting when the elderly
\par gentleman advanced from his corner, and begged the favour of a word.
\par 
\par "Willingly, sir," said Monsieur Defarge, and quietly stepped with him to
\par the door.
\par 
\par Their conference was very short, but very decided. Almost at the first
\par word, Monsieur Defarge started and became deeply attentive. It had
\par not lasted a minute, when he nodded and went out. The gentleman then
\par beckoned to the young lady, and they, too, went out. Madame Defarge
\par knitted with nimble fingers and steady eyebrows, and saw nothing.
\par 
\par Mr. Jarvis Lorry and Miss Manette, emerging from the wine-shop thus,
\par joined Monsieur Defarge in the doorway to which he had directed his own
\par company just before. It opened from a stinking little black courtyard,
\par and was the general public entrance to a great pile of houses, inhabited
\par by a great number of people. In the gloomy tile-paved entry to the
\par gloomy tile-paved staircase, Monsieur Defarge bent down on one knee
\par to the child of his old master, and put her hand to his lips. It was
\par a gentle action, but not at all gently done; a very remarkable
\par transformation had come over him in a few seconds. He had no good-humour
\par in his face, nor any openness of aspect left, but had become a secret,
\par angry, dangerous man.
\par 
\par "It is very high; it is a little difficult. Better to begin slowly."
\par Thus, Monsieur Defarge, in a stern voice, to Mr. Lorry, as they began
\par ascending the stairs.
\par 
\par "Is he alone?" the latter whispered.
\par 
\par "Alone! God help him, who should be with him!" said the other, in the
\par same low voice.
\par 
\par "Is he always alone, then?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "Of his own desire?"
\par 
\par "Of his own necessity. As he was, when I first saw him after they
\par found me and demanded to know if I would take him, and, at my peril be
\par discreet--as he was then, so he is now."
\par 
\par "He is greatly changed?"
\par 
\par "Changed!"
\par 
\par The keeper of the wine-shop stopped to strike the wall with his hand,
\par and mutter a tremendous curse. No direct answer could have been half so
\par forcible. Mr. Lorry's spirits grew heavier and heavier, as he and his
\par two companions ascended higher and higher.
\par 
\par Such a staircase, with its accessories, in the older and more crowded
\par parts of Paris, would be bad enough now; but, at that time, it was vile
\par indeed to unaccustomed and unhardened senses. Every little habitation
\par within the great foul nest of one high building--that is to say,
\par the room or rooms within every door that opened on the general
\par staircase--left its own heap of refuse on its own landing, besides
\par flinging other refuse from its own windows. The uncontrollable and
\par hopeless mass of decomposition so engendered, would have polluted
\par the air, even if poverty and deprivation had not loaded it with their
\par intangible impurities; the two bad sources combined made it almost
\par insupportable. Through such an atmosphere, by a steep dark shaft of dirt
\par and poison, the way lay. Yielding to his own disturbance of mind, and to
\par his young companion's agitation, which became greater every instant, Mr.
\par Jarvis Lorry twice stopped to rest. Each of these stoppages was made
\par at a doleful grating, by which any languishing good airs that were left
\par uncorrupted, seemed to escape, and all spoilt and sickly vapours seemed
\par to crawl in. Through the rusted bars, tastes, rather than glimpses, were
\par caught of the jumbled neighbourhood; and nothing within range, nearer
\par or lower than the summits of the two great towers of Notre-Dame, had any
\par promise on it of healthy life or wholesome aspirations.
\par 
\par At last, the top of the staircase was gained, and they stopped for the
\par third time. There was yet an upper staircase, of a steeper inclination
\par and of contracted dimensions, to be ascended, before the garret story
\par was reached. The keeper of the wine-shop, always going a little in
\par advance, and always going on the side which Mr. Lorry took, as though he
\par dreaded to be asked any question by the young lady, turned himself about
\par here, and, carefully feeling in the pockets of the coat he carried over
\par his shoulder, took out a key.
\par 
\par "The door is locked then, my friend?" said Mr. Lorry, surprised.
\par 
\par "Ay. Yes," was the grim reply of Monsieur Defarge.
\par 
\par "You think it necessary to keep the unfortunate gentleman so retired?"
\par 
\par "I think it necessary to turn the key." Monsieur Defarge whispered it
\par closer in his ear, and frowned heavily.
\par 
\par "Why?"
\par 
\par "Why! Because he has lived so long, locked up, that he would be
\par frightened--rave--tear himself to pieces--die--come to I know not what
\par harm--if his door was left open."
\par 
\par "Is it possible!" exclaimed Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "Is it possible!" repeated Defarge, bitterly. "Yes. And a beautiful
\par world we live in, when it _is_ possible, and when many other such things
\par are possible, and not only possible, but done--done, see you!--under
\par that sky there, every day. Long live the Devil. Let us go on."
\par 
\par This dialogue had been held in so very low a whisper, that not a word
\par of it had reached the young lady's ears. But, by this time she trembled
\par under such strong emotion, and her face expressed such deep anxiety,
\par and, above all, such dread and terror, that Mr. Lorry felt it incumbent
\par on him to speak a word or two of reassurance.
\par 
\par "Courage, dear miss! Courage! Business! The worst will be over in a
\par moment; it is but passing the room-door, and the worst is over. Then,
\par all the good you bring to him, all the relief, all the happiness you
\par bring to him, begin. Let our good friend here, assist you on that side.
\par That's well, friend Defarge. Come, now. Business, business!"
\par 
\par They went up slowly and softly. The staircase was short, and they were
\par soon at the top. There, as it had an abrupt turn in it, they came all at
\par once in sight of three men, whose heads were bent down close together at
\par the side of a door, and who were intently looking into the room to which
\par the door belonged, through some chinks or holes in the wall. On hearing
\par footsteps close at hand, these three turned, and rose, and showed
\par themselves to be the three of one name who had been drinking in the
\par wine-shop.
\par 
\par "I forgot them in the surprise of your visit," explained Monsieur
\par Defarge. "Leave us, good boys; we have business here."
\par 
\par The three glided by, and went silently down.
\par 
\par There appearing to be no other door on that floor, and the keeper of
\par the wine-shop going straight to this one when they were left alone, Mr.
\par Lorry asked him in a whisper, with a little anger:
\par 
\par "Do you make a show of Monsieur Manette?"
\par 
\par "I show him, in the way you have seen, to a chosen few."
\par 
\par "Is that well?"
\par 
\par "_I_ think it is well."
\par 
\par "Who are the few? How do you choose them?"
\par 
\par "I choose them as real men, of my name--Jacques is my name--to whom the
\par sight is likely to do good. Enough; you are English; that is another
\par thing. Stay there, if you please, a little moment."
\par 
\par With an admonitory gesture to keep them back, he stooped, and looked in
\par through the crevice in the wall. Soon raising his head again, he struck
\par twice or thrice upon the door--evidently with no other object than to
\par make a noise there. With the same intention, he drew the key across it,
\par three or four times, before he put it clumsily into the lock, and turned
\par it as heavily as he could.
\par 
\par The door slowly opened inward under his hand, and he looked into the
\par room and said something. A faint voice answered something. Little more
\par than a single syllable could have been spoken on either side.
\par 
\par He looked back over his shoulder, and beckoned them to enter. Mr. Lorry
\par got his arm securely round the daughter's waist, and held her; for he
\par felt that she was sinking.
\par 
\par "A-a-a-business, business!" he urged, with a moisture that was not of
\par business shining on his cheek. "Come in, come in!"
\par 
\par "I am afraid of it," she answered, shuddering.
\par 
\par "Of it? What?"
\par 
\par "I mean of him. Of my father."
\par 
\par Rendered in a manner desperate, by her state and by the beckoning of
\par their conductor, he drew over his neck the arm that shook upon his
\par shoulder, lifted her a little, and hurried her into the room. He sat her
\par down just within the door, and held her, clinging to him.
\par 
\par Defarge drew out the key, closed the door, locked it on the inside,
\par took out the key again, and held it in his hand. All this he did,
\par methodically, and with as loud and harsh an accompaniment of noise as he
\par could make. Finally, he walked across the room with a measured tread to
\par where the window was. He stopped there, and faced round.
\par 
\par The garret, built to be a depository for firewood and the like, was dim
\par and dark: for, the window of dormer shape, was in truth a door in the
\par roof, with a little crane over it for the hoisting up of stores from
\par the street: unglazed, and closing up the middle in two pieces, like any
\par other door of French construction. To exclude the cold, one half of this
\par door was fast closed, and the other was opened but a very little way.
\par Such a scanty portion of light was admitted through these means, that it
\par was difficult, on first coming in, to see anything; and long habit
\par alone could have slowly formed in any one, the ability to do any work
\par requiring nicety in such obscurity. Yet, work of that kind was being
\par done in the garret; for, with his back towards the door, and his face
\par towards the window where the keeper of the wine-shop stood looking at
\par him, a white-haired man sat on a low bench, stooping forward and very
\par busy, making shoes.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VI. The Shoemaker
\par 
\par 
\par "Good day!" said Monsieur Defarge, looking down at the white head that
\par bent low over the shoemaking.
\par 
\par It was raised for a moment, and a very faint voice responded to the
\par salutation, as if it were at a distance:
\par 
\par "Good day!"
\par 
\par "You are still hard at work, I see?"
\par 
\par After a long silence, the head was lifted for another moment, and the
\par voice replied, "Yes--I am working." This time, a pair of haggard eyes
\par had looked at the questioner, before the face had dropped again.
\par 
\par The faintness of the voice was pitiable and dreadful. It was not the
\par faintness of physical weakness, though confinement and hard fare no
\par doubt had their part in it. Its deplorable peculiarity was, that it was
\par the faintness of solitude and disuse. It was like the last feeble echo
\par of a sound made long and long ago. So entirely had it lost the life and
\par resonance of the human voice, that it affected the senses like a once
\par beautiful colour faded away into a poor weak stain. So sunken and
\par suppressed it was, that it was like a voice underground. So expressive
\par it was, of a hopeless and lost creature, that a famished traveller,
\par wearied out by lonely wandering in a wilderness, would have remembered
\par home and friends in such a tone before lying down to die.
\par 
\par Some minutes of silent work had passed: and the haggard eyes had looked
\par up again: not with any interest or curiosity, but with a dull mechanical
\par perception, beforehand, that the spot where the only visitor they were
\par aware of had stood, was not yet empty.
\par 
\par "I want," said Defarge, who had not removed his gaze from the shoemaker,
\par "to let in a little more light here. You can bear a little more?"
\par 
\par The shoemaker stopped his work; looked with a vacant air of listening,
\par at the floor on one side of him; then similarly, at the floor on the
\par other side of him; then, upward at the speaker.
\par 
\par "What did you say?"
\par 
\par "You can bear a little more light?"
\par 
\par "I must bear it, if you let it in." (Laying the palest shadow of a
\par stress upon the second word.)
\par 
\par The opened half-door was opened a little further, and secured at that
\par angle for the time. A broad ray of light fell into the garret, and
\par showed the workman with an unfinished shoe upon his lap, pausing in his
\par labour. His few common tools and various scraps of leather were at his
\par feet and on his bench. He had a white beard, raggedly cut, but not very
\par long, a hollow face, and exceedingly bright eyes. The hollowness and
\par thinness of his face would have caused them to look large, under his yet
\par dark eyebrows and his confused white hair, though they had been really
\par otherwise; but, they were naturally large, and looked unnaturally so.
\par His yellow rags of shirt lay open at the throat, and showed his body
\par to be withered and worn. He, and his old canvas frock, and his loose
\par stockings, and all his poor tatters of clothes, had, in a long seclusion
\par from direct light and air, faded down to such a dull uniformity of
\par parchment-yellow, that it would have been hard to say which was which.
\par 
\par He had put up a hand between his eyes and the light, and the very bones
\par of it seemed transparent. So he sat, with a steadfastly vacant gaze,
\par pausing in his work. He never looked at the figure before him, without
\par first looking down on this side of himself, then on that, as if he had
\par lost the habit of associating place with sound; he never spoke, without
\par first wandering in this manner, and forgetting to speak.
\par 
\par "Are you going to finish that pair of shoes to-day?" asked Defarge,
\par motioning to Mr. Lorry to come forward.
\par 
\par "What did you say?"
\par 
\par "Do you mean to finish that pair of shoes to-day?"
\par 
\par "I can't say that I mean to. I suppose so. I don't know."
\par 
\par But, the question reminded him of his work, and he bent over it again.
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry came silently forward, leaving the daughter by the door. When
\par he had stood, for a minute or two, by the side of Defarge, the shoemaker
\par looked up. He showed no surprise at seeing another figure, but the
\par unsteady fingers of one of his hands strayed to his lips as he looked at
\par it (his lips and his nails were of the same pale lead-colour), and then
\par the hand dropped to his work, and he once more bent over the shoe. The
\par look and the action had occupied but an instant.
\par 
\par "You have a visitor, you see," said Monsieur Defarge.
\par 
\par "What did you say?"
\par 
\par "Here is a visitor."
\par 
\par The shoemaker looked up as before, but without removing a hand from his
\par work.
\par 
\par "Come!" said Defarge. "Here is monsieur, who knows a well-made shoe when
\par he sees one. Show him that shoe you are working at. Take it, monsieur."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry took it in his hand.
\par 
\par "Tell monsieur what kind of shoe it is, and the maker's name."
\par 
\par There was a longer pause than usual, before the shoemaker replied:
\par 
\par "I forget what it was you asked me. What did you say?"
\par 
\par "I said, couldn't you describe the kind of shoe, for monsieur's
\par information?"
\par 
\par "It is a lady's shoe. It is a young lady's walking-shoe. It is in the
\par present mode. I never saw the mode. I have had a pattern in my hand." He
\par glanced at the shoe with some little passing touch of pride.
\par 
\par "And the maker's name?" said Defarge.
\par 
\par Now that he had no work to hold, he laid the knuckles of the right hand
\par in the hollow of the left, and then the knuckles of the left hand in the
\par hollow of the right, and then passed a hand across his bearded chin, and
\par so on in regular changes, without a moment's intermission. The task of
\par recalling him from the vagrancy into which he always sank when he
\par had spoken, was like recalling some very weak person from a swoon, or
\par endeavouring, in the hope of some disclosure, to stay the spirit of a
\par fast-dying man.
\par 
\par "Did you ask me for my name?"
\par 
\par "Assuredly I did."
\par 
\par "One Hundred and Five, North Tower."
\par 
\par "Is that all?"
\par 
\par "One Hundred and Five, North Tower."
\par 
\par With a weary sound that was not a sigh, nor a groan, he bent to work
\par again, until the silence was again broken.
\par 
\par "You are not a shoemaker by trade?" said Mr. Lorry, looking steadfastly
\par at him.
\par 
\par His haggard eyes turned to Defarge as if he would have transferred the
\par question to him: but as no help came from that quarter, they turned back
\par on the questioner when they had sought the ground.
\par 
\par "I am not a shoemaker by trade? No, I was not a shoemaker by trade. I-I
\par learnt it here. I taught myself. I asked leave to--"
\par 
\par He lapsed away, even for minutes, ringing those measured changes on his
\par hands the whole time. His eyes came slowly back, at last, to the face
\par from which they had wandered; when they rested on it, he started, and
\par resumed, in the manner of a sleeper that moment awake, reverting to a
\par subject of last night.
\par 
\par "I asked leave to teach myself, and I got it with much difficulty after
\par a long while, and I have made shoes ever since."
\par 
\par As he held out his hand for the shoe that had been taken from him, Mr.
\par Lorry said, still looking steadfastly in his face:
\par 
\par "Monsieur Manette, do you remember nothing of me?"
\par 
\par The shoe dropped to the ground, and he sat looking fixedly at the
\par questioner.
\par 
\par "Monsieur Manette"; Mr. Lorry laid his hand upon Defarge's arm; "do you
\par remember nothing of this man? Look at him. Look at me. Is there no old
\par banker, no old business, no old servant, no old time, rising in your
\par mind, Monsieur Manette?"
\par 
\par As the captive of many years sat looking fixedly, by turns, at Mr.
\par Lorry and at Defarge, some long obliterated marks of an actively intent
\par intelligence in the middle of the forehead, gradually forced themselves
\par through the black mist that had fallen on him. They were overclouded
\par again, they were fainter, they were gone; but they had been there. And
\par so exactly was the expression repeated on the fair young face of her who
\par had crept along the wall to a point where she could see him, and where
\par she now stood looking at him, with hands which at first had been only
\par raised in frightened compassion, if not even to keep him off and
\par shut out the sight of him, but which were now extending towards him,
\par trembling with eagerness to lay the spectral face upon her warm young
\par breast, and love it back to life and hope--so exactly was the expression
\par repeated (though in stronger characters) on her fair young face, that it
\par looked as though it had passed like a moving light, from him to her.
\par 
\par Darkness had fallen on him in its place. He looked at the two, less and
\par less attentively, and his eyes in gloomy abstraction sought the ground
\par and looked about him in the old way. Finally, with a deep long sigh, he
\par took the shoe up, and resumed his work.
\par 
\par "Have you recognised him, monsieur?" asked Defarge in a whisper.
\par 
\par "Yes; for a moment. At first I thought it quite hopeless, but I have
\par unquestionably seen, for a single moment, the face that I once knew so
\par well. Hush! Let us draw further back. Hush!"
\par 
\par She had moved from the wall of the garret, very near to the bench on
\par which he sat. There was something awful in his unconsciousness of the
\par figure that could have put out its hand and touched him as he stooped
\par over his labour.
\par 
\par Not a word was spoken, not a sound was made. She stood, like a spirit,
\par beside him, and he bent over his work.
\par 
\par It happened, at length, that he had occasion to change the instrument
\par in his hand, for his shoemaker's knife. It lay on that side of him
\par which was not the side on which she stood. He had taken it up, and was
\par stooping to work again, when his eyes caught the skirt of her dress. He
\par raised them, and saw her face. The two spectators started forward,
\par but she stayed them with a motion of her hand. She had no fear of his
\par striking at her with the knife, though they had.
\par 
\par He stared at her with a fearful look, and after a while his lips began
\par to form some words, though no sound proceeded from them. By degrees, in
\par the pauses of his quick and laboured breathing, he was heard to say:
\par 
\par "What is this?"
\par 
\par With the tears streaming down her face, she put her two hands to her
\par lips, and kissed them to him; then clasped them on her breast, as if she
\par laid his ruined head there.
\par 
\par "You are not the gaoler's daughter?"
\par 
\par She sighed "No."
\par 
\par "Who are you?"
\par 
\par Not yet trusting the tones of her voice, she sat down on the bench
\par beside him. He recoiled, but she laid her hand upon his arm. A strange
\par thrill struck him when she did so, and visibly passed over his frame; he
\par laid the knife down softly, as he sat staring at her.
\par 
\par Her golden hair, which she wore in long curls, had been hurriedly pushed
\par aside, and fell down over her neck. Advancing his hand by little and
\par little, he took it up and looked at it. In the midst of the action
\par he went astray, and, with another deep sigh, fell to work at his
\par shoemaking.
\par 
\par But not for long. Releasing his arm, she laid her hand upon his
\par shoulder. After looking doubtfully at it, two or three times, as if to
\par be sure that it was really there, he laid down his work, put his hand
\par to his neck, and took off a blackened string with a scrap of folded rag
\par attached to it. He opened this, carefully, on his knee, and it contained
\par a very little quantity of hair: not more than one or two long golden
\par hairs, which he had, in some old day, wound off upon his finger.
\par 
\par He took her hair into his hand again, and looked closely at it. "It is
\par the same. How can it be! When was it! How was it!"
\par 
\par As the concentrated expression returned to his forehead, he seemed to
\par become conscious that it was in hers too. He turned her full to the
\par light, and looked at her.
\par 
\par "She had laid her head upon my shoulder, that night when I was summoned
\par out--she had a fear of my going, though I had none--and when I was
\par brought to the North Tower they found these upon my sleeve. 'You will
\par leave me them? They can never help me to escape in the body, though they
\par may in the spirit.' Those were the words I said. I remember them very
\par well."
\par 
\par He formed this speech with his lips many times before he could utter it.
\par But when he did find spoken words for it, they came to him coherently,
\par though slowly.
\par 
\par "How was this?--_Was it you_?"
\par 
\par Once more, the two spectators started, as he turned upon her with a
\par frightful suddenness. But she sat perfectly still in his grasp, and only
\par said, in a low voice, "I entreat you, good gentlemen, do not come near
\par us, do not speak, do not move!"
\par 
\par "Hark!" he exclaimed. "Whose voice was that?"
\par 
\par His hands released her as he uttered this cry, and went up to his white
\par hair, which they tore in a frenzy. It died out, as everything but his
\par shoemaking did die out of him, and he refolded his little packet and
\par tried to secure it in his breast; but he still looked at her, and
\par gloomily shook his head.
\par 
\par "No, no, no; you are too young, too blooming. It can't be. See what the
\par prisoner is. These are not the hands she knew, this is not the face
\par she knew, this is not a voice she ever heard. No, no. She was--and He
\par was--before the slow years of the North Tower--ages ago. What is your
\par name, my gentle angel?"
\par 
\par Hailing his softened tone and manner, his daughter fell upon her knees
\par before him, with her appealing hands upon his breast.
\par 
\par "O, sir, at another time you shall know my name, and who my mother was,
\par and who my father, and how I never knew their hard, hard history. But I
\par cannot tell you at this time, and I cannot tell you here. All that I may
\par tell you, here and now, is, that I pray to you to touch me and to bless
\par me. Kiss me, kiss me! O my dear, my dear!"
\par 
\par His cold white head mingled with her radiant hair, which warmed and
\par lighted it as though it were the light of Freedom shining on him.
\par 
\par "If you hear in my voice--I don't know that it is so, but I hope it
\par is--if you hear in my voice any resemblance to a voice that once was
\par sweet music in your ears, weep for it, weep for it! If you touch, in
\par touching my hair, anything that recalls a beloved head that lay on your
\par breast when you were young and free, weep for it, weep for it! If, when
\par I hint to you of a Home that is before us, where I will be true to you
\par with all my duty and with all my faithful service, I bring back the
\par remembrance of a Home long desolate, while your poor heart pined away,
\par weep for it, weep for it!"
\par 
\par She held him closer round the neck, and rocked him on her breast like a
\par child.
\par 
\par "If, when I tell you, dearest dear, that your agony is over, and that I
\par have come here to take you from it, and that we go to England to be at
\par peace and at rest, I cause you to think of your useful life laid waste,
\par and of our native France so wicked to you, weep for it, weep for it! And
\par if, when I shall tell you of my name, and of my father who is living,
\par and of my mother who is dead, you learn that I have to kneel to my
\par honoured father, and implore his pardon for having never for his sake
\par striven all day and lain awake and wept all night, because the love of
\par my poor mother hid his torture from me, weep for it, weep for it! Weep
\par for her, then, and for me! Good gentlemen, thank God! I feel his sacred
\par tears upon my face, and his sobs strike against my heart. O, see! Thank
\par God for us, thank God!"
\par 
\par He had sunk in her arms, and his face dropped on her breast: a sight so
\par touching, yet so terrible in the tremendous wrong and suffering which
\par had gone before it, that the two beholders covered their faces.
\par 
\par When the quiet of the garret had been long undisturbed, and his heaving
\par breast and shaken form had long yielded to the calm that must follow all
\par storms--emblem to humanity, of the rest and silence into which the storm
\par called Life must hush at last--they came forward to raise the father and
\par daughter from the ground. He had gradually dropped to the floor, and lay
\par there in a lethargy, worn out. She had nestled down with him, that his
\par head might lie upon her arm; and her hair drooping over him curtained
\par him from the light.
\par 
\par "If, without disturbing him," she said, raising her hand to Mr. Lorry as
\par he stooped over them, after repeated blowings of his nose, "all could be
\par arranged for our leaving Paris at once, so that, from the very door, he
\par could be taken away--"
\par 
\par "But, consider. Is he fit for the journey?" asked Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "More fit for that, I think, than to remain in this city, so dreadful to
\par him."
\par 
\par "It is true," said Defarge, who was kneeling to look on and hear. "More
\par than that; Monsieur Manette is, for all reasons, best out of France.
\par Say, shall I hire a carriage and post-horses?"
\par 
\par "That's business," said Mr. Lorry, resuming on the shortest notice his
\par methodical manners; "and if business is to be done, I had better do it."
\par 
\par "Then be so kind," urged Miss Manette, "as to leave us here. You see how
\par composed he has become, and you cannot be afraid to leave him with me
\par now. Why should you be? If you will lock the door to secure us from
\par interruption, I do not doubt that you will find him, when you come back,
\par as quiet as you leave him. In any case, I will take care of him until
\par you return, and then we will remove him straight."
\par 
\par Both Mr. Lorry and Defarge were rather disinclined to this course, and
\par in favour of one of them remaining. But, as there were not only carriage
\par and horses to be seen to, but travelling papers; and as time pressed,
\par for the day was drawing to an end, it came at last to their hastily
\par dividing the business that was necessary to be done, and hurrying away
\par to do it.
\par 
\par Then, as the darkness closed in, the daughter laid her head down on the
\par hard ground close at the father's side, and watched him. The darkness
\par deepened and deepened, and they both lay quiet, until a light gleamed
\par through the chinks in the wall.
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry and Monsieur Defarge had made all ready for the journey, and
\par had brought with them, besides travelling cloaks and wrappers, bread and
\par meat, wine, and hot coffee. Monsieur Defarge put this provender, and the
\par lamp he carried, on the shoemaker's bench (there was nothing else in the
\par garret but a pallet bed), and he and Mr. Lorry roused the captive, and
\par assisted him to his feet.
\par 
\par No human intelligence could have read the mysteries of his mind, in
\par the scared blank wonder of his face. Whether he knew what had happened,
\par whether he recollected what they had said to him, whether he knew that
\par he was free, were questions which no sagacity could have solved. They
\par tried speaking to him; but, he was so confused, and so very slow to
\par answer, that they took fright at his bewilderment, and agreed for
\par the time to tamper with him no more. He had a wild, lost manner of
\par occasionally clasping his head in his hands, that had not been seen
\par in him before; yet, he had some pleasure in the mere sound of his
\par daughter's voice, and invariably turned to it when she spoke.
\par 
\par In the submissive way of one long accustomed to obey under coercion, he
\par ate and drank what they gave him to eat and drink, and put on the cloak
\par and other wrappings, that they gave him to wear. He readily responded to
\par his daughter's drawing her arm through his, and took--and kept--her hand
\par in both his own.
\par 
\par They began to descend; Monsieur Defarge going first with the lamp, Mr.
\par Lorry closing the little procession. They had not traversed many steps
\par of the long main staircase when he stopped, and stared at the roof and
\par round at the walls.
\par 
\par "You remember the place, my father? You remember coming up here?"
\par 
\par "What did you say?"
\par 
\par But, before she could repeat the question, he murmured an answer as if
\par she had repeated it.
\par 
\par "Remember? No, I don't remember. It was so very long ago."
\par 
\par That he had no recollection whatever of his having been brought from his
\par prison to that house, was apparent to them. They heard him mutter,
\par "One Hundred and Five, North Tower;" and when he looked about him, it
\par evidently was for the strong fortress-walls which had long encompassed
\par him. On their reaching the courtyard he instinctively altered his
\par tread, as being in expectation of a drawbridge; and when there was
\par no drawbridge, and he saw the carriage waiting in the open street, he
\par dropped his daughter's hand and clasped his head again.
\par 
\par No crowd was about the door; no people were discernible at any of the
\par many windows; not even a chance passerby was in the street. An unnatural
\par silence and desertion reigned there. Only one soul was to be seen, and
\par that was Madame Defarge--who leaned against the door-post, knitting, and
\par saw nothing.
\par 
\par The prisoner had got into a coach, and his daughter had followed
\par him, when Mr. Lorry's feet were arrested on the step by his asking,
\par miserably, for his shoemaking tools and the unfinished shoes. Madame
\par Defarge immediately called to her husband that she would get them, and
\par went, knitting, out of the lamplight, through the courtyard. She quickly
\par brought them down and handed them in;--and immediately afterwards leaned
\par against the door-post, knitting, and saw nothing.
\par 
\par Defarge got upon the box, and gave the word "To the Barrier!" The
\par postilion cracked his whip, and they clattered away under the feeble
\par over-swinging lamps.
\par 
\par Under the over-swinging lamps--swinging ever brighter in the better
\par streets, and ever dimmer in the worse--and by lighted shops, gay crowds,
\par illuminated coffee-houses, and theatre-doors, to one of the city
\par gates. Soldiers with lanterns, at the guard-house there. "Your papers,
\par travellers!" "See here then, Monsieur the Officer," said Defarge,
\par getting down, and taking him gravely apart, "these are the papers of
\par monsieur inside, with the white head. They were consigned to me, with
\par him, at the--" He dropped his voice, there was a flutter among the
\par military lanterns, and one of them being handed into the coach by an arm
\par in uniform, the eyes connected with the arm looked, not an every day
\par or an every night look, at monsieur with the white head. "It is well.
\par Forward!" from the uniform. "Adieu!" from Defarge. And so, under a short
\par grove of feebler and feebler over-swinging lamps, out under the great
\par grove of stars.
\par 
\par Beneath that arch of unmoved and eternal lights; some, so remote from
\par this little earth that the learned tell us it is doubtful whether their
\par rays have even yet discovered it, as a point in space where anything
\par is suffered or done: the shadows of the night were broad and black.
\par All through the cold and restless interval, until dawn, they once more
\par whispered in the ears of Mr. Jarvis Lorry--sitting opposite the buried
\par man who had been dug out, and wondering what subtle powers were for ever
\par lost to him, and what were capable of restoration--the old inquiry:
\par 
\par "I hope you care to be recalled to life?"
\par 
\par And the old answer:
\par 
\par "I can't say."
\par 
\par 
\par The end of the first book.
\par 
