\par 
\par Book the Second--the Golden Thread
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par I. Five Years Later
\par 
\par 
\par Tellson's Bank by Temple Bar was an old-fashioned place, even in the
\par year one thousand seven hundred and eighty. It was very small, very
\par dark, very ugly, very incommodious. It was an old-fashioned place,
\par moreover, in the moral attribute that the partners in the House were
\par proud of its smallness, proud of its darkness, proud of its ugliness,
\par proud of its incommodiousness. They were even boastful of its eminence
\par in those particulars, and were fired by an express conviction that, if
\par it were less objectionable, it would be less respectable. This was
\par no passive belief, but an active weapon which they flashed at more
\par convenient places of business. Tellson's (they said) wanted
\par no elbow-room, Tellson's wanted no light, Tellson's wanted no
\par embellishment. Noakes and Co.'s might, or Snooks Brothers' might; but
\par Tellson's, thank Heaven--!
\par 
\par Any one of these partners would have disinherited his son on the
\par question of rebuilding Tellson's. In this respect the House was much
\par on a par with the Country; which did very often disinherit its sons for
\par suggesting improvements in laws and customs that had long been highly
\par objectionable, but were only the more respectable.
\par 
\par Thus it had come to pass, that Tellson's was the triumphant perfection
\par of inconvenience. After bursting open a door of idiotic obstinacy with
\par a weak rattle in its throat, you fell into Tellson's down two steps,
\par and came to your senses in a miserable little shop, with two little
\par counters, where the oldest of men made your cheque shake as if the
\par wind rustled it, while they examined the signature by the dingiest of
\par windows, which were always under a shower-bath of mud from Fleet-street,
\par and which were made the dingier by their own iron bars proper, and the
\par heavy shadow of Temple Bar. If your business necessitated your seeing
\par "the House," you were put into a species of Condemned Hold at the back,
\par where you meditated on a misspent life, until the House came with its
\par hands in its pockets, and you could hardly blink at it in the dismal
\par twilight. Your money came out of, or went into, wormy old wooden
\par drawers, particles of which flew up your nose and down your throat when
\par they were opened and shut. Your bank-notes had a musty odour, as if they
\par were fast decomposing into rags again. Your plate was stowed away among
\par the neighbouring cesspools, and evil communications corrupted its good
\par polish in a day or two. Your deeds got into extemporised strong-rooms
\par made of kitchens and sculleries, and fretted all the fat out of their
\par parchments into the banking-house air. Your lighter boxes of family
\par papers went up-stairs into a Barmecide room, that always had a great
\par dining-table in it and never had a dinner, and where, even in the year
\par one thousand seven hundred and eighty, the first letters written to you
\par by your old love, or by your little children, were but newly released
\par from the horror of being ogled through the windows, by the heads
\par exposed on Temple Bar with an insensate brutality and ferocity worthy of
\par Abyssinia or Ashantee.
\par 
\par But indeed, at that time, putting to death was a recipe much in vogue
\par with all trades and professions, and not least of all with Tellson's.
\par Death is Nature's remedy for all things, and why not Legislation's?
\par Accordingly, the forger was put to Death; the utterer of a bad note
\par was put to Death; the unlawful opener of a letter was put to Death; the
\par purloiner of forty shillings and sixpence was put to Death; the holder
\par of a horse at Tellson's door, who made off with it, was put to
\par Death; the coiner of a bad shilling was put to Death; the sounders of
\par three-fourths of the notes in the whole gamut of Crime, were put to
\par Death. Not that it did the least good in the way of prevention--it
\par might almost have been worth remarking that the fact was exactly the
\par reverse--but, it cleared off (as to this world) the trouble of each
\par particular case, and left nothing else connected with it to be looked
\par after. Thus, Tellson's, in its day, like greater places of business,
\par its contemporaries, had taken so many lives, that, if the heads laid
\par low before it had been ranged on Temple Bar instead of being privately
\par disposed of, they would probably have excluded what little light the
\par ground floor had, in a rather significant manner.
\par 
\par Cramped in all kinds of dim cupboards and hutches at Tellson's, the
\par oldest of men carried on the business gravely. When they took a young
\par man into Tellson's London house, they hid him somewhere till he was
\par old. They kept him in a dark place, like a cheese, until he had the full
\par Tellson flavour and blue-mould upon him. Then only was he permitted to
\par be seen, spectacularly poring over large books, and casting his breeches
\par and gaiters into the general weight of the establishment.
\par 
\par Outside Tellson's--never by any means in it, unless called in--was an
\par odd-job-man, an occasional porter and messenger, who served as the live
\par sign of the house. He was never absent during business hours, unless
\par upon an errand, and then he was represented by his son: a grisly urchin
\par of twelve, who was his express image. People understood that Tellson's,
\par in a stately way, tolerated the odd-job-man. The house had always
\par tolerated some person in that capacity, and time and tide had drifted
\par this person to the post. His surname was Cruncher, and on the youthful
\par occasion of his renouncing by proxy the works of darkness, in the
\par easterly parish church of Hounsditch, he had received the added
\par appellation of Jerry.
\par 
\par The scene was Mr. Cruncher's private lodging in Hanging-sword-alley,
\par Whitefriars: the time, half-past seven of the clock on a windy March
\par morning, Anno Domini seventeen hundred and eighty. (Mr. Cruncher himself
\par always spoke of the year of our Lord as Anna Dominoes: apparently under
\par the impression that the Christian era dated from the invention of a
\par popular game, by a lady who had bestowed her name upon it.)
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher's apartments were not in a savoury neighbourhood, and were
\par but two in number, even if a closet with a single pane of glass in it
\par might be counted as one. But they were very decently kept. Early as
\par it was, on the windy March morning, the room in which he lay abed was
\par already scrubbed throughout; and between the cups and saucers arranged
\par for breakfast, and the lumbering deal table, a very clean white cloth
\par was spread.
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher reposed under a patchwork counterpane, like a Harlequin
\par at home. At first, he slept heavily, but, by degrees, began to roll
\par and surge in bed, until he rose above the surface, with his spiky hair
\par looking as if it must tear the sheets to ribbons. At which juncture, he
\par exclaimed, in a voice of dire exasperation:
\par 
\par "Bust me, if she ain't at it agin!"
\par 
\par A woman of orderly and industrious appearance rose from her knees in a
\par corner, with sufficient haste and trepidation to show that she was the
\par person referred to.
\par 
\par "What!" said Mr. Cruncher, looking out of bed for a boot. "You're at it
\par agin, are you?"
\par 
\par After hailing the morn with this second salutation, he threw a boot at
\par the woman as a third. It was a very muddy boot, and may introduce the
\par odd circumstance connected with Mr. Cruncher's domestic economy, that,
\par whereas he often came home after banking hours with clean boots, he
\par often got up next morning to find the same boots covered with clay.
\par 
\par "What," said Mr. Cruncher, varying his apostrophe after missing his
\par mark--"what are you up to, Aggerawayter?"
\par 
\par "I was only saying my prayers."
\par 
\par "Saying your prayers! You're a nice woman! What do you mean by flopping
\par yourself down and praying agin me?"
\par 
\par "I was not praying against you; I was praying for you."
\par 
\par "You weren't. And if you were, I won't be took the liberty with. Here!
\par your mother's a nice woman, young Jerry, going a praying agin your
\par father's prosperity. You've got a dutiful mother, you have, my son.
\par You've got a religious mother, you have, my boy: going and flopping
\par herself down, and praying that the bread-and-butter may be snatched out
\par of the mouth of her only child."
\par 
\par Master Cruncher (who was in his shirt) took this very ill, and, turning
\par to his mother, strongly deprecated any praying away of his personal
\par board.
\par 
\par "And what do you suppose, you conceited female," said Mr. Cruncher, with
\par unconscious inconsistency, "that the worth of _your_ prayers may be?
\par Name the price that you put _your_ prayers at!"
\par 
\par "They only come from the heart, Jerry. They are worth no more than
\par that."
\par 
\par "Worth no more than that," repeated Mr. Cruncher. "They ain't worth
\par much, then. Whether or no, I won't be prayed agin, I tell you. I can't
\par afford it. I'm not a going to be made unlucky by _your_ sneaking. If
\par you must go flopping yourself down, flop in favour of your husband and
\par child, and not in opposition to 'em. If I had had any but a unnat'ral
\par wife, and this poor boy had had any but a unnat'ral mother, I might
\par have made some money last week instead of being counter-prayed and
\par countermined and religiously circumwented into the worst of luck.
\par B-u-u-ust me!" said Mr. Cruncher, who all this time had been putting
\par on his clothes, "if I ain't, what with piety and one blowed thing and
\par another, been choused this last week into as bad luck as ever a poor
\par devil of a honest tradesman met with! Young Jerry, dress yourself, my
\par boy, and while I clean my boots keep a eye upon your mother now and
\par then, and if you see any signs of more flopping, give me a call. For, I
\par tell you," here he addressed his wife once more, "I won't be gone agin,
\par in this manner. I am as rickety as a hackney-coach, I'm as sleepy as
\par laudanum, my lines is strained to that degree that I shouldn't know, if
\par it wasn't for the pain in 'em, which was me and which somebody else, yet
\par I'm none the better for it in pocket; and it's my suspicion that you've
\par been at it from morning to night to prevent me from being the better for
\par it in pocket, and I won't put up with it, Aggerawayter, and what do you
\par say now!"
\par 
\par Growling, in addition, such phrases as "Ah! yes! You're religious, too.
\par You wouldn't put yourself in opposition to the interests of your husband
\par and child, would you? Not you!" and throwing off other sarcastic sparks
\par from the whirling grindstone of his indignation, Mr. Cruncher betook
\par himself to his boot-cleaning and his general preparation for business.
\par In the meantime, his son, whose head was garnished with tenderer spikes,
\par and whose young eyes stood close by one another, as his father's did,
\par kept the required watch upon his mother. He greatly disturbed that poor
\par woman at intervals, by darting out of his sleeping closet, where he made
\par his toilet, with a suppressed cry of "You are going to flop, mother.
\par --Halloa, father!" and, after raising this fictitious alarm, darting in
\par again with an undutiful grin.
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher's temper was not at all improved when he came to his
\par breakfast. He resented Mrs. Cruncher's saying grace with particular
\par animosity.
\par 
\par "Now, Aggerawayter! What are you up to? At it again?"
\par 
\par His wife explained that she had merely "asked a blessing."
\par 
\par "Don't do it!" said Mr. Crunches looking about, as if he rather expected
\par to see the loaf disappear under the efficacy of his wife's petitions. "I
\par ain't a going to be blest out of house and home. I won't have my wittles
\par blest off my table. Keep still!"
\par 
\par Exceedingly red-eyed and grim, as if he had been up all night at a party
\par which had taken anything but a convivial turn, Jerry Cruncher worried
\par his breakfast rather than ate it, growling over it like any four-footed
\par inmate of a menagerie. Towards nine o'clock he smoothed his ruffled
\par aspect, and, presenting as respectable and business-like an exterior as
\par he could overlay his natural self with, issued forth to the occupation
\par of the day.
\par 
\par It could scarcely be called a trade, in spite of his favourite
\par description of himself as "a honest tradesman." His stock consisted of
\par a wooden stool, made out of a broken-backed chair cut down, which stool,
\par young Jerry, walking at his father's side, carried every morning to
\par beneath the banking-house window that was nearest Temple Bar: where,
\par with the addition of the first handful of straw that could be gleaned
\par from any passing vehicle to keep the cold and wet from the odd-job-man's
\par feet, it formed the encampment for the day. On this post of his, Mr.
\par Cruncher was as well known to Fleet-street and the Temple, as the Bar
\par itself,--and was almost as in-looking.
\par 
\par Encamped at a quarter before nine, in good time to touch his
\par three-cornered hat to the oldest of men as they passed in to Tellson's,
\par Jerry took up his station on this windy March morning, with young Jerry
\par standing by him, when not engaged in making forays through the Bar, to
\par inflict bodily and mental injuries of an acute description on passing
\par boys who were small enough for his amiable purpose. Father and son,
\par extremely like each other, looking silently on at the morning traffic
\par in Fleet-street, with their two heads as near to one another as the two
\par eyes of each were, bore a considerable resemblance to a pair of monkeys.
\par The resemblance was not lessened by the accidental circumstance, that
\par the mature Jerry bit and spat out straw, while the twinkling eyes of the
\par youthful Jerry were as restlessly watchful of him as of everything else
\par in Fleet-street.
\par 
\par The head of one of the regular indoor messengers attached to Tellson's
\par establishment was put through the door, and the word was given:
\par 
\par "Porter wanted!"
\par 
\par "Hooray, father! Here's an early job to begin with!"
\par 
\par Having thus given his parent God speed, young Jerry seated himself on
\par the stool, entered on his reversionary interest in the straw his father
\par had been chewing, and cogitated.
\par 
\par "Al-ways rusty! His fingers is al-ways rusty!" muttered young Jerry.
\par "Where does my father get all that iron rust from? He don't get no iron
\par rust here!"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par II. A Sight
\par 
\par 
\par "You know the Old Bailey well, no doubt?" said one of the oldest of
\par clerks to Jerry the messenger.
\par 
\par "Ye-es, sir," returned Jerry, in something of a dogged manner. "I _do_
\par know the Bailey."
\par 
\par "Just so. And you know Mr. Lorry."
\par 
\par "I know Mr. Lorry, sir, much better than I know the Bailey. Much
\par better," said Jerry, not unlike a reluctant witness at the establishment
\par in question, "than I, as a honest tradesman, wish to know the Bailey."
\par 
\par "Very well. Find the door where the witnesses go in, and show the
\par door-keeper this note for Mr. Lorry. He will then let you in."
\par 
\par "Into the court, sir?"
\par 
\par "Into the court."
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher's eyes seemed to get a little closer to one another, and to
\par interchange the inquiry, "What do you think of this?"
\par 
\par "Am I to wait in the court, sir?" he asked, as the result of that
\par conference.
\par 
\par "I am going to tell you. The door-keeper will pass the note to Mr.
\par Lorry, and do you make any gesture that will attract Mr. Lorry's
\par attention, and show him where you stand. Then what you have to do, is,
\par to remain there until he wants you."
\par 
\par "Is that all, sir?"
\par 
\par "That's all. He wishes to have a messenger at hand. This is to tell him
\par you are there."
\par 
\par As the ancient clerk deliberately folded and superscribed the note,
\par Mr. Cruncher, after surveying him in silence until he came to the
\par blotting-paper stage, remarked:
\par 
\par "I suppose they'll be trying Forgeries this morning?"
\par 
\par "Treason!"
\par 
\par "That's quartering," said Jerry. "Barbarous!"
\par 
\par "It is the law," remarked the ancient clerk, turning his surprised
\par spectacles upon him. "It is the law."
\par 
\par "It's hard in the law to spile a man, I think. It's hard enough to kill
\par him, but it's wery hard to spile him, sir."
\par 
\par "Not at all," retained the ancient clerk. "Speak well of the law. Take
\par care of your chest and voice, my good friend, and leave the law to take
\par care of itself. I give you that advice."
\par 
\par "It's the damp, sir, what settles on my chest and voice," said Jerry. "I
\par leave you to judge what a damp way of earning a living mine is."
\par 
\par "Well, well," said the old clerk; "we all have our various ways of
\par gaining a livelihood. Some of us have damp ways, and some of us have dry
\par ways. Here is the letter. Go along."
\par 
\par Jerry took the letter, and, remarking to himself with less internal
\par deference than he made an outward show of, "You are a lean old one,
\par too," made his bow, informed his son, in passing, of his destination,
\par and went his way.
\par 
\par They hanged at Tyburn, in those days, so the street outside Newgate had
\par not obtained one infamous notoriety that has since attached to it.
\par But, the gaol was a vile place, in which most kinds of debauchery and
\par villainy were practised, and where dire diseases were bred, that came
\par into court with the prisoners, and sometimes rushed straight from the
\par dock at my Lord Chief Justice himself, and pulled him off the bench. It
\par had more than once happened, that the Judge in the black cap pronounced
\par his own doom as certainly as the prisoner's, and even died before him.
\par For the rest, the Old Bailey was famous as a kind of deadly inn-yard,
\par from which pale travellers set out continually, in carts and coaches, on
\par a violent passage into the other world: traversing some two miles and a
\par half of public street and road, and shaming few good citizens, if any.
\par So powerful is use, and so desirable to be good use in the beginning. It
\par was famous, too, for the pillory, a wise old institution, that inflicted
\par a punishment of which no one could foresee the extent; also, for
\par the whipping-post, another dear old institution, very humanising and
\par softening to behold in action; also, for extensive transactions in
\par blood-money, another fragment of ancestral wisdom, systematically
\par leading to the most frightful mercenary crimes that could be committed
\par under Heaven. Altogether, the Old Bailey, at that date, was a choice
\par illustration of the precept, that "Whatever is is right;" an aphorism
\par that would be as final as it is lazy, did it not include the troublesome
\par consequence, that nothing that ever was, was wrong.
\par 
\par Making his way through the tainted crowd, dispersed up and down this
\par hideous scene of action, with the skill of a man accustomed to make his
\par way quietly, the messenger found out the door he sought, and handed in
\par his letter through a trap in it. For, people then paid to see the play
\par at the Old Bailey, just as they paid to see the play in Bedlam--only the
\par former entertainment was much the dearer. Therefore, all the Old Bailey
\par doors were well guarded--except, indeed, the social doors by which the
\par criminals got there, and those were always left wide open.
\par 
\par After some delay and demur, the door grudgingly turned on its hinges a
\par very little way, and allowed Mr. Jerry Cruncher to squeeze himself into
\par court.
\par 
\par "What's on?" he asked, in a whisper, of the man he found himself next
\par to.
\par 
\par "Nothing yet."
\par 
\par "What's coming on?"
\par 
\par "The Treason case."
\par 
\par "The quartering one, eh?"
\par 
\par "Ah!" returned the man, with a relish; "he'll be drawn on a hurdle to
\par be half hanged, and then he'll be taken down and sliced before his own
\par face, and then his inside will be taken out and burnt while he looks on,
\par and then his head will be chopped off, and he'll be cut into quarters.
\par That's the sentence."
\par 
\par "If he's found Guilty, you mean to say?" Jerry added, by way of proviso.
\par 
\par "Oh! they'll find him guilty," said the other. "Don't you be afraid of
\par that."
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher's attention was here diverted to the door-keeper, whom he
\par saw making his way to Mr. Lorry, with the note in his hand. Mr. Lorry
\par sat at a table, among the gentlemen in wigs: not far from a wigged
\par gentleman, the prisoner's counsel, who had a great bundle of papers
\par before him: and nearly opposite another wigged gentleman with his hands
\par in his pockets, whose whole attention, when Mr. Cruncher looked at him
\par then or afterwards, seemed to be concentrated on the ceiling of the
\par court. After some gruff coughing and rubbing of his chin and signing
\par with his hand, Jerry attracted the notice of Mr. Lorry, who had stood up
\par to look for him, and who quietly nodded and sat down again.
\par 
\par "What's _he_ got to do with the case?" asked the man he had spoken with.
\par 
\par "Blest if I know," said Jerry.
\par 
\par "What have _you_ got to do with it, then, if a person may inquire?"
\par 
\par "Blest if I know that either," said Jerry.
\par 
\par The entrance of the Judge, and a consequent great stir and settling
\par down in the court, stopped the dialogue. Presently, the dock became the
\par central point of interest. Two gaolers, who had been standing there,
\par went out, and the prisoner was brought in, and put to the bar.
\par 
\par Everybody present, except the one wigged gentleman who looked at the
\par ceiling, stared at him. All the human breath in the place, rolled
\par at him, like a sea, or a wind, or a fire. Eager faces strained round
\par pillars and corners, to get a sight of him; spectators in back rows
\par stood up, not to miss a hair of him; people on the floor of the court,
\par laid their hands on the shoulders of the people before them, to help
\par themselves, at anybody's cost, to a view of him--stood a-tiptoe, got
\par upon ledges, stood upon next to nothing, to see every inch of him.
\par Conspicuous among these latter, like an animated bit of the spiked wall
\par of Newgate, Jerry stood: aiming at the prisoner the beery breath of a
\par whet he had taken as he came along, and discharging it to mingle with
\par the waves of other beer, and gin, and tea, and coffee, and what not,
\par that flowed at him, and already broke upon the great windows behind him
\par in an impure mist and rain.
\par 
\par The object of all this staring and blaring, was a young man of about
\par five-and-twenty, well-grown and well-looking, with a sunburnt cheek and
\par a dark eye. His condition was that of a young gentleman. He was plainly
\par dressed in black, or very dark grey, and his hair, which was long and
\par dark, was gathered in a ribbon at the back of his neck; more to be out
\par of his way than for ornament. As an emotion of the mind will express
\par itself through any covering of the body, so the paleness which his
\par situation engendered came through the brown upon his cheek, showing the
\par soul to be stronger than the sun. He was otherwise quite self-possessed,
\par bowed to the Judge, and stood quiet.
\par 
\par The sort of interest with which this man was stared and breathed at,
\par was not a sort that elevated humanity. Had he stood in peril of a less
\par horrible sentence--had there been a chance of any one of its savage
\par details being spared--by just so much would he have lost in his
\par fascination. The form that was to be doomed to be so shamefully mangled,
\par was the sight; the immortal creature that was to be so butchered
\par and torn asunder, yielded the sensation. Whatever gloss the various
\par spectators put upon the interest, according to their several arts and
\par powers of self-deceit, the interest was, at the root of it, Ogreish.
\par 
\par Silence in the court! Charles Darnay had yesterday pleaded Not Guilty to
\par an indictment denouncing him (with infinite jingle and jangle) for that
\par he was a false traitor to our serene, illustrious, excellent, and so
\par forth, prince, our Lord the King, by reason of his having, on divers
\par occasions, and by divers means and ways, assisted Lewis, the French
\par King, in his wars against our said serene, illustrious, excellent, and
\par so forth; that was to say, by coming and going, between the dominions of
\par our said serene, illustrious, excellent, and so forth, and those of the
\par said French Lewis, and wickedly, falsely, traitorously, and otherwise
\par evil-adverbiously, revealing to the said French Lewis what forces our
\par said serene, illustrious, excellent, and so forth, had in preparation
\par to send to Canada and North America. This much, Jerry, with his head
\par becoming more and more spiky as the law terms bristled it, made out with
\par huge satisfaction, and so arrived circuitously at the understanding that
\par the aforesaid, and over and over again aforesaid, Charles Darnay, stood
\par there before him upon his trial; that the jury were swearing in; and
\par that Mr. Attorney-General was making ready to speak.
\par 
\par The accused, who was (and who knew he was) being mentally hanged,
\par beheaded, and quartered, by everybody there, neither flinched from
\par the situation, nor assumed any theatrical air in it. He was quiet and
\par attentive; watched the opening proceedings with a grave interest;
\par and stood with his hands resting on the slab of wood before him, so
\par composedly, that they had not displaced a leaf of the herbs with which
\par it was strewn. The court was all bestrewn with herbs and sprinkled with
\par vinegar, as a precaution against gaol air and gaol fever.
\par 
\par Over the prisoner's head there was a mirror, to throw the light down
\par upon him. Crowds of the wicked and the wretched had been reflected in
\par it, and had passed from its surface and this earth's together. Haunted
\par in a most ghastly manner that abominable place would have been, if the
\par glass could ever have rendered back its reflections, as the ocean is one
\par day to give up its dead. Some passing thought of the infamy and disgrace
\par for which it had been reserved, may have struck the prisoner's mind. Be
\par that as it may, a change in his position making him conscious of a bar
\par of light across his face, he looked up; and when he saw the glass his
\par face flushed, and his right hand pushed the herbs away.
\par 
\par It happened, that the action turned his face to that side of the court
\par which was on his left. About on a level with his eyes, there sat,
\par in that corner of the Judge's bench, two persons upon whom his look
\par immediately rested; so immediately, and so much to the changing of his
\par aspect, that all the eyes that were turned upon him, turned to them.
\par 
\par The spectators saw in the two figures, a young lady of little more than
\par twenty, and a gentleman who was evidently her father; a man of a very
\par remarkable appearance in respect of the absolute whiteness of his hair,
\par and a certain indescribable intensity of face: not of an active kind,
\par but pondering and self-communing. When this expression was upon him, he
\par looked as if he were old; but when it was stirred and broken up--as
\par it was now, in a moment, on his speaking to his daughter--he became a
\par handsome man, not past the prime of life.
\par 
\par His daughter had one of her hands drawn through his arm, as she sat by
\par him, and the other pressed upon it. She had drawn close to him, in her
\par dread of the scene, and in her pity for the prisoner. Her forehead had
\par been strikingly expressive of an engrossing terror and compassion
\par that saw nothing but the peril of the accused. This had been so very
\par noticeable, so very powerfully and naturally shown, that starers who
\par had had no pity for him were touched by her; and the whisper went about,
\par "Who are they?"
\par 
\par Jerry, the messenger, who had made his own observations, in his own
\par manner, and who had been sucking the rust off his fingers in his
\par absorption, stretched his neck to hear who they were. The crowd about
\par him had pressed and passed the inquiry on to the nearest attendant, and
\par from him it had been more slowly pressed and passed back; at last it got
\par to Jerry:
\par 
\par "Witnesses."
\par 
\par "For which side?"
\par 
\par "Against."
\par 
\par "Against what side?"
\par 
\par "The prisoner's."
\par 
\par The Judge, whose eyes had gone in the general direction, recalled them,
\par leaned back in his seat, and looked steadily at the man whose life was
\par in his hand, as Mr. Attorney-General rose to spin the rope, grind the
\par axe, and hammer the nails into the scaffold.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par III. A Disappointment
\par 
\par 
\par Mr. Attorney-General had to inform the jury, that the prisoner before
\par them, though young in years, was old in the treasonable practices which
\par claimed the forfeit of his life. That this correspondence with the
\par public enemy was not a correspondence of to-day, or of yesterday, or
\par even of last year, or of the year before. That, it was certain the
\par prisoner had, for longer than that, been in the habit of passing and
\par repassing between France and England, on secret business of which
\par he could give no honest account. That, if it were in the nature of
\par traitorous ways to thrive (which happily it never was), the real
\par wickedness and guilt of his business might have remained undiscovered.
\par That Providence, however, had put it into the heart of a person who
\par was beyond fear and beyond reproach, to ferret out the nature of the
\par prisoner's schemes, and, struck with horror, to disclose them to his
\par Majesty's Chief Secretary of State and most honourable Privy Council.
\par That, this patriot would be produced before them. That, his position and
\par attitude were, on the whole, sublime. That, he had been the prisoner's
\par friend, but, at once in an auspicious and an evil hour detecting his
\par infamy, had resolved to immolate the traitor he could no longer cherish
\par in his bosom, on the sacred altar of his country. That, if statues
\par were decreed in Britain, as in ancient Greece and Rome, to public
\par benefactors, this shining citizen would assuredly have had one. That, as
\par they were not so decreed, he probably would not have one. That, Virtue,
\par as had been observed by the poets (in many passages which he well
\par knew the jury would have, word for word, at the tips of their tongues;
\par whereat the jury's countenances displayed a guilty consciousness that
\par they knew nothing about the passages), was in a manner contagious; more
\par especially the bright virtue known as patriotism, or love of country.
\par That, the lofty example of this immaculate and unimpeachable witness
\par for the Crown, to refer to whom however unworthily was an honour, had
\par communicated itself to the prisoner's servant, and had engendered in him
\par a holy determination to examine his master's table-drawers and pockets,
\par and secrete his papers. That, he (Mr. Attorney-General) was prepared to
\par hear some disparagement attempted of this admirable servant; but that,
\par in a general way, he preferred him to his (Mr. Attorney-General's)
\par brothers and sisters, and honoured him more than his (Mr.
\par Attorney-General's) father and mother. That, he called with confidence
\par on the jury to come and do likewise. That, the evidence of these two
\par witnesses, coupled with the documents of their discovering that would be
\par produced, would show the prisoner to have been furnished with lists of
\par his Majesty's forces, and of their disposition and preparation, both by
\par sea and land, and would leave no doubt that he had habitually conveyed
\par such information to a hostile power. That, these lists could not be
\par proved to be in the prisoner's handwriting; but that it was all the
\par same; that, indeed, it was rather the better for the prosecution, as
\par showing the prisoner to be artful in his precautions. That, the proof
\par would go back five years, and would show the prisoner already engaged
\par in these pernicious missions, within a few weeks before the date of the
\par very first action fought between the British troops and the Americans.
\par That, for these reasons, the jury, being a loyal jury (as he knew they
\par were), and being a responsible jury (as _they_ knew they were), must
\par positively find the prisoner Guilty, and make an end of him, whether
\par they liked it or not. That, they never could lay their heads upon their
\par pillows; that, they never could tolerate the idea of their wives laying
\par their heads upon their pillows; that, they never could endure the notion
\par of their children laying their heads upon their pillows; in short, that
\par there never more could be, for them or theirs, any laying of heads upon
\par pillows at all, unless the prisoner's head was taken off. That head
