\par was a true Briton, and hoped there were many like him.
\par 
\par The blue-flies buzzed again, and Mr. Attorney-General called Mr. Jarvis
\par Lorry.
\par 
\par "Mr. Jarvis Lorry, are you a clerk in Tellson's bank?"
\par 
\par "I am."
\par 
\par "On a certain Friday night in November one thousand seven hundred and
\par seventy-five, did business occasion you to travel between London and
\par Dover by the mail?"
\par 
\par "It did."
\par 
\par "Were there any other passengers in the mail?"
\par 
\par "Two."
\par 
\par "Did they alight on the road in the course of the night?"
\par 
\par "They did."
\par 
\par "Mr. Lorry, look upon the prisoner. Was he one of those two passengers?"
\par 
\par "I cannot undertake to say that he was."
\par 
\par "Does he resemble either of these two passengers?"
\par 
\par "Both were so wrapped up, and the night was so dark, and we were all so
\par reserved, that I cannot undertake to say even that."
\par 
\par "Mr. Lorry, look again upon the prisoner. Supposing him wrapped up as
\par those two passengers were, is there anything in his bulk and stature to
\par render it unlikely that he was one of them?"
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par "You will not swear, Mr. Lorry, that he was not one of them?"
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par "So at least you say he may have been one of them?"
\par 
\par "Yes. Except that I remember them both to have been--like
\par myself--timorous of highwaymen, and the prisoner has not a timorous
\par air."
\par 
\par "Did you ever see a counterfeit of timidity, Mr. Lorry?"
\par 
\par "I certainly have seen that."
\par 
\par "Mr. Lorry, look once more upon the prisoner. Have you seen him, to your
\par certain knowledge, before?"
\par 
\par "I have."
\par 
\par "When?"
\par 
\par "I was returning from France a few days afterwards, and, at Calais, the
\par prisoner came on board the packet-ship in which I returned, and made the
\par voyage with me."
\par 
\par "At what hour did he come on board?"
\par 
\par "At a little after midnight."
\par 
\par "In the dead of the night. Was he the only passenger who came on board
\par at that untimely hour?"
\par 
\par "He happened to be the only one."
\par 
\par "Never mind about 'happening,' Mr. Lorry. He was the only passenger who
\par came on board in the dead of the night?"
\par 
\par "He was."
\par 
\par "Were you travelling alone, Mr. Lorry, or with any companion?"
\par 
\par "With two companions. A gentleman and lady. They are here."
\par 
\par "They are here. Had you any conversation with the prisoner?"
\par 
\par "Hardly any. The weather was stormy, and the passage long and rough, and
\par I lay on a sofa, almost from shore to shore."
\par 
\par "Miss Manette!"
\par 
\par The young lady, to whom all eyes had been turned before, and were now
\par turned again, stood up where she had sat. Her father rose with her, and
\par kept her hand drawn through his arm.
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, look upon the prisoner."
\par 
\par To be confronted with such pity, and such earnest youth and beauty, was
\par far more trying to the accused than to be confronted with all the crowd.
\par Standing, as it were, apart with her on the edge of his grave, not all
\par the staring curiosity that looked on, could, for the moment, nerve him
\par to remain quite still. His hurried right hand parcelled out the herbs
\par before him into imaginary beds of flowers in a garden; and his efforts
\par to control and steady his breathing shook the lips from which the colour
\par rushed to his heart. The buzz of the great flies was loud again.
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, have you seen the prisoner before?"
\par 
\par "Yes, sir."
\par 
\par "Where?"
\par 
\par "On board of the packet-ship just now referred to, sir, and on the same
\par occasion."
\par 
\par "You are the young lady just now referred to?"
\par 
\par "O! most unhappily, I am!"
\par 
\par The plaintive tone of her compassion merged into the less musical voice
\par of the Judge, as he said something fiercely: "Answer the questions put
\par to you, and make no remark upon them."
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, had you any conversation with the prisoner on that
\par passage across the Channel?"
\par 
\par "Yes, sir."
\par 
\par "Recall it."
\par 
\par In the midst of a profound stillness, she faintly began: "When the
\par gentleman came on board--"
\par 
\par "Do you mean the prisoner?" inquired the Judge, knitting his brows.
\par 
\par "Yes, my Lord."
\par 
\par "Then say the prisoner."
\par 
\par "When the prisoner came on board, he noticed that my father," turning
\par her eyes lovingly to him as he stood beside her, "was much fatigued
\par and in a very weak state of health. My father was so reduced that I was
\par afraid to take him out of the air, and I had made a bed for him on the
\par deck near the cabin steps, and I sat on the deck at his side to take
\par care of him. There were no other passengers that night, but we four.
\par The prisoner was so good as to beg permission to advise me how I could
\par shelter my father from the wind and weather, better than I had done. I
\par had not known how to do it well, not understanding how the wind would
\par set when we were out of the harbour. He did it for me. He expressed
\par great gentleness and kindness for my father's state, and I am sure he
\par felt it. That was the manner of our beginning to speak together."
\par 
\par "Let me interrupt you for a moment. Had he come on board alone?"
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par "How many were with him?"
\par 
\par "Two French gentlemen."
\par 
\par "Had they conferred together?"
\par 
\par "They had conferred together until the last moment, when it was
\par necessary for the French gentlemen to be landed in their boat."
\par 
\par "Had any papers been handed about among them, similar to these lists?"
\par 
\par "Some papers had been handed about among them, but I don't know what
\par papers."
\par 
\par "Like these in shape and size?"
\par 
\par "Possibly, but indeed I don't know, although they stood whispering very
\par near to me: because they stood at the top of the cabin steps to have the
\par light of the lamp that was hanging there; it was a dull lamp, and they
\par spoke very low, and I did not hear what they said, and saw only that
\par they looked at papers."
\par 
\par "Now, to the prisoner's conversation, Miss Manette."
\par 
\par "The prisoner was as open in his confidence with me--which arose out
\par of my helpless situation--as he was kind, and good, and useful to my
\par father. I hope," bursting into tears, "I may not repay him by doing him
\par harm to-day."
\par 
\par Buzzing from the blue-flies.
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, if the prisoner does not perfectly understand that
\par you give the evidence which it is your duty to give--which you must
\par give--and which you cannot escape from giving--with great unwillingness,
\par he is the only person present in that condition. Please to go on."
\par 
\par "He told me that he was travelling on business of a delicate and
\par difficult nature, which might get people into trouble, and that he was
\par therefore travelling under an assumed name. He said that this business
\par had, within a few days, taken him to France, and might, at intervals,
\par take him backwards and forwards between France and England for a long
\par time to come."
\par 
\par "Did he say anything about America, Miss Manette? Be particular."
\par 
\par "He tried to explain to me how that quarrel had arisen, and he said
\par that, so far as he could judge, it was a wrong and foolish one on
\par England's part. He added, in a jesting way, that perhaps George
\par Washington might gain almost as great a name in history as George the
\par Third. But there was no harm in his way of saying this: it was said
\par laughingly, and to beguile the time."
\par 
\par Any strongly marked expression of face on the part of a chief actor in
\par a scene of great interest to whom many eyes are directed, will be
\par unconsciously imitated by the spectators. Her forehead was painfully
\par anxious and intent as she gave this evidence, and, in the pauses when
\par she stopped for the Judge to write it down, watched its effect upon
\par the counsel for and against. Among the lookers-on there was the same
\par expression in all quarters of the court; insomuch, that a great majority
\par of the foreheads there, might have been mirrors reflecting the witness,
\par when the Judge looked up from his notes to glare at that tremendous
\par heresy about George Washington.
\par 
\par Mr. Attorney-General now signified to my Lord, that he deemed it
\par necessary, as a matter of precaution and form, to call the young lady's
\par father, Doctor Manette. Who was called accordingly.
\par 
\par "Doctor Manette, look upon the prisoner. Have you ever seen him before?"
\par 
\par "Once. When he called at my lodgings in London. Some three years, or
\par three years and a half ago."
\par 
\par "Can you identify him as your fellow-passenger on board the packet, or
\par speak to his conversation with your daughter?"
\par 
\par "Sir, I can do neither."
\par 
\par "Is there any particular and special reason for your being unable to do
\par either?"
\par 
\par He answered, in a low voice, "There is."
\par 
\par "Has it been your misfortune to undergo a long imprisonment, without
\par trial, or even accusation, in your native country, Doctor Manette?"
\par 
\par He answered, in a tone that went to every heart, "A long imprisonment."
\par 
\par "Were you newly released on the occasion in question?"
\par 
\par "They tell me so."
\par 
\par "Have you no remembrance of the occasion?"
\par 
\par "None. My mind is a blank, from some time--I cannot even say what
\par time--when I employed myself, in my captivity, in making shoes, to the
\par time when I found myself living in London with my dear daughter
\par here. She had become familiar to me, when a gracious God restored
\par my faculties; but, I am quite unable even to say how she had become
\par familiar. I have no remembrance of the process."
\par 
\par Mr. Attorney-General sat down, and the father and daughter sat down
\par together.
\par 
\par A singular circumstance then arose in the case. The object in hand being
\par to show that the prisoner went down, with some fellow-plotter untracked,
\par in the Dover mail on that Friday night in November five years ago, and
\par got out of the mail in the night, as a blind, at a place where he did
\par not remain, but from which he travelled back some dozen miles or more,
\par to a garrison and dockyard, and there collected information; a witness
\par was called to identify him as having been at the precise time required,
\par in the coffee-room of an hotel in that garrison-and-dockyard town,
\par waiting for another person. The prisoner's counsel was cross-examining
\par this witness with no result, except that he had never seen the prisoner
\par on any other occasion, when the wigged gentleman who had all this time
\par been looking at the ceiling of the court, wrote a word or two on a
\par little piece of paper, screwed it up, and tossed it to him. Opening
\par this piece of paper in the next pause, the counsel looked with great
\par attention and curiosity at the prisoner.
\par 
\par "You say again you are quite sure that it was the prisoner?"
\par 
\par The witness was quite sure.
\par 
\par "Did you ever see anybody very like the prisoner?"
\par 
\par Not so like (the witness said) as that he could be mistaken.
\par 
\par "Look well upon that gentleman, my learned friend there," pointing
\par to him who had tossed the paper over, "and then look well upon the
\par prisoner. How say you? Are they very like each other?"
\par 
\par Allowing for my learned friend's appearance being careless and slovenly
\par if not debauched, they were sufficiently like each other to surprise,
\par not only the witness, but everybody present, when they were thus brought
\par into comparison. My Lord being prayed to bid my learned friend lay aside
\par his wig, and giving no very gracious consent, the likeness became
\par much more remarkable. My Lord inquired of Mr. Stryver (the prisoner's
\par counsel), whether they were next to try Mr. Carton (name of my learned
\par friend) for treason? But, Mr. Stryver replied to my Lord, no; but he
\par would ask the witness to tell him whether what happened once, might
\par happen twice; whether he would have been so confident if he had seen
\par this illustration of his rashness sooner, whether he would be so
\par confident, having seen it; and more. The upshot of which, was, to smash
\par this witness like a crockery vessel, and shiver his part of the case to
\par useless lumber.
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher had by this time taken quite a lunch of rust off his
\par fingers in his following of the evidence. He had now to attend while Mr.
\par Stryver fitted the prisoner's case on the jury, like a compact suit
\par of clothes; showing them how the patriot, Barsad, was a hired spy and
\par traitor, an unblushing trafficker in blood, and one of the greatest
\par scoundrels upon earth since accursed Judas--which he certainly did look
\par rather like. How the virtuous servant, Cly, was his friend and partner,
\par and was worthy to be; how the watchful eyes of those forgers and false
\par swearers had rested on the prisoner as a victim, because some family
\par affairs in France, he being of French extraction, did require his making
\par those passages across the Channel--though what those affairs were, a
\par consideration for others who were near and dear to him, forbade him,
\par even for his life, to disclose. How the evidence that had been warped
\par and wrested from the young lady, whose anguish in giving it they
\par had witnessed, came to nothing, involving the mere little innocent
\par gallantries and politenesses likely to pass between any young gentleman
\par and young lady so thrown together;--with the exception of that
\par reference to George Washington, which was altogether too extravagant and
\par impossible to be regarded in any other light than as a monstrous joke.
\par How it would be a weakness in the government to break down in this
\par attempt to practise for popularity on the lowest national antipathies
\par and fears, and therefore Mr. Attorney-General had made the most of it;
\par how, nevertheless, it rested upon nothing, save that vile and infamous
\par character of evidence too often disfiguring such cases, and of which the
\par State Trials of this country were full. But, there my Lord interposed
\par (with as grave a face as if it had not been true), saying that he could
\par not sit upon that Bench and suffer those allusions.
\par 
\par Mr. Stryver then called his few witnesses, and Mr. Cruncher had next to
\par attend while Mr. Attorney-General turned the whole suit of clothes Mr.
\par Stryver had fitted on the jury, inside out; showing how Barsad and
\par Cly were even a hundred times better than he had thought them, and the
\par prisoner a hundred times worse. Lastly, came my Lord himself, turning
\par the suit of clothes, now inside out, now outside in, but on the whole
\par decidedly trimming and shaping them into grave-clothes for the prisoner.
\par 
\par And now, the jury turned to consider, and the great flies swarmed again.
\par 
\par Mr. Carton, who had so long sat looking at the ceiling of the court,
\par changed neither his place nor his attitude, even in this excitement.
\par While his teamed friend, Mr. Stryver, massing his papers before him,
\par whispered with those who sat near, and from time to time glanced
\par anxiously at the jury; while all the spectators moved more or less, and
\par grouped themselves anew; while even my Lord himself arose from his seat,
\par and slowly paced up and down his platform, not unattended by a suspicion
\par in the minds of the audience that his state was feverish; this one man
\par sat leaning back, with his torn gown half off him, his untidy wig put
\par on just as it had happened to light on his head after its removal, his
\par hands in his pockets, and his eyes on the ceiling as they had been all
\par day. Something especially reckless in his demeanour, not only gave him
