\par 
\par Mr. Lorry reddened as if he were conscious of having debated the point
\par in his mind, and Mr. Carton made his way to the outside of the bar.
\par The way out of court lay in that direction, and Jerry followed him, all
\par eyes, ears, and spikes.
\par 
\par "Mr. Darnay!"
\par 
\par The prisoner came forward directly.
\par 
\par "You will naturally be anxious to hear of the witness, Miss Manette. She
\par will do very well. You have seen the worst of her agitation."
\par 
\par "I am deeply sorry to have been the cause of it. Could you tell her so
\par for me, with my fervent acknowledgments?"
\par 
\par "Yes, I could. I will, if you ask it."
\par 
\par Mr. Carton's manner was so careless as to be almost insolent. He stood,
\par half turned from the prisoner, lounging with his elbow against the bar.
\par 
\par "I do ask it. Accept my cordial thanks."
\par 
\par "What," said Carton, still only half turned towards him, "do you expect,
\par Mr. Darnay?"
\par 
\par "The worst."
\par 
\par "It's the wisest thing to expect, and the likeliest. But I think their
\par withdrawing is in your favour."
\par 
\par Loitering on the way out of court not being allowed, Jerry heard no
\par more: but left them--so like each other in feature, so unlike each other
\par in manner--standing side by side, both reflected in the glass above
\par them.
\par 
\par An hour and a half limped heavily away in the thief-and-rascal crowded
\par passages below, even though assisted off with mutton pies and ale.
\par The hoarse messenger, uncomfortably seated on a form after taking that
\par refection, had dropped into a doze, when a loud murmur and a rapid tide
\par of people setting up the stairs that led to the court, carried him along
\par with them.
\par 
\par "Jerry! Jerry!" Mr. Lorry was already calling at the door when he got
\par there.
\par 
\par "Here, sir! It's a fight to get back again. Here I am, sir!"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry handed him a paper through the throng. "Quick! Have you got
\par it?"
\par 
\par "Yes, sir."
\par 
\par Hastily written on the paper was the word "ACQUITTED."
\par 
\par "If you had sent the message, 'Recalled to Life,' again," muttered
\par Jerry, as he turned, "I should have known what you meant, this time."
\par 
\par He had no opportunity of saying, or so much as thinking, anything else,
\par until he was clear of the Old Bailey; for, the crowd came pouring out
\par with a vehemence that nearly took him off his legs, and a loud buzz
\par swept into the street as if the baffled blue-flies were dispersing in
\par search of other carrion.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par IV. Congratulatory
\par 
\par 
\par From the dimly-lighted passages of the court, the last sediment of the
\par human stew that had been boiling there all day, was straining off, when
\par Doctor Manette, Lucie Manette, his daughter, Mr. Lorry, the solicitor
\par for the defence, and its counsel, Mr. Stryver, stood gathered round Mr.
\par Charles Darnay--just released--congratulating him on his escape from
\par death.
\par 
\par It would have been difficult by a far brighter light, to recognise
\par in Doctor Manette, intellectual of face and upright of bearing, the
\par shoemaker of the garret in Paris. Yet, no one could have looked at him
\par twice, without looking again: even though the opportunity of observation
\par had not extended to the mournful cadence of his low grave voice, and
\par to the abstraction that overclouded him fitfully, without any apparent
\par reason. While one external cause, and that a reference to his long
\par lingering agony, would always--as on the trial--evoke this condition
\par from the depths of his soul, it was also in its nature to arise of
\par itself, and to draw a gloom over him, as incomprehensible to those
\par unacquainted with his story as if they had seen the shadow of the actual
\par Bastille thrown upon him by a summer sun, when the substance was three
\par hundred miles away.
\par 
\par Only his daughter had the power of charming this black brooding from
\par his mind. She was the golden thread that united him to a Past beyond his
\par misery, and to a Present beyond his misery: and the sound of her voice,
\par the light of her face, the touch of her hand, had a strong beneficial
\par influence with him almost always. Not absolutely always, for she could
\par recall some occasions on which her power had failed; but they were few
\par and slight, and she believed them over.
\par 
\par Mr. Darnay had kissed her hand fervently and gratefully, and had turned
\par to Mr. Stryver, whom he warmly thanked. Mr. Stryver, a man of little
\par more than thirty, but looking twenty years older than he was, stout,
\par loud, red, bluff, and free from any drawback of delicacy, had a pushing
\par way of shouldering himself (morally and physically) into companies and
\par conversations, that argued well for his shouldering his way up in life.
\par 
\par He still had his wig and gown on, and he said, squaring himself at his
\par late client to that degree that he squeezed the innocent Mr. Lorry clean
\par out of the group: "I am glad to have brought you off with honour, Mr.
\par Darnay. It was an infamous prosecution, grossly infamous; but not the
\par less likely to succeed on that account."
\par 
\par "You have laid me under an obligation to you for life--in two senses,"
\par said his late client, taking his hand.
\par 
\par "I have done my best for you, Mr. Darnay; and my best is as good as
\par another man's, I believe."
\par 
\par It clearly being incumbent on some one to say, "Much better," Mr. Lorry
\par said it; perhaps not quite disinterestedly, but with the interested
\par object of squeezing himself back again.
\par 
\par "You think so?" said Mr. Stryver. "Well! you have been present all day,
\par and you ought to know. You are a man of business, too."
\par 
\par "And as such," quoth Mr. Lorry, whom the counsel learned in the law had
\par now shouldered back into the group, just as he had previously shouldered
\par him out of it--"as such I will appeal to Doctor Manette, to break up
\par this conference and order us all to our homes. Miss Lucie looks ill, Mr.
\par Darnay has had a terrible day, we are worn out."
\par 
\par "Speak for yourself, Mr. Lorry," said Stryver; "I have a night's work to
\par do yet. Speak for yourself."
\par 
\par "I speak for myself," answered Mr. Lorry, "and for Mr. Darnay, and for
\par Miss Lucie, and--Miss Lucie, do you not think I may speak for us all?"
\par He asked her the question pointedly, and with a glance at her father.
\par 
\par His face had become frozen, as it were, in a very curious look at
\par Darnay: an intent look, deepening into a frown of dislike and distrust,
\par not even unmixed with fear. With this strange expression on him his
\par thoughts had wandered away.
\par 
\par "My father," said Lucie, softly laying her hand on his.
\par 
\par He slowly shook the shadow off, and turned to her.
\par 
\par "Shall we go home, my father?"
\par 
\par With a long breath, he answered "Yes."
\par 
\par The friends of the acquitted prisoner had dispersed, under the
\par impression--which he himself had originated--that he would not be
\par released that night. The lights were nearly all extinguished in the
\par passages, the iron gates were being closed with a jar and a rattle,
\par and the dismal place was deserted until to-morrow morning's interest of
\par gallows, pillory, whipping-post, and branding-iron, should repeople it.
\par Walking between her father and Mr. Darnay, Lucie Manette passed into
\par the open air. A hackney-coach was called, and the father and daughter
\par departed in it.
\par 
\par Mr. Stryver had left them in the passages, to shoulder his way back
\par to the robing-room. Another person, who had not joined the group, or
\par interchanged a word with any one of them, but who had been leaning
\par against the wall where its shadow was darkest, had silently strolled
\par out after the rest, and had looked on until the coach drove away. He now
\par stepped up to where Mr. Lorry and Mr. Darnay stood upon the pavement.
\par 
\par "So, Mr. Lorry! Men of business may speak to Mr. Darnay now?"
\par 
\par Nobody had made any acknowledgment of Mr. Carton's part in the day's
\par proceedings; nobody had known of it. He was unrobed, and was none the
\par better for it in appearance.
\par 
\par "If you knew what a conflict goes on in the business mind, when the
\par business mind is divided between good-natured impulse and business
\par appearances, you would be amused, Mr. Darnay."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry reddened, and said, warmly, "You have mentioned that before,
\par sir. We men of business, who serve a House, are not our own masters. We
\par have to think of the House more than ourselves."
\par 
\par "_I_ know, _I_ know," rejoined Mr. Carton, carelessly. "Don't be
\par nettled, Mr. Lorry. You are as good as another, I have no doubt: better,
\par I dare say."
\par 
\par "And indeed, sir," pursued Mr. Lorry, not minding him, "I really don't
\par know what you have to do with the matter. If you'll excuse me, as very
\par much your elder, for saying so, I really don't know that it is your
\par business."
\par 
\par "Business! Bless you, _I_ have no business," said Mr. Carton.
\par 
\par "It is a pity you have not, sir."
\par 
\par "I think so, too."
\par 
\par "If you had," pursued Mr. Lorry, "perhaps you would attend to it."
\par 
\par "Lord love you, no!--I shouldn't," said Mr. Carton.
\par 
\par "Well, sir!" cried Mr. Lorry, thoroughly heated by his indifference,
\par "business is a very good thing, and a very respectable thing. And, sir,
\par if business imposes its restraints and its silences and impediments, Mr.
\par Darnay as a young gentleman of generosity knows how to make allowance
\par for that circumstance. Mr. Darnay, good night, God bless you, sir!
\par I hope you have been this day preserved for a prosperous and happy
\par life.--Chair there!"
\par 
\par Perhaps a little angry with himself, as well as with the barrister, Mr.
\par Lorry bustled into the chair, and was carried off to Tellson's. Carton,
\par who smelt of port wine, and did not appear to be quite sober, laughed
\par then, and turned to Darnay:
\par 
\par "This is a strange chance that throws you and me together. This must
\par be a strange night to you, standing alone here with your counterpart on
\par these street stones?"
\par 
\par "I hardly seem yet," returned Charles Darnay, "to belong to this world
\par again."
\par 
\par "I don't wonder at it; it's not so long since you were pretty far
\par advanced on your way to another. You speak faintly."
\par 
\par "I begin to think I _am_ faint."
\par 
\par "Then why the devil don't you dine? I dined, myself, while those
\par numskulls were deliberating which world you should belong to--this, or
\par some other. Let me show you the nearest tavern to dine well at."
\par 
\par Drawing his arm through his own, he took him down Ludgate-hill to
\par Fleet-street, and so, up a covered way, into a tavern. Here, they were
\par shown into a little room, where Charles Darnay was soon recruiting
\par his strength with a good plain dinner and good wine: while Carton sat
\par opposite to him at the same table, with his separate bottle of port
\par before him, and his fully half-insolent manner upon him.
\par 
\par "Do you feel, yet, that you belong to this terrestrial scheme again, Mr.
\par Darnay?"
\par 
\par "I am frightfully confused regarding time and place; but I am so far
\par mended as to feel that."
\par 
\par "It must be an immense satisfaction!"
\par 
\par He said it bitterly, and filled up his glass again: which was a large
\par one.
\par 
\par "As to me, the greatest desire I have, is to forget that I belong to it.
\par It has no good in it for me--except wine like this--nor I for it. So we
\par are not much alike in that particular. Indeed, I begin to think we are
\par not much alike in any particular, you and I."
\par 
\par Confused by the emotion of the day, and feeling his being there with
\par this Double of coarse deportment, to be like a dream, Charles Darnay was
\par at a loss how to answer; finally, answered not at all.
\par 
\par "Now your dinner is done," Carton presently said, "why don't you call a
\par health, Mr. Darnay; why don't you give your toast?"
\par 
\par "What health? What toast?"
\par 
\par "Why, it's on the tip of your tongue. It ought to be, it must be, I'll
\par swear it's there."
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, then!"
\par 
\par "Miss Manette, then!"
\par 
\par Looking his companion full in the face while he drank the toast, Carton
\par flung his glass over his shoulder against the wall, where it shivered to
\par pieces; then, rang the bell, and ordered in another.
\par 
\par "That's a fair young lady to hand to a coach in the dark, Mr. Darnay!"
\par he said, filling his new goblet.
\par 
\par A slight frown and a laconic "Yes," were the answer.
\par 
\par "That's a fair young lady to be pitied by and wept for by! How does it
\par feel? Is it worth being tried for one's life, to be the object of such
\par sympathy and compassion, Mr. Darnay?"
\par 
\par Again Darnay answered not a word.
\par 
\par "She was mightily pleased to have your message, when I gave it her. Not
\par that she showed she was pleased, but I suppose she was."
\par 
\par The allusion served as a timely reminder to Darnay that this
\par disagreeable companion had, of his own free will, assisted him in the
\par strait of the day. He turned the dialogue to that point, and thanked him
\par for it.
\par 
\par "I neither want any thanks, nor merit any," was the careless rejoinder.
\par "It was nothing to do, in the first place; and I don't know why I did
\par it, in the second. Mr. Darnay, let me ask you a question."
\par 
\par "Willingly, and a small return for your good offices."
\par 
\par "Do you think I particularly like you?"
\par 
\par "Really, Mr. Carton," returned the other, oddly disconcerted, "I have
\par not asked myself the question."
\par 
\par "But ask yourself the question now."
\par 
\par "You have acted as if you do; but I don't think you do."
\par 
\par "_I_ don't think I do," said Carton. "I begin to have a very good
\par opinion of your understanding."
\par 
\par "Nevertheless," pursued Darnay, rising to ring the bell, "there is
\par nothing in that, I hope, to prevent my calling the reckoning, and our
\par parting without ill-blood on either side."
\par 
\par Carton rejoining, "Nothing in life!" Darnay rang. "Do you call the whole
\par reckoning?" said Carton. On his answering in the affirmative, "Then
\par bring me another pint of this same wine, drawer, and come and wake me at
\par ten."
\par 
\par The bill being paid, Charles Darnay rose and wished him good night.
\par Without returning the wish, Carton rose too, with something of a threat
\par of defiance in his manner, and said, "A last word, Mr. Darnay: you think
\par I am drunk?"
\par 
\par "I think you have been drinking, Mr. Carton."
\par 
\par "Think? You know I have been drinking."
\par 
\par "Since I must say so, I know it."
\par 
\par "Then you shall likewise know why. I am a disappointed drudge, sir. I
\par care for no man on earth, and no man on earth cares for me."
\par 
\par "Much to be regretted. You might have used your talents better."
\par 
\par "May be so, Mr. Darnay; may be not. Don't let your sober face elate you,
\par however; you don't know what it may come to. Good night!"
\par 
\par When he was left alone, this strange being took up a candle, went to a
\par glass that hung against the wall, and surveyed himself minutely in it.
\par 
\par "Do you particularly like the man?" he muttered, at his own image; "why
\par should you particularly like a man who resembles you? There is nothing
\par in you to like; you know that. Ah, confound you! What a change you have
\par made in yourself! A good reason for taking to a man, that he shows you
\par what you have fallen away from, and what you might have been! Change
\par places with him, and would you have been looked at by those blue eyes as
\par he was, and commiserated by that agitated face as he was? Come on, and
\par have it out in plain words! You hate the fellow."
\par 
\par He resorted to his pint of wine for consolation, drank it all in a few
\par minutes, and fell asleep on his arms, with his hair straggling over the
\par table, and a long winding-sheet in the candle dripping down upon him.
