\par 
\par 
\par V. The Jackal
\par 
\par 
\par Those were drinking days, and most men drank hard. So very great is
\par the improvement Time has brought about in such habits, that a moderate
\par statement of the quantity of wine and punch which one man would swallow
\par in the course of a night, without any detriment to his reputation as a
\par perfect gentleman, would seem, in these days, a ridiculous exaggeration.
\par The learned profession of the law was certainly not behind any other
\par learned profession in its Bacchanalian propensities; neither was Mr.
\par Stryver, already fast shouldering his way to a large and lucrative
\par practice, behind his compeers in this particular, any more than in the
\par drier parts of the legal race.
\par 
\par A favourite at the Old Bailey, and eke at the Sessions, Mr. Stryver had
\par begun cautiously to hew away the lower staves of the ladder on which
\par he mounted. Sessions and Old Bailey had now to summon their favourite,
\par specially, to their longing arms; and shouldering itself towards the
\par visage of the Lord Chief Justice in the Court of King's Bench, the
\par florid countenance of Mr. Stryver might be daily seen, bursting out of
\par the bed of wigs, like a great sunflower pushing its way at the sun from
\par among a rank garden-full of flaring companions.
\par 
\par It had once been noted at the Bar, that while Mr. Stryver was a glib
\par man, and an unscrupulous, and a ready, and a bold, he had not that
\par faculty of extracting the essence from a heap of statements, which is
\par among the most striking and necessary of the advocate's accomplishments.
\par But, a remarkable improvement came upon him as to this. The more
\par business he got, the greater his power seemed to grow of getting at its
\par pith and marrow; and however late at night he sat carousing with Sydney
\par Carton, he always had his points at his fingers' ends in the morning.
\par 
\par Sydney Carton, idlest and most unpromising of men, was Stryver's great
\par ally. What the two drank together, between Hilary Term and Michaelmas,
\par might have floated a king's ship. Stryver never had a case in hand,
\par anywhere, but Carton was there, with his hands in his pockets, staring
\par at the ceiling of the court; they went the same Circuit, and even there
\par they prolonged their usual orgies late into the night, and Carton was
\par rumoured to be seen at broad day, going home stealthily and unsteadily
\par to his lodgings, like a dissipated cat. At last, it began to get about,
\par among such as were interested in the matter, that although Sydney Carton
\par would never be a lion, he was an amazingly good jackal, and that he
\par rendered suit and service to Stryver in that humble capacity.
\par 
\par "Ten o'clock, sir," said the man at the tavern, whom he had charged to
\par wake him--"ten o'clock, sir."
\par 
\par "_What's_ the matter?"
\par 
\par "Ten o'clock, sir."
\par 
\par "What do you mean? Ten o'clock at night?"
\par 
\par "Yes, sir. Your honour told me to call you."
\par 
\par "Oh! I remember. Very well, very well."
\par 
\par After a few dull efforts to get to sleep again, which the man
\par dexterously combated by stirring the fire continuously for five minutes,
\par he got up, tossed his hat on, and walked out. He turned into the Temple,
\par and, having revived himself by twice pacing the pavements of King's
\par Bench-walk and Paper-buildings, turned into the Stryver chambers.
\par 
\par The Stryver clerk, who never assisted at these conferences, had gone
\par home, and the Stryver principal opened the door. He had his slippers on,
\par and a loose bed-gown, and his throat was bare for his greater ease. He
\par had that rather wild, strained, seared marking about the eyes, which
\par may be observed in all free livers of his class, from the portrait of
\par Jeffries downward, and which can be traced, under various disguises of
\par Art, through the portraits of every Drinking Age.
\par 
\par "You are a little late, Memory," said Stryver.
\par 
\par "About the usual time; it may be a quarter of an hour later."
\par 
\par They went into a dingy room lined with books and littered with papers,
\par where there was a blazing fire. A kettle steamed upon the hob, and in
\par the midst of the wreck of papers a table shone, with plenty of wine upon
\par it, and brandy, and rum, and sugar, and lemons.
\par 
\par "You have had your bottle, I perceive, Sydney."
\par 
\par "Two to-night, I think. I have been dining with the day's client; or
\par seeing him dine--it's all one!"
\par 
\par "That was a rare point, Sydney, that you brought to bear upon the
\par identification. How did you come by it? When did it strike you?"
\par 
\par "I thought he was rather a handsome fellow, and I thought I should have
\par been much the same sort of fellow, if I had had any luck."
\par 
\par Mr. Stryver laughed till he shook his precocious paunch.
\par 
\par "You and your luck, Sydney! Get to work, get to work."
\par 
\par Sullenly enough, the jackal loosened his dress, went into an adjoining
\par room, and came back with a large jug of cold water, a basin, and a towel
\par or two. Steeping the towels in the water, and partially wringing them
\par out, he folded them on his head in a manner hideous to behold, sat down
\par at the table, and said, "Now I am ready!"
\par 
\par "Not much boiling down to be done to-night, Memory," said Mr. Stryver,
\par gaily, as he looked among his papers.
\par 
\par "How much?"
\par 
\par "Only two sets of them."
\par 
\par "Give me the worst first."
\par 
\par "There they are, Sydney. Fire away!"
\par 
\par The lion then composed himself on his back on a sofa on one side of the
\par drinking-table, while the jackal sat at his own paper-bestrewn table
\par proper, on the other side of it, with the bottles and glasses ready to
\par his hand. Both resorted to the drinking-table without stint, but each in
\par a different way; the lion for the most part reclining with his hands in
\par his waistband, looking at the fire, or occasionally flirting with some
\par lighter document; the jackal, with knitted brows and intent face,
\par so deep in his task, that his eyes did not even follow the hand he
\par stretched out for his glass--which often groped about, for a minute or
\par more, before it found the glass for his lips. Two or three times, the
\par matter in hand became so knotty, that the jackal found it imperative on
\par him to get up, and steep his towels anew. From these pilgrimages to the
\par jug and basin, he returned with such eccentricities of damp headgear as
\par no words can describe; which were made the more ludicrous by his anxious
\par gravity.
\par 
\par At length the jackal had got together a compact repast for the lion, and
\par proceeded to offer it to him. The lion took it with care and caution,
\par made his selections from it, and his remarks upon it, and the jackal
\par assisted both. When the repast was fully discussed, the lion put his
\par hands in his waistband again, and lay down to meditate. The jackal then
\par invigorated himself with a bumper for his throttle, and a fresh application
\par to his head, and applied himself to the collection of a second meal;
\par this was administered to the lion in the same manner, and was not
\par disposed of until the clocks struck three in the morning.
\par 
\par "And now we have done, Sydney, fill a bumper of punch," said Mr.
\par Stryver.
\par 
\par The jackal removed the towels from his head, which had been steaming
\par again, shook himself, yawned, shivered, and complied.
\par 
\par "You were very sound, Sydney, in the matter of those crown witnesses
\par to-day. Every question told."
\par 
\par "I always am sound; am I not?"
\par 
\par "I don't gainsay it. What has roughened your temper? Put some punch to
\par it and smooth it again."
\par 
\par With a deprecatory grunt, the jackal again complied.
\par 
\par "The old Sydney Carton of old Shrewsbury School," said Stryver, nodding
\par his head over him as he reviewed him in the present and the past, "the
\par old seesaw Sydney. Up one minute and down the next; now in spirits and
\par now in despondency!"
\par 
\par "Ah!" returned the other, sighing: "yes! The same Sydney, with the same
\par luck. Even then, I did exercises for other boys, and seldom did my own."
\par 
\par "And why not?"
\par 
\par "God knows. It was my way, I suppose."
\par 
\par He sat, with his hands in his pockets and his legs stretched out before
\par him, looking at the fire.
\par 
\par "Carton," said his friend, squaring himself at him with a bullying air,
\par as if the fire-grate had been the furnace in which sustained endeavour
\par was forged, and the one delicate thing to be done for the old Sydney
\par Carton of old Shrewsbury School was to shoulder him into it, "your way
\par is, and always was, a lame way. You summon no energy and purpose. Look
\par at me."
\par 
\par "Oh, botheration!" returned Sydney, with a lighter and more
\par good-humoured laugh, "don't _you_ be moral!"
\par 
\par "How have I done what I have done?" said Stryver; "how do I do what I
\par do?"
\par 
\par "Partly through paying me to help you, I suppose. But it's not worth
\par your while to apostrophise me, or the air, about it; what you want to
\par do, you do. You were always in the front rank, and I was always behind."
\par 
\par "I had to get into the front rank; I was not born there, was I?"
\par 
\par "I was not present at the ceremony; but my opinion is you were," said
\par Carton. At this, he laughed again, and they both laughed.
\par 
\par "Before Shrewsbury, and at Shrewsbury, and ever since Shrewsbury,"
\par pursued Carton, "you have fallen into your rank, and I have fallen into
\par mine. Even when we were fellow-students in the Student-Quarter of Paris,
\par picking up French, and French law, and other French crumbs that we
\par didn't get much good of, you were always somewhere, and I was always
\par nowhere."
\par 
\par "And whose fault was that?"
\par 
\par "Upon my soul, I am not sure that it was not yours. You were always
\par driving and riving and shouldering and passing, to that restless degree
\par that I had no chance for my life but in rust and repose. It's a gloomy
\par thing, however, to talk about one's own past, with the day breaking.
\par Turn me in some other direction before I go."
\par 
\par "Well then! Pledge me to the pretty witness," said Stryver, holding up
\par his glass. "Are you turned in a pleasant direction?"
\par 
\par Apparently not, for he became gloomy again.
\par 
\par "Pretty witness," he muttered, looking down into his glass. "I have had
\par enough of witnesses to-day and to-night; who's your pretty witness?"
\par 
\par "The picturesque doctor's daughter, Miss Manette."
\par 
\par "_She_ pretty?"
\par 
\par "Is she not?"
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par "Why, man alive, she was the admiration of the whole Court!"
\par 
\par "Rot the admiration of the whole Court! Who made the Old Bailey a judge
\par of beauty? She was a golden-haired doll!"
\par 
\par "Do you know, Sydney," said Mr. Stryver, looking at him with sharp eyes,
\par and slowly drawing a hand across his florid face: "do you know, I rather
\par thought, at the time, that you sympathised with the golden-haired doll,
\par and were quick to see what happened to the golden-haired doll?"
\par 
\par "Quick to see what happened! If a girl, doll or no doll, swoons within a
\par yard or two of a man's nose, he can see it without a perspective-glass.
\par I pledge you, but I deny the beauty. And now I'll have no more drink;
\par I'll get to bed."
\par 
\par When his host followed him out on the staircase with a candle, to light
\par him down the stairs, the day was coldly looking in through its grimy
\par windows. When he got out of the house, the air was cold and sad, the
\par dull sky overcast, the river dark and dim, the whole scene like a
\par lifeless desert. And wreaths of dust were spinning round and round
\par before the morning blast, as if the desert-sand had risen far away, and
\par the first spray of it in its advance had begun to overwhelm the city.
\par 
\par Waste forces within him, and a desert all around, this man stood still
\par on his way across a silent terrace, and saw for a moment, lying in the
\par wilderness before him, a mirage of honourable ambition, self-denial, and
\par perseverance. In the fair city of this vision, there were airy galleries
\par from which the loves and graces looked upon him, gardens in which the
\par fruits of life hung ripening, waters of Hope that sparkled in his sight.
\par A moment, and it was gone. Climbing to a high chamber in a well of
\par houses, he threw himself down in his clothes on a neglected bed, and its
\par pillow was wet with wasted tears.
\par 
\par Sadly, sadly, the sun rose; it rose upon no sadder sight than the man of
\par good abilities and good emotions, incapable of their directed exercise,
\par incapable of his own help and his own happiness, sensible of the blight
\par on him, and resigning himself to let it eat him away.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VI. Hundreds of People
\par 
\par 
\par The quiet lodgings of Doctor Manette were in a quiet street-corner not
\par far from Soho-square. On the afternoon of a certain fine Sunday when the
\par waves of four months had rolled over the trial for treason, and carried
\par it, as to the public interest and memory, far out to sea, Mr. Jarvis
\par Lorry walked along the sunny streets from Clerkenwell where he lived,
\par on his way to dine with the Doctor. After several relapses into
\par business-absorption, Mr. Lorry had become the Doctor's friend, and the
\par quiet street-corner was the sunny part of his life.
\par 
\par On this certain fine Sunday, Mr. Lorry walked towards Soho, early in
\par the afternoon, for three reasons of habit. Firstly, because, on fine
\par Sundays, he often walked out, before dinner, with the Doctor and Lucie;
\par secondly, because, on unfavourable Sundays, he was accustomed to be with
\par them as the family friend, talking, reading, looking out of window, and
\par generally getting through the day; thirdly, because he happened to have
\par his own little shrewd doubts to solve, and knew how the ways of the
\par Doctor's household pointed to that time as a likely time for solving
\par them.
\par 
\par A quainter corner than the corner where the Doctor lived, was not to be
\par found in London. There was no way through it, and the front windows of
\par the Doctor's lodgings commanded a pleasant little vista of street that
\par had a congenial air of retirement on it. There were few buildings then,
\par north of the Oxford-road, and forest-trees flourished, and wild flowers
\par grew, and the hawthorn blossomed, in the now vanished fields. As a
\par consequence, country airs circulated in Soho with vigorous freedom,
\par instead of languishing into the parish like stray paupers without a
\par settlement; and there was many a good south wall, not far off, on which
\par the peaches ripened in their season.
\par 
\par The summer light struck into the corner brilliantly in the earlier part
\par of the day; but, when the streets grew hot, the corner was in shadow,
\par though not in shadow so remote but that you could see beyond it into a
\par glare of brightness. It was a cool spot, staid but cheerful, a wonderful
\par place for echoes, and a very harbour from the raging streets.
\par 
\par There ought to have been a tranquil bark in such an anchorage, and
\par there was. The Doctor occupied two floors of a large stiff house, where
\par several callings purported to be pursued by day, but whereof little was
\par audible any day, and which was shunned by all of them at night. In
\par a building at the back, attainable by a courtyard where a plane-tree
\par rustled its green leaves, church-organs claimed to be made, and silver
\par to be chased, and likewise gold to be beaten by some mysterious giant
\par who had a golden arm starting out of the wall of the front hall--as if
\par he had beaten himself precious, and menaced a similar conversion of all
\par visitors. Very little of these trades, or of a lonely lodger rumoured
\par to live up-stairs, or of a dim coach-trimming maker asserted to have
\par a counting-house below, was ever heard or seen. Occasionally, a stray
\par workman putting his coat on, traversed the hall, or a stranger peered
\par about there, or a distant clink was heard across the courtyard, or a
\par thump from the golden giant. These, however, were only the exceptions
\par required to prove the rule that the sparrows in the plane-tree behind
\par the house, and the echoes in the corner before it, had their own way
\par from Sunday morning unto Saturday night.
\par 
\par Doctor Manette received such patients here as his old reputation, and
\par its revival in the floating whispers of his story, brought him.
\par His scientific knowledge, and his vigilance and skill in conducting
\par ingenious experiments, brought him otherwise into moderate request, and
\par he earned as much as he wanted.
\par 
\par These things were within Mr. Jarvis Lorry's knowledge, thoughts, and
\par notice, when he rang the door-bell of the tranquil house in the corner,
\par on the fine Sunday afternoon.
\par 
\par "Doctor Manette at home?"
\par 
\par Expected home.
\par 
\par "Miss Lucie at home?"
\par 
\par Expected home.
\par 
\par "Miss Pross at home?"
\par 
\par Possibly at home, but of a certainty impossible for handmaid to
\par anticipate intentions of Miss Pross, as to admission or denial of the
\par fact.
\par 
\par "As I am at home myself," said Mr. Lorry, "I'll go upstairs."
\par 
\par Although the Doctor's daughter had known nothing of the country of her
\par birth, she appeared to have innately derived from it that ability to
\par make much of little means, which is one of its most useful and most
\par agreeable characteristics. Simple as the furniture was, it was set off
\par by so many little adornments, of no value but for their taste and fancy,
\par that its effect was delightful. The disposition of everything in the
\par rooms, from the largest object to the least; the arrangement of colours,
\par the elegant variety and contrast obtained by thrift in trifles, by
\par delicate hands, clear eyes, and good sense; were at once so pleasant in
\par themselves, and so expressive of their originator, that, as Mr. Lorry
\par stood looking about him, the very chairs and tables seemed to ask him,
\par with something of that peculiar expression which he knew so well by this
\par time, whether he approved?
\par 
\par There were three rooms on a floor, and, the doors by which they
\par communicated being put open that the air might pass freely through them
\par all, Mr. Lorry, smilingly observant of that fanciful resemblance which
\par he detected all around him, walked from one to another. The first was
\par the best room, and in it were Lucie's birds, and flowers, and books,
\par and desk, and work-table, and box of water-colours; the second was
\par the Doctor's consulting-room, used also as the dining-room; the third,
\par changingly speckled by the rustle of the plane-tree in the yard, was the
\par Doctor's bedroom, and there, in a corner, stood the disused shoemaker's
\par bench and tray of tools, much as it had stood on the fifth floor of the
\par dismal house by the wine-shop, in the suburb of Saint Antoine in Paris.
\par 
\par "I wonder," said Mr. Lorry, pausing in his looking about, "that he keeps
\par that reminder of his sufferings about him!"
\par 
\par "And why wonder at that?" was the abrupt inquiry that made him start.
\par 
\par It proceeded from Miss Pross, the wild red woman, strong of hand, whose
\par acquaintance he had first made at the Royal George Hotel at Dover, and
\par had since improved.
\par 
\par "I should have thought--" Mr. Lorry began.
\par 
\par "Pooh! You'd have thought!" said Miss Pross; and Mr. Lorry left off.
\par 
\par "How do you do?" inquired that lady then--sharply, and yet as if to
\par express that she bore him no malice.
\par 
\par "I am pretty well, I thank you," answered Mr. Lorry, with meekness; "how
\par are you?"
\par 
\par "Nothing to boast of," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par "Indeed?"
\par 
\par "Ah! indeed!" said Miss Pross. "I am very much put out about my
\par Ladybird."
\par 
\par "Indeed?"
\par 
\par "For gracious sake say something else besides 'indeed,' or you'll
\par fidget me to death," said Miss Pross: whose character (dissociated from
\par stature) was shortness.
\par 
\par "Really, then?" said Mr. Lorry, as an amendment.
\par 
\par "Really, is bad enough," returned Miss Pross, "but better. Yes, I am
\par very much put out."
\par 
\par "May I ask the cause?"
\par 
\par "I don't want dozens of people who are not at all worthy of Ladybird, to
\par come here looking after her," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par "_Do_ dozens come for that purpose?"
\par 
\par "Hundreds," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par It was characteristic of this lady (as of some other people before her
\par time and since) that whenever her original proposition was questioned,
\par she exaggerated it.
\par 
\par "Dear me!" said Mr. Lorry, as the safest remark he could think of.
\par 
\par "I have lived with the darling--or the darling has lived with me, and
\par paid me for it; which she certainly should never have done, you may take
\par your affidavit, if I could have afforded to keep either myself or her
\par for nothing--since she was ten years old. And it's really very hard,"
\par said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par Not seeing with precision what was very hard, Mr. Lorry shook his head;
\par using that important part of himself as a sort of fairy cloak that would
\par fit anything.
\par 
\par "All sorts of people who are not in the least degree worthy of the pet,
\par are always turning up," said Miss Pross. "When you began it--"
\par 
\par "_I_ began it, Miss Pross?"
\par 
\par "Didn't you? Who brought her father to life?"
\par 
\par "Oh! If _that_ was beginning it--" said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "It wasn't ending it, I suppose? I say, when you began it, it was hard
\par enough; not that I have any fault to find with Doctor Manette, except
\par that he is not worthy of such a daughter, which is no imputation on
\par him, for it was not to be expected that anybody should be, under any
\par circumstances. But it really is doubly and trebly hard to have crowds
\par and multitudes of people turning up after him (I could have forgiven
\par him), to take Ladybird's affections away from me."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry knew Miss Pross to be very jealous, but he also knew her by
\par this time to be, beneath the service of her eccentricity, one of those
\par unselfish creatures--found only among women--who will, for pure love and
\par admiration, bind themselves willing slaves, to youth when they have lost
\par it, to beauty that they never had, to accomplishments that they were
\par never fortunate enough to gain, to bright hopes that never shone upon
\par their own sombre lives. He knew enough of the world to know that there
\par is nothing in it better than the faithful service of the heart; so
\par rendered and so free from any mercenary taint, he had such an exalted
\par respect for it, that in the retributive arrangements made by his own
\par mind--we all make such arrangements, more or less--he stationed Miss
\par Pross much nearer to the lower Angels than many ladies immeasurably
\par better got up both by Nature and Art, who had balances at Tellson's.
\par 
\par "There never was, nor will be, but one man worthy of Ladybird," said
\par Miss Pross; "and that was my brother Solomon, if he hadn't made a
\par mistake in life."
\par 
\par Here again: Mr. Lorry's inquiries into Miss Pross's personal history had
\par established the fact that her brother Solomon was a heartless scoundrel
\par who had stripped her of everything she possessed, as a stake to
\par speculate with, and had abandoned her in her poverty for evermore, with
\par no touch of compunction. Miss Pross's fidelity of belief in Solomon
\par (deducting a mere trifle for this slight mistake) was quite a serious
\par matter with Mr. Lorry, and had its weight in his good opinion of her.
\par 
\par "As we happen to be alone for the moment, and are both people of
\par business," he said, when they had got back to the drawing-room and had
\par sat down there in friendly relations, "let me ask you--does the Doctor,
\par in talking with Lucie, never refer to the shoemaking time, yet?"
\par 
\par "Never."
\par 
\par "And yet keeps that bench and those tools beside him?"
\par 
\par "Ah!" returned Miss Pross, shaking her head. "But I don't say he don't
\par refer to it within himself."
\par 
\par "Do you believe that he thinks of it much?"
\par 
\par "I do," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par "Do you imagine--" Mr. Lorry had begun, when Miss Pross took him up
\par short with:
\par 
\par "Never imagine anything. Have no imagination at all."
\par 
\par "I stand corrected; do you suppose--you go so far as to suppose,
\par sometimes?"
\par 
\par "Now and then," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par "Do you suppose," Mr. Lorry went on, with a laughing twinkle in his
\par bright eye, as it looked kindly at her, "that Doctor Manette has any
\par theory of his own, preserved through all those years, relative to
\par the cause of his being so oppressed; perhaps, even to the name of his
\par oppressor?"
\par 
\par "I don't suppose anything about it but what Ladybird tells me."
\par 
\par "And that is--?"
\par 
\par "That she thinks he has."
\par 
\par "Now don't be angry at my asking all these questions; because I am a
\par mere dull man of business, and you are a woman of business."
\par 
\par "Dull?" Miss Pross inquired, with placidity.
\par 
\par Rather wishing his modest adjective away, Mr. Lorry replied, "No, no,
\par no. Surely not. To return to business:--Is it not remarkable that Doctor
\par Manette, unquestionably innocent of any crime as we are all well assured
\par he is, should never touch upon that question? I will not say with me,
\par though he had business relations with me many years ago, and we are now
\par intimate; I will say with the fair daughter to whom he is so devotedly
\par attached, and who is so devotedly attached to him? Believe me, Miss
\par Pross, I don't approach the topic with you, out of curiosity, but out of
\par zealous interest."
\par 
\par "Well! To the best of my understanding, and bad's the best, you'll tell
\par me," said Miss Pross, softened by the tone of the apology, "he is afraid
\par of the whole subject."
\par 
\par "Afraid?"
\par 
\par "It's plain enough, I should think, why he may be. It's a dreadful
\par remembrance. Besides that, his loss of himself grew out of it. Not
\par knowing how he lost himself, or how he recovered himself, he may never
\par feel certain of not losing himself again. That alone wouldn't make the
\par subject pleasant, I should think."
\par 
\par It was a profounder remark than Mr. Lorry had looked for. "True," said
\par he, "and fearful to reflect upon. Yet, a doubt lurks in my mind, Miss
\par Pross, whether it is good for Doctor Manette to have that suppression
\par always shut up within him. Indeed, it is this doubt and the uneasiness
\par it sometimes causes me that has led me to our present confidence."
\par 
\par "Can't be helped," said Miss Pross, shaking her head. "Touch that
\par string, and he instantly changes for the worse. Better leave it alone.
\par In short, must leave it alone, like or no like. Sometimes, he gets up in
\par the dead of the night, and will be heard, by us overhead there, walking
\par up and down, walking up and down, in his room. Ladybird has learnt to
\par know then that his mind is walking up and down, walking up and down, in
\par his old prison. She hurries to him, and they go on together, walking up
\par and down, walking up and down, until he is composed. But he never says
\par a word of the true reason of his restlessness, to her, and she finds it
\par best not to hint at it to him. In silence they go walking up and down
\par together, walking up and down together, till her love and company have
\par brought him to himself."
\par 
\par Notwithstanding Miss Pross's denial of her own imagination, there was a
\par perception of the pain of being monotonously haunted by one sad idea,
\par in her repetition of the phrase, walking up and down, which testified to
\par her possessing such a thing.
\par 
\par The corner has been mentioned as a wonderful corner for echoes; it
\par had begun to echo so resoundingly to the tread of coming feet, that it
\par seemed as though the very mention of that weary pacing to and fro had
\par set it going.
\par 
\par "Here they are!" said Miss Pross, rising to break up the conference;
\par "and now we shall have hundreds of people pretty soon!"
\par 
\par It was such a curious corner in its acoustical properties, such a
\par peculiar Ear of a place, that as Mr. Lorry stood at the open window,
\par looking for the father and daughter whose steps he heard, he fancied
\par they would never approach. Not only would the echoes die away, as though
\par the steps had gone; but, echoes of other steps that never came would be
\par heard in their stead, and would die away for good when they seemed close
\par at hand. However, father and daughter did at last appear, and Miss Pross
\par was ready at the street door to receive them.
\par 
\par Miss Pross was a pleasant sight, albeit wild, and red, and grim, taking
\par off her darling's bonnet when she came up-stairs, and touching it up
\par with the ends of her handkerchief, and blowing the dust off it, and
\par folding her mantle ready for laying by, and smoothing her rich hair with
\par as much pride as she could possibly have taken in her own hair if she
\par had been the vainest and handsomest of women. Her darling was a pleasant
\par sight too, embracing her and thanking her, and protesting against
\par her taking so much trouble for her--which last she only dared to do
\par playfully, or Miss Pross, sorely hurt, would have retired to her own
\par chamber and cried. The Doctor was a pleasant sight too, looking on at
\par them, and telling Miss Pross how she spoilt Lucie, in accents and with
\par eyes that had as much spoiling in them as Miss Pross had, and would
\par have had more if it were possible. Mr. Lorry was a pleasant sight too,
\par beaming at all this in his little wig, and thanking his bachelor
\par stars for having lighted him in his declining years to a Home. But, no
\par Hundreds of people came to see the sights, and Mr. Lorry looked in vain
\par for the fulfilment of Miss Pross's prediction.
\par 
\par Dinner-time, and still no Hundreds of people. In the arrangements of
\par the little household, Miss Pross took charge of the lower regions, and
\par always acquitted herself marvellously. Her dinners, of a very modest
\par quality, were so well cooked and so well served, and so neat in their
\par contrivances, half English and half French, that nothing could be
\par better. Miss Pross's friendship being of the thoroughly practical
\par kind, she had ravaged Soho and the adjacent provinces, in search of
\par impoverished French, who, tempted by shillings and half-crowns, would
\par impart culinary mysteries to her. From these decayed sons and daughters
\par of Gaul, she had acquired such wonderful arts, that the woman and girl
\par who formed the staff of domestics regarded her as quite a Sorceress,
\par or Cinderella's Godmother: who would send out for a fowl, a rabbit,
\par a vegetable or two from the garden, and change them into anything she
\par pleased.
\par 
\par On Sundays, Miss Pross dined at the Doctor's table, but on other days
\par persisted in taking her meals at unknown periods, either in the lower
\par regions, or in her own room on the second floor--a blue chamber, to
\par which no one but her Ladybird ever gained admittance. On this occasion,
\par Miss Pross, responding to Ladybird's pleasant face and pleasant efforts
\par to please her, unbent exceedingly; so the dinner was very pleasant, too.
\par 
\par It was an oppressive day, and, after dinner, Lucie proposed that the
\par wine should be carried out under the plane-tree, and they should sit
\par there in the air. As everything turned upon her, and revolved about her,
\par they went out under the plane-tree, and she carried the wine down for
\par the special benefit of Mr. Lorry. She had installed herself, some
\par time before, as Mr. Lorry's cup-bearer; and while they sat under the
\par plane-tree, talking, she kept his glass replenished. Mysterious backs
\par and ends of houses peeped at them as they talked, and the plane-tree
\par whispered to them in its own way above their heads.
\par 
\par Still, the Hundreds of people did not present themselves. Mr. Darnay
\par presented himself while they were sitting under the plane-tree, but he
\par was only One.
\par 
\par Doctor Manette received him kindly, and so did Lucie. But, Miss Pross
\par suddenly became afflicted with a twitching in the head and body, and
\par retired into the house. She was not unfrequently the victim of this
\par disorder, and she called it, in familiar conversation, "a fit of the
\par jerks."
\par 
\par The Doctor was in his best condition, and looked specially young. The
\par resemblance between him and Lucie was very strong at such times, and as
\par they sat side by side, she leaning on his shoulder, and he resting
\par his arm on the back of her chair, it was very agreeable to trace the
\par likeness.
\par 
\par He had been talking all day, on many subjects, and with unusual
\par vivacity. "Pray, Doctor Manette," said Mr. Darnay, as they sat under the
\par plane-tree--and he said it in the natural pursuit of the topic in hand,
\par which happened to be the old buildings of London--"have you seen much of
\par the Tower?"
\par 
\par "Lucie and I have been there; but only casually. We have seen enough of
\par it, to know that it teems with interest; little more."
\par 
\par "_I_ have been there, as you remember," said Darnay, with a smile,
\par though reddening a little angrily, "in another character, and not in a
\par character that gives facilities for seeing much of it. They told me a
\par curious thing when I was there."
\par 
\par "What was that?" Lucie asked.
\par 
\par "In making some alterations, the workmen came upon an old dungeon, which
\par had been, for many years, built up and forgotten. Every stone of
\par its inner wall was covered by inscriptions which had been carved by
\par prisoners--dates, names, complaints, and prayers. Upon a corner stone
\par in an angle of the wall, one prisoner, who seemed to have gone to
\par execution, had cut as his last work, three letters. They were done with
\par some very poor instrument, and hurriedly, with an unsteady hand.
\par At first, they were read as D. I. C.; but, on being more carefully
\par examined, the last letter was found to be G. There was no record or
\par legend of any prisoner with those initials, and many fruitless guesses
\par were made what the name could have been. At length, it was suggested
\par that the letters were not initials, but the complete word, DIG. The
\par floor was examined very carefully under the inscription, and, in the
\par earth beneath a stone, or tile, or some fragment of paving, were found
\par the ashes of a paper, mingled with the ashes of a small leathern case
\par or bag. What the unknown prisoner had written will never be read, but he
\par had written something, and hidden it away to keep it from the gaoler."
\par 
\par "My father," exclaimed Lucie, "you are ill!"
\par 
\par He had suddenly started up, with his hand to his head. His manner and
\par his look quite terrified them all.
\par 
\par "No, my dear, not ill. There are large drops of rain falling, and they
\par made me start. We had better go in."
\par 
\par He recovered himself almost instantly. Rain was really falling in large
\par drops, and he showed the back of his hand with rain-drops on it. But, he
\par said not a single word in reference to the discovery that had been told
\par of, and, as they went into the house, the business eye of Mr. Lorry
\par either detected, or fancied it detected, on his face, as it turned
\par towards Charles Darnay, the same singular look that had been upon it
\par when it turned towards him in the passages of the Court House.
\par 
\par He recovered himself so quickly, however, that Mr. Lorry had doubts of
\par his business eye. The arm of the golden giant in the hall was not more
\par steady than he was, when he stopped under it to remark to them that he
\par was not yet proof against slight surprises (if he ever would be), and
\par that the rain had startled him.
\par 
\par Tea-time, and Miss Pross making tea, with another fit of the jerks upon
\par her, and yet no Hundreds of people. Mr. Carton had lounged in, but he
\par made only Two.
\par 
\par The night was so very sultry, that although they sat with doors and
\par windows open, they were overpowered by heat. When the tea-table was
\par done with, they all moved to one of the windows, and looked out into the
\par heavy twilight. Lucie sat by her father; Darnay sat beside her; Carton
\par leaned against a window. The curtains were long and white, and some of
\par the thunder-gusts that whirled into the corner, caught them up to the
\par ceiling, and waved them like spectral wings.
\par 
\par "The rain-drops are still falling, large, heavy, and few," said Doctor
\par Manette. "It comes slowly."
\par 
\par "It comes surely," said Carton.
\par 
\par They spoke low, as people watching and waiting mostly do; as people in a
\par dark room, watching and waiting for Lightning, always do.
\par 
\par There was a great hurry in the streets of people speeding away to
\par get shelter before the storm broke; the wonderful corner for echoes
\par resounded with the echoes of footsteps coming and going, yet not a
\par footstep was there.
\par 
\par "A multitude of people, and yet a solitude!" said Darnay, when they had
\par listened for a while.
\par 
\par "Is it not impressive, Mr. Darnay?" asked Lucie. "Sometimes, I have
\par sat here of an evening, until I have fancied--but even the shade of
\par a foolish fancy makes me shudder to-night, when all is so black and
\par solemn--"
\par 
\par "Let us shudder too. We may know what it is."
\par 
\par "It will seem nothing to you. Such whims are only impressive as we
\par originate them, I think; they are not to be communicated. I have
\par sometimes sat alone here of an evening, listening, until I have made
\par the echoes out to be the echoes of all the footsteps that are coming
\par by-and-bye into our lives."
\par 
\par "There is a great crowd coming one day into our lives, if that be so,"
\par Sydney Carton struck in, in his moody way.
\par 
\par The footsteps were incessant, and the hurry of them became more and more
\par rapid. The corner echoed and re-echoed with the tread of feet; some,
\par as it seemed, under the windows; some, as it seemed, in the room; some
\par coming, some going, some breaking off, some stopping altogether; all in
\par the distant streets, and not one within sight.
\par 
\par "Are all these footsteps destined to come to all of us, Miss Manette, or
\par are we to divide them among us?"
\par 
\par "I don't know, Mr. Darnay; I told you it was a foolish fancy, but you
\par asked for it. When I have yielded myself to it, I have been alone, and
\par then I have imagined them the footsteps of the people who are to come
\par into my life, and my father's."
\par 
\par "I take them into mine!" said Carton. "_I_ ask no questions and make no
\par stipulations. There is a great crowd bearing down upon us, Miss Manette,
\par and I see them--by the Lightning." He added the last words, after there
\par had been a vivid flash which had shown him lounging in the window.
\par 
\par "And I hear them!" he added again, after a peal of thunder. "Here they
\par come, fast, fierce, and furious!"
\par 
\par It was the rush and roar of rain that he typified, and it stopped him,
\par for no voice could be heard in it. A memorable storm of thunder and
\par lightning broke with that sweep of water, and there was not a moment's
\par interval in crash, and fire, and rain, until after the moon rose at
\par midnight.
\par 
\par The great bell of Saint Paul's was striking one in the cleared air, when
\par Mr. Lorry, escorted by Jerry, high-booted and bearing a lantern, set
\par forth on his return-passage to Clerkenwell. There were solitary patches
\par of road on the way between Soho and Clerkenwell, and Mr. Lorry, mindful
\par of foot-pads, always retained Jerry for this service: though it was
\par usually performed a good two hours earlier.
\par 
\par "What a night it has been! Almost a night, Jerry," said Mr. Lorry, "to
\par bring the dead out of their graves."
\par 
\par "I never see the night myself, master--nor yet I don't expect to--what
\par would do that," answered Jerry.
\par 
\par "Good night, Mr. Carton," said the man of business. "Good night, Mr.
\par Darnay. Shall we ever see such a night again, together!"
\par 
\par Perhaps. Perhaps, see the great crowd of people with its rush and roar,
\par bearing down upon them, too.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VII. Monseigneur in Town
\par 
\par 
\par Monseigneur, one of the great lords in power at the Court, held his
\par fortnightly reception in his grand hotel in Paris. Monseigneur was in
\par his inner room, his sanctuary of sanctuaries, the Holiest of Holiests to
\par the crowd of worshippers in the suite of rooms without. Monseigneur
\par was about to take his chocolate. Monseigneur could swallow a great many
\par things with ease, and was by some few sullen minds supposed to be rather
\par rapidly swallowing France; but, his morning's chocolate could not so
\par much as get into the throat of Monseigneur, without the aid of four
\par strong men besides the Cook.
\par 
\par Yes. It took four men, all four ablaze with gorgeous decoration, and the
\par Chief of them unable to exist with fewer than two gold watches in his
\par pocket, emulative of the noble and chaste fashion set by Monseigneur, to
\par conduct the happy chocolate to Monseigneur's lips. One lacquey carried
\par the chocolate-pot into the sacred presence; a second, milled and frothed
\par the chocolate with the little instrument he bore for that function;
\par a third, presented the favoured napkin; a fourth (he of the two gold
\par watches), poured the chocolate out. It was impossible for Monseigneur to
\par dispense with one of these attendants on the chocolate and hold his high
\par place under the admiring Heavens. Deep would have been the blot upon
\par his escutcheon if his chocolate had been ignobly waited on by only three
\par men; he must have died of two.
\par 
\par Monseigneur had been out at a little supper last night, where the Comedy
\par and the Grand Opera were charmingly represented. Monseigneur was out at
\par a little supper most nights, with fascinating company. So polite and so
\par impressible was Monseigneur, that the Comedy and the Grand Opera had far
\par more influence with him in the tiresome articles of state affairs and
\par state secrets, than the needs of all France. A happy circumstance
\par for France, as the like always is for all countries similarly
\par favoured!--always was for England (by way of example), in the regretted
\par days of the merry Stuart who sold it.
\par 
\par Monseigneur had one truly noble idea of general public business, which
\par was, to let everything go on in its own way; of particular public
\par business, Monseigneur had the other truly noble idea that it must all go
\par his way--tend to his own power and pocket. Of his pleasures, general and
\par particular, Monseigneur had the other truly noble idea, that the world
\par was made for them. The text of his order (altered from the original
\par by only a pronoun, which is not much) ran: "The earth and the fulness
\par thereof are mine, saith Monseigneur."
\par 
\par Yet, Monseigneur had slowly found that vulgar embarrassments crept into
\par his affairs, both private and public; and he had, as to both classes of
\par affairs, allied himself perforce with a Farmer-General. As to finances
\par public, because Monseigneur could not make anything at all of them, and
\par must consequently let them out to somebody who could; as to finances
\par private, because Farmer-Generals were rich, and Monseigneur, after
\par generations of great luxury and expense, was growing poor. Hence
\par Monseigneur had taken his sister from a convent, while there was yet
\par time to ward off the impending veil, the cheapest garment she could
\par wear, and had bestowed her as a prize upon a very rich Farmer-General,
\par poor in family. Which Farmer-General, carrying an appropriate cane with
\par a golden apple on the top of it, was now among the company in the outer
\par rooms, much prostrated before by mankind--always excepting superior
\par mankind of the blood of Monseigneur, who, his own wife included, looked
\par down upon him with the loftiest contempt.
\par 
\par A sumptuous man was the Farmer-General. Thirty horses stood in his
\par stables, twenty-four male domestics sat in his halls, six body-women
\par waited on his wife. As one who pretended to do nothing but plunder and
\par forage where he could, the Farmer-General--howsoever his matrimonial
\par relations conduced to social morality--was at least the greatest reality
\par among the personages who attended at the hotel of Monseigneur that day.
\par 
\par For, the rooms, though a beautiful scene to look at, and adorned with
\par every device of decoration that the taste and skill of the time could
\par achieve, were, in truth, not a sound business; considered with any
\par reference to the scarecrows in the rags and nightcaps elsewhere (and not
\par so far off, either, but that the watching towers of Notre Dame, almost
\par equidistant from the two extremes, could see them both), they would
\par have been an exceedingly uncomfortable business--if that could have
\par been anybody's business, at the house of Monseigneur. Military officers
\par destitute of military knowledge; naval officers with no idea of a ship;
\par civil officers without a notion of affairs; brazen ecclesiastics, of the
\par worst world worldly, with sensual eyes, loose tongues, and looser lives;
\par all totally unfit for their several callings, all lying horribly in
\par pretending to belong to them, but all nearly or remotely of the order of
\par Monseigneur, and therefore foisted on all public employments from which
\par anything was to be got; these were to be told off by the score and the
\par score. People not immediately connected with Monseigneur or the State,
\par yet equally unconnected with anything that was real, or with lives
\par passed in travelling by any straight road to any true earthly end, were
\par no less abundant. Doctors who made great fortunes out of dainty remedies
\par for imaginary disorders that never existed, smiled upon their courtly
\par patients in the ante-chambers of Monseigneur. Projectors who had
\par discovered every kind of remedy for the little evils with which the
\par State was touched, except the remedy of setting to work in earnest to
\par root out a single sin, poured their distracting babble into any ears
\par they could lay hold of, at the reception of Monseigneur. Unbelieving
\par Philosophers who were remodelling the world with words, and making
\par card-towers of Babel to scale the skies with, talked with Unbelieving
\par Chemists who had an eye on the transmutation of metals, at this
\par wonderful gathering accumulated by Monseigneur. Exquisite gentlemen of
\par the finest breeding, which was at that remarkable time--and has been
\par since--to be known by its fruits of indifference to every natural
\par subject of human interest, were in the most exemplary state of
\par exhaustion, at the hotel of Monseigneur. Such homes had these various
\par notabilities left behind them in the fine world of Paris, that the spies
\par among the assembled devotees of Monseigneur--forming a goodly half
\par of the polite company--would have found it hard to discover among
\par the angels of that sphere one solitary wife, who, in her manners and
\par appearance, owned to being a Mother. Indeed, except for the mere act of
\par bringing a troublesome creature into this world--which does not go far
\par towards the realisation of the name of mother--there was no such thing
\par known to the fashion. Peasant women kept the unfashionable babies close,
\par and brought them up, and charming grandmammas of sixty dressed and
\par supped as at twenty.
\par 
\par The leprosy of unreality disfigured every human creature in attendance
\par upon Monseigneur. In the outermost room were half a dozen exceptional
\par people who had had, for a few years, some vague misgiving in them that
\par things in general were going rather wrong. As a promising way of setting
\par them right, half of the half-dozen had become members of a fantastic
\par sect of Convulsionists, and were even then considering within themselves
\par whether they should foam, rage, roar, and turn cataleptic on the
\par spot--thereby setting up a highly intelligible finger-post to the
\par Future, for Monseigneur's guidance. Besides these Dervishes, were other
\par three who had rushed into another sect, which mended matters with a
\par jargon about "the Centre of Truth:" holding that Man had got out of the
\par Centre of Truth--which did not need much demonstration--but had not got
\par out of the Circumference, and that he was to be kept from flying out of
\par the Circumference, and was even to be shoved back into the Centre,
\par by fasting and seeing of spirits. Among these, accordingly, much
\par discoursing with spirits went on--and it did a world of good which never
\par became manifest.
\par 
\par But, the comfort was, that all the company at the grand hotel of
\par Monseigneur were perfectly dressed. If the Day of Judgment had only been
\par ascertained to be a dress day, everybody there would have been eternally
\par correct. Such frizzling and powdering and sticking up of hair, such
\par delicate complexions artificially preserved and mended, such gallant
\par swords to look at, and such delicate honour to the sense of smell, would
\par surely keep anything going, for ever and ever. The exquisite gentlemen
\par of the finest breeding wore little pendent trinkets that chinked as they
\par languidly moved; these golden fetters rang like precious little bells;
\par and what with that ringing, and with the rustle of silk and brocade and
\par fine linen, there was a flutter in the air that fanned Saint Antoine and
\par his devouring hunger far away.
\par 
\par Dress was the one unfailing talisman and charm used for keeping all
\par things in their places. Everybody was dressed for a Fancy Ball that
\par was never to leave off. From the Palace of the Tuileries, through
\par Monseigneur and the whole Court, through the Chambers, the Tribunals
\par of Justice, and all society (except the scarecrows), the Fancy Ball
\par descended to the Common Executioner: who, in pursuance of the charm, was
\par required to officiate "frizzled, powdered, in a gold-laced coat, pumps,
\par and white silk stockings." At the gallows and the wheel--the axe was a
\par rarity--Monsieur Paris, as it was the episcopal mode among his brother
\par Professors of the provinces, Monsieur Orleans, and the rest, to call
\par him, presided in this dainty dress. And who among the company at
\par Monseigneur's reception in that seventeen hundred and eightieth year
\par of our Lord, could possibly doubt, that a system rooted in a frizzled
\par hangman, powdered, gold-laced, pumped, and white-silk stockinged, would
\par see the very stars out!
\par 
\par Monseigneur having eased his four men of their burdens and taken his
\par chocolate, caused the doors of the Holiest of Holiests to be thrown
\par open, and issued forth. Then, what submission, what cringing and
\par fawning, what servility, what abject humiliation! As to bowing down in
\par body and spirit, nothing in that way was left for Heaven--which may have
\par been one among other reasons why the worshippers of Monseigneur never
\par troubled it.
\par 
\par Bestowing a word of promise here and a smile there, a whisper on one
\par happy slave and a wave of the hand on another, Monseigneur affably
\par passed through his rooms to the remote region of the Circumference of
\par Truth. There, Monseigneur turned, and came back again, and so in due
\par course of time got himself shut up in his sanctuary by the chocolate
\par sprites, and was seen no more.
\par 
\par The show being over, the flutter in the air became quite a little storm,
\par and the precious little bells went ringing downstairs. There was soon
\par but one person left of all the crowd, and he, with his hat under his arm
\par and his snuff-box in his hand, slowly passed among the mirrors on his
\par way out.
\par 
\par "I devote you," said this person, stopping at the last door on his way,
\par and turning in the direction of the sanctuary, "to the Devil!"
\par 
\par With that, he shook the snuff from his fingers as if he had shaken the
\par dust from his feet, and quietly walked downstairs.
\par 
\par He was a man of about sixty, handsomely dressed, haughty in manner, and
\par with a face like a fine mask. A face of a transparent paleness; every
\par feature in it clearly defined; one set expression on it. The nose,
\par beautifully formed otherwise, was very slightly pinched at the top
\par of each nostril. In those two compressions, or dints, the only little
\par change that the face ever showed, resided. They persisted in changing
\par colour sometimes, and they would be occasionally dilated and contracted
\par by something like a faint pulsation; then, they gave a look of
\par treachery, and cruelty, to the whole countenance. Examined with
\par attention, its capacity of helping such a look was to be found in the
\par line of the mouth, and the lines of the orbits of the eyes, being much
\par too horizontal and thin; still, in the effect of the face made, it was a
\par handsome face, and a remarkable one.
\par 
\par Its owner went downstairs into the courtyard, got into his carriage, and
\par drove away. Not many people had talked with him at the reception; he had
\par stood in a little space apart, and Monseigneur might have been warmer
\par in his manner. It appeared, under the circumstances, rather agreeable
\par to him to see the common people dispersed before his horses, and
\par often barely escaping from being run down. His man drove as if he were
\par charging an enemy, and the furious recklessness of the man brought no
\par check into the face, or to the lips, of the master. The complaint had
\par sometimes made itself audible, even in that deaf city and dumb age,
\par that, in the narrow streets without footways, the fierce patrician
\par custom of hard driving endangered and maimed the mere vulgar in a
\par barbarous manner. But, few cared enough for that to think of it a second
\par time, and, in this matter, as in all others, the common wretches were
\par left to get out of their difficulties as they could.
\par 
\par With a wild rattle and clatter, and an inhuman abandonment of
\par consideration not easy to be understood in these days, the carriage
\par dashed through streets and swept round corners, with women screaming
\par before it, and men clutching each other and clutching children out of
\par its way. At last, swooping at a street corner by a fountain, one of its
\par wheels came to a sickening little jolt, and there was a loud cry from a
\par number of voices, and the horses reared and plunged.
\par 
\par But for the latter inconvenience, the carriage probably would not have
\par stopped; carriages were often known to drive on, and leave their wounded
\par behind, and why not? But the frightened valet had got down in a hurry,
\par and there were twenty hands at the horses' bridles.
\par 
\par "What has gone wrong?" said Monsieur, calmly looking out.
\par 
\par A tall man in a nightcap had caught up a bundle from among the feet of
\par the horses, and had laid it on the basement of the fountain, and was
\par down in the mud and wet, howling over it like a wild animal.
\par 
\par "Pardon, Monsieur the Marquis!" said a ragged and submissive man, "it is
\par a child."
\par 
\par "Why does he make that abominable noise? Is it his child?"
\par 
\par "Excuse me, Monsieur the Marquis--it is a pity--yes."
\par 
\par The fountain was a little removed; for the street opened, where it was,
\par into a space some ten or twelve yards square. As the tall man suddenly
\par got up from the ground, and came running at the carriage, Monsieur the
\par Marquis clapped his hand for an instant on his sword-hilt.
\par 
\par "Killed!" shrieked the man, in wild desperation, extending both arms at
\par their length above his head, and staring at him. "Dead!"
\par 
\par The people closed round, and looked at Monsieur the Marquis. There was
\par nothing revealed by the many eyes that looked at him but watchfulness
\par and eagerness; there was no visible menacing or anger. Neither did the
\par people say anything; after the first cry, they had been silent, and they
\par remained so. The voice of the submissive man who had spoken, was flat
\par and tame in its extreme submission. Monsieur the Marquis ran his eyes
\par over them all, as if they had been mere rats come out of their holes.
\par 
\par He took out his purse.
\par 
\par "It is extraordinary to me," said he, "that you people cannot take care
\par of yourselves and your children. One or the other of you is for ever in
\par the way. How do I know what injury you have done my horses. See! Give
\par him that."
\par 
\par He threw out a gold coin for the valet to pick up, and all the heads
\par craned forward that all the eyes might look down at it as it fell. The
\par tall man called out again with a most unearthly cry, "Dead!"
\par 
\par He was arrested by the quick arrival of another man, for whom the rest
\par made way. On seeing him, the miserable creature fell upon his shoulder,
\par sobbing and crying, and pointing to the fountain, where some women were
\par stooping over the motionless bundle, and moving gently about it. They
\par were as silent, however, as the men.
\par 
\par "I know all, I know all," said the last comer. "Be a brave man, my
\par Gaspard! It is better for the poor little plaything to die so, than to
\par live. It has died in a moment without pain. Could it have lived an hour
\par as happily?"
\par 
\par "You are a philosopher, you there," said the Marquis, smiling. "How do
\par they call you?"
\par 
\par "They call me Defarge."
\par 
\par "Of what trade?"
\par 
\par "Monsieur the Marquis, vendor of wine."
\par 
\par "Pick up that, philosopher and vendor of wine," said the Marquis,
\par throwing him another gold coin, "and spend it as you will. The horses
\par there; are they right?"
\par 
\par Without deigning to look at the assemblage a second time, Monsieur the
\par Marquis leaned back in his seat, and was just being driven away with the
\par air of a gentleman who had accidentally broke some common thing, and had
\par paid for it, and could afford to pay for it; when his ease was suddenly
\par disturbed by a coin flying into his carriage, and ringing on its floor.
\par 
\par "Hold!" said Monsieur the Marquis. "Hold the horses! Who threw that?"
\par 
\par He looked to the spot where Defarge the vendor of wine had stood, a
\par moment before; but the wretched father was grovelling on his face on
\par the pavement in that spot, and the figure that stood beside him was the
\par figure of a dark stout woman, knitting.
\par 
\par "You dogs!" said the Marquis, but smoothly, and with an unchanged front,
\par except as to the spots on his nose: "I would ride over any of you very
\par willingly, and exterminate you from the earth. If I knew which rascal
\par threw at the carriage, and if that brigand were sufficiently near it, he
\par should be crushed under the wheels."
\par 
\par So cowed was their condition, and so long and hard their experience of
\par what such a man could do to them, within the law and beyond it, that not
\par a voice, or a hand, or even an eye was raised. Among the men, not one.
\par But the woman who stood knitting looked up steadily, and looked the
\par Marquis in the face. It was not for his dignity to notice it; his
\par contemptuous eyes passed over her, and over all the other rats; and he
\par leaned back in his seat again, and gave the word "Go on!"
\par 
\par He was driven on, and other carriages came whirling by in quick
\par succession; the Minister, the State-Projector, the Farmer-General, the
\par Doctor, the Lawyer, the Ecclesiastic, the Grand Opera, the Comedy, the
\par whole Fancy Ball in a bright continuous flow, came whirling by. The rats
\par had crept out of their holes to look on, and they remained looking
\par on for hours; soldiers and police often passing between them and the
\par spectacle, and making a barrier behind which they slunk, and through
\par which they peeped. The father had long ago taken up his bundle and
\par bidden himself away with it, when the women who had tended the bundle
\par while it lay on the base of the fountain, sat there watching the running
\par of the water and the rolling of the Fancy Ball--when the one woman who
\par had stood conspicuous, knitting, still knitted on with the steadfastness
\par of Fate. The water of the fountain ran, the swift river ran, the day ran
\par into evening, so much life in the city ran into death according to rule,
\par time and tide waited for no man, the rats were sleeping close together
\par in their dark holes again, the Fancy Ball was lighted up at supper, all
\par things ran their course.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VIII. Monseigneur in the Country
\par 
\par 
\par A beautiful landscape, with the corn bright in it, but not abundant.
\par Patches of poor rye where corn should have been, patches of poor peas
\par and beans, patches of most coarse vegetable substitutes for wheat. On
\par inanimate nature, as on the men and women who cultivated it, a prevalent
\par tendency towards an appearance of vegetating unwillingly--a dejected
\par disposition to give up, and wither away.
\par 
\par Monsieur the Marquis in his travelling carriage (which might have been
\par lighter), conducted by four post-horses and two postilions, fagged up
\par a steep hill. A blush on the countenance of Monsieur the Marquis was
\par no impeachment of his high breeding; it was not from within; it was
\par occasioned by an external circumstance beyond his control--the setting
\par sun.
\par 
\par The sunset struck so brilliantly into the travelling carriage when it
\par gained the hill-top, that its occupant was steeped in crimson. "It will
\par die out," said Monsieur the Marquis, glancing at his hands, "directly."
\par 
\par In effect, the sun was so low that it dipped at the moment. When the
\par heavy drag had been adjusted to the wheel, and the carriage slid down
\par hill, with a cinderous smell, in a cloud of dust, the red glow departed
\par quickly; the sun and the Marquis going down together, there was no glow
\par left when the drag was taken off.
\par 
\par But, there remained a broken country, bold and open, a little village
\par at the bottom of the hill, a broad sweep and rise beyond it, a
\par church-tower, a windmill, a forest for the chase, and a crag with a
\par fortress on it used as a prison. Round upon all these darkening objects
\par as the night drew on, the Marquis looked, with the air of one who was
\par coming near home.
\par 
\par The village had its one poor street, with its poor brewery, poor
\par tannery, poor tavern, poor stable-yard for relays of post-horses, poor
\par fountain, all usual poor appointments. It had its poor people too. All
\par its people were poor, and many of them were sitting at their doors,
\par shredding spare onions and the like for supper, while many were at the
\par fountain, washing leaves, and grasses, and any such small yieldings of
\par the earth that could be eaten. Expressive signs of what made them poor,
\par were not wanting; the tax for the state, the tax for the church, the tax
\par for the lord, tax local and tax general, were to be paid here and to be
\par paid there, according to solemn inscription in the little village, until
\par the wonder was, that there was any village left unswallowed.
\par 
\par Few children were to be seen, and no dogs. As to the men and women,
\par their choice on earth was stated in the prospect--Life on the lowest
\par terms that could sustain it, down in the little village under the mill;
\par or captivity and Death in the dominant prison on the crag.
\par 
\par Heralded by a courier in advance, and by the cracking of his postilions'
\par whips, which twined snake-like about their heads in the evening air, as
\par if he came attended by the Furies, Monsieur the Marquis drew up in
\par his travelling carriage at the posting-house gate. It was hard by the
\par fountain, and the peasants suspended their operations to look at him.
\par He looked at them, and saw in them, without knowing it, the slow
\par sure filing down of misery-worn face and figure, that was to make the
\par meagreness of Frenchmen an English superstition which should survive the
\par truth through the best part of a hundred years.
\par 
\par Monsieur the Marquis cast his eyes over the submissive faces that
\par drooped before him, as the like of himself had drooped before
\par Monseigneur of the Court--only the difference was, that these faces
\par drooped merely to suffer and not to propitiate--when a grizzled mender
\par of the roads joined the group.
\par 
\par "Bring me hither that fellow!" said the Marquis to the courier.
\par 
\par The fellow was brought, cap in hand, and the other fellows closed round
\par to look and listen, in the manner of the people at the Paris fountain.
\par 
\par "I passed you on the road?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, it is true. I had the honour of being passed on the road."
\par 
\par "Coming up the hill, and at the top of the hill, both?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, it is true."
\par 
\par "What did you look at, so fixedly?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, I looked at the man."
\par 
\par He stooped a little, and with his tattered blue cap pointed under the
\par carriage. All his fellows stooped to look under the carriage.
\par 
\par "What man, pig? And why look there?"
\par 
\par "Pardon, Monseigneur; he swung by the chain of the shoe--the drag."
\par 
\par "Who?" demanded the traveller.
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, the man."
\par 
\par "May the Devil carry away these idiots! How do you call the man? You
\par know all the men of this part of the country. Who was he?"
\par 
\par "Your clemency, Monseigneur! He was not of this part of the country. Of
\par all the days of my life, I never saw him."
\par 
\par "Swinging by the chain? To be suffocated?"
\par 
\par "With your gracious permission, that was the wonder of it, Monseigneur.
\par His head hanging over--like this!"
\par 
\par He turned himself sideways to the carriage, and leaned back, with his
\par face thrown up to the sky, and his head hanging down; then recovered
\par himself, fumbled with his cap, and made a bow.
\par 
\par "What was he like?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, he was whiter than the miller. All covered with dust,
\par white as a spectre, tall as a spectre!"
\par 
\par The picture produced an immense sensation in the little crowd; but all
\par eyes, without comparing notes with other eyes, looked at Monsieur
\par the Marquis. Perhaps, to observe whether he had any spectre on his
\par conscience.
\par 
\par "Truly, you did well," said the Marquis, felicitously sensible that such
\par vermin were not to ruffle him, "to see a thief accompanying my carriage,
\par and not open that great mouth of yours. Bah! Put him aside, Monsieur
\par Gabelle!"
\par 
\par Monsieur Gabelle was the Postmaster, and some other taxing functionary
\par united; he had come out with great obsequiousness to assist at this
\par examination, and had held the examined by the drapery of his arm in an
\par official manner.
\par 
\par "Bah! Go aside!" said Monsieur Gabelle.
\par 
\par "Lay hands on this stranger if he seeks to lodge in your village
\par to-night, and be sure that his business is honest, Gabelle."
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, I am flattered to devote myself to your orders."
\par 
\par "Did he run away, fellow?--where is that Accursed?"
\par 
\par The accursed was already under the carriage with some half-dozen
\par particular friends, pointing out the chain with his blue cap. Some
\par half-dozen other particular friends promptly hauled him out, and
\par presented him breathless to Monsieur the Marquis.
\par 
\par "Did the man run away, Dolt, when we stopped for the drag?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, he precipitated himself over the hill-side, head first, as
\par a person plunges into the river."
\par 
\par "See to it, Gabelle. Go on!"
\par 
\par The half-dozen who were peering at the chain were still among the
\par wheels, like sheep; the wheels turned so suddenly that they were lucky
\par to save their skins and bones; they had very little else to save, or
\par they might not have been so fortunate.
\par 
\par The burst with which the carriage started out of the village and up the
\par rise beyond, was soon checked by the steepness of the hill. Gradually,
\par it subsided to a foot pace, swinging and lumbering upward among the many
\par sweet scents of a summer night. The postilions, with a thousand gossamer
\par gnats circling about them in lieu of the Furies, quietly mended the
\par points to the lashes of their whips; the valet walked by the horses; the
\par courier was audible, trotting on ahead into the dull distance.
\par 
\par At the steepest point of the hill there was a little burial-ground,
\par with a Cross and a new large figure of Our Saviour on it; it was a poor
\par figure in wood, done by some inexperienced rustic carver, but he had
\par studied the figure from the life--his own life, maybe--for it was
\par dreadfully spare and thin.
\par 
\par To this distressful emblem of a great distress that had long been
\par growing worse, and was not at its worst, a woman was kneeling. She
\par turned her head as the carriage came up to her, rose quickly, and
\par presented herself at the carriage-door.
\par 
\par "It is you, Monseigneur! Monseigneur, a petition."
\par 
\par With an exclamation of impatience, but with his unchangeable face,
\par Monseigneur looked out.
\par 
\par "How, then! What is it? Always petitions!"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur. For the love of the great God! My husband, the forester."
\par 
\par "What of your husband, the forester? Always the same with you people. He
\par cannot pay something?"
\par 
\par "He has paid all, Monseigneur. He is dead."
\par 
\par "Well! He is quiet. Can I restore him to you?"
\par 
\par "Alas, no, Monseigneur! But he lies yonder, under a little heap of poor
\par grass."
\par 
\par "Well?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, there are so many little heaps of poor grass?"
\par 
\par "Again, well?"
\par 
\par She looked an old woman, but was young. Her manner was one of passionate
\par grief; by turns she clasped her veinous and knotted hands together
\par with wild energy, and laid one of them on the carriage-door--tenderly,
\par caressingly, as if it had been a human breast, and could be expected to
\par feel the appealing touch.
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, hear me! Monseigneur, hear my petition! My husband died of
\par want; so many die of want; so many more will die of want."
\par 
\par "Again, well? Can I feed them?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, the good God knows; but I don't ask it. My petition is,
\par that a morsel of stone or wood, with my husband's name, may be placed
\par over him to show where he lies. Otherwise, the place will be quickly
\par forgotten, it will never be found when I am dead of the same malady, I
\par shall be laid under some other heap of poor grass. Monseigneur, they
\par are so many, they increase so fast, there is so much want. Monseigneur!
\par Monseigneur!"
\par 
\par The valet had put her away from the door, the carriage had broken into
\par a brisk trot, the postilions had quickened the pace, she was left far
\par behind, and Monseigneur, again escorted by the Furies, was rapidly
\par diminishing the league or two of distance that remained between him and
\par his chateau.
\par 
\par The sweet scents of the summer night rose all around him, and rose, as
\par the rain falls, impartially, on the dusty, ragged, and toil-worn group
\par at the fountain not far away; to whom the mender of roads, with the aid
\par of the blue cap without which he was nothing, still enlarged upon his
\par man like a spectre, as long as they could bear it. By degrees, as they
\par could bear no more, they dropped off one by one, and lights twinkled
\par in little casements; which lights, as the casements darkened, and more
\par stars came out, seemed to have shot up into the sky instead of having
\par been extinguished.
\par 
\par The shadow of a large high-roofed house, and of many over-hanging trees,
\par was upon Monsieur the Marquis by that time; and the shadow was exchanged
\par for the light of a flambeau, as his carriage stopped, and the great door
\par of his chateau was opened to him.
\par 
\par "Monsieur Charles, whom I expect; is he arrived from England?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, not yet."
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par IX. The Gorgon's Head
\par 
\par 
\par It was a heavy mass of building, that chateau of Monsieur the Marquis,
\par with a large stone courtyard before it, and two stone sweeps of
\par staircase meeting in a stone terrace before the principal door. A stony
\par business altogether, with heavy stone balustrades, and stone urns, and
\par stone flowers, and stone faces of men, and stone heads of lions, in
\par all directions. As if the Gorgon's head had surveyed it, when it was
\par finished, two centuries ago.
\par 
\par Up the broad flight of shallow steps, Monsieur the Marquis, flambeau
\par preceded, went from his carriage, sufficiently disturbing the darkness
\par to elicit loud remonstrance from an owl in the roof of the great pile
\par of stable building away among the trees. All else was so quiet, that the
\par flambeau carried up the steps, and the other flambeau held at the great
\par door, burnt as if they were in a close room of state, instead of being
\par in the open night-air. Other sound than the owl's voice there was none,
\par save the falling of a fountain into its stone basin; for, it was one of
\par those dark nights that hold their breath by the hour together, and then
\par heave a long low sigh, and hold their breath again.
\par 
\par The great door clanged behind him, and Monsieur the Marquis crossed a
\par hall grim with certain old boar-spears, swords, and knives of the chase;
\par grimmer with certain heavy riding-rods and riding-whips, of which many a
\par peasant, gone to his benefactor Death, had felt the weight when his lord
\par was angry.
\par 
\par Avoiding the larger rooms, which were dark and made fast for the night,
\par Monsieur the Marquis, with his flambeau-bearer going on before, went up
\par the staircase to a door in a corridor. This thrown open, admitted him
\par to his own private apartment of three rooms: his bed-chamber and two
\par others. High vaulted rooms with cool uncarpeted floors, great dogs upon
\par the hearths for the burning of wood in winter time, and all luxuries
\par befitting the state of a marquis in a luxurious age and country.
\par The fashion of the last Louis but one, of the line that was never to
\par break--the fourteenth Louis--was conspicuous in their rich furniture;
\par but, it was diversified by many objects that were illustrations of old
\par pages in the history of France.
\par 
\par A supper-table was laid for two, in the third of the rooms; a round
\par room, in one of the chateau's four extinguisher-topped towers. A small
\par lofty room, with its window wide open, and the wooden jalousie-blinds
\par closed, so that the dark night only showed in slight horizontal lines of
\par black, alternating with their broad lines of stone colour.
\par 
\par "My nephew," said the Marquis, glancing at the supper preparation; "they
\par said he was not arrived."
\par 
\par Nor was he; but, he had been expected with Monseigneur.
\par 
\par "Ah! It is not probable he will arrive to-night; nevertheless, leave the
\par table as it is. I shall be ready in a quarter of an hour."
\par 
\par In a quarter of an hour Monseigneur was ready, and sat down alone to his
\par sumptuous and choice supper. His chair was opposite to the window, and
\par he had taken his soup, and was raising his glass of Bordeaux to his
\par lips, when he put it down.
\par 
\par "What is that?" he calmly asked, looking with attention at the
\par horizontal lines of black and stone colour.
\par 
\par "Monseigneur? That?"
\par 
\par "Outside the blinds. Open the blinds."
\par 
\par It was done.
\par 
\par "Well?"
\par 
\par "Monseigneur, it is nothing. The trees and the night are all that are
\par here."
\par 
\par The servant who spoke, had thrown the blinds wide, had looked out into
\par the vacant darkness, and stood with that blank behind him, looking round
\par for instructions.
\par 
\par "Good," said the imperturbable master. "Close them again."
\par 
\par That was done too, and the Marquis went on with his supper. He was
\par half way through it, when he again stopped with his glass in his hand,
\par hearing the sound of wheels. It came on briskly, and came up to the
\par front of the chateau.
\par 
\par "Ask who is arrived."
\par 
\par It was the nephew of Monseigneur. He had been some few leagues behind
\par Monseigneur, early in the afternoon. He had diminished the distance
\par rapidly, but not so rapidly as to come up with Monseigneur on the road.
\par He had heard of Monseigneur, at the posting-houses, as being before him.
\par 
\par He was to be told (said Monseigneur) that supper awaited him then and
\par there, and that he was prayed to come to it. In a little while he came.
\par He had been known in England as Charles Darnay.
\par 
\par Monseigneur received him in a courtly manner, but they did not shake
\par hands.
\par 
\par "You left Paris yesterday, sir?" he said to Monseigneur, as he took his
\par seat at table.
\par 
\par "Yesterday. And you?"
\par 
\par "I come direct."
\par 
\par "From London?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "You have been a long time coming," said the Marquis, with a smile.
\par 
\par "On the contrary; I come direct."
\par 
\par "Pardon me! I mean, not a long time on the journey; a long time
\par intending the journey."
\par 
\par "I have been detained by"--the nephew stopped a moment in his
\par answer--"various business."
\par 
\par "Without doubt," said the polished uncle.
\par 
\par So long as a servant was present, no other words passed between them.
\par When coffee had been served and they were alone together, the nephew,
\par looking at the uncle and meeting the eyes of the face that was like a
\par fine mask, opened a conversation.
\par 
\par "I have come back, sir, as you anticipate, pursuing the object that
\par took me away. It carried me into great and unexpected peril; but it is
\par a sacred object, and if it had carried me to death I hope it would have
\par sustained me."
\par 
\par "Not to death," said the uncle; "it is not necessary to say, to death."
\par 
\par "I doubt, sir," returned the nephew, "whether, if it had carried me to
\par the utmost brink of death, you would have cared to stop me there."
\par 
\par The deepened marks in the nose, and the lengthening of the fine straight
\par lines in the cruel face, looked ominous as to that; the uncle made a
\par graceful gesture of protest, which was so clearly a slight form of good
\par breeding that it was not reassuring.
\par 
\par "Indeed, sir," pursued the nephew, "for anything I know, you may have
\par expressly worked to give a more suspicious appearance to the suspicious
\par circumstances that surrounded me."
\par 
\par "No, no, no," said the uncle, pleasantly.
\par 
\par "But, however that may be," resumed the nephew, glancing at him with
\par deep distrust, "I know that your diplomacy would stop me by any means,
\par and would know no scruple as to means."
\par 
\par "My friend, I told you so," said the uncle, with a fine pulsation in the
\par two marks. "Do me the favour to recall that I told you so, long ago."
\par 
\par "I recall it."
\par 
\par "Thank you," said the Marquis--very sweetly indeed.
\par 
\par His tone lingered in the air, almost like the tone of a musical
\par instrument.
\par 
\par "In effect, sir," pursued the nephew, "I believe it to be at once your
\par bad fortune, and my good fortune, that has kept me out of a prison in
\par France here."
\par 
\par "I do not quite understand," returned the uncle, sipping his coffee.
\par "Dare I ask you to explain?"
\par 
\par "I believe that if you were not in disgrace with the Court, and had not
\par been overshadowed by that cloud for years past, a letter de cachet would
\par have sent me to some fortress indefinitely."
\par 
\par "It is possible," said the uncle, with great calmness. "For the honour
\par of the family, I could even resolve to incommode you to that extent.
\par Pray excuse me!"
\par 
\par "I perceive that, happily for me, the Reception of the day before
\par yesterday was, as usual, a cold one," observed the nephew.
\par 
\par "I would not say happily, my friend," returned the uncle, with refined
\par politeness; "I would not be sure of that. A good opportunity for
\par consideration, surrounded by the advantages of solitude, might influence
\par your destiny to far greater advantage than you influence it for
\par yourself. But it is useless to discuss the question. I am, as you say,
\par at a disadvantage. These little instruments of correction, these gentle
\par aids to the power and honour of families, these slight favours that
\par might so incommode you, are only to be obtained now by interest
\par and importunity. They are sought by so many, and they are granted
\par (comparatively) to so few! It used not to be so, but France in all such
\par things is changed for the worse. Our not remote ancestors held the right
\par of life and death over the surrounding vulgar. From this room, many such
\par dogs have been taken out to be hanged; in the next room (my bedroom),
\par one fellow, to our knowledge, was poniarded on the spot for professing
\par some insolent delicacy respecting his daughter--_his_ daughter? We have
\par lost many privileges; a new philosophy has become the mode; and the
\par assertion of our station, in these days, might (I do not go so far as
\par to say would, but might) cause us real inconvenience. All very bad, very
\par bad!"
\par 
\par The Marquis took a gentle little pinch of snuff, and shook his head;
\par as elegantly despondent as he could becomingly be of a country still
\par containing himself, that great means of regeneration.
\par 
\par "We have so asserted our station, both in the old time and in the modern
\par time also," said the nephew, gloomily, "that I believe our name to be
\par more detested than any name in France."
\par 
\par "Let us hope so," said the uncle. "Detestation of the high is the
\par involuntary homage of the low."
\par 
\par "There is not," pursued the nephew, in his former tone, "a face I can
\par look at, in all this country round about us, which looks at me with any
\par deference on it but the dark deference of fear and slavery."
\par 
\par "A compliment," said the Marquis, "to the grandeur of the family,
\par merited by the manner in which the family has sustained its grandeur.
\par Hah!" And he took another gentle little pinch of snuff, and lightly
\par crossed his legs.
\par 
\par But, when his nephew, leaning an elbow on the table, covered his eyes
\par thoughtfully and dejectedly with his hand, the fine mask looked at
\par him sideways with a stronger concentration of keenness, closeness,
\par and dislike, than was comportable with its wearer's assumption of
\par indifference.
\par 
\par "Repression is the only lasting philosophy. The dark deference of fear
\par and slavery, my friend," observed the Marquis, "will keep the dogs
\par obedient to the whip, as long as this roof," looking up to it, "shuts
\par out the sky."
\par 
\par That might not be so long as the Marquis supposed. If a picture of the
\par chateau as it was to be a very few years hence, and of fifty like it as
\par they too were to be a very few years hence, could have been shown to
\par him that night, he might have been at a loss to claim his own from
\par the ghastly, fire-charred, plunder-wrecked rains. As for the roof
\par he vaunted, he might have found _that_ shutting out the sky in a new
\par way--to wit, for ever, from the eyes of the bodies into which its lead
\par was fired, out of the barrels of a hundred thousand muskets.
\par 
\par "Meanwhile," said the Marquis, "I will preserve the honour and repose
\par of the family, if you will not. But you must be fatigued. Shall we
\par terminate our conference for the night?"
\par 
\par "A moment more."
\par 
\par "An hour, if you please."
\par 
\par "Sir," said the nephew, "we have done wrong, and are reaping the fruits
\par of wrong."
\par 
\par "_We_ have done wrong?" repeated the Marquis, with an inquiring smile,
\par and delicately pointing, first to his nephew, then to himself.
\par 
\par "Our family; our honourable family, whose honour is of so much account
\par to both of us, in such different ways. Even in my father's time, we did
\par a world of wrong, injuring every human creature who came between us and
\par our pleasure, whatever it was. Why need I speak of my father's time,
\par when it is equally yours? Can I separate my father's twin-brother, joint
\par inheritor, and next successor, from himself?"
\par 
\par "Death has done that!" said the Marquis.
\par 
\par "And has left me," answered the nephew, "bound to a system that is
\par frightful to me, responsible for it, but powerless in it; seeking to
\par execute the last request of my dear mother's lips, and obey the last
\par look of my dear mother's eyes, which implored me to have mercy and to
\par redress; and tortured by seeking assistance and power in vain."
\par 
\par "Seeking them from me, my nephew," said the Marquis, touching him on the
\par breast with his forefinger--they were now standing by the hearth--"you
\par will for ever seek them in vain, be assured."
\par 
\par Every fine straight line in the clear whiteness of his face, was
\par cruelly, craftily, and closely compressed, while he stood looking
\par quietly at his nephew, with his snuff-box in his hand. Once again he
\par touched him on the breast, as though his finger were the fine point of
\par a small sword, with which, in delicate finesse, he ran him through the
\par body, and said,
\par 
\par "My friend, I will die, perpetuating the system under which I have
\par lived."
\par 
\par When he had said it, he took a culminating pinch of snuff, and put his
\par box in his pocket.
\par 
\par "Better to be a rational creature," he added then, after ringing a small
\par bell on the table, "and accept your natural destiny. But you are lost,
\par Monsieur Charles, I see."
\par 
\par "This property and France are lost to me," said the nephew, sadly; "I
\par renounce them."
\par 
\par "Are they both yours to renounce? France may be, but is the property? It
\par is scarcely worth mentioning; but, is it yet?"
\par 
\par "I had no intention, in the words I used, to claim it yet. If it passed
\par to me from you, to-morrow--"
\par 
\par "Which I have the vanity to hope is not probable."
\par 
\par "--or twenty years hence--"
\par 
\par "You do me too much honour," said the Marquis; "still, I prefer that
\par supposition."
\par 
\par "--I would abandon it, and live otherwise and elsewhere. It is little to
\par relinquish. What is it but a wilderness of misery and ruin!"
\par 
\par "Hah!" said the Marquis, glancing round the luxurious room.
\par 
\par "To the eye it is fair enough, here; but seen in its integrity,
\par under the sky, and by the daylight, it is a crumbling tower of waste,
\par mismanagement, extortion, debt, mortgage, oppression, hunger, nakedness,
\par and suffering."
\par 
\par "Hah!" said the Marquis again, in a well-satisfied manner.
\par 
\par "If it ever becomes mine, it shall be put into some hands better
\par qualified to free it slowly (if such a thing is possible) from the
\par weight that drags it down, so that the miserable people who cannot leave
\par it and who have been long wrung to the last point of endurance, may, in
\par another generation, suffer less; but it is not for me. There is a curse
\par on it, and on all this land."
\par 
\par "And you?" said the uncle. "Forgive my curiosity; do you, under your new
\par philosophy, graciously intend to live?"
\par 
\par "I must do, to live, what others of my countrymen, even with nobility at
\par their backs, may have to do some day--work."
\par 
\par "In England, for example?"
\par 
\par "Yes. The family honour, sir, is safe from me in this country. The
\par family name can suffer from me in no other, for I bear it in no other."
\par 
\par The ringing of the bell had caused the adjoining bed-chamber to be
\par lighted. It now shone brightly, through the door of communication. The
\par Marquis looked that way, and listened for the retreating step of his
\par valet.
\par 
\par "England is very attractive to you, seeing how indifferently you have
\par prospered there," he observed then, turning his calm face to his nephew
\par with a smile.
\par 
\par "I have already said, that for my prospering there, I am sensible I may
\par be indebted to you, sir. For the rest, it is my Refuge."
\par 
\par "They say, those boastful English, that it is the Refuge of many. You
\par know a compatriot who has found a Refuge there? A Doctor?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "With a daughter?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "Yes," said the Marquis. "You are fatigued. Good night!"
\par 
\par As he bent his head in his most courtly manner, there was a secrecy
\par in his smiling face, and he conveyed an air of mystery to those words,
\par which struck the eyes and ears of his nephew forcibly. At the same
\par time, the thin straight lines of the setting of the eyes, and the thin
\par straight lips, and the markings in the nose, curved with a sarcasm that
\par looked handsomely diabolic.
\par 
\par "Yes," repeated the Marquis. "A Doctor with a daughter. Yes. So
\par commences the new philosophy! You are fatigued. Good night!"
\par 
\par It would have been of as much avail to interrogate any stone face
\par outside the chateau as to interrogate that face of his. The nephew
\par looked at him, in vain, in passing on to the door.
\par 
\par "Good night!" said the uncle. "I look to the pleasure of seeing you
\par again in the morning. Good repose! Light Monsieur my nephew to his
\par chamber there!--And burn Monsieur my nephew in his bed, if you will," he
\par added to himself, before he rang his little bell again, and summoned his
\par valet to his own bedroom.
\par 
\par The valet come and gone, Monsieur the Marquis walked to and fro in his
\par loose chamber-robe, to prepare himself gently for sleep, that hot still
\par night. Rustling about the room, his softly-slippered feet making no
\par noise on the floor, he moved like a refined tiger:--looked like some
\par enchanted marquis of the impenitently wicked sort, in story, whose
\par periodical change into tiger form was either just going off, or just
\par coming on.
\par 
\par He moved from end to end of his voluptuous bedroom, looking again at the
\par scraps of the day's journey that came unbidden into his mind; the slow
\par toil up the hill at sunset, the setting sun, the descent, the mill, the
\par prison on the crag, the little village in the hollow, the peasants at
\par the fountain, and the mender of roads with his blue cap pointing out the
\par chain under the carriage. That fountain suggested the Paris fountain,
\par the little bundle lying on the step, the women bending over it, and the
\par tall man with his arms up, crying, "Dead!"
\par 
\par "I am cool now," said Monsieur the Marquis, "and may go to bed."
\par 
\par So, leaving only one light burning on the large hearth, he let his thin
\par gauze curtains fall around him, and heard the night break its silence
\par with a long sigh as he composed himself to sleep.
\par 
\par The stone faces on the outer walls stared blindly at the black night
\par for three heavy hours; for three heavy hours, the horses in the stables
\par rattled at their racks, the dogs barked, and the owl made a noise with
\par very little resemblance in it to the noise conventionally assigned to
\par the owl by men-poets. But it is the obstinate custom of such creatures
\par hardly ever to say what is set down for them.
\par 
\par For three heavy hours, the stone faces of the chateau, lion and human,
\par stared blindly at the night. Dead darkness lay on all the landscape,
\par dead darkness added its own hush to the hushing dust on all the roads.
\par The burial-place had got to the pass that its little heaps of poor grass
\par were undistinguishable from one another; the figure on the Cross might
\par have come down, for anything that could be seen of it. In the village,
\par taxers and taxed were fast asleep. Dreaming, perhaps, of banquets, as
\par the starved usually do, and of ease and rest, as the driven slave and
\par the yoked ox may, its lean inhabitants slept soundly, and were fed and
\par freed.
\par 
\par The fountain in the village flowed unseen and unheard, and the fountain
\par at the chateau dropped unseen and unheard--both melting away, like the
\par minutes that were falling from the spring of Time--through three dark
\par hours. Then, the grey water of both began to be ghostly in the light,
\par and the eyes of the stone faces of the chateau were opened.
\par 
\par Lighter and lighter, until at last the sun touched the tops of the still
\par trees, and poured its radiance over the hill. In the glow, the water
\par of the chateau fountain seemed to turn to blood, and the stone faces
\par crimsoned. The carol of the birds was loud and high, and, on the
\par weather-beaten sill of the great window of the bed-chamber of Monsieur
\par the Marquis, one little bird sang its sweetest song with all its might.
\par At this, the nearest stone face seemed to stare amazed, and, with open
\par mouth and dropped under-jaw, looked awe-stricken.
\par 
\par Now, the sun was full up, and movement began in the village. Casement
\par windows opened, crazy doors were unbarred, and people came forth
\par shivering--chilled, as yet, by the new sweet air. Then began the rarely
\par lightened toil of the day among the village population. Some, to the
\par fountain; some, to the fields; men and women here, to dig and delve; men
\par and women there, to see to the poor live stock, and lead the bony cows
\par out, to such pasture as could be found by the roadside. In the church
\par and at the Cross, a kneeling figure or two; attendant on the latter
\par prayers, the led cow, trying for a breakfast among the weeds at its
\par foot.
\par 
\par The chateau awoke later, as became its quality, but awoke gradually and
\par surely. First, the lonely boar-spears and knives of the chase had been
\par reddened as of old; then, had gleamed trenchant in the morning sunshine;
\par now, doors and windows were thrown open, horses in their stables looked
\par round over their shoulders at the light and freshness pouring in at
\par doorways, leaves sparkled and rustled at iron-grated windows, dogs
\par pulled hard at their chains, and reared impatient to be loosed.
\par 
\par All these trivial incidents belonged to the routine of life, and the
\par return of morning. Surely, not so the ringing of the great bell of the
\par chateau, nor the running up and down the stairs; nor the hurried
\par figures on the terrace; nor the booting and tramping here and there and
\par everywhere, nor the quick saddling of horses and riding away?
\par 
\par What winds conveyed this hurry to the grizzled mender of roads, already
\par at work on the hill-top beyond the village, with his day's dinner (not
\par much to carry) lying in a bundle that it was worth no crow's while to
\par peck at, on a heap of stones? Had the birds, carrying some grains of it
\par to a distance, dropped one over him as they sow chance seeds? Whether or
\par no, the mender of roads ran, on the sultry morning, as if for his life,
\par down the hill, knee-high in dust, and never stopped till he got to the
\par fountain.
\par 
\par All the people of the village were at the fountain, standing about
\par in their depressed manner, and whispering low, but showing no other
\par emotions than grim curiosity and surprise. The led cows, hastily brought
\par in and tethered to anything that would hold them, were looking stupidly
\par on, or lying down chewing the cud of nothing particularly repaying their
\par trouble, which they had picked up in their interrupted saunter. Some of
