\par 
\par X. Two Promises
\par 
\par 
\par More months, to the number of twelve, had come and gone, and Mr. Charles
\par Darnay was established in England as a higher teacher of the French
\par language who was conversant with French literature. In this age, he
\par would have been a Professor; in that age, he was a Tutor. He read with
\par young men who could find any leisure and interest for the study of a
\par living tongue spoken all over the world, and he cultivated a taste for
\par its stores of knowledge and fancy. He could write of them, besides, in
\par sound English, and render them into sound English. Such masters were not
\par at that time easily found; Princes that had been, and Kings that were
\par to be, were not yet of the Teacher class, and no ruined nobility had
\par dropped out of Tellson's ledgers, to turn cooks and carpenters. As a
\par tutor, whose attainments made the student's way unusually pleasant and
\par profitable, and as an elegant translator who brought something to his
\par work besides mere dictionary knowledge, young Mr. Darnay soon became
\par known and encouraged. He was well acquainted, more-over, with the
\par circumstances of his country, and those were of ever-growing interest.
\par So, with great perseverance and untiring industry, he prospered.
\par 
\par In London, he had expected neither to walk on pavements of gold, nor
\par to lie on beds of roses; if he had had any such exalted expectation, he
\par would not have prospered. He had expected labour, and he found it, and
\par did it and made the best of it. In this, his prosperity consisted.
\par 
\par A certain portion of his time was passed at Cambridge, where he
\par read with undergraduates as a sort of tolerated smuggler who drove a
\par contraband trade in European languages, instead of conveying Greek
\par and Latin through the Custom-house. The rest of his time he passed in
\par London.
\par 
\par Now, from the days when it was always summer in Eden, to these days
\par when it is mostly winter in fallen latitudes, the world of a man has
\par invariably gone one way--Charles Darnay's way--the way of the love of a
\par woman.
\par 
\par He had loved Lucie Manette from the hour of his danger. He had never
\par heard a sound so sweet and dear as the sound of her compassionate voice;
\par he had never seen a face so tenderly beautiful, as hers when it was
\par confronted with his own on the edge of the grave that had been dug for
\par him. But, he had not yet spoken to her on the subject; the assassination
\par at the deserted chateau far away beyond the heaving water and the long,
\par long, dusty roads--the solid stone chateau which had itself become the
\par mere mist of a dream--had been done a year, and he had never yet, by so
\par much as a single spoken word, disclosed to her the state of his heart.
\par 
\par That he had his reasons for this, he knew full well. It was again a
\par summer day when, lately arrived in London from his college occupation,
\par he turned into the quiet corner in Soho, bent on seeking an opportunity
\par of opening his mind to Doctor Manette. It was the close of the summer
\par day, and he knew Lucie to be out with Miss Pross.
\par 
\par He found the Doctor reading in his arm-chair at a window. The energy
\par which had at once supported him under his old sufferings and aggravated
\par their sharpness, had been gradually restored to him. He was now a
\par very energetic man indeed, with great firmness of purpose, strength
\par of resolution, and vigour of action. In his recovered energy he was
\par sometimes a little fitful and sudden, as he had at first been in the
\par exercise of his other recovered faculties; but, this had never been
\par frequently observable, and had grown more and more rare.
\par 
\par He studied much, slept little, sustained a great deal of fatigue with
\par ease, and was equably cheerful. To him, now entered Charles Darnay, at
\par sight of whom he laid aside his book and held out his hand.
\par 
\par "Charles Darnay! I rejoice to see you. We have been counting on your
\par return these three or four days past. Mr. Stryver and Sydney Carton were
\par both here yesterday, and both made you out to be more than due."
\par 
\par "I am obliged to them for their interest in the matter," he answered,
\par a little coldly as to them, though very warmly as to the Doctor. "Miss
\par Manette--"
\par 
\par "Is well," said the Doctor, as he stopped short, "and your return will
\par delight us all. She has gone out on some household matters, but will
\par soon be home."
\par 
\par "Doctor Manette, I knew she was from home. I took the opportunity of her
\par being from home, to beg to speak to you."
\par 
\par There was a blank silence.
\par 
\par "Yes?" said the Doctor, with evident constraint. "Bring your chair here,
\par and speak on."
\par 
\par He complied as to the chair, but appeared to find the speaking on less
\par easy.
\par 
\par "I have had the happiness, Doctor Manette, of being so intimate here,"
\par so he at length began, "for some year and a half, that I hope the topic
\par on which I am about to touch may not--"
\par 
\par He was stayed by the Doctor's putting out his hand to stop him. When he
\par had kept it so a little while, he said, drawing it back:
\par 
\par "Is Lucie the topic?"
\par 
\par "She is."
\par 
\par "It is hard for me to speak of her at any time. It is very hard for me
\par to hear her spoken of in that tone of yours, Charles Darnay."
\par 
\par "It is a tone of fervent admiration, true homage, and deep love, Doctor
\par Manette!" he said deferentially.
\par 
\par There was another blank silence before her father rejoined:
\par 
\par "I believe it. I do you justice; I believe it."
\par 
\par His constraint was so manifest, and it was so manifest, too, that it
\par originated in an unwillingness to approach the subject, that Charles
\par Darnay hesitated.
\par 
\par "Shall I go on, sir?"
\par 
\par Another blank.
\par 
\par "Yes, go on."
\par 
\par "You anticipate what I would say, though you cannot know how earnestly
\par I say it, how earnestly I feel it, without knowing my secret heart, and
\par the hopes and fears and anxieties with which it has long been
\par laden. Dear Doctor Manette, I love your daughter fondly, dearly,
\par disinterestedly, devotedly. If ever there were love in the world, I love
\par her. You have loved yourself; let your old love speak for me!"
\par 
\par The Doctor sat with his face turned away, and his eyes bent on the
\par ground. At the last words, he stretched out his hand again, hurriedly,
\par and cried:
\par 
\par "Not that, sir! Let that be! I adjure you, do not recall that!"
\par 
\par His cry was so like a cry of actual pain, that it rang in Charles
\par Darnay's ears long after he had ceased. He motioned with the hand he had
\par extended, and it seemed to be an appeal to Darnay to pause. The latter
\par so received it, and remained silent.
\par 
\par "I ask your pardon," said the Doctor, in a subdued tone, after some
\par moments. "I do not doubt your loving Lucie; you may be satisfied of it."
\par 
\par He turned towards him in his chair, but did not look at him, or
\par raise his eyes. His chin dropped upon his hand, and his white hair
\par overshadowed his face:
\par 
\par "Have you spoken to Lucie?"
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par "Nor written?"
\par 
\par "Never."
\par 
\par "It would be ungenerous to affect not to know that your self-denial is
\par to be referred to your consideration for her father. Her father thanks
\par you."
\par 
\par He offered his hand; but his eyes did not go with it.
\par 
\par "I know," said Darnay, respectfully, "how can I fail to know, Doctor
\par Manette, I who have seen you together from day to day, that between
\par you and Miss Manette there is an affection so unusual, so touching, so
\par belonging to the circumstances in which it has been nurtured, that it
\par can have few parallels, even in the tenderness between a father and
\par child. I know, Doctor Manette--how can I fail to know--that, mingled
\par with the affection and duty of a daughter who has become a woman, there
\par is, in her heart, towards you, all the love and reliance of infancy
\par itself. I know that, as in her childhood she had no parent, so she is
\par now devoted to you with all the constancy and fervour of her present
\par years and character, united to the trustfulness and attachment of the
\par early days in which you were lost to her. I know perfectly well that if
\par you had been restored to her from the world beyond this life, you could
\par hardly be invested, in her sight, with a more sacred character than that
\par in which you are always with her. I know that when she is clinging to
\par you, the hands of baby, girl, and woman, all in one, are round your
\par neck. I know that in loving you she sees and loves her mother at her
\par own age, sees and loves you at my age, loves her mother broken-hearted,
\par loves you through your dreadful trial and in your blessed restoration. I
\par have known this, night and day, since I have known you in your home."
\par 
\par Her father sat silent, with his face bent down. His breathing was a
\par little quickened; but he repressed all other signs of agitation.
\par 
\par "Dear Doctor Manette, always knowing this, always seeing her and you
\par with this hallowed light about you, I have forborne, and forborne, as
\par long as it was in the nature of man to do it. I have felt, and do even
\par now feel, that to bring my love--even mine--between you, is to touch
\par your history with something not quite so good as itself. But I love her.
\par Heaven is my witness that I love her!"
\par 
\par "I believe it," answered her father, mournfully. "I have thought so
\par before now. I believe it."
\par 
\par "But, do not believe," said Darnay, upon whose ear the mournful voice
\par struck with a reproachful sound, "that if my fortune were so cast as
\par that, being one day so happy as to make her my wife, I must at any time
\par put any separation between her and you, I could or would breathe a
\par word of what I now say. Besides that I should know it to be hopeless, I
\par should know it to be a baseness. If I had any such possibility, even at
\par a remote distance of years, harboured in my thoughts, and hidden in my
\par heart--if it ever had been there--if it ever could be there--I could not
\par now touch this honoured hand."
\par 
\par He laid his own upon it as he spoke.
\par 
\par "No, dear Doctor Manette. Like you, a voluntary exile from France; like
\par you, driven from it by its distractions, oppressions, and miseries; like
\par you, striving to live away from it by my own exertions, and trusting
\par in a happier future; I look only to sharing your fortunes, sharing your
\par life and home, and being faithful to you to the death. Not to divide
\par with Lucie her privilege as your child, companion, and friend; but to
\par come in aid of it, and bind her closer to you, if such a thing can be."
\par 
\par His touch still lingered on her father's hand. Answering the touch for a
\par moment, but not coldly, her father rested his hands upon the arms of
\par his chair, and looked up for the first time since the beginning of the
\par conference. A struggle was evidently in his face; a struggle with that
\par occasional look which had a tendency in it to dark doubt and dread.
\par 
\par "You speak so feelingly and so manfully, Charles Darnay, that I thank
\par you with all my heart, and will open all my heart--or nearly so. Have
\par you any reason to believe that Lucie loves you?"
\par 
\par "None. As yet, none."
\par 
\par "Is it the immediate object of this confidence, that you may at once
\par ascertain that, with my knowledge?"
\par 
\par "Not even so. I might not have the hopefulness to do it for weeks; I
\par might (mistaken or not mistaken) have that hopefulness to-morrow."
\par 
\par "Do you seek any guidance from me?"
\par 
\par "I ask none, sir. But I have thought it possible that you might have it
\par in your power, if you should deem it right, to give me some."
\par 
\par "Do you seek any promise from me?"
\par 
\par "I do seek that."
\par 
\par "What is it?"
\par 
\par "I well understand that, without you, I could have no hope. I well
\par understand that, even if Miss Manette held me at this moment in her
\par innocent heart--do not think I have the presumption to assume so much--I
\par could retain no place in it against her love for her father."
\par 
\par "If that be so, do you see what, on the other hand, is involved in it?"
\par 
\par "I understand equally well, that a word from her father in any suitor's
\par favour, would outweigh herself and all the world. For which reason,
\par Doctor Manette," said Darnay, modestly but firmly, "I would not ask that
\par word, to save my life."
\par 
\par "I am sure of it. Charles Darnay, mysteries arise out of close love, as
\par well as out of wide division; in the former case, they are subtle and
\par delicate, and difficult to penetrate. My daughter Lucie is, in this one
\par respect, such a mystery to me; I can make no guess at the state of her
\par heart."
\par 
\par "May I ask, sir, if you think she is--" As he hesitated, her father
\par supplied the rest.
\par 
\par "Is sought by any other suitor?"
\par 
\par "It is what I meant to say."
\par 
\par Her father considered a little before he answered:
\par 
\par "You have seen Mr. Carton here, yourself. Mr. Stryver is here too,
\par occasionally. If it be at all, it can only be by one of these."
\par 
\par "Or both," said Darnay.
\par 
\par "I had not thought of both; I should not think either, likely. You want
\par a promise from me. Tell me what it is."
\par 
\par "It is, that if Miss Manette should bring to you at any time, on her own
\par part, such a confidence as I have ventured to lay before you, you will
\par bear testimony to what I have said, and to your belief in it. I hope you
\par may be able to think so well of me, as to urge no influence against
\par me. I say nothing more of my stake in this; this is what I ask. The
\par condition on which I ask it, and which you have an undoubted right to
\par require, I will observe immediately."
\par 
\par "I give the promise," said the Doctor, "without any condition. I believe
\par your object to be, purely and truthfully, as you have stated it. I
\par believe your intention is to perpetuate, and not to weaken, the ties
\par between me and my other and far dearer self. If she should ever tell me
\par that you are essential to her perfect happiness, I will give her to you.
\par If there were--Charles Darnay, if there were--"
\par 
\par The young man had taken his hand gratefully; their hands were joined as
\par the Doctor spoke:
\par 
\par "--any fancies, any reasons, any apprehensions, anything whatsoever,
\par new or old, against the man she really loved--the direct responsibility
\par thereof not lying on his head--they should all be obliterated for her
\par sake. She is everything to me; more to me than suffering, more to me
\par than wrong, more to me--Well! This is idle talk."
\par 
\par So strange was the way in which he faded into silence, and so strange
\par his fixed look when he had ceased to speak, that Darnay felt his own
\par hand turn cold in the hand that slowly released and dropped it.
\par 
\par "You said something to me," said Doctor Manette, breaking into a smile.
\par "What was it you said to me?"
\par 
\par He was at a loss how to answer, until he remembered having spoken of a
\par condition. Relieved as his mind reverted to that, he answered:
\par 
\par "Your confidence in me ought to be returned with full confidence on my
\par part. My present name, though but slightly changed from my mother's, is
\par not, as you will remember, my own. I wish to tell you what that is, and
\par why I am in England."
\par 
\par "Stop!" said the Doctor of Beauvais.
\par 
\par "I wish it, that I may the better deserve your confidence, and have no
\par secret from you."
\par 
\par "Stop!"
\par 
\par For an instant, the Doctor even had his two hands at his ears; for
\par another instant, even had his two hands laid on Darnay's lips.
\par 
\par "Tell me when I ask you, not now. If your suit should prosper, if Lucie
\par should love you, you shall tell me on your marriage morning. Do you
\par promise?"
\par 
\par "Willingly.
\par 
\par "Give me your hand. She will be home directly, and it is better she
\par should not see us together to-night. Go! God bless you!"
\par 
\par It was dark when Charles Darnay left him, and it was an hour later and
\par darker when Lucie came home; she hurried into the room alone--for
\par Miss Pross had gone straight up-stairs--and was surprised to find his
\par reading-chair empty.
\par 
\par "My father!" she called to him. "Father dear!"
\par 
\par Nothing was said in answer, but she heard a low hammering sound in his
\par bedroom. Passing lightly across the intermediate room, she looked in at
\par his door and came running back frightened, crying to herself, with her
\par blood all chilled, "What shall I do! What shall I do!"
\par 
\par Her uncertainty lasted but a moment; she hurried back, and tapped at
\par his door, and softly called to him. The noise ceased at the sound of
\par her voice, and he presently came out to her, and they walked up and down
\par together for a long time.
\par 
\par She came down from her bed, to look at him in his sleep that night. He
\par slept heavily, and his tray of shoemaking tools, and his old unfinished
\par work, were all as usual.
