\par XI. A Companion Picture
\par 
\par 
\par "Sydney," said Mr. Stryver, on that self-same night, or morning, to his
\par jackal; "mix another bowl of punch; I have something to say to you."
\par 
\par Sydney had been working double tides that night, and the night before,
\par and the night before that, and a good many nights in succession, making
\par a grand clearance among Mr. Stryver's papers before the setting in
\par of the long vacation. The clearance was effected at last; the Stryver
\par arrears were handsomely fetched up; everything was got rid of until
\par November should come with its fogs atmospheric, and fogs legal, and
\par bring grist to the mill again.
\par 
\par Sydney was none the livelier and none the soberer for so much
\par application. It had taken a deal of extra wet-towelling to pull him
\par through the night; a correspondingly extra quantity of wine had preceded
\par the towelling; and he was in a very damaged condition, as he now pulled
\par his turban off and threw it into the basin in which he had steeped it at
\par intervals for the last six hours.
\par 
\par "Are you mixing that other bowl of punch?" said Stryver the portly, with
\par his hands in his waistband, glancing round from the sofa where he lay on
\par his back.
\par 
\par "I am."
\par 
\par "Now, look here! I am going to tell you something that will rather
\par surprise you, and that perhaps will make you think me not quite as
\par shrewd as you usually do think me. I intend to marry."
\par 
\par "_Do_ you?"
\par 
\par "Yes. And not for money. What do you say now?"
\par 
\par "I don't feel disposed to say much. Who is she?"
\par 
\par "Guess."
\par 
\par "Do I know her?"
\par 
\par "Guess."
\par 
\par "I am not going to guess, at five o'clock in the morning, with my brains
\par frying and sputtering in my head. If you want me to guess, you must ask
\par me to dinner."
\par 
\par "Well then, I'll tell you," said Stryver, coming slowly into a sitting
\par posture. "Sydney, I rather despair of making myself intelligible to you,
\par because you are such an insensible dog."
\par 
\par "And you," returned Sydney, busy concocting the punch, "are such a
\par sensitive and poetical spirit--"
\par 
\par "Come!" rejoined Stryver, laughing boastfully, "though I don't prefer
\par any claim to being the soul of Romance (for I hope I know better), still
\par I am a tenderer sort of fellow than _you_."
\par 
\par "You are a luckier, if you mean that."
\par 
\par "I don't mean that. I mean I am a man of more--more--"
