\par big as he was, and four times as offensive.
\par 
\par "Now, let me recommend you," pursued Stryver, "to look it in the face.
\par I have looked it in the face, in my different way; look it in the face,
\par you, in your different way. Marry. Provide somebody to take care of
\par you. Never mind your having no enjoyment of women's society, nor
\par understanding of it, nor tact for it. Find out somebody. Find out some
\par respectable woman with a little property--somebody in the landlady way,
\par or lodging-letting way--and marry her, against a rainy day. That's the
\par kind of thing for _you_. Now think of it, Sydney."
\par 
\par "I'll think of it," said Sydney.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XII. The Fellow of Delicacy
\par 
\par 
\par Mr. Stryver having made up his mind to that magnanimous bestowal of good
\par fortune on the Doctor's daughter, resolved to make her happiness known
\par to her before he left town for the Long Vacation. After some mental
\par debating of the point, he came to the conclusion that it would be as
\par well to get all the preliminaries done with, and they could then arrange
\par at their leisure whether he should give her his hand a week or two
\par before Michaelmas Term, or in the little Christmas vacation between it
\par and Hilary.
\par 
\par As to the strength of his case, he had not a doubt about it, but clearly
\par saw his way to the verdict. Argued with the jury on substantial worldly
\par grounds--the only grounds ever worth taking into account--it was a
\par plain case, and had not a weak spot in it. He called himself for the
\par plaintiff, there was no getting over his evidence, the counsel for
\par the defendant threw up his brief, and the jury did not even turn to
\par consider. After trying it, Stryver, C. J., was satisfied that no plainer
\par case could be.
\par 
\par Accordingly, Mr. Stryver inaugurated the Long Vacation with a formal
\par proposal to take Miss Manette to Vauxhall Gardens; that failing, to
\par Ranelagh; that unaccountably failing too, it behoved him to present
\par himself in Soho, and there declare his noble mind.
\par 
\par Towards Soho, therefore, Mr. Stryver shouldered his way from the Temple,
\par while the bloom of the Long Vacation's infancy was still upon it.
\par Anybody who had seen him projecting himself into Soho while he was yet
\par on Saint Dunstan's side of Temple Bar, bursting in his full-blown way
\par along the pavement, to the jostlement of all weaker people, might have
\par seen how safe and strong he was.
\par 
\par His way taking him past Tellson's, and he both banking at Tellson's and
\par knowing Mr. Lorry as the intimate friend of the Manettes, it entered Mr.
\par Stryver's mind to enter the bank, and reveal to Mr. Lorry the brightness
\par of the Soho horizon. So, he pushed open the door with the weak rattle
\par in its throat, stumbled down the two steps, got past the two ancient
\par cashiers, and shouldered himself into the musty back closet where Mr.
\par Lorry sat at great books ruled for figures, with perpendicular iron
\par bars to his window as if that were ruled for figures too, and everything
\par under the clouds were a sum.
\par 
\par "Halloa!" said Mr. Stryver. "How do you do? I hope you are well!"
\par 
\par It was Stryver's grand peculiarity that he always seemed too big for any
\par place, or space. He was so much too big for Tellson's, that old clerks
\par in distant corners looked up with looks of remonstrance, as though he
\par squeezed them against the wall. The House itself, magnificently reading
\par the paper quite in the far-off perspective, lowered displeased, as if
\par the Stryver head had been butted into its responsible waistcoat.
\par 
\par The discreet Mr. Lorry said, in a sample tone of the voice he would
\par recommend under the circumstances, "How do you do, Mr. Stryver? How do
\par you do, sir?" and shook hands. There was a peculiarity in his manner
\par of shaking hands, always to be seen in any clerk at Tellson's who shook
\par hands with a customer when the House pervaded the air. He shook in a
\par self-abnegating way, as one who shook for Tellson and Co.
\par 
\par "Can I do anything for you, Mr. Stryver?" asked Mr. Lorry, in his
\par business character.
\par 
\par "Why, no, thank you; this is a private visit to yourself, Mr. Lorry; I
\par have come for a private word."
\par 
\par "Oh indeed!" said Mr. Lorry, bending down his ear, while his eye strayed
\par to the House afar off.
\par 
\par "I am going," said Mr. Stryver, leaning his arms confidentially on the
\par desk: whereupon, although it was a large double one, there appeared to
\par be not half desk enough for him: "I am going to make an offer of myself
\par in marriage to your agreeable little friend, Miss Manette, Mr. Lorry."
\par 
\par "Oh dear me!" cried Mr. Lorry, rubbing his chin, and looking at his
\par visitor dubiously.
\par 
\par "Oh dear me, sir?" repeated Stryver, drawing back. "Oh dear you, sir?
\par What may your meaning be, Mr. Lorry?"
\par 
\par "My meaning," answered the man of business, "is, of course, friendly and
\par appreciative, and that it does you the greatest credit, and--in short,
\par my meaning is everything you could desire. But--really, you know, Mr.
\par Stryver--" Mr. Lorry paused, and shook his head at him in the oddest
\par manner, as if he were compelled against his will to add, internally,
\par "you know there really is so much too much of you!"
\par 
\par "Well!" said Stryver, slapping the desk with his contentious hand,
\par opening his eyes wider, and taking a long breath, "if I understand you,
\par Mr. Lorry, I'll be hanged!"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry adjusted his little wig at both ears as a means towards that
\par end, and bit the feather of a pen.
\par 
\par "D--n it all, sir!" said Stryver, staring at him, "am I not eligible?"
\par 
\par "Oh dear yes! Yes. Oh yes, you're eligible!" said Mr. Lorry. "If you say
\par eligible, you are eligible."
\par 
\par "Am I not prosperous?" asked Stryver.
\par 
\par "Oh! if you come to prosperous, you are prosperous," said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "And advancing?"
\par 
\par "If you come to advancing you know," said Mr. Lorry, delighted to be
\par able to make another admission, "nobody can doubt that."
\par 
\par "Then what on earth is your meaning, Mr. Lorry?" demanded Stryver,
\par perceptibly crestfallen.
\par 
\par "Well! I--Were you going there now?" asked Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "Straight!" said Stryver, with a plump of his fist on the desk.
\par 
\par "Then I think I wouldn't, if I was you."
\par 
\par "Why?" said Stryver. "Now, I'll put you in a corner," forensically
\par shaking a forefinger at him. "You are a man of business and bound to
\par have a reason. State your reason. Why wouldn't you go?"
\par 
\par "Because," said Mr. Lorry, "I wouldn't go on such an object without
\par having some cause to believe that I should succeed."
\par 
\par "D--n _me_!" cried Stryver, "but this beats everything."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry glanced at the distant House, and glanced at the angry
\par Stryver.
\par 
\par "Here's a man of business--a man of years--a man of experience--_in_
\par a Bank," said Stryver; "and having summed up three leading reasons for
\par complete success, he says there's no reason at all! Says it with his
\par head on!" Mr. Stryver remarked upon the peculiarity as if it would have
\par been infinitely less remarkable if he had said it with his head off.
\par 
\par "When I speak of success, I speak of success with the young lady; and
\par when I speak of causes and reasons to make success probable, I speak of
\par causes and reasons that will tell as such with the young lady. The young
\par lady, my good sir," said Mr. Lorry, mildly tapping the Stryver arm, "the
\par young lady. The young lady goes before all."
\par 
\par "Then you mean to tell me, Mr. Lorry," said Stryver, squaring his
\par elbows, "that it is your deliberate opinion that the young lady at
\par present in question is a mincing Fool?"
\par 
\par "Not exactly so. I mean to tell you, Mr. Stryver," said Mr. Lorry,
\par reddening, "that I will hear no disrespectful word of that young lady
\par from any lips; and that if I knew any man--which I hope I do not--whose
\par taste was so coarse, and whose temper was so overbearing, that he could
\par not restrain himself from speaking disrespectfully of that young lady at
\par this desk, not even Tellson's should prevent my giving him a piece of my
\par mind."
\par 
\par The necessity of being angry in a suppressed tone had put Mr. Stryver's
\par blood-vessels into a dangerous state when it was his turn to be angry;
\par Mr. Lorry's veins, methodical as their courses could usually be, were in
\par no better state now it was his turn.
\par 
\par "That is what I mean to tell you, sir," said Mr. Lorry. "Pray let there
\par be no mistake about it."
\par 
\par Mr. Stryver sucked the end of a ruler for a little while, and then stood
\par hitting a tune out of his teeth with it, which probably gave him the
\par toothache. He broke the awkward silence by saying:
\par 
\par "This is something new to me, Mr. Lorry. You deliberately advise me not
\par to go up to Soho and offer myself--_my_self, Stryver of the King's Bench
\par bar?"
\par 
\par "Do you ask me for my advice, Mr. Stryver?"
\par 
\par "Yes, I do."
\par 
\par "Very good. Then I give it, and you have repeated it correctly."
\par 
\par "And all I can say of it is," laughed Stryver with a vexed laugh, "that
\par this--ha, ha!--beats everything past, present, and to come."
\par 
\par "Now understand me," pursued Mr. Lorry. "As a man of business, I am
\par not justified in saying anything about this matter, for, as a man of
\par business, I know nothing of it. But, as an old fellow, who has carried
\par Miss Manette in his arms, who is the trusted friend of Miss Manette and
\par of her father too, and who has a great affection for them both, I have
\par spoken. The confidence is not of my seeking, recollect. Now, you think I
\par may not be right?"
\par 
\par "Not I!" said Stryver, whistling. "I can't undertake to find third
\par parties in common sense; I can only find it for myself. I suppose sense
\par in certain quarters; you suppose mincing bread-and-butter nonsense. It's
\par new to me, but you are right, I dare say."
\par 
\par "What I suppose, Mr. Stryver, I claim to characterise for myself--And
\par understand me, sir," said Mr. Lorry, quickly flushing again, "I
\par will not--not even at Tellson's--have it characterised for me by any
\par gentleman breathing."
\par 
\par "There! I beg your pardon!" said Stryver.
\par 
\par "Granted. Thank you. Well, Mr. Stryver, I was about to say:--it might be
\par painful to you to find yourself mistaken, it might be painful to Doctor
\par Manette to have the task of being explicit with you, it might be very
\par painful to Miss Manette to have the task of being explicit with you. You
\par know the terms upon which I have the honour and happiness to stand with
\par the family. If you please, committing you in no way, representing you
\par in no way, I will undertake to correct my advice by the exercise of a
\par little new observation and judgment expressly brought to bear upon
\par it. If you should then be dissatisfied with it, you can but test its
\par soundness for yourself; if, on the other hand, you should be satisfied
\par with it, and it should be what it now is, it may spare all sides what is
\par best spared. What do you say?"
\par 
\par "How long would you keep me in town?"
\par 
\par "Oh! It is only a question of a few hours. I could go to Soho in the
\par evening, and come to your chambers afterwards."
\par 
\par "Then I say yes," said Stryver: "I won't go up there now, I am not so
\par hot upon it as that comes to; I say yes, and I shall expect you to look
\par in to-night. Good morning."
\par 
\par Then Mr. Stryver turned and burst out of the Bank, causing such a
\par concussion of air on his passage through, that to stand up against it
\par bowing behind the two counters, required the utmost remaining strength
\par of the two ancient clerks. Those venerable and feeble persons were
\par always seen by the public in the act of bowing, and were popularly
\par believed, when they had bowed a customer out, still to keep on bowing in
\par the empty office until they bowed another customer in.
\par 
\par The barrister was keen enough to divine that the banker would not have
\par gone so far in his expression of opinion on any less solid ground than
\par moral certainty. Unprepared as he was for the large pill he had to
\par swallow, he got it down. "And now," said Mr. Stryver, shaking his
\par forensic forefinger at the Temple in general, when it was down, "my way
\par out of this, is, to put you all in the wrong."
\par 
\par It was a bit of the art of an Old Bailey tactician, in which he found
\par great relief. "You shall not put me in the wrong, young lady," said Mr.
\par Stryver; "I'll do that for you."
\par 
\par Accordingly, when Mr. Lorry called that night as late as ten o'clock,
\par Mr. Stryver, among a quantity of books and papers littered out for the
\par purpose, seemed to have nothing less on his mind than the subject of
\par the morning. He even showed surprise when he saw Mr. Lorry, and was
\par altogether in an absent and preoccupied state.
\par 
\par "Well!" said that good-natured emissary, after a full half-hour of
\par bootless attempts to bring him round to the question. "I have been to
\par Soho."
\par 
\par "To Soho?" repeated Mr. Stryver, coldly. "Oh, to be sure! What am I
\par thinking of!"
\par 
\par "And I have no doubt," said Mr. Lorry, "that I was right in the
\par conversation we had. My opinion is confirmed, and I reiterate my
\par advice."
\par 
\par "I assure you," returned Mr. Stryver, in the friendliest way, "that I
\par am sorry for it on your account, and sorry for it on the poor father's
\par account. I know this must always be a sore subject with the family; let
\par us say no more about it."
\par 
\par "I don't understand you," said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "I dare say not," rejoined Stryver, nodding his head in a smoothing and
\par final way; "no matter, no matter."
\par 
\par "But it does matter," Mr. Lorry urged.
\par 
\par "No it doesn't; I assure you it doesn't. Having supposed that there was
\par sense where there is no sense, and a laudable ambition where there is
\par not a laudable ambition, I am well out of my mistake, and no harm is
\par done. Young women have committed similar follies often before, and have
\par repented them in poverty and obscurity often before. In an unselfish
\par aspect, I am sorry that the thing is dropped, because it would have been
\par a bad thing for me in a worldly point of view; in a selfish aspect, I am
\par glad that the thing has dropped, because it would have been a bad thing
\par for me in a worldly point of view--it is hardly necessary to say I could
\par have gained nothing by it. There is no harm at all done. I have not
\par proposed to the young lady, and, between ourselves, I am by no means
\par certain, on reflection, that I ever should have committed myself to
\par that extent. Mr. Lorry, you cannot control the mincing vanities and
\par giddinesses of empty-headed girls; you must not expect to do it, or you
\par will always be disappointed. Now, pray say no more about it. I tell you,
\par I regret it on account of others, but I am satisfied on my own account.
\par And I am really very much obliged to you for allowing me to sound you,
\par and for giving me your advice; you know the young lady better than I do;
\par you were right, it never would have done."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry was so taken aback, that he looked quite stupidly at Mr.
\par Stryver shouldering him towards the door, with an appearance of
\par showering generosity, forbearance, and goodwill, on his erring head.
\par "Make the best of it, my dear sir," said Stryver; "say no more about it;
\par thank you again for allowing me to sound you; good night!"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry was out in the night, before he knew where he was. Mr. Stryver
\par was lying back on his sofa, winking at his ceiling.
