\par 
\par 
\par XIII. The Fellow of No Delicacy
\par 
\par 
\par If Sydney Carton ever shone anywhere, he certainly never shone in the
\par house of Doctor Manette. He had been there often, during a whole year,
\par and had always been the same moody and morose lounger there. When he
\par cared to talk, he talked well; but, the cloud of caring for nothing,
\par which overshadowed him with such a fatal darkness, was very rarely
\par pierced by the light within him.
\par 
\par And yet he did care something for the streets that environed that house,
\par and for the senseless stones that made their pavements. Many a night
\par he vaguely and unhappily wandered there, when wine had brought no
\par transitory gladness to him; many a dreary daybreak revealed his solitary
\par figure lingering there, and still lingering there when the first beams
\par of the sun brought into strong relief, removed beauties of architecture
\par in spires of churches and lofty buildings, as perhaps the quiet time
\par brought some sense of better things, else forgotten and unattainable,
\par into his mind. Of late, the neglected bed in the Temple Court had known
\par him more scantily than ever; and often when he had thrown himself upon
\par it no longer than a few minutes, he had got up again, and haunted that
\par neighbourhood.
\par 
\par On a day in August, when Mr. Stryver (after notifying to his jackal
\par that "he had thought better of that marrying matter") had carried his
\par delicacy into Devonshire, and when the sight and scent of flowers in the
\par City streets had some waifs of goodness in them for the worst, of health
\par for the sickliest, and of youth for the oldest, Sydney's feet still trod
\par those stones. From being irresolute and purposeless, his feet became
\par animated by an intention, and, in the working out of that intention,
\par they took him to the Doctor's door.
\par 
\par He was shown up-stairs, and found Lucie at her work, alone. She had
\par never been quite at her ease with him, and received him with some little
\par embarrassment as he seated himself near her table. But, looking up at
\par his face in the interchange of the first few common-places, she observed
\par a change in it.
\par 
\par "I fear you are not well, Mr. Carton!"
\par 
\par "No. But the life I lead, Miss Manette, is not conducive to health. What
\par is to be expected of, or by, such profligates?"
\par 
\par "Is it not--forgive me; I have begun the question on my lips--a pity to
\par live no better life?"
\par 
\par "God knows it is a shame!"
\par 
\par "Then why not change it?"
\par 
\par Looking gently at him again, she was surprised and saddened to see that
\par there were tears in his eyes. There were tears in his voice too, as he
\par answered:
\par 
\par "It is too late for that. I shall never be better than I am. I shall
\par sink lower, and be worse."
\par 
\par He leaned an elbow on her table, and covered his eyes with his hand. The
\par table trembled in the silence that followed.
\par 
\par She had never seen him softened, and was much distressed. He knew her to
\par be so, without looking at her, and said:
\par 
\par "Pray forgive me, Miss Manette. I break down before the knowledge of
\par what I want to say to you. Will you hear me?"
\par 
\par "If it will do you any good, Mr. Carton, if it would make you happier,
\par it would make me very glad!"
\par 
\par "God bless you for your sweet compassion!"
\par 
\par He unshaded his face after a little while, and spoke steadily.
\par 
\par "Don't be afraid to hear me. Don't shrink from anything I say. I am like
\par one who died young. All my life might have been."
\par 
\par "No, Mr. Carton. I am sure that the best part of it might still be; I am
\par sure that you might be much, much worthier of yourself."
\par 
\par "Say of you, Miss Manette, and although I know better--although in the
\par mystery of my own wretched heart I know better--I shall never forget
\par it!"
\par 
\par She was pale and trembling. He came to her relief with a fixed despair
\par of himself which made the interview unlike any other that could have
\par been holden.
\par 
\par "If it had been possible, Miss Manette, that you could have returned the
\par love of the man you see before yourself--flung away, wasted, drunken,
\par poor creature of misuse as you know him to be--he would have been
\par conscious this day and hour, in spite of his happiness, that he would
\par bring you to misery, bring you to sorrow and repentance, blight you,
\par disgrace you, pull you down with him. I know very well that you can have
\par no tenderness for me; I ask for none; I am even thankful that it cannot
\par be."
\par 
\par "Without it, can I not save you, Mr. Carton? Can I not recall
\par you--forgive me again!--to a better course? Can I in no way repay your
\par confidence? I know this is a confidence," she modestly said, after a
\par little hesitation, and in earnest tears, "I know you would say this to
\par no one else. Can I turn it to no good account for yourself, Mr. Carton?"
\par 
\par He shook his head.
\par 
\par "To none. No, Miss Manette, to none. If you will hear me through a very
\par little more, all you can ever do for me is done. I wish you to know that
\par you have been the last dream of my soul. In my degradation I have not
\par been so degraded but that the sight of you with your father, and of this
\par home made such a home by you, has stirred old shadows that I thought had
\par died out of me. Since I knew you, I have been troubled by a remorse that
\par I thought would never reproach me again, and have heard whispers from
\par old voices impelling me upward, that I thought were silent for ever. I
\par have had unformed ideas of striving afresh, beginning anew, shaking off
\par sloth and sensuality, and fighting out the abandoned fight. A dream, all
\par a dream, that ends in nothing, and leaves the sleeper where he lay down,
\par but I wish you to know that you inspired it."
\par 
\par "Will nothing of it remain? O Mr. Carton, think again! Try again!"
\par 
\par "No, Miss Manette; all through it, I have known myself to be quite
\par undeserving. And yet I have had the weakness, and have still the
\par weakness, to wish you to know with what a sudden mastery you kindled me,
\par heap of ashes that I am, into fire--a fire, however, inseparable in
\par its nature from myself, quickening nothing, lighting nothing, doing no
\par service, idly burning away."
\par 
\par "Since it is my misfortune, Mr. Carton, to have made you more unhappy
\par than you were before you knew me--"
\par 
\par "Don't say that, Miss Manette, for you would have reclaimed me, if
\par anything could. You will not be the cause of my becoming worse."
\par 
\par "Since the state of your mind that you describe, is, at all events,
\par attributable to some influence of mine--this is what I mean, if I can
\par make it plain--can I use no influence to serve you? Have I no power for
\par good, with you, at all?"
\par 
\par "The utmost good that I am capable of now, Miss Manette, I have come
\par here to realise. Let me carry through the rest of my misdirected life,
\par the remembrance that I opened my heart to you, last of all the world;
\par and that there was something left in me at this time which you could
\par deplore and pity."
\par 
\par "Which I entreated you to believe, again and again, most fervently, with
\par all my heart, was capable of better things, Mr. Carton!"
\par 
\par "Entreat me to believe it no more, Miss Manette. I have proved myself,
\par and I know better. I distress you; I draw fast to an end. Will you let
\par me believe, when I recall this day, that the last confidence of my life
\par was reposed in your pure and innocent breast, and that it lies there
\par alone, and will be shared by no one?"
\par 
\par "If that will be a consolation to you, yes."
\par 
\par "Not even by the dearest one ever to be known to you?"
\par 
\par "Mr. Carton," she answered, after an agitated pause, "the secret is
\par yours, not mine; and I promise to respect it."
\par 
\par "Thank you. And again, God bless you."
\par 
\par He put her hand to his lips, and moved towards the door.
\par 
\par "Be under no apprehension, Miss Manette, of my ever resuming this
\par conversation by so much as a passing word. I will never refer to it
\par again. If I were dead, that could not be surer than it is henceforth. In
\par the hour of my death, I shall hold sacred the one good remembrance--and
\par shall thank and bless you for it--that my last avowal of myself was made
\par to you, and that my name, and faults, and miseries were gently carried
\par in your heart. May it otherwise be light and happy!"
\par 
\par He was so unlike what he had ever shown himself to be, and it was so
\par sad to think how much he had thrown away, and how much he every day kept
\par down and perverted, that Lucie Manette wept mournfully for him as he
\par stood looking back at her.
\par 
\par "Be comforted!" he said, "I am not worth such feeling, Miss Manette. An
\par hour or two hence, and the low companions and low habits that I scorn
\par but yield to, will render me less worth such tears as those, than any
\par wretch who creeps along the streets. Be comforted! But, within myself, I
\par shall always be, towards you, what I am now, though outwardly I shall be
\par what you have heretofore seen me. The last supplication but one I make
\par to you, is, that you will believe this of me."
\par 
\par "I will, Mr. Carton."
\par 
\par "My last supplication of all, is this; and with it, I will relieve
\par you of a visitor with whom I well know you have nothing in unison, and
\par between whom and you there is an impassable space. It is useless to say
\par it, I know, but it rises out of my soul. For you, and for any dear to
\par you, I would do anything. If my career were of that better kind that
\par there was any opportunity or capacity of sacrifice in it, I would
\par embrace any sacrifice for you and for those dear to you. Try to hold
\par me in your mind, at some quiet times, as ardent and sincere in this one
\par thing. The time will come, the time will not be long in coming, when new
\par ties will be formed about you--ties that will bind you yet more tenderly
\par and strongly to the home you so adorn--the dearest ties that will ever
\par grace and gladden you. O Miss Manette, when the little picture of a
\par happy father's face looks up in yours, when you see your own bright
\par beauty springing up anew at your feet, think now and then that there is
\par a man who would give his life, to keep a life you love beside you!"
\par 
\par He said, "Farewell!" said a last "God bless you!" and left her.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XIV. The Honest Tradesman
\par 
\par 
\par To the eyes of Mr. Jeremiah Cruncher, sitting on his stool in
\par Fleet-street with his grisly urchin beside him, a vast number and
\par variety of objects in movement were every day presented. Who could sit
\par upon anything in Fleet-street during the busy hours of the day, and
\par not be dazed and deafened by two immense processions, one ever tending
\par westward with the sun, the other ever tending eastward from the sun,
\par both ever tending to the plains beyond the range of red and purple where
\par the sun goes down!
\par 
\par With his straw in his mouth, Mr. Cruncher sat watching the two streams,
\par like the heathen rustic who has for several centuries been on duty
\par watching one stream--saving that Jerry had no expectation of their ever
\par running dry. Nor would it have been an expectation of a hopeful kind,
\par since a small part of his income was derived from the pilotage of timid
\par women (mostly of a full habit and past the middle term of life) from
\par Tellson's side of the tides to the opposite shore. Brief as such
\par companionship was in every separate instance, Mr. Cruncher never failed
\par to become so interested in the lady as to express a strong desire to
\par have the honour of drinking her very good health. And it was from
\par the gifts bestowed upon him towards the execution of this benevolent
\par purpose, that he recruited his finances, as just now observed.
\par 
\par Time was, when a poet sat upon a stool in a public place, and mused in
\par the sight of men. Mr. Cruncher, sitting on a stool in a public place,
\par but not being a poet, mused as little as possible, and looked about him.
\par 
\par It fell out that he was thus engaged in a season when crowds were
\par few, and belated women few, and when his affairs in general were so
\par unprosperous as to awaken a strong suspicion in his breast that Mrs.
\par Cruncher must have been "flopping" in some pointed manner, when an
\par unusual concourse pouring down Fleet-street westward, attracted his
\par attention. Looking that way, Mr. Cruncher made out that some kind of
\par funeral was coming along, and that there was popular objection to this
\par funeral, which engendered uproar.
\par 
\par "Young Jerry," said Mr. Cruncher, turning to his offspring, "it's a
\par buryin'."
\par 
\par "Hooroar, father!" cried Young Jerry.
\par 
\par The young gentleman uttered this exultant sound with mysterious
\par significance. The elder gentleman took the cry so ill, that he watched
\par his opportunity, and smote the young gentleman on the ear.
\par 
\par "What d'ye mean? What are you hooroaring at? What do you want to conwey
\par to your own father, you young Rip? This boy is a getting too many for
\par _me_!" said Mr. Cruncher, surveying him. "Him and his hooroars! Don't
\par let me hear no more of you, or you shall feel some more of me. D'ye
\par hear?"
\par 
\par "I warn't doing no harm," Young Jerry protested, rubbing his cheek.
\par 
\par "Drop it then," said Mr. Cruncher; "I won't have none of _your_ no
\par harms. Get a top of that there seat, and look at the crowd."
\par 
\par His son obeyed, and the crowd approached; they were bawling and hissing
\par round a dingy hearse and dingy mourning coach, in which mourning coach
\par there was only one mourner, dressed in the dingy trappings that were
\par considered essential to the dignity of the position. The position
\par appeared by no means to please him, however, with an increasing rabble
\par surrounding the coach, deriding him, making grimaces at him, and
\par incessantly groaning and calling out: "Yah! Spies! Tst! Yaha! Spies!"
\par with many compliments too numerous and forcible to repeat.
\par 
\par Funerals had at all times a remarkable attraction for Mr. Cruncher; he
\par always pricked up his senses, and became excited, when a funeral passed
\par Tellson's. Naturally, therefore, a funeral with this uncommon attendance
\par excited him greatly, and he asked of the first man who ran against him:
\par 
\par "What is it, brother? What's it about?"
\par 
\par "_I_ don't know," said the man. "Spies! Yaha! Tst! Spies!"
\par 
\par He asked another man. "Who is it?"
\par 
\par "_I_ don't know," returned the man, clapping his hands to his mouth
\par nevertheless, and vociferating in a surprising heat and with the
\par greatest ardour, "Spies! Yaha! Tst, tst! Spi--ies!"
\par 
\par At length, a person better informed on the merits of the case, tumbled
\par against him, and from this person he learned that the funeral was the
\par funeral of one Roger Cly.
\par 
\par "Was he a spy?" asked Mr. Cruncher.
\par 
\par "Old Bailey spy," returned his informant. "Yaha! Tst! Yah! Old Bailey
\par Spi--i--ies!"
\par 
\par "Why, to be sure!" exclaimed Jerry, recalling the Trial at which he had
\par assisted. "I've seen him. Dead, is he?"
\par 
\par "Dead as mutton," returned the other, "and can't be too dead. Have 'em
\par out, there! Spies! Pull 'em out, there! Spies!"
\par 
\par The idea was so acceptable in the prevalent absence of any idea,
\par that the crowd caught it up with eagerness, and loudly repeating the
\par suggestion to have 'em out, and to pull 'em out, mobbed the two vehicles
\par so closely that they came to a stop. On the crowd's opening the coach
\par doors, the one mourner scuffled out by himself and was in their hands
\par for a moment; but he was so alert, and made such good use of his time,
\par that in another moment he was scouring away up a bye-street, after
\par shedding his cloak, hat, long hatband, white pocket-handkerchief, and
\par other symbolical tears.
\par 
\par These, the people tore to pieces and scattered far and wide with great
\par enjoyment, while the tradesmen hurriedly shut up their shops; for a
\par crowd in those times stopped at nothing, and was a monster much dreaded.
\par They had already got the length of opening the hearse to take the coffin
\par out, when some brighter genius proposed instead, its being escorted to
\par its destination amidst general rejoicing. Practical suggestions being
\par much needed, this suggestion, too, was received with acclamation, and
\par the coach was immediately filled with eight inside and a dozen out,
\par while as many people got on the roof of the hearse as could by any
\par exercise of ingenuity stick upon it. Among the first of these volunteers
\par was Jerry Cruncher himself, who modestly concealed his spiky head from
\par the observation of Tellson's, in the further corner of the mourning
\par coach.
\par 
\par The officiating undertakers made some protest against these changes in
\par the ceremonies; but, the river being alarmingly near, and several voices
\par remarking on the efficacy of cold immersion in bringing refractory
\par members of the profession to reason, the protest was faint and brief.
\par The remodelled procession started, with a chimney-sweep driving the
\par hearse--advised by the regular driver, who was perched beside him, under
\par close inspection, for the purpose--and with a pieman, also attended
\par by his cabinet minister, driving the mourning coach. A bear-leader, a
\par popular street character of the time, was impressed as an additional
\par ornament, before the cavalcade had gone far down the Strand; and his
\par bear, who was black and very mangy, gave quite an Undertaking air to
\par that part of the procession in which he walked.
\par 
\par Thus, with beer-drinking, pipe-smoking, song-roaring, and infinite
\par caricaturing of woe, the disorderly procession went its way, recruiting
\par at every step, and all the shops shutting up before it. Its destination
\par was the old church of Saint Pancras, far off in the fields. It got there
\par in course of time; insisted on pouring into the burial-ground; finally,
\par accomplished the interment of the deceased Roger Cly in its own way, and
\par highly to its own satisfaction.
\par 
\par The dead man disposed of, and the crowd being under the necessity of
\par providing some other entertainment for itself, another brighter
\par genius (or perhaps the same) conceived the humour of impeaching casual
\par passers-by, as Old Bailey spies, and wreaking vengeance on them. Chase
\par was given to some scores of inoffensive persons who had never been near
\par the Old Bailey in their lives, in the realisation of this fancy, and
\par they were roughly hustled and maltreated. The transition to the sport of
\par window-breaking, and thence to the plundering of public-houses, was easy
\par and natural. At last, after several hours, when sundry summer-houses had
\par been pulled down, and some area-railings had been torn up, to arm
\par the more belligerent spirits, a rumour got about that the Guards were
\par coming. Before this rumour, the crowd gradually melted away, and perhaps
\par the Guards came, and perhaps they never came, and this was the usual
\par progress of a mob.
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher did not assist at the closing sports, but had remained
\par behind in the churchyard, to confer and condole with the undertakers.
\par The place had a soothing influence on him. He procured a pipe from a
\par neighbouring public-house, and smoked it, looking in at the railings and
\par maturely considering the spot.
\par 
\par "Jerry," said Mr. Cruncher, apostrophising himself in his usual way,
\par "you see that there Cly that day, and you see with your own eyes that he
\par was a young 'un and a straight made 'un."
\par 
\par Having smoked his pipe out, and ruminated a little longer, he turned
\par himself about, that he might appear, before the hour of closing, on his
\par station at Tellson's. Whether his meditations on mortality had touched
\par his liver, or whether his general health had been previously at all
\par amiss, or whether he desired to show a little attention to an eminent
\par man, is not so much to the purpose, as that he made a short call upon
\par his medical adviser--a distinguished surgeon--on his way back.
\par 
\par Young Jerry relieved his father with dutiful interest, and reported No
\par job in his absence. The bank closed, the ancient clerks came out, the
\par usual watch was set, and Mr. Cruncher and his son went home to tea.
\par 
\par "Now, I tell you where it is!" said Mr. Cruncher to his wife, on
\par entering. "If, as a honest tradesman, my wenturs goes wrong to-night, I
\par shall make sure that you've been praying again me, and I shall work you
\par for it just the same as if I seen you do it."
\par 
\par The dejected Mrs. Cruncher shook her head.
\par 
\par "Why, you're at it afore my face!" said Mr. Cruncher, with signs of
\par angry apprehension.
\par 
\par "I am saying nothing."
\par 
\par "Well, then; don't meditate nothing. You might as well flop as meditate.
\par You may as well go again me one way as another. Drop it altogether."
\par 
\par "Yes, Jerry."
\par 
\par "Yes, Jerry," repeated Mr. Cruncher sitting down to tea. "Ah! It _is_
\par yes, Jerry. That's about it. You may say yes, Jerry."
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher had no particular meaning in these sulky corroborations,
\par but made use of them, as people not unfrequently do, to express general
\par ironical dissatisfaction.
\par 
\par "You and your yes, Jerry," said Mr. Cruncher, taking a bite out of his
\par bread-and-butter, and seeming to help it down with a large invisible
\par oyster out of his saucer. "Ah! I think so. I believe you."
\par 
\par "You are going out to-night?" asked his decent wife, when he took
\par another bite.
\par 
\par "Yes, I am."
\par 
\par "May I go with you, father?" asked his son, briskly.
\par 
\par "No, you mayn't. I'm a going--as your mother knows--a fishing. That's
\par where I'm going to. Going a fishing."
\par 
\par "Your fishing-rod gets rayther rusty; don't it, father?"
\par 
\par "Never you mind."
\par 
\par "Shall you bring any fish home, father?"
\par 
\par "If I don't, you'll have short commons, to-morrow," returned that
\par gentleman, shaking his head; "that's questions enough for you; I ain't a
\par going out, till you've been long abed."
\par 
\par He devoted himself during the remainder of the evening to keeping a
\par most vigilant watch on Mrs. Cruncher, and sullenly holding her in
\par conversation that she might be prevented from meditating any petitions
\par to his disadvantage. With this view, he urged his son to hold her in
\par conversation also, and led the unfortunate woman a hard life by dwelling
\par on any causes of complaint he could bring against her, rather than
\par he would leave her for a moment to her own reflections. The devoutest
\par person could have rendered no greater homage to the efficacy of an
\par honest prayer than he did in this distrust of his wife. It was as if a
\par professed unbeliever in ghosts should be frightened by a ghost story.
\par 
\par "And mind you!" said Mr. Cruncher. "No games to-morrow! If I, as a
\par honest tradesman, succeed in providing a jinte of meat or two, none
\par of your not touching of it, and sticking to bread. If I, as a honest
\par tradesman, am able to provide a little beer, none of your declaring
\par on water. When you go to Rome, do as Rome does. Rome will be a ugly
\par customer to you, if you don't. _I_'m your Rome, you know."
\par 
\par Then he began grumbling again:
\par 
\par "With your flying into the face of your own wittles and drink! I don't
\par know how scarce you mayn't make the wittles and drink here, by your
\par flopping tricks and your unfeeling conduct. Look at your boy: he _is_
\par your'n, ain't he? He's as thin as a lath. Do you call yourself a mother,
\par and not know that a mother's first duty is to blow her boy out?"
\par 
\par This touched Young Jerry on a tender place; who adjured his mother to
\par perform her first duty, and, whatever else she did or neglected, above
\par all things to lay especial stress on the discharge of that maternal
\par function so affectingly and delicately indicated by his other parent.
\par 
\par Thus the evening wore away with the Cruncher family, until Young Jerry
\par was ordered to bed, and his mother, laid under similar injunctions,
\par obeyed them. Mr. Cruncher beguiled the earlier watches of the night with
\par solitary pipes, and did not start upon his excursion until nearly one
\par o'clock. Towards that small and ghostly hour, he rose up from his chair,
\par took a key out of his pocket, opened a locked cupboard, and brought
\par forth a sack, a crowbar of convenient size, a rope and chain, and other
\par fishing tackle of that nature. Disposing these articles about him
\par in skilful manner, he bestowed a parting defiance on Mrs. Cruncher,
\par extinguished the light, and went out.
\par 
\par Young Jerry, who had only made a feint of undressing when he went to
\par bed, was not long after his father. Under cover of the darkness he
\par followed out of the room, followed down the stairs, followed down the
\par court, followed out into the streets. He was in no uneasiness concerning
\par his getting into the house again, for it was full of lodgers, and the
\par door stood ajar all night.
\par 
\par Impelled by a laudable ambition to study the art and mystery of his
\par father's honest calling, Young Jerry, keeping as close to house fronts,
\par walls, and doorways, as his eyes were close to one another, held his
\par honoured parent in view. The honoured parent steering Northward, had not
\par gone far, when he was joined by another disciple of Izaak Walton, and
\par the two trudged on together.
\par 
\par Within half an hour from the first starting, they were beyond the
\par winking lamps, and the more than winking watchmen, and were out upon a
\par lonely road. Another fisherman was picked up here--and that so silently,
\par that if Young Jerry had been superstitious, he might have supposed the
\par second follower of the gentle craft to have, all of a sudden, split
\par himself into two.
\par 
\par The three went on, and Young Jerry went on, until the three stopped
\par under a bank overhanging the road. Upon the top of the bank was a low
\par brick wall, surmounted by an iron railing. In the shadow of bank and
\par wall the three turned out of the road, and up a blind lane, of which
\par the wall--there, risen to some eight or ten feet high--formed one side.
\par Crouching down in a corner, peeping up the lane, the next object that
\par Young Jerry saw, was the form of his honoured parent, pretty well
\par defined against a watery and clouded moon, nimbly scaling an iron gate.
\par He was soon over, and then the second fisherman got over, and then the
\par third. They all dropped softly on the ground within the gate, and lay
\par there a little--listening perhaps. Then, they moved away on their hands
\par and knees.
\par 
\par It was now Young Jerry's turn to approach the gate: which he did,
\par holding his breath. Crouching down again in a corner there, and looking
\par in, he made out the three fishermen creeping through some rank grass!
\par and all the gravestones in the churchyard--it was a large churchyard
\par that they were in--looking on like ghosts in white, while the church
\par tower itself looked on like the ghost of a monstrous giant. They did not
\par creep far, before they stopped and stood upright. And then they began to
\par fish.
\par 
\par They fished with a spade, at first. Presently the honoured parent
\par appeared to be adjusting some instrument like a great corkscrew.
\par Whatever tools they worked with, they worked hard, until the awful
\par striking of the church clock so terrified Young Jerry, that he made off,
\par with his hair as stiff as his father's.
\par 
\par But, his long-cherished desire to know more about these matters, not
\par only stopped him in his running away, but lured him back again. They
\par were still fishing perseveringly, when he peeped in at the gate for
\par the second time; but, now they seemed to have got a bite. There was a
\par screwing and complaining sound down below, and their bent figures were
\par strained, as if by a weight. By slow degrees the weight broke away the
\par earth upon it, and came to the surface. Young Jerry very well knew what
\par it would be; but, when he saw it, and saw his honoured parent about to
\par wrench it open, he was so frightened, being new to the sight, that he
\par made off again, and never stopped until he had run a mile or more.
\par 
\par He would not have stopped then, for anything less necessary than breath,
\par it being a spectral sort of race that he ran, and one highly desirable
\par to get to the end of. He had a strong idea that the coffin he had seen
\par was running after him; and, pictured as hopping on behind him, bolt
\par upright, upon its narrow end, always on the point of overtaking him
\par and hopping on at his side--perhaps taking his arm--it was a pursuer to
\par shun. It was an inconsistent and ubiquitous fiend too, for, while it
\par was making the whole night behind him dreadful, he darted out into the
\par roadway to avoid dark alleys, fearful of its coming hopping out of them
\par like a dropsical boy's kite without tail and wings. It hid in doorways
\par too, rubbing its horrible shoulders against doors, and drawing them up
\par to its ears, as if it were laughing. It got into shadows on the road,
\par and lay cunningly on its back to trip him up. All this time it was
\par incessantly hopping on behind and gaining on him, so that when the boy
\par got to his own door he had reason for being half dead. And even then
\par it would not leave him, but followed him upstairs with a bump on every
\par stair, scrambled into bed with him, and bumped down, dead and heavy, on
\par his breast when he fell asleep.
\par 
\par From his oppressed slumber, Young Jerry in his closet was awakened after
\par daybreak and before sunrise, by the presence of his father in the
\par family room. Something had gone wrong with him; at least, so Young Jerry
\par inferred, from the circumstance of his holding Mrs. Cruncher by the
\par ears, and knocking the back of her head against the head-board of the
\par bed.
\par 
\par "I told you I would," said Mr. Cruncher, "and I did."
\par 
\par "Jerry, Jerry, Jerry!" his wife implored.
\par 
\par "You oppose yourself to the profit of the business," said Jerry, "and me
\par and my partners suffer. You was to honour and obey; why the devil don't
\par you?"
\par 
\par "I try to be a good wife, Jerry," the poor woman protested, with tears.
\par 
\par "Is it being a good wife to oppose your husband's business? Is it
\par honouring your husband to dishonour his business? Is it obeying your
\par husband to disobey him on the wital subject of his business?"
\par 
\par "You hadn't taken to the dreadful business then, Jerry."
\par 
\par "It's enough for you," retorted Mr. Cruncher, "to be the wife of a
\par honest tradesman, and not to occupy your female mind with calculations
\par when he took to his trade or when he didn't. A honouring and obeying
\par wife would let his trade alone altogether. Call yourself a religious
\par woman? If you're a religious woman, give me a irreligious one! You have
\par no more nat'ral sense of duty than the bed of this here Thames river has
\par of a pile, and similarly it must be knocked into you."
\par 
\par The altercation was conducted in a low tone of voice, and terminated in
\par the honest tradesman's kicking off his clay-soiled boots, and lying down
\par at his length on the floor. After taking a timid peep at him lying on
\par his back, with his rusty hands under his head for a pillow, his son lay
\par down too, and fell asleep again.
\par 
\par There was no fish for breakfast, and not much of anything else. Mr.
\par Cruncher was out of spirits, and out of temper, and kept an iron pot-lid
\par by him as a projectile for the correction of Mrs. Cruncher, in case
\par he should observe any symptoms of her saying Grace. He was brushed
\par and washed at the usual hour, and set off with his son to pursue his
\par ostensible calling.
\par 
\par Young Jerry, walking with the stool under his arm at his father's side
\par along sunny and crowded Fleet-street, was a very different Young Jerry
\par from him of the previous night, running home through darkness and
\par solitude from his grim pursuer. His cunning was fresh with the day,
\par and his qualms were gone with the night--in which particulars it is not
\par improbable that he had compeers in Fleet-street and the City of London,
\par that fine morning.
\par 
\par "Father," said Young Jerry, as they walked along: taking care to keep
\par at arm's length and to have the stool well between them: "what's a
\par Resurrection-Man?"
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher came to a stop on the pavement before he answered, "How
\par should I know?"
\par 
\par "I thought you knowed everything, father," said the artless boy.
\par 
\par "Hem! Well," returned Mr. Cruncher, going on again, and lifting off his
\par hat to give his spikes free play, "he's a tradesman."
\par 
\par "What's his goods, father?" asked the brisk Young Jerry.
\par 
\par "His goods," said Mr. Cruncher, after turning it over in his mind, "is a
\par branch of Scientific goods."
\par 
\par "Persons' bodies, ain't it, father?" asked the lively boy.
\par 
\par "I believe it is something of that sort," said Mr. Cruncher.
\par 
\par "Oh, father, I should so like to be a Resurrection-Man when I'm quite
\par growed up!"
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher was soothed, but shook his head in a dubious and moral way.
\par "It depends upon how you dewelop your talents. Be careful to dewelop
\par your talents, and never to say no more than you can help to nobody, and
\par there's no telling at the present time what you may not come to be fit
\par for." As Young Jerry, thus encouraged, went on a few yards in advance,
\par to plant the stool in the shadow of the Bar, Mr. Cruncher added to
\par himself: "Jerry, you honest tradesman, there's hopes wot that boy will
\par yet be a blessing to you, and a recompense to you for his mother!"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XV. Knitting
\par 
\par 
\par There had been earlier drinking than usual in the wine-shop of Monsieur
\par Defarge. As early as six o'clock in the morning, sallow faces peeping
\par through its barred windows had descried other faces within, bending over
\par measures of wine. Monsieur Defarge sold a very thin wine at the best
\par of times, but it would seem to have been an unusually thin wine that
\par he sold at this time. A sour wine, moreover, or a souring, for its
\par influence on the mood of those who drank it was to make them gloomy. No
\par vivacious Bacchanalian flame leaped out of the pressed grape of Monsieur
\par Defarge: but, a smouldering fire that burnt in the dark, lay hidden in
\par the dregs of it.
\par 
\par This had been the third morning in succession, on which there had been
\par early drinking at the wine-shop of Monsieur Defarge. It had begun
\par on Monday, and here was Wednesday come. There had been more of early
\par brooding than drinking; for, many men had listened and whispered and
\par slunk about there from the time of the opening of the door, who could
\par not have laid a piece of money on the counter to save their souls. These
\par were to the full as interested in the place, however, as if they could
\par have commanded whole barrels of wine; and they glided from seat to seat,
\par and from corner to corner, swallowing talk in lieu of drink, with greedy
\par looks.
\par 
\par Notwithstanding an unusual flow of company, the master of the wine-shop
\par was not visible. He was not missed; for, nobody who crossed the
\par threshold looked for him, nobody asked for him, nobody wondered to see
\par only Madame Defarge in her seat, presiding over the distribution of
\par wine, with a bowl of battered small coins before her, as much defaced
\par and beaten out of their original impress as the small coinage of
\par humanity from whose ragged pockets they had come.
\par 
\par A suspended interest and a prevalent absence of mind, were perhaps
\par observed by the spies who looked in at the wine-shop, as they looked in
\par at every place, high and low, from the king's palace to the criminal's
\par gaol. Games at cards languished, players at dominoes musingly built
\par towers with them, drinkers drew figures on the tables with spilt drops
\par of wine, Madame Defarge herself picked out the pattern on her sleeve
\par with her toothpick, and saw and heard something inaudible and invisible
\par a long way off.
\par 
\par Thus, Saint Antoine in this vinous feature of his, until midday. It was
\par high noontide, when two dusty men passed through his streets and under
\par his swinging lamps: of whom, one was Monsieur Defarge: the other a
\par mender of roads in a blue cap. All adust and athirst, the two entered
\par the wine-shop. Their arrival had lighted a kind of fire in the breast
\par of Saint Antoine, fast spreading as they came along, which stirred and
\par flickered in flames of faces at most doors and windows. Yet, no one had
\par followed them, and no man spoke when they entered the wine-shop, though
\par the eyes of every man there were turned upon them.
\par 
\par "Good day, gentlemen!" said Monsieur Defarge.
\par 
\par It may have been a signal for loosening the general tongue. It elicited
\par an answering chorus of "Good day!"
\par 
\par "It is bad weather, gentlemen," said Defarge, shaking his head.
\par 
\par Upon which, every man looked at his neighbour, and then all cast down
\par their eyes and sat silent. Except one man, who got up and went out.
\par 
\par "My wife," said Defarge aloud, addressing Madame Defarge: "I have
\par travelled certain leagues with this good mender of roads, called
\par Jacques. I met him--by accident--a day and half's journey out of Paris.
\par He is a good child, this mender of roads, called Jacques. Give him to
\par drink, my wife!"
\par 
\par A second man got up and went out. Madame Defarge set wine before the
\par mender of roads called Jacques, who doffed his blue cap to the company,
\par and drank. In the breast of his blouse he carried some coarse dark
\par bread; he ate of this between whiles, and sat munching and drinking near
\par Madame Defarge's counter. A third man got up and went out.
\par 
\par Defarge refreshed himself with a draught of wine--but, he took less
\par than was given to the stranger, as being himself a man to whom it was no
\par rarity--and stood waiting until the countryman had made his breakfast.
\par He looked at no one present, and no one now looked at him; not even
\par Madame Defarge, who had taken up her knitting, and was at work.
\par 
\par "Have you finished your repast, friend?" he asked, in due season.
\par 
\par "Yes, thank you."
\par 
\par "Come, then! You shall see the apartment that I told you you could
\par occupy. It will suit you to a marvel."
\par 
\par Out of the wine-shop into the street, out of the street into a
\par courtyard, out of the courtyard up a steep staircase, out of the
\par staircase into a garret--formerly the garret where a white-haired man
\par sat on a low bench, stooping forward and very busy, making shoes.
\par 
\par No white-haired man was there now; but, the three men were there who had
\par gone out of the wine-shop singly. And between them and the white-haired
\par man afar off, was the one small link, that they had once looked in at
\par him through the chinks in the wall.
\par 
\par Defarge closed the door carefully, and spoke in a subdued voice:
\par 
\par "Jacques One, Jacques Two, Jacques Three! This is the witness
\par encountered by appointment, by me, Jacques Four. He will tell you all.
\par Speak, Jacques Five!"
\par 
\par The mender of roads, blue cap in hand, wiped his swarthy forehead with
\par it, and said, "Where shall I commence, monsieur?"
\par 
\par "Commence," was Monsieur Defarge's not unreasonable reply, "at the
\par commencement."
\par 
\par "I saw him then, messieurs," began the mender of roads, "a year ago this
\par running summer, underneath the carriage of the Marquis, hanging by the
\par chain. Behold the manner of it. I leaving my work on the road, the sun
\par going to bed, the carriage of the Marquis slowly ascending the hill, he
\par hanging by the chain--like this."
\par 
\par Again the mender of roads went through the whole performance; in which
\par he ought to have been perfect by that time, seeing that it had been
\par the infallible resource and indispensable entertainment of his village
\par during a whole year.
\par 
\par Jacques One struck in, and asked if he had ever seen the man before?
\par 
\par "Never," answered the mender of roads, recovering his perpendicular.
\par 
\par Jacques Three demanded how he afterwards recognised him then?
\par 
\par "By his tall figure," said the mender of roads, softly, and with his
\par finger at his nose. "When Monsieur the Marquis demands that evening,
\par 'Say, what is he like?' I make response, 'Tall as a spectre.'"
\par 
\par "You should have said, short as a dwarf," returned Jacques Two.
\par 
\par "But what did I know? The deed was not then accomplished, neither did he
\par confide in me. Observe! Under those circumstances even, I do not
\par offer my testimony. Monsieur the Marquis indicates me with his finger,
\par standing near our little fountain, and says, 'To me! Bring that rascal!'
\par My faith, messieurs, I offer nothing."
\par 
\par "He is right there, Jacques," murmured Defarge, to him who had
\par interrupted. "Go on!"
\par 
\par "Good!" said the mender of roads, with an air of mystery. "The tall man
\par is lost, and he is sought--how many months? Nine, ten, eleven?"
\par 
\par "No matter, the number," said Defarge. "He is well hidden, but at last
\par he is unluckily found. Go on!"
\par 
\par "I am again at work upon the hill-side, and the sun is again about to
\par go to bed. I am collecting my tools to descend to my cottage down in the
\par village below, where it is already dark, when I raise my eyes, and see
\par coming over the hill six soldiers. In the midst of them is a tall man
\par with his arms bound--tied to his sides--like this!"
\par 
\par With the aid of his indispensable cap, he represented a man with his
\par elbows bound fast at his hips, with cords that were knotted behind him.
\par 
\par "I stand aside, messieurs, by my heap of stones, to see the soldiers
\par and their prisoner pass (for it is a solitary road, that, where any
\par spectacle is well worth looking at), and at first, as they approach, I
\par see no more than that they are six soldiers with a tall man bound, and
\par that they are almost black to my sight--except on the side of the sun
\par going to bed, where they have a red edge, messieurs. Also, I see that
\par their long shadows are on the hollow ridge on the opposite side of the
\par road, and are on the hill above it, and are like the shadows of giants.
\par Also, I see that they are covered with dust, and that the dust moves
\par with them as they come, tramp, tramp! But when they advance quite near
\par to me, I recognise the tall man, and he recognises me. Ah, but he would
\par be well content to precipitate himself over the hill-side once again, as
\par on the evening when he and I first encountered, close to the same spot!"
\par 
\par He described it as if he were there, and it was evident that he saw it
\par vividly; perhaps he had not seen much in his life.
\par 
\par "I do not show the soldiers that I recognise the tall man; he does not
\par show the soldiers that he recognises me; we do it, and we know it, with
\par our eyes. 'Come on!' says the chief of that company, pointing to the
\par village, 'bring him fast to his tomb!' and they bring him faster. I
\par follow. His arms are swelled because of being bound so tight, his wooden
\par shoes are large and clumsy, and he is lame. Because he is lame, and
\par consequently slow, they drive him with their guns--like this!"
\par 
\par He imitated the action of a man's being impelled forward by the
\par butt-ends of muskets.
\par 
\par "As they descend the hill like madmen running a race, he falls. They
\par laugh and pick him up again. His face is bleeding and covered with dust,
\par but he cannot touch it; thereupon they laugh again. They bring him into
\par the village; all the village runs to look; they take him past the mill,
\par and up to the prison; all the village sees the prison gate open in the
\par darkness of the night, and swallow him--like this!"
\par 
\par He opened his mouth as wide as he could, and shut it with a sounding
\par snap of his teeth. Observant of his unwillingness to mar the effect by
\par opening it again, Defarge said, "Go on, Jacques."
\par 
\par "All the village," pursued the mender of roads, on tiptoe and in a low
\par voice, "withdraws; all the village whispers by the fountain; all the
\par village sleeps; all the village dreams of that unhappy one, within the
\par locks and bars of the prison on the crag, and never to come out of it,
\par except to perish. In the morning, with my tools upon my shoulder, eating
\par my morsel of black bread as I go, I make a circuit by the prison, on
\par my way to my work. There I see him, high up, behind the bars of a lofty
\par iron cage, bloody and dusty as last night, looking through. He has no
\par hand free, to wave to me; I dare not call to him; he regards me like a
\par dead man."
\par 
\par Defarge and the three glanced darkly at one another. The looks of all
\par of them were dark, repressed, and revengeful, as they listened to the
\par countryman's story; the manner of all of them, while it was secret, was
\par authoritative too. They had the air of a rough tribunal; Jacques One
\par and Two sitting on the old pallet-bed, each with his chin resting on
\par his hand, and his eyes intent on the road-mender; Jacques Three, equally
\par intent, on one knee behind them, with his agitated hand always gliding
\par over the network of fine nerves about his mouth and nose; Defarge
\par standing between them and the narrator, whom he had stationed in the
\par light of the window, by turns looking from him to them, and from them to
\par him.
\par 
\par "Go on, Jacques," said Defarge.
\par 
\par "He remains up there in his iron cage some days. The village looks
\par at him by stealth, for it is afraid. But it always looks up, from a
\par distance, at the prison on the crag; and in the evening, when the work
\par of the day is achieved and it assembles to gossip at the fountain, all
\par faces are turned towards the prison. Formerly, they were turned towards
\par the posting-house; now, they are turned towards the prison. They
\par whisper at the fountain, that although condemned to death he will not be
\par executed; they say that petitions have been presented in Paris, showing
\par that he was enraged and made mad by the death of his child; they say
\par that a petition has been presented to the King himself. What do I know?
\par It is possible. Perhaps yes, perhaps no."
\par 
\par "Listen then, Jacques," Number One of that name sternly interposed.
\par "Know that a petition was presented to the King and Queen. All here,
\par yourself excepted, saw the King take it, in his carriage in the street,
\par sitting beside the Queen. It is Defarge whom you see here, who, at the
\par hazard of his life, darted out before the horses, with the petition in
\par his hand."
\par 
\par "And once again listen, Jacques!" said the kneeling Number Three:
\par his fingers ever wandering over and over those fine nerves, with a
\par strikingly greedy air, as if he hungered for something--that was neither
\par food nor drink; "the guard, horse and foot, surrounded the petitioner,
\par and struck him blows. You hear?"
\par 
\par "I hear, messieurs."
\par 
\par "Go on then," said Defarge.
\par 
\par "Again; on the other hand, they whisper at the fountain," resumed the
\par countryman, "that he is brought down into our country to be executed on
\par the spot, and that he will very certainly be executed. They even whisper
\par that because he has slain Monseigneur, and because Monseigneur was the
\par father of his tenants--serfs--what you will--he will be executed as a
\par parricide. One old man says at the fountain, that his right hand, armed
\par with the knife, will be burnt off before his face; that, into wounds
\par which will be made in his arms, his breast, and his legs, there will be
\par poured boiling oil, melted lead, hot resin, wax, and sulphur; finally,
\par that he will be torn limb from limb by four strong horses. That old man
\par says, all this was actually done to a prisoner who made an attempt on
\par the life of the late King, Louis Fifteen. But how do I know if he lies?
\par I am not a scholar."
\par 
\par "Listen once again then, Jacques!" said the man with the restless hand
\par and the craving air. "The name of that prisoner was Damiens, and it was
\par all done in open day, in the open streets of this city of Paris; and
\par nothing was more noticed in the vast concourse that saw it done, than
\par the crowd of ladies of quality and fashion, who were full of eager
\par attention to the last--to the last, Jacques, prolonged until nightfall,
\par when he had lost two legs and an arm, and still breathed! And it was
\par done--why, how old are you?"
\par 
\par "Thirty-five," said the mender of roads, who looked sixty.
\par 
\par "It was done when you were more than ten years old; you might have seen
\par it."
\par 
\par "Enough!" said Defarge, with grim impatience. "Long live the Devil! Go
\par on."
\par 
\par "Well! Some whisper this, some whisper that; they speak of nothing else;
\par even the fountain appears to fall to that tune. At length, on Sunday
\par night when all the village is asleep, come soldiers, winding down from
\par the prison, and their guns ring on the stones of the little street.
\par Workmen dig, workmen hammer, soldiers laugh and sing; in the morning, by
\par the fountain, there is raised a gallows forty feet high, poisoning the
\par water."
\par 
\par The mender of roads looked _through_ rather than _at_ the low ceiling,
\par and pointed as if he saw the gallows somewhere in the sky.
\par 
\par "All work is stopped, all assemble there, nobody leads the cows out,
\par the cows are there with the rest. At midday, the roll of drums. Soldiers
\par have marched into the prison in the night, and he is in the midst
\par of many soldiers. He is bound as before, and in his mouth there is
\par a gag--tied so, with a tight string, making him look almost as if he
\par laughed." He suggested it, by creasing his face with his two thumbs,
\par from the corners of his mouth to his ears. "On the top of the gallows is
\par fixed the knife, blade upwards, with its point in the air. He is hanged
\par there forty feet high--and is left hanging, poisoning the water."
\par 
\par They looked at one another, as he used his blue cap to wipe his face,
\par on which the perspiration had started afresh while he recalled the
\par spectacle.
\par 
\par "It is frightful, messieurs. How can the women and the children draw
\par water! Who can gossip of an evening, under that shadow! Under it, have
\par I said? When I left the village, Monday evening as the sun was going to
\par bed, and looked back from the hill, the shadow struck across the church,
\par across the mill, across the prison--seemed to strike across the earth,
\par messieurs, to where the sky rests upon it!"
\par 
\par The hungry man gnawed one of his fingers as he looked at the other
\par three, and his finger quivered with the craving that was on him.
\par 
\par "That's all, messieurs. I left at sunset (as I had been warned to do),
\par and I walked on, that night and half next day, until I met (as I was
\par warned I should) this comrade. With him, I came on, now riding and now
\par walking, through the rest of yesterday and through last night. And here
\par you see me!"
\par 
\par After a gloomy silence, the first Jacques said, "Good! You have acted
\par and recounted faithfully. Will you wait for us a little, outside the
\par door?"
\par 
\par "Very willingly," said the mender of roads. Whom Defarge escorted to the
\par top of the stairs, and, leaving seated there, returned.
\par 
\par The three had risen, and their heads were together when he came back to
\par the garret.
\par 
\par "How say you, Jacques?" demanded Number One. "To be registered?"
\par 
\par "To be registered, as doomed to destruction," returned Defarge.
\par 
\par "Magnificent!" croaked the man with the craving.
\par 
\par "The chateau, and all the race?" inquired the first.
\par 
\par "The chateau and all the race," returned Defarge. "Extermination."
\par 
\par The hungry man repeated, in a rapturous croak, "Magnificent!" and began
\par gnawing another finger.
\par 
\par "Are you sure," asked Jacques Two, of Defarge, "that no embarrassment
\par can arise from our manner of keeping the register? Without doubt it is
\par safe, for no one beyond ourselves can decipher it; but shall we always
\par be able to decipher it--or, I ought to say, will she?"
\par 
\par "Jacques," returned Defarge, drawing himself up, "if madame my wife
\par undertook to keep the register in her memory alone, she would not lose
\par a word of it--not a syllable of it. Knitted, in her own stitches and her
\par own symbols, it will always be as plain to her as the sun. Confide in
\par Madame Defarge. It would be easier for the weakest poltroon that lives,
\par to erase himself from existence, than to erase one letter of his name or
\par crimes from the knitted register of Madame Defarge."
\par 
\par There was a murmur of confidence and approval, and then the man who
\par hungered, asked: "Is this rustic to be sent back soon? I hope so. He is
\par very simple; is he not a little dangerous?"
\par 
\par "He knows nothing," said Defarge; "at least nothing more than would
\par easily elevate himself to a gallows of the same height. I charge myself
\par with him; let him remain with me; I will take care of him, and set him
\par on his road. He wishes to see the fine world--the King, the Queen, and
\par Court; let him see them on Sunday."
\par 
\par "What?" exclaimed the hungry man, staring. "Is it a good sign, that he
\par wishes to see Royalty and Nobility?"
\par 
\par "Jacques," said Defarge; "judiciously show a cat milk, if you wish her
\par to thirst for it. Judiciously show a dog his natural prey, if you wish
\par him to bring it down one day."
\par 
\par Nothing more was said, and the mender of roads, being found already
\par dozing on the topmost stair, was advised to lay himself down on the
\par pallet-bed and take some rest. He needed no persuasion, and was soon
\par asleep.
\par 
\par Worse quarters than Defarge's wine-shop, could easily have been found
\par in Paris for a provincial slave of that degree. Saving for a mysterious
\par dread of madame by which he was constantly haunted, his life was very
\par new and agreeable. But, madame sat all day at her counter, so expressly
\par unconscious of him, and so particularly determined not to perceive that
\par his being there had any connection with anything below the surface, that
\par he shook in his wooden shoes whenever his eye lighted on her. For, he
\par contended with himself that it was impossible to foresee what that lady
\par might pretend next; and he felt assured that if she should take it
\par into her brightly ornamented head to pretend that she had seen him do a
\par murder and afterwards flay the victim, she would infallibly go through
\par with it until the play was played out.
\par 
\par Therefore, when Sunday came, the mender of roads was not enchanted
\par (though he said he was) to find that madame was to accompany monsieur
\par and himself to Versailles. It was additionally disconcerting to have
\par madame knitting all the way there, in a public conveyance; it was
\par additionally disconcerting yet, to have madame in the crowd in the
\par afternoon, still with her knitting in her hands as the crowd waited to
\par see the carriage of the King and Queen.
\par 
\par "You work hard, madame," said a man near her.
\par 
\par "Yes," answered Madame Defarge; "I have a good deal to do."
\par 
\par "What do you make, madame?"
\par 
\par "Many things."
\par 
\par "For instance--"
\par 
\par "For instance," returned Madame Defarge, composedly, "shrouds."
\par 
\par The man moved a little further away, as soon as he could, and the mender
\par of roads fanned himself with his blue cap: feeling it mightily close
\par and oppressive. If he needed a King and Queen to restore him, he was
\par fortunate in having his remedy at hand; for, soon the large-faced King
\par and the fair-faced Queen came in their golden coach, attended by the
\par shining Bull's Eye of their Court, a glittering multitude of laughing
\par ladies and fine lords; and in jewels and silks and powder and splendour
\par and elegantly spurning figures and handsomely disdainful faces of both
\par sexes, the mender of roads bathed himself, so much to his temporary
\par intoxication, that he cried Long live the King, Long live the Queen,
\par Long live everybody and everything! as if he had never heard of
\par ubiquitous Jacques in his time. Then, there were gardens, courtyards,
\par terraces, fountains, green banks, more King and Queen, more Bull's Eye,
\par more lords and ladies, more Long live they all! until he absolutely wept
\par with sentiment. During the whole of this scene, which lasted some three
\par hours, he had plenty of shouting and weeping and sentimental company,
\par and throughout Defarge held him by the collar, as if to restrain him
\par from flying at the objects of his brief devotion and tearing them to
\par pieces.
\par 
\par "Bravo!" said Defarge, clapping him on the back when it was over, like a
\par patron; "you are a good boy!"
\par 
\par The mender of roads was now coming to himself, and was mistrustful of
\par having made a mistake in his late demonstrations; but no.
\par 
\par "You are the fellow we want," said Defarge, in his ear; "you make
\par these fools believe that it will last for ever. Then, they are the more
\par insolent, and it is the nearer ended."
\par 
\par "Hey!" cried the mender of roads, reflectively; "that's true."
\par 
\par "These fools know nothing. While they despise your breath, and would
\par stop it for ever and ever, in you or in a hundred like you rather than
\par in one of their own horses or dogs, they only know what your breath
\par tells them. Let it deceive them, then, a little longer; it cannot
\par deceive them too much."
\par 
\par Madame Defarge looked superciliously at the client, and nodded in
\par confirmation.
\par 
\par "As to you," said she, "you would shout and shed tears for anything, if
\par it made a show and a noise. Say! Would you not?"
\par 
\par "Truly, madame, I think so. For the moment."
\par 
\par "If you were shown a great heap of dolls, and were set upon them to
\par pluck them to pieces and despoil them for your own advantage, you would
\par pick out the richest and gayest. Say! Would you not?"
\par 
\par "Truly yes, madame."
\par 
\par "Yes. And if you were shown a flock of birds, unable to fly, and were
\par set upon them to strip them of their feathers for your own advantage,
\par you would set upon the birds of the finest feathers; would you not?"
\par 
\par "It is true, madame."
\par 
\par "You have seen both dolls and birds to-day," said Madame Defarge, with
\par a wave of her hand towards the place where they had last been apparent;
\par "now, go home!"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XVI. Still Knitting
\par 
\par 
\par Madame Defarge and monsieur her husband returned amicably to the
\par bosom of Saint Antoine, while a speck in a blue cap toiled through the
\par darkness, and through the dust, and down the weary miles of avenue by
\par the wayside, slowly tending towards that point of the compass where
\par the chateau of Monsieur the Marquis, now in his grave, listened to
\par the whispering trees. Such ample leisure had the stone faces, now,
\par for listening to the trees and to the fountain, that the few village
\par scarecrows who, in their quest for herbs to eat and fragments of dead
\par stick to burn, strayed within sight of the great stone courtyard and
\par terrace staircase, had it borne in upon their starved fancy that
\par the expression of the faces was altered. A rumour just lived in the
\par village--had a faint and bare existence there, as its people had--that
\par when the knife struck home, the faces changed, from faces of pride to
\par faces of anger and pain; also, that when that dangling figure was hauled
\par up forty feet above the fountain, they changed again, and bore a cruel
\par look of being avenged, which they would henceforth bear for ever. In the
\par stone face over the great window of the bed-chamber where the murder
\par was done, two fine dints were pointed out in the sculptured nose, which
\par everybody recognised, and which nobody had seen of old; and on the
\par scarce occasions when two or three ragged peasants emerged from the
\par crowd to take a hurried peep at Monsieur the Marquis petrified, a
\par skinny finger would not have pointed to it for a minute, before they all
\par started away among the moss and leaves, like the more fortunate hares
\par who could find a living there.
\par 
\par Chateau and hut, stone face and dangling figure, the red stain on the
\par stone floor, and the pure water in the village well--thousands of acres
\par of land--a whole province of France--all France itself--lay under the
\par night sky, concentrated into a faint hair-breadth line. So does a whole
\par world, with all its greatnesses and littlenesses, lie in a twinkling
\par star. And as mere human knowledge can split a ray of light and analyse
\par the manner of its composition, so, sublimer intelligences may read in
\par the feeble shining of this earth of ours, every thought and act, every
\par vice and virtue, of every responsible creature on it.
\par 
\par The Defarges, husband and wife, came lumbering under the starlight,
\par in their public vehicle, to that gate of Paris whereunto their
\par journey naturally tended. There was the usual stoppage at the barrier
\par guardhouse, and the usual lanterns came glancing forth for the usual
\par examination and inquiry. Monsieur Defarge alighted; knowing one or two
\par of the soldiery there, and one of the police. The latter he was intimate
\par with, and affectionately embraced.
\par 
\par When Saint Antoine had again enfolded the Defarges in his dusky wings,
\par and they, having finally alighted near the Saint's boundaries, were
\par picking their way on foot through the black mud and offal of his
\par streets, Madame Defarge spoke to her husband:
\par 
\par "Say then, my friend; what did Jacques of the police tell thee?"
\par 
\par "Very little to-night, but all he knows. There is another spy
\par commissioned for our quarter. There may be many more, for all that he
\par can say, but he knows of one."
\par 
\par "Eh well!" said Madame Defarge, raising her eyebrows with a cool
\par business air. "It is necessary to register him. How do they call that
\par man?"
\par 
\par "He is English."
\par 
\par "So much the better. His name?"
\par 
\par "Barsad," said Defarge, making it French by pronunciation. But, he had
\par been so careful to get it accurately, that he then spelt it with perfect
\par correctness.
\par 
\par "Barsad," repeated madame. "Good. Christian name?"
\par 
\par "John."
\par 
\par "John Barsad," repeated madame, after murmuring it once to herself.
\par "Good. His appearance; is it known?"
\par 
\par "Age, about forty years; height, about five feet nine; black hair;
\par complexion dark; generally, rather handsome visage; eyes dark, face
\par thin, long, and sallow; nose aquiline, but not straight, having a
\par peculiar inclination towards the left cheek; expression, therefore,
\par sinister."
\par 
\par "Eh my faith. It is a portrait!" said madame, laughing. "He shall be
\par registered to-morrow."
\par 
\par They turned into the wine-shop, which was closed (for it was midnight),
\par and where Madame Defarge immediately took her post at her desk, counted
\par the small moneys that had been taken during her absence, examined the
\par stock, went through the entries in the book, made other entries of
\par her own, checked the serving man in every possible way, and finally
\par dismissed him to bed. Then she turned out the contents of the bowl
\par of money for the second time, and began knotting them up in her
\par handkerchief, in a chain of separate knots, for safe keeping through the
\par night. All this while, Defarge, with his pipe in his mouth, walked
\par up and down, complacently admiring, but never interfering; in which
\par condition, indeed, as to the business and his domestic affairs, he
\par walked up and down through life.
\par 
\par The night was hot, and the shop, close shut and surrounded by so foul a
\par neighbourhood, was ill-smelling. Monsieur Defarge's olfactory sense was
\par by no means delicate, but the stock of wine smelt much stronger than
\par it ever tasted, and so did the stock of rum and brandy and aniseed. He
\par whiffed the compound of scents away, as he put down his smoked-out pipe.
\par 
\par "You are fatigued," said madame, raising her glance as she knotted the
\par money. "There are only the usual odours."
\par 
\par "I am a little tired," her husband acknowledged.
\par 
\par "You are a little depressed, too," said madame, whose quick eyes had
