\par When the time comes, let loose a tiger and a devil; but wait for the
\par time with the tiger and the devil chained--not shown--yet always ready."
\par 
\par Madame enforced the conclusion of this piece of advice by striking her
\par little counter with her chain of money as if she knocked its brains
\par out, and then gathering the heavy handkerchief under her arm in a serene
\par manner, and observing that it was time to go to bed.
\par 
\par Next noontide saw the admirable woman in her usual place in the
\par wine-shop, knitting away assiduously. A rose lay beside her, and if she
\par now and then glanced at the flower, it was with no infraction of her
\par usual preoccupied air. There were a few customers, drinking or not
\par drinking, standing or seated, sprinkled about. The day was very hot,
\par and heaps of flies, who were extending their inquisitive and adventurous
\par perquisitions into all the glutinous little glasses near madame, fell
\par dead at the bottom. Their decease made no impression on the other flies
\par out promenading, who looked at them in the coolest manner (as if they
\par themselves were elephants, or something as far removed), until they met
\par the same fate. Curious to consider how heedless flies are!--perhaps they
\par thought as much at Court that sunny summer day.
\par 
\par A figure entering at the door threw a shadow on Madame Defarge which she
\par felt to be a new one. She laid down her knitting, and began to pin her
\par rose in her head-dress, before she looked at the figure.
\par 
\par It was curious. The moment Madame Defarge took up the rose, the
\par customers ceased talking, and began gradually to drop out of the
\par wine-shop.
\par 
\par "Good day, madame," said the new-comer.
\par 
\par "Good day, monsieur."
\par 
\par She said it aloud, but added to herself, as she resumed her knitting:
\par "Hah! Good day, age about forty, height about five feet nine, black
\par hair, generally rather handsome visage, complexion dark, eyes dark,
\par thin, long and sallow face, aquiline nose but not straight, having a
\par peculiar inclination towards the left cheek which imparts a sinister
\par expression! Good day, one and all!"
\par 
\par "Have the goodness to give me a little glass of old cognac, and a
\par mouthful of cool fresh water, madame."
\par 
\par Madame complied with a polite air.
\par 
\par "Marvellous cognac this, madame!"
\par 
\par It was the first time it had ever been so complimented, and Madame
\par Defarge knew enough of its antecedents to know better. She said,
\par however, that the cognac was flattered, and took up her knitting. The
\par visitor watched her fingers for a few moments, and took the opportunity
\par of observing the place in general.
\par 
\par "You knit with great skill, madame."
\par 
\par "I am accustomed to it."
\par 
\par "A pretty pattern too!"
\par 
\par "_You_ think so?" said madame, looking at him with a smile.
\par 
\par "Decidedly. May one ask what it is for?"
\par 
\par "Pastime," said madame, still looking at him with a smile while her
\par fingers moved nimbly.
\par 
\par "Not for use?"
\par 
\par "That depends. I may find a use for it one day. If I do--Well," said
\par madame, drawing a breath and nodding her head with a stern kind of
\par coquetry, "I'll use it!"
\par 
\par It was remarkable; but, the taste of Saint Antoine seemed to be
\par decidedly opposed to a rose on the head-dress of Madame Defarge. Two
\par men had entered separately, and had been about to order drink, when,
\par catching sight of that novelty, they faltered, made a pretence of
\par looking about as if for some friend who was not there, and went away.
\par Nor, of those who had been there when this visitor entered, was there
\par one left. They had all dropped off. The spy had kept his eyes open,
\par but had been able to detect no sign. They had lounged away in a
\par poverty-stricken, purposeless, accidental manner, quite natural and
\par unimpeachable.
\par 
\par "_John_," thought madame, checking off her work as her fingers knitted,
\par and her eyes looked at the stranger. "Stay long enough, and I shall knit
\par 'BARSAD' before you go."
\par 
\par "You have a husband, madame?"
\par 
\par "I have."
\par 
\par "Children?"
\par 
\par "No children."
\par 
\par "Business seems bad?"
\par 
\par "Business is very bad; the people are so poor."
\par 
\par "Ah, the unfortunate, miserable people! So oppressed, too--as you say."
\par 
\par "As _you_ say," madame retorted, correcting him, and deftly knitting an
\par extra something into his name that boded him no good.
\par 
\par "Pardon me; certainly it was I who said so, but you naturally think so.
\par Of course."
\par 
\par "_I_ think?" returned madame, in a high voice. "I and my husband have
\par enough to do to keep this wine-shop open, without thinking. All we
\par think, here, is how to live. That is the subject _we_ think of, and
\par it gives us, from morning to night, enough to think about, without
\par embarrassing our heads concerning others. _I_ think for others? No, no."
\par 
\par The spy, who was there to pick up any crumbs he could find or make, did
\par not allow his baffled state to express itself in his sinister face; but,
\par stood with an air of gossiping gallantry, leaning his elbow on Madame
\par Defarge's little counter, and occasionally sipping his cognac.
\par 
\par "A bad business this, madame, of Gaspard's execution. Ah! the poor
\par Gaspard!" With a sigh of great compassion.
\par 
\par "My faith!" returned madame, coolly and lightly, "if people use knives
\par for such purposes, they have to pay for it. He knew beforehand what the
\par price of his luxury was; he has paid the price."
\par 
\par "I believe," said the spy, dropping his soft voice to a tone
\par that invited confidence, and expressing an injured revolutionary
\par susceptibility in every muscle of his wicked face: "I believe there
\par is much compassion and anger in this neighbourhood, touching the poor
\par fellow? Between ourselves."
\par 
\par "Is there?" asked madame, vacantly.
\par 
\par "Is there not?"
\par 
\par "--Here is my husband!" said Madame Defarge.
\par 
\par As the keeper of the wine-shop entered at the door, the spy saluted
\par him by touching his hat, and saying, with an engaging smile, "Good day,
\par Jacques!" Defarge stopped short, and stared at him.
\par 
\par "Good day, Jacques!" the spy repeated; with not quite so much
\par confidence, or quite so easy a smile under the stare.
\par 
\par "You deceive yourself, monsieur," returned the keeper of the wine-shop.
\par "You mistake me for another. That is not my name. I am Ernest Defarge."
\par 
\par "It is all the same," said the spy, airily, but discomfited too: "good
\par day!"
\par 
\par "Good day!" answered Defarge, drily.
\par 
\par "I was saying to madame, with whom I had the pleasure of chatting when
\par you entered, that they tell me there is--and no wonder!--much sympathy
\par and anger in Saint Antoine, touching the unhappy fate of poor Gaspard."
\par 
\par "No one has told me so," said Defarge, shaking his head. "I know nothing
\par of it."
\par 
\par Having said it, he passed behind the little counter, and stood with his
\par hand on the back of his wife's chair, looking over that barrier at the
\par person to whom they were both opposed, and whom either of them would
\par have shot with the greatest satisfaction.
\par 
\par The spy, well used to his business, did not change his unconscious
\par attitude, but drained his little glass of cognac, took a sip of fresh
\par water, and asked for another glass of cognac. Madame Defarge poured it
\par out for him, took to her knitting again, and hummed a little song over
\par it.
\par 
\par "You seem to know this quarter well; that is to say, better than I do?"
\par observed Defarge.
\par 
\par "Not at all, but I hope to know it better. I am so profoundly interested
\par in its miserable inhabitants."
\par 
\par "Hah!" muttered Defarge.
\par 
\par "The pleasure of conversing with you, Monsieur Defarge, recalls to me,"
\par pursued the spy, "that I have the honour of cherishing some interesting
\par associations with your name."
\par 
\par "Indeed!" said Defarge, with much indifference.
\par 
\par "Yes, indeed. When Doctor Manette was released, you, his old domestic,
\par had the charge of him, I know. He was delivered to you. You see I am
\par informed of the circumstances?"
\par 
\par "Such is the fact, certainly," said Defarge. He had had it conveyed
\par to him, in an accidental touch of his wife's elbow as she knitted and
\par warbled, that he would do best to answer, but always with brevity.
\par 
\par "It was to you," said the spy, "that his daughter came; and it was
\par from your care that his daughter took him, accompanied by a neat brown
\par monsieur; how is he called?--in a little wig--Lorry--of the bank of
\par Tellson and Company--over to England."
\par 
\par "Such is the fact," repeated Defarge.
\par 
\par "Very interesting remembrances!" said the spy. "I have known Doctor
\par Manette and his daughter, in England."
\par 
\par "Yes?" said Defarge.
\par 
\par "You don't hear much about them now?" said the spy.
\par 
\par "No," said Defarge.
\par 
\par "In effect," madame struck in, looking up from her work and her little
\par song, "we never hear about them. We received the news of their safe
\par arrival, and perhaps another letter, or perhaps two; but, since then,
\par they have gradually taken their road in life--we, ours--and we have held
\par no correspondence."
\par 
\par "Perfectly so, madame," replied the spy. "She is going to be married."
\par 
\par "Going?" echoed madame. "She was pretty enough to have been married long
\par ago. You English are cold, it seems to me."
\par 
\par "Oh! You know I am English."
\par 
\par "I perceive your tongue is," returned madame; "and what the tongue is, I
\par suppose the man is."
\par 
\par He did not take the identification as a compliment; but he made the best
\par of it, and turned it off with a laugh. After sipping his cognac to the
\par end, he added:
\par 
\par "Yes, Miss Manette is going to be married. But not to an Englishman; to
\par one who, like herself, is French by birth. And speaking of Gaspard (ah,
\par poor Gaspard! It was cruel, cruel!), it is a curious thing that she is
\par going to marry the nephew of Monsieur the Marquis, for whom Gaspard
\par was exalted to that height of so many feet; in other words, the present
\par Marquis. But he lives unknown in England, he is no Marquis there; he is
\par Mr. Charles Darnay. D'Aulnais is the name of his mother's family."
\par 
\par Madame Defarge knitted steadily, but the intelligence had a palpable
\par effect upon her husband. Do what he would, behind the little counter,
\par as to the striking of a light and the lighting of his pipe, he was
\par troubled, and his hand was not trustworthy. The spy would have been no
\par spy if he had failed to see it, or to record it in his mind.
\par 
\par Having made, at least, this one hit, whatever it might prove to be
\par worth, and no customers coming in to help him to any other, Mr. Barsad
\par paid for what he had drunk, and took his leave: taking occasion to say,
\par in a genteel manner, before he departed, that he looked forward to the
\par pleasure of seeing Monsieur and Madame Defarge again. For some minutes
\par after he had emerged into the outer presence of Saint Antoine, the
\par husband and wife remained exactly as he had left them, lest he should
\par come back.
\par 
\par "Can it be true," said Defarge, in a low voice, looking down at his wife
\par as he stood smoking with his hand on the back of her chair: "what he has
\par said of Ma'amselle Manette?"
\par 
\par "As he has said it," returned madame, lifting her eyebrows a little, "it
\par is probably false. But it may be true."
\par 
\par "If it is--" Defarge began, and stopped.
\par 
\par "If it is?" repeated his wife.
\par 
\par "--And if it does come, while we live to see it triumph--I hope, for her
\par sake, Destiny will keep her husband out of France."
\par 
\par "Her husband's destiny," said Madame Defarge, with her usual composure,
\par "will take him where he is to go, and will lead him to the end that is
\par to end him. That is all I know."
\par 
\par "But it is very strange--now, at least, is it not very strange"--said
\par Defarge, rather pleading with his wife to induce her to admit it,
\par "that, after all our sympathy for Monsieur her father, and herself, her
\par husband's name should be proscribed under your hand at this moment, by
\par the side of that infernal dog's who has just left us?"
\par 
\par "Stranger things than that will happen when it does come," answered
\par madame. "I have them both here, of a certainty; and they are both here
\par for their merits; that is enough."
\par 
\par She rolled up her knitting when she had said those words, and presently
\par took the rose out of the handkerchief that was wound about her head.
\par Either Saint Antoine had an instinctive sense that the objectionable
\par decoration was gone, or Saint Antoine was on the watch for its
\par disappearance; howbeit, the Saint took courage to lounge in, very
\par shortly afterwards, and the wine-shop recovered its habitual aspect.
\par 
\par In the evening, at which season of all others Saint Antoine turned
\par himself inside out, and sat on door-steps and window-ledges, and came
\par to the corners of vile streets and courts, for a breath of air, Madame
\par Defarge with her work in her hand was accustomed to pass from place
\par to place and from group to group: a Missionary--there were many like
\par her--such as the world will do well never to breed again. All the women
\par knitted. They knitted worthless things; but, the mechanical work was a
\par mechanical substitute for eating and drinking; the hands moved for the
\par jaws and the digestive apparatus: if the bony fingers had been still,
\par the stomachs would have been more famine-pinched.
\par 
\par But, as the fingers went, the eyes went, and the thoughts. And as Madame
\par Defarge moved on from group to group, all three went quicker and fiercer
\par among every little knot of women that she had spoken with, and left
\par behind.
\par 
\par Her husband smoked at his door, looking after her with admiration. "A
\par great woman," said he, "a strong woman, a grand woman, a frightfully
\par grand woman!"
\par 
\par Darkness closed around, and then came the ringing of church bells and
\par the distant beating of the military drums in the Palace Courtyard, as
\par the women sat knitting, knitting. Darkness encompassed them. Another
\par darkness was closing in as surely, when the church bells, then ringing
\par pleasantly in many an airy steeple over France, should be melted into
\par thundering cannon; when the military drums should be beating to drown a
\par wretched voice, that night all potent as the voice of Power and Plenty,
\par Freedom and Life. So much was closing in about the women who sat
\par knitting, knitting, that they their very selves were closing in around
\par a structure yet unbuilt, where they were to sit knitting, knitting,
\par counting dropping heads.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XVII. One Night
\par 
\par 
\par Never did the sun go down with a brighter glory on the quiet corner in
\par Soho, than one memorable evening when the Doctor and his daughter sat
\par under the plane-tree together. Never did the moon rise with a milder
\par radiance over great London, than on that night when it found them still
\par seated under the tree, and shone upon their faces through its leaves.
\par 
\par Lucie was to be married to-morrow. She had reserved this last evening
\par for her father, and they sat alone under the plane-tree.
\par 
\par "You are happy, my dear father?"
\par 
\par "Quite, my child."
\par 
\par They had said little, though they had been there a long time. When it
\par was yet light enough to work and read, she had neither engaged herself
\par in her usual work, nor had she read to him. She had employed herself in
\par both ways, at his side under the tree, many and many a time; but, this
\par time was not quite like any other, and nothing could make it so.
\par 
\par "And I am very happy to-night, dear father. I am deeply happy in the
\par love that Heaven has so blessed--my love for Charles, and Charles's love
\par for me. But, if my life were not to be still consecrated to you, or
\par if my marriage were so arranged as that it would part us, even by
\par the length of a few of these streets, I should be more unhappy and
\par self-reproachful now than I can tell you. Even as it is--"
\par 
\par Even as it was, she could not command her voice.
\par 
\par In the sad moonlight, she clasped him by the neck, and laid her face
\par upon his breast. In the moonlight which is always sad, as the light of
\par the sun itself is--as the light called human life is--at its coming and
\par its going.
\par 
\par "Dearest dear! Can you tell me, this last time, that you feel quite,
\par quite sure, no new affections of mine, and no new duties of mine, will
\par ever interpose between us? _I_ know it well, but do you know it? In your
\par own heart, do you feel quite certain?"
\par 
\par Her father answered, with a cheerful firmness of conviction he could
\par scarcely have assumed, "Quite sure, my darling! More than that," he
\par added, as he tenderly kissed her: "my future is far brighter, Lucie,
\par seen through your marriage, than it could have been--nay, than it ever
\par was--without it."
\par 
\par "If I could hope _that_, my father!--"
\par 
\par "Believe it, love! Indeed it is so. Consider how natural and how plain
\par it is, my dear, that it should be so. You, devoted and young, cannot
\par fully appreciate the anxiety I have felt that your life should not be
\par wasted--"
\par 
\par She moved her hand towards his lips, but he took it in his, and repeated
\par the word.
\par 
\par "--wasted, my child--should not be wasted, struck aside from the
\par natural order of things--for my sake. Your unselfishness cannot entirely
\par comprehend how much my mind has gone on this; but, only ask yourself,
\par how could my happiness be perfect, while yours was incomplete?"
\par 
\par "If I had never seen Charles, my father, I should have been quite happy
\par with you."
\par 
\par He smiled at her unconscious admission that she would have been unhappy
\par without Charles, having seen him; and replied:
\par 
\par "My child, you did see him, and it is Charles. If it had not been
\par Charles, it would have been another. Or, if it had been no other, I
\par should have been the cause, and then the dark part of my life would have
\par cast its shadow beyond myself, and would have fallen on you."
\par 
\par It was the first time, except at the trial, of her ever hearing him
\par refer to the period of his suffering. It gave her a strange and new
\par sensation while his words were in her ears; and she remembered it long
\par afterwards.
\par 
\par "See!" said the Doctor of Beauvais, raising his hand towards the moon.
\par "I have looked at her from my prison-window, when I could not bear her
\par light. I have looked at her when it has been such torture to me to think
\par of her shining upon what I had lost, that I have beaten my head against
\par my prison-walls. I have looked at her, in a state so dull and lethargic,
\par that I have thought of nothing but the number of horizontal lines I
\par could draw across her at the full, and the number of perpendicular lines
\par with which I could intersect them." He added in his inward and pondering
\par manner, as he looked at the moon, "It was twenty either way, I remember,
\par and the twentieth was difficult to squeeze in."
\par 
\par The strange thrill with which she heard him go back to that time,
\par deepened as he dwelt upon it; but, there was nothing to shock her in
\par the manner of his reference. He only seemed to contrast his present
\par cheerfulness and felicity with the dire endurance that was over.
\par 
\par "I have looked at her, speculating thousands of times upon the unborn
\par child from whom I had been rent. Whether it was alive. Whether it had
\par been born alive, or the poor mother's shock had killed it. Whether it
\par was a son who would some day avenge his father. (There was a time in my
\par imprisonment, when my desire for vengeance was unbearable.) Whether it
\par was a son who would never know his father's story; who might even live
\par to weigh the possibility of his father's having disappeared of his own
\par will and act. Whether it was a daughter who would grow to be a woman."
\par 
\par She drew closer to him, and kissed his cheek and his hand.
\par 
\par "I have pictured my daughter, to myself, as perfectly forgetful of
\par me--rather, altogether ignorant of me, and unconscious of me. I have
\par cast up the years of her age, year after year. I have seen her married
\par to a man who knew nothing of my fate. I have altogether perished from
\par the remembrance of the living, and in the next generation my place was a
\par blank."
\par 
\par "My father! Even to hear that you had such thoughts of a daughter who
\par never existed, strikes to my heart as if I had been that child."
\par 
\par "You, Lucie? It is out of the Consolation and restoration you have
\par brought to me, that these remembrances arise, and pass between us and
\par the moon on this last night.--What did I say just now?"
\par 
\par "She knew nothing of you. She cared nothing for you."
\par 
\par "So! But on other moonlight nights, when the sadness and the silence
\par have touched me in a different way--have affected me with something as
\par like a sorrowful sense of peace, as any emotion that had pain for its
\par foundations could--I have imagined her as coming to me in my cell, and
\par leading me out into the freedom beyond the fortress. I have seen her
\par image in the moonlight often, as I now see you; except that I never held
\par her in my arms; it stood between the little grated window and the door.
\par But, you understand that that was not the child I am speaking of?"
\par 
\par "The figure was not; the--the--image; the fancy?"
\par 
\par "No. That was another thing. It stood before my disturbed sense of
\par sight, but it never moved. The phantom that my mind pursued, was another
\par and more real child. Of her outward appearance I know no more than
\par that she was like her mother. The other had that likeness too--as you
\par have--but was not the same. Can you follow me, Lucie? Hardly, I think?
\par I doubt you must have been a solitary prisoner to understand these
\par perplexed distinctions."
\par 
\par His collected and calm manner could not prevent her blood from running
\par cold, as he thus tried to anatomise his old condition.
\par 
\par "In that more peaceful state, I have imagined her, in the moonlight,
\par coming to me and taking me out to show me that the home of her married
\par life was full of her loving remembrance of her lost father. My picture
\par was in her room, and I was in her prayers. Her life was active,
\par cheerful, useful; but my poor history pervaded it all."
\par 
\par "I was that child, my father, I was not half so good, but in my love
\par that was I."
\par 
\par "And she showed me her children," said the Doctor of Beauvais, "and
\par they had heard of me, and had been taught to pity me. When they passed
\par a prison of the State, they kept far from its frowning walls, and looked
\par up at its bars, and spoke in whispers. She could never deliver me; I
\par imagined that she always brought me back after showing me such things.
\par But then, blessed with the relief of tears, I fell upon my knees, and
\par blessed her."
\par 
\par "I am that child, I hope, my father. O my dear, my dear, will you bless
\par me as fervently to-morrow?"
\par 
\par "Lucie, I recall these old troubles in the reason that I have to-night
\par for loving you better than words can tell, and thanking God for my great
\par happiness. My thoughts, when they were wildest, never rose near the
\par happiness that I have known with you, and that we have before us."
\par 
\par He embraced her, solemnly commended her to Heaven, and humbly thanked
\par Heaven for having bestowed her on him. By-and-bye, they went into the
\par house.
\par 
\par There was no one bidden to the marriage but Mr. Lorry; there was even to
\par be no bridesmaid but the gaunt Miss Pross. The marriage was to make no
\par change in their place of residence; they had been able to extend it,
\par by taking to themselves the upper rooms formerly belonging to the
\par apocryphal invisible lodger, and they desired nothing more.
\par 
\par Doctor Manette was very cheerful at the little supper. They were only
\par three at table, and Miss Pross made the third. He regretted that Charles
\par was not there; was more than half disposed to object to the loving
\par little plot that kept him away; and drank to him affectionately.
\par 
\par So, the time came for him to bid Lucie good night, and they separated.
\par But, in the stillness of the third hour of the morning, Lucie came
\par downstairs again, and stole into his room; not free from unshaped fears,
\par beforehand.
\par 
\par All things, however, were in their places; all was quiet; and he lay
\par asleep, his white hair picturesque on the untroubled pillow, and his
\par hands lying quiet on the coverlet. She put her needless candle in the
\par shadow at a distance, crept up to his bed, and put her lips to his;
\par then, leaned over him, and looked at him.
\par 
\par Into his handsome face, the bitter waters of captivity had worn; but, he
\par covered up their tracks with a determination so strong, that he held the
\par mastery of them even in his sleep. A more remarkable face in its quiet,
\par resolute, and guarded struggle with an unseen assailant, was not to be
\par beheld in all the wide dominions of sleep, that night.
\par 
\par She timidly laid her hand on his dear breast, and put up a prayer that
\par she might ever be as true to him as her love aspired to be, and as his
\par sorrows deserved. Then, she withdrew her hand, and kissed his lips once
\par more, and went away. So, the sunrise came, and the shadows of the leaves
\par of the plane-tree moved upon his face, as softly as her lips had moved
\par in praying for him.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XVIII. Nine Days
\par 
\par 
\par The marriage-day was shining brightly, and they were ready outside the
\par closed door of the Doctor's room, where he was speaking with Charles
\par Darnay. They were ready to go to church; the beautiful bride, Mr.
\par Lorry, and Miss Pross--to whom the event, through a gradual process of
\par reconcilement to the inevitable, would have been one of absolute bliss,
\par but for the yet lingering consideration that her brother Solomon should
\par have been the bridegroom.
\par 
\par "And so," said Mr. Lorry, who could not sufficiently admire the bride,
\par and who had been moving round her to take in every point of her quiet,
\par pretty dress; "and so it was for this, my sweet Lucie, that I brought
\par you across the Channel, such a baby! Lord bless me! How little I thought
\par what I was doing! How lightly I valued the obligation I was conferring
\par on my friend Mr. Charles!"
\par 
\par "You didn't mean it," remarked the matter-of-fact Miss Pross, "and
\par therefore how could you know it? Nonsense!"
\par 
\par "Really? Well; but don't cry," said the gentle Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "I am not crying," said Miss Pross; "_you_ are."
\par 
\par "I, my Pross?" (By this time, Mr. Lorry dared to be pleasant with her,
\par on occasion.)
\par 
\par "You were, just now; I saw you do it, and I don't wonder at it. Such
\par a present of plate as you have made 'em, is enough to bring tears into
\par anybody's eyes. There's not a fork or a spoon in the collection," said
\par Miss Pross, "that I didn't cry over, last night after the box came, till
\par I couldn't see it."
\par 
\par "I am highly gratified," said Mr. Lorry, "though, upon my honour, I
\par had no intention of rendering those trifling articles of remembrance
\par invisible to any one. Dear me! This is an occasion that makes a man
\par speculate on all he has lost. Dear, dear, dear! To think that there
\par might have been a Mrs. Lorry, any time these fifty years almost!"
\par 
\par "Not at all!" From Miss Pross.
\par 
\par "You think there never might have been a Mrs. Lorry?" asked the
\par gentleman of that name.
\par 
\par "Pooh!" rejoined Miss Pross; "you were a bachelor in your cradle."
\par 
\par "Well!" observed Mr. Lorry, beamingly adjusting his little wig, "that
\par seems probable, too."
\par 
\par "And you were cut out for a bachelor," pursued Miss Pross, "before you
\par were put in your cradle."
\par 
\par "Then, I think," said Mr. Lorry, "that I was very unhandsomely dealt
\par with, and that I ought to have had a voice in the selection of my
\par pattern. Enough! Now, my dear Lucie," drawing his arm soothingly round
\par her waist, "I hear them moving in the next room, and Miss Pross and
\par I, as two formal folks of business, are anxious not to lose the final
\par opportunity of saying something to you that you wish to hear. You leave
\par your good father, my dear, in hands as earnest and as loving as your
\par own; he shall be taken every conceivable care of; during the next
\par fortnight, while you are in Warwickshire and thereabouts, even Tellson's
\par shall go to the wall (comparatively speaking) before him. And when, at
\par the fortnight's end, he comes to join you and your beloved husband, on
\par your other fortnight's trip in Wales, you shall say that we have sent
\par him to you in the best health and in the happiest frame. Now, I hear
\par Somebody's step coming to the door. Let me kiss my dear girl with an
\par old-fashioned bachelor blessing, before Somebody comes to claim his
\par own."
\par 
\par For a moment, he held the fair face from him to look at the
\par well-remembered expression on the forehead, and then laid the bright
\par golden hair against his little brown wig, with a genuine tenderness and
\par delicacy which, if such things be old-fashioned, were as old as Adam.
\par 
\par The door of the Doctor's room opened, and he came out with Charles
\par Darnay. He was so deadly pale--which had not been the case when they
\par went in together--that no vestige of colour was to be seen in his face.
\par But, in the composure of his manner he was unaltered, except that to the
\par shrewd glance of Mr. Lorry it disclosed some shadowy indication that the
\par old air of avoidance and dread had lately passed over him, like a cold
\par wind.
\par 
\par He gave his arm to his daughter, and took her down-stairs to the chariot
\par which Mr. Lorry had hired in honour of the day. The rest followed in
\par another carriage, and soon, in a neighbouring church, where no strange
\par eyes looked on, Charles Darnay and Lucie Manette were happily married.
\par 
\par Besides the glancing tears that shone among the smiles of the little
\par group when it was done, some diamonds, very bright and sparkling,
\par glanced on the bride's hand, which were newly released from the
\par dark obscurity of one of Mr. Lorry's pockets. They returned home to
\par breakfast, and all went well, and in due course the golden hair that had
\par mingled with the poor shoemaker's white locks in the Paris garret, were
\par mingled with them again in the morning sunlight, on the threshold of the
\par door at parting.
\par 
\par It was a hard parting, though it was not for long. But her father
\par cheered her, and said at last, gently disengaging himself from her
\par enfolding arms, "Take her, Charles! She is yours!"
\par 
\par And her agitated hand waved to them from a chaise window, and she was
\par gone.
\par 
\par The corner being out of the way of the idle and curious, and the
\par preparations having been very simple and few, the Doctor, Mr. Lorry,
\par and Miss Pross, were left quite alone. It was when they turned into
\par the welcome shade of the cool old hall, that Mr. Lorry observed a great
\par change to have come over the Doctor; as if the golden arm uplifted
\par there, had struck him a poisoned blow.
\par 
\par He had naturally repressed much, and some revulsion might have been
\par expected in him when the occasion for repression was gone. But, it was
\par the old scared lost look that troubled Mr. Lorry; and through his absent
\par manner of clasping his head and drearily wandering away into his own
\par room when they got up-stairs, Mr. Lorry was reminded of Defarge the
\par wine-shop keeper, and the starlight ride.
\par 
\par "I think," he whispered to Miss Pross, after anxious consideration, "I
\par think we had best not speak to him just now, or at all disturb him.
\par I must look in at Tellson's; so I will go there at once and come back
\par presently. Then, we will take him a ride into the country, and dine
\par there, and all will be well."
\par 
\par It was easier for Mr. Lorry to look in at Tellson's, than to look out of
\par Tellson's. He was detained two hours. When he came back, he ascended the
\par old staircase alone, having asked no question of the servant; going thus
\par into the Doctor's rooms, he was stopped by a low sound of knocking.
\par 
\par "Good God!" he said, with a start. "What's that?"
\par 
\par Miss Pross, with a terrified face, was at his ear. "O me, O me! All is
\par lost!" cried she, wringing her hands. "What is to be told to Ladybird?
\par He doesn't know me, and is making shoes!"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry said what he could to calm her, and went himself into the
\par Doctor's room. The bench was turned towards the light, as it had been
\par when he had seen the shoemaker at his work before, and his head was bent
\par down, and he was very busy.
\par 
\par "Doctor Manette. My dear friend, Doctor Manette!"
\par 
\par The Doctor looked at him for a moment--half inquiringly, half as if he
\par were angry at being spoken to--and bent over his work again.
\par 
\par He had laid aside his coat and waistcoat; his shirt was open at the
\par throat, as it used to be when he did that work; and even the old
\par haggard, faded surface of face had come back to him. He worked
\par hard--impatiently--as if in some sense of having been interrupted.
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry glanced at the work in his hand, and observed that it was a
\par shoe of the old size and shape. He took up another that was lying by
\par him, and asked what it was.
\par 
\par "A young lady's walking shoe," he muttered, without looking up. "It
\par ought to have been finished long ago. Let it be."
\par 
\par "But, Doctor Manette. Look at me!"
\par 
\par He obeyed, in the old mechanically submissive manner, without pausing in
\par his work.
\par 
\par "You know me, my dear friend? Think again. This is not your proper
\par occupation. Think, dear friend!"
\par 
\par Nothing would induce him to speak more. He looked up, for an instant at
\par a time, when he was requested to do so; but, no persuasion would extract
\par a word from him. He worked, and worked, and worked, in silence, and
\par words fell on him as they would have fallen on an echoless wall, or on
\par the air. The only ray of hope that Mr. Lorry could discover, was, that
\par he sometimes furtively looked up without being asked. In that, there
\par seemed a faint expression of curiosity or perplexity--as though he were
\par trying to reconcile some doubts in his mind.
\par 
\par Two things at once impressed themselves on Mr. Lorry, as important above
\par all others; the first, that this must be kept secret from Lucie;
\par the second, that it must be kept secret from all who knew him. In
\par conjunction with Miss Pross, he took immediate steps towards the latter
\par precaution, by giving out that the Doctor was not well, and required a
\par few days of complete rest. In aid of the kind deception to be practised
\par on his daughter, Miss Pross was to write, describing his having been
\par called away professionally, and referring to an imaginary letter of
\par two or three hurried lines in his own hand, represented to have been
\par addressed to her by the same post.
\par 
\par These measures, advisable to be taken in any case, Mr. Lorry took in
\par the hope of his coming to himself. If that should happen soon, he kept
\par another course in reserve; which was, to have a certain opinion that he
\par thought the best, on the Doctor's case.
\par 
\par In the hope of his recovery, and of resort to this third course
\par being thereby rendered practicable, Mr. Lorry resolved to watch him
\par attentively, with as little appearance as possible of doing so. He
\par therefore made arrangements to absent himself from Tellson's for the
\par first time in his life, and took his post by the window in the same
\par room.
\par 
\par He was not long in discovering that it was worse than useless to speak
\par to him, since, on being pressed, he became worried. He abandoned that
\par attempt on the first day, and resolved merely to keep himself always
\par before him, as a silent protest against the delusion into which he had
\par fallen, or was falling. He remained, therefore, in his seat near the
\par window, reading and writing, and expressing in as many pleasant and
\par natural ways as he could think of, that it was a free place.
\par 
\par Doctor Manette took what was given him to eat and drink, and worked on,
\par that first day, until it was too dark to see--worked on, half an hour
\par after Mr. Lorry could not have seen, for his life, to read or write.
\par When he put his tools aside as useless, until morning, Mr. Lorry rose
\par and said to him:
\par 
\par "Will you go out?"
\par 
\par He looked down at the floor on either side of him in the old manner,
\par looked up in the old manner, and repeated in the old low voice:
\par 
\par "Out?"
\par 
\par "Yes; for a walk with me. Why not?"
\par 
\par He made no effort to say why not, and said not a word more. But, Mr.
\par Lorry thought he saw, as he leaned forward on his bench in the dusk,
\par with his elbows on his knees and his head in his hands, that he was in
\par some misty way asking himself, "Why not?" The sagacity of the man of
\par business perceived an advantage here, and determined to hold it.
\par 
\par Miss Pross and he divided the night into two watches, and observed him
\par at intervals from the adjoining room. He paced up and down for a long
\par time before he lay down; but, when he did finally lay himself down, he
\par fell asleep. In the morning, he was up betimes, and went straight to his
\par bench and to work.
\par 
\par On this second day, Mr. Lorry saluted him cheerfully by his name,
\par and spoke to him on topics that had been of late familiar to them. He
\par returned no reply, but it was evident that he heard what was said, and
\par that he thought about it, however confusedly. This encouraged Mr. Lorry
\par to have Miss Pross in with her work, several times during the day;
\par at those times, they quietly spoke of Lucie, and of her father then
\par present, precisely in the usual manner, and as if there were nothing
\par amiss. This was done without any demonstrative accompaniment, not long
\par enough, or often enough to harass him; and it lightened Mr. Lorry's
\par friendly heart to believe that he looked up oftener, and that he
\par appeared to be stirred by some perception of inconsistencies surrounding
\par him.
\par 
\par When it fell dark again, Mr. Lorry asked him as before:
\par 
\par "Dear Doctor, will you go out?"
\par 
\par As before, he repeated, "Out?"
\par 
\par "Yes; for a walk with me. Why not?"
\par 
\par This time, Mr. Lorry feigned to go out when he could extract no answer
\par from him, and, after remaining absent for an hour, returned. In the
\par meanwhile, the Doctor had removed to the seat in the window, and had
\par sat there looking down at the plane-tree; but, on Mr. Lorry's return, he
\par slipped away to his bench.
\par 
\par The time went very slowly on, and Mr. Lorry's hope darkened, and his
\par heart grew heavier again, and grew yet heavier and heavier every day.
\par The third day came and went, the fourth, the fifth. Five days, six days,
\par seven days, eight days, nine days.
\par 
\par With a hope ever darkening, and with a heart always growing heavier and
\par heavier, Mr. Lorry passed through this anxious time. The secret was
\par well kept, and Lucie was unconscious and happy; but he could not fail to
\par observe that the shoemaker, whose hand had been a little out at first,
\par was growing dreadfully skilful, and that he had never been so intent on
\par his work, and that his hands had never been so nimble and expert, as in
\par the dusk of the ninth evening.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XIX. An Opinion
\par 
\par 
\par Worn out by anxious watching, Mr. Lorry fell asleep at his post. On the
\par tenth morning of his suspense, he was startled by the shining of the sun
\par into the room where a heavy slumber had overtaken him when it was dark
\par night.
\par 
\par He rubbed his eyes and roused himself; but he doubted, when he had
\par done so, whether he was not still asleep. For, going to the door of the
\par Doctor's room and looking in, he perceived that the shoemaker's bench
\par and tools were put aside again, and that the Doctor himself sat reading
\par at the window. He was in his usual morning dress, and his face (which
\par Mr. Lorry could distinctly see), though still very pale, was calmly
\par studious and attentive.
\par 
\par Even when he had satisfied himself that he was awake, Mr. Lorry felt
\par giddily uncertain for some few moments whether the late shoemaking might
\par not be a disturbed dream of his own; for, did not his eyes show him his
\par friend before him in his accustomed clothing and aspect, and employed
\par as usual; and was there any sign within their range, that the change of
\par which he had so strong an impression had actually happened?
\par 
\par It was but the inquiry of his first confusion and astonishment, the
\par answer being obvious. If the impression were not produced by a real
\par corresponding and sufficient cause, how came he, Jarvis Lorry, there?
\par How came he to have fallen asleep, in his clothes, on the sofa in Doctor
\par Manette's consulting-room, and to be debating these points outside the
\par Doctor's bedroom door in the early morning?
\par 
\par Within a few minutes, Miss Pross stood whispering at his side. If he
\par had had any particle of doubt left, her talk would of necessity have
\par resolved it; but he was by that time clear-headed, and had none.
\par He advised that they should let the time go by until the regular
\par breakfast-hour, and should then meet the Doctor as if nothing unusual
\par had occurred. If he appeared to be in his customary state of mind, Mr.
\par Lorry would then cautiously proceed to seek direction and guidance from
\par the opinion he had been, in his anxiety, so anxious to obtain.
\par 
\par Miss Pross, submitting herself to his judgment, the scheme was worked
\par out with care. Having abundance of time for his usual methodical
\par toilette, Mr. Lorry presented himself at the breakfast-hour in his usual
\par white linen, and with his usual neat leg. The Doctor was summoned in the
\par usual way, and came to breakfast.
\par 
\par So far as it was possible to comprehend him without overstepping those
\par delicate and gradual approaches which Mr. Lorry felt to be the only safe
\par advance, he at first supposed that his daughter's marriage had taken
\par place yesterday. An incidental allusion, purposely thrown out, to
\par the day of the week, and the day of the month, set him thinking and
\par counting, and evidently made him uneasy. In all other respects, however,
\par he was so composedly himself, that Mr. Lorry determined to have the aid
\par he sought. And that aid was his own.
\par 
\par Therefore, when the breakfast was done and cleared away, and he and the
\par Doctor were left together, Mr. Lorry said, feelingly:
\par 
\par "My dear Manette, I am anxious to have your opinion, in confidence, on a
\par very curious case in which I am deeply interested; that is to say, it is
\par very curious to me; perhaps, to your better information it may be less
\par so."
\par 
\par Glancing at his hands, which were discoloured by his late work, the
\par Doctor looked troubled, and listened attentively. He had already glanced
\par at his hands more than once.
\par 
\par "Doctor Manette," said Mr. Lorry, touching him affectionately on the
\par arm, "the case is the case of a particularly dear friend of mine. Pray
\par give your mind to it, and advise me well for his sake--and above all,
\par for his daughter's--his daughter's, my dear Manette."
\par 
\par "If I understand," said the Doctor, in a subdued tone, "some mental
\par shock--?"
\par 
\par "Yes!"
\par 
\par "Be explicit," said the Doctor. "Spare no detail."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry saw that they understood one another, and proceeded.
\par 
\par "My dear Manette, it is the case of an old and a prolonged shock,
\par of great acuteness and severity to the affections, the feelings,
\par the--the--as you express it--the mind. The mind. It is the case of a
\par shock under which the sufferer was borne down, one cannot say for how
\par long, because I believe he cannot calculate the time himself, and there
\par are no other means of getting at it. It is the case of a shock from
\par which the sufferer recovered, by a process that he cannot trace
\par himself--as I once heard him publicly relate in a striking manner. It is
\par the case of a shock from which he has recovered, so completely, as to
\par be a highly intelligent man, capable of close application of mind, and
\par great exertion of body, and of constantly making fresh additions to his
\par stock of knowledge, which was already very large. But, unfortunately,
\par there has been," he paused and took a deep breath--"a slight relapse."
\par 
\par The Doctor, in a low voice, asked, "Of how long duration?"
\par 
\par "Nine days and nights."
\par 
\par "How did it show itself? I infer," glancing at his hands again, "in the
\par resumption of some old pursuit connected with the shock?"
\par 
\par "That is the fact."
\par 
\par "Now, did you ever see him," asked the Doctor, distinctly and
\par collectedly, though in the same low voice, "engaged in that pursuit
\par originally?"
\par 
\par "Once."
\par 
\par "And when the relapse fell on him, was he in most respects--or in all
\par respects--as he was then?"
\par 
\par "I think in all respects."
\par 
\par "You spoke of his daughter. Does his daughter know of the relapse?"
\par 
\par "No. It has been kept from her, and I hope will always be kept from her.
\par It is known only to myself, and to one other who may be trusted."
\par 
\par The Doctor grasped his hand, and murmured, "That was very kind. That was
\par very thoughtful!" Mr. Lorry grasped his hand in return, and neither of
\par the two spoke for a little while.
\par 
\par "Now, my dear Manette," said Mr. Lorry, at length, in his most
\par considerate and most affectionate way, "I am a mere man of business,
\par and unfit to cope with such intricate and difficult matters. I do not
\par possess the kind of information necessary; I do not possess the kind of
\par intelligence; I want guiding. There is no man in this world on whom
\par I could so rely for right guidance, as on you. Tell me, how does this
\par relapse come about? Is there danger of another? Could a repetition of it
\par be prevented? How should a repetition of it be treated? How does it come
\par about at all? What can I do for my friend? No man ever can have been
\par more desirous in his heart to serve a friend, than I am to serve mine,
\par if I knew how.
\par 
\par "But I don't know how to originate, in such a case. If your sagacity,
\par knowledge, and experience, could put me on the right track, I might be
\par able to do so much; unenlightened and undirected, I can do so little.
\par Pray discuss it with me; pray enable me to see it a little more clearly,
\par and teach me how to be a little more useful."
\par 
\par Doctor Manette sat meditating after these earnest words were spoken, and
\par Mr. Lorry did not press him.
\par 
\par "I think it probable," said the Doctor, breaking silence with an effort,
\par "that the relapse you have described, my dear friend, was not quite
\par unforeseen by its subject."
\par 
\par "Was it dreaded by him?" Mr. Lorry ventured to ask.
\par 
\par "Very much." He said it with an involuntary shudder.
\par 
\par "You have no idea how such an apprehension weighs on the sufferer's
\par mind, and how difficult--how almost impossible--it is, for him to force
\par himself to utter a word upon the topic that oppresses him."
\par 
\par "Would he," asked Mr. Lorry, "be sensibly relieved if he could prevail
\par upon himself to impart that secret brooding to any one, when it is on
\par him?"
\par 
\par "I think so. But it is, as I have told you, next to impossible. I even
\par believe it--in some cases--to be quite impossible."
\par 
\par "Now," said Mr. Lorry, gently laying his hand on the Doctor's arm again,
\par after a short silence on both sides, "to what would you refer this
\par attack?"
\par 
\par "I believe," returned Doctor Manette, "that there had been a strong and
\par extraordinary revival of the train of thought and remembrance that
\par was the first cause of the malady. Some intense associations of a most
\par distressing nature were vividly recalled, I think. It is probable that
\par there had long been a dread lurking in his mind, that those associations
\par would be recalled--say, under certain circumstances--say, on a
\par particular occasion. He tried to prepare himself in vain; perhaps the
\par effort to prepare himself made him less able to bear it."
\par 
\par "Would he remember what took place in the relapse?" asked Mr. Lorry,
\par with natural hesitation.
\par 
\par The Doctor looked desolately round the room, shook his head, and
\par answered, in a low voice, "Not at all."
\par 
\par "Now, as to the future," hinted Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "As to the future," said the Doctor, recovering firmness, "I should have
\par great hope. As it pleased Heaven in its mercy to restore him so soon, I
\par should have great hope. He, yielding under the pressure of a complicated
\par something, long dreaded and long vaguely foreseen and contended against,
\par and recovering after the cloud had burst and passed, I should hope that
\par the worst was over."
\par 
\par "Well, well! That's good comfort. I am thankful!" said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "I am thankful!" repeated the Doctor, bending his head with reverence.
\par 
\par "There are two other points," said Mr. Lorry, "on which I am anxious to
\par be instructed. I may go on?"
\par 
\par "You cannot do your friend a better service." The Doctor gave him his
\par hand.
\par 
\par "To the first, then. He is of a studious habit, and unusually energetic;
\par he applies himself with great ardour to the acquisition of professional
\par knowledge, to the conducting of experiments, to many things. Now, does
\par he do too much?"
\par 
\par "I think not. It may be the character of his mind, to be always in
\par singular need of occupation. That may be, in part, natural to it; in
\par part, the result of affliction. The less it was occupied with healthy
\par things, the more it would be in danger of turning in the unhealthy
\par direction. He may have observed himself, and made the discovery."
\par 
\par "You are sure that he is not under too great a strain?"
\par 
\par "I think I am quite sure of it."
\par 
\par "My dear Manette, if he were overworked now--"
\par 
\par "My dear Lorry, I doubt if that could easily be. There has been a
\par violent stress in one direction, and it needs a counterweight."
\par 
\par "Excuse me, as a persistent man of business. Assuming for a moment,
\par that he _was_ overworked; it would show itself in some renewal of this
\par disorder?"
\par 
\par "I do not think so. I do not think," said Doctor Manette with the
\par firmness of self-conviction, "that anything but the one train of
\par association would renew it. I think that, henceforth, nothing but some
\par extraordinary jarring of that chord could renew it. After what has
\par happened, and after his recovery, I find it difficult to imagine any
\par such violent sounding of that string again. I trust, and I almost
\par believe, that the circumstances likely to renew it are exhausted."
\par 
\par He spoke with the diffidence of a man who knew how slight a thing
\par would overset the delicate organisation of the mind, and yet with the
\par confidence of a man who had slowly won his assurance out of personal
\par endurance and distress. It was not for his friend to abate that
\par confidence. He professed himself more relieved and encouraged than he
\par really was, and approached his second and last point. He felt it to
\par be the most difficult of all; but, remembering his old Sunday morning
\par conversation with Miss Pross, and remembering what he had seen in the
\par last nine days, he knew that he must face it.
\par 
\par "The occupation resumed under the influence of this passing affliction
\par so happily recovered from," said Mr. Lorry, clearing his throat, "we
\par will call--Blacksmith's work, Blacksmith's work. We will say, to put a
\par case and for the sake of illustration, that he had been used, in his bad
\par time, to work at a little forge. We will say that he was unexpectedly
\par found at his forge again. Is it not a pity that he should keep it by
\par him?"
\par 
\par The Doctor shaded his forehead with his hand, and beat his foot
\par nervously on the ground.
\par 
\par "He has always kept it by him," said Mr. Lorry, with an anxious look at
\par his friend. "Now, would it not be better that he should let it go?"
\par 
\par Still, the Doctor, with shaded forehead, beat his foot nervously on the
\par ground.
\par 
\par "You do not find it easy to advise me?" said Mr. Lorry. "I quite
\par understand it to be a nice question. And yet I think--" And there he
\par shook his head, and stopped.
\par 
\par "You see," said Doctor Manette, turning to him after an uneasy pause,
\par "it is very hard to explain, consistently, the innermost workings
\par of this poor man's mind. He once yearned so frightfully for that
\par occupation, and it was so welcome when it came; no doubt it relieved
\par his pain so much, by substituting the perplexity of the fingers for
\par the perplexity of the brain, and by substituting, as he became more
\par practised, the ingenuity of the hands, for the ingenuity of the mental
\par torture; that he has never been able to bear the thought of putting it
\par quite out of his reach. Even now, when I believe he is more hopeful of
\par himself than he has ever been, and even speaks of himself with a kind
\par of confidence, the idea that he might need that old employment, and not
\par find it, gives him a sudden sense of terror, like that which one may
\par fancy strikes to the heart of a lost child."
\par 
\par He looked like his illustration, as he raised his eyes to Mr. Lorry's
\par face.
\par 
\par "But may not--mind! I ask for information, as a plodding man of business
\par who only deals with such material objects as guineas, shillings, and
\par bank-notes--may not the retention of the thing involve the retention of
\par the idea? If the thing were gone, my dear Manette, might not the fear go
\par with it? In short, is it not a concession to the misgiving, to keep the
\par forge?"
\par 
\par There was another silence.
\par 
\par "You see, too," said the Doctor, tremulously, "it is such an old
\par companion."
\par 
\par "I would not keep it," said Mr. Lorry, shaking his head; for he gained
\par in firmness as he saw the Doctor disquieted. "I would recommend him to
\par sacrifice it. I only want your authority. I am sure it does no good.
\par Come! Give me your authority, like a dear good man. For his daughter's
\par sake, my dear Manette!"
\par 
\par Very strange to see what a struggle there was within him!
\par 
\par "In her name, then, let it be done; I sanction it. But, I would not take
\par it away while he was present. Let it be removed when he is not there;
\par let him miss his old companion after an absence."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry readily engaged for that, and the conference was ended. They
\par passed the day in the country, and the Doctor was quite restored. On the
\par three following days he remained perfectly well, and on the fourteenth
\par day he went away to join Lucie and her husband. The precaution that
\par had been taken to account for his silence, Mr. Lorry had previously
\par explained to him, and he had written to Lucie in accordance with it, and
\par she had no suspicions.
\par 
\par On the night of the day on which he left the house, Mr. Lorry went into
\par his room with a chopper, saw, chisel, and hammer, attended by Miss Pross
\par carrying a light. There, with closed doors, and in a mysterious and
\par guilty manner, Mr. Lorry hacked the shoemaker's bench to pieces, while
\par Miss Pross held the candle as if she were assisting at a murder--for
\par which, indeed, in her grimness, she was no unsuitable figure. The
\par burning of the body (previously reduced to pieces convenient for the
\par purpose) was commenced without delay in the kitchen fire; and the tools,
\par shoes, and leather, were buried in the garden. So wicked do destruction
\par and secrecy appear to honest minds, that Mr. Lorry and Miss Pross,
\par while engaged in the commission of their deed and in the removal of its
\par traces, almost felt, and almost looked, like accomplices in a horrible
\par crime.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XX. A Plea
\par 
\par 
\par When the newly-married pair came home, the first person who appeared, to
\par offer his congratulations, was Sydney Carton. They had not been at home
\par many hours, when he presented himself. He was not improved in habits, or
\par in looks, or in manner; but there was a certain rugged air of fidelity
\par about him, which was new to the observation of Charles Darnay.
\par 
\par He watched his opportunity of taking Darnay aside into a window, and of
\par speaking to him when no one overheard.
\par 
\par "Mr. Darnay," said Carton, "I wish we might be friends."
\par 
\par "We are already friends, I hope."
\par 
\par "You are good enough to say so, as a fashion of speech; but, I don't
\par mean any fashion of speech. Indeed, when I say I wish we might be
\par friends, I scarcely mean quite that, either."
\par 
\par Charles Darnay--as was natural--asked him, in all good-humour and
\par good-fellowship, what he did mean?
\par 
\par "Upon my life," said Carton, smiling, "I find that easier to comprehend
\par in my own mind, than to convey to yours. However, let me try. You
\par remember a certain famous occasion when I was more drunk than--than
\par usual?"
\par 
\par "I remember a certain famous occasion when you forced me to confess that
\par you had been drinking."
\par 
\par "I remember it too. The curse of those occasions is heavy upon me, for I
\par always remember them. I hope it may be taken into account one day,
\par when all days are at an end for me! Don't be alarmed; I am not going to
\par preach."
\par 
\par "I am not at all alarmed. Earnestness in you, is anything but alarming
\par to me."
\par 
\par "Ah!" said Carton, with a careless wave of his hand, as if he waved that
\par away. "On the drunken occasion in question (one of a large number, as
\par you know), I was insufferable about liking you, and not liking you. I
\par wish you would forget it."
\par 
\par "I forgot it long ago."
\par 
\par "Fashion of speech again! But, Mr. Darnay, oblivion is not so easy to
\par me, as you represent it to be to you. I have by no means forgotten it,
\par and a light answer does not help me to forget it."
\par 
\par "If it was a light answer," returned Darnay, "I beg your forgiveness
\par for it. I had no other object than to turn a slight thing, which, to my
\par surprise, seems to trouble you too much, aside. I declare to you, on the
\par faith of a gentleman, that I have long dismissed it from my mind. Good
\par Heaven, what was there to dismiss! Have I had nothing more important to
\par remember, in the great service you rendered me that day?"
\par 
\par "As to the great service," said Carton, "I am bound to avow to you, when
\par you speak of it in that way, that it was mere professional claptrap, I
\par don't know that I cared what became of you, when I rendered it.--Mind! I
\par say when I rendered it; I am speaking of the past."
\par 
\par "You make light of the obligation," returned Darnay, "but I will not
\par quarrel with _your_ light answer."
\par 
\par "Genuine truth, Mr. Darnay, trust me! I have gone aside from my purpose;
\par I was speaking about our being friends. Now, you know me; you know I am
\par incapable of all the higher and better flights of men. If you doubt it,
\par ask Stryver, and he'll tell you so."
\par 
\par "I prefer to form my own opinion, without the aid of his."
\par 
\par "Well! At any rate you know me as a dissolute dog, who has never done
\par any good, and never will."
\par 
\par "I don't know that you 'never will.'"
\par 
\par "But I do, and you must take my word for it. Well! If you could endure
\par to have such a worthless fellow, and a fellow of such indifferent
\par reputation, coming and going at odd times, I should ask that I might be
\par permitted to come and go as a privileged person here; that I might
\par be regarded as an useless (and I would add, if it were not for the
\par resemblance I detected between you and me, an unornamental) piece of
\par furniture, tolerated for its old service, and taken no notice of. I
\par doubt if I should abuse the permission. It is a hundred to one if I
\par should avail myself of it four times in a year. It would satisfy me, I
\par dare say, to know that I had it."
\par 
\par "Will you try?"
\par 
\par "That is another way of saying that I am placed on the footing I have
\par indicated. I thank you, Darnay. I may use that freedom with your name?"
\par 
\par "I think so, Carton, by this time."
\par 
\par They shook hands upon it, and Sydney turned away. Within a minute
\par afterwards, he was, to all outward appearance, as unsubstantial as ever.
\par 
\par When he was gone, and in the course of an evening passed with Miss
\par Pross, the Doctor, and Mr. Lorry, Charles Darnay made some mention of
\par this conversation in general terms, and spoke of Sydney Carton as a
\par problem of carelessness and recklessness. He spoke of him, in short, not
\par bitterly or meaning to bear hard upon him, but as anybody might who saw
\par him as he showed himself.
\par 
\par He had no idea that this could dwell in the thoughts of his fair young
\par wife; but, when he afterwards joined her in their own rooms, he found
\par her waiting for him with the old pretty lifting of the forehead strongly
\par marked.
\par 
\par "We are thoughtful to-night!" said Darnay, drawing his arm about her.
\par 
\par "Yes, dearest Charles," with her hands on his breast, and the inquiring
\par and attentive expression fixed upon him; "we are rather thoughtful
\par to-night, for we have something on our mind to-night."
\par 
\par "What is it, my Lucie?"
\par 
\par "Will you promise not to press one question on me, if I beg you not to
\par ask it?"
\par 
\par "Will I promise? What will I not promise to my Love?"
\par 
\par What, indeed, with his hand putting aside the golden hair from the
\par cheek, and his other hand against the heart that beat for him!
\par 
\par "I think, Charles, poor Mr. Carton deserves more consideration and
\par respect than you expressed for him to-night."
\par 
\par "Indeed, my own? Why so?"
\par 
\par "That is what you are not to ask me. But I think--I know--he does."
\par 
\par "If you know it, it is enough. What would you have me do, my Life?"
\par 
\par "I would ask you, dearest, to be very generous with him always, and very
\par lenient on his faults when he is not by. I would ask you to believe that
\par he has a heart he very, very seldom reveals, and that there are deep
\par wounds in it. My dear, I have seen it bleeding."
\par 
\par "It is a painful reflection to me," said Charles Darnay, quite
\par astounded, "that I should have done him any wrong. I never thought this
\par of him."
\par 
\par "My husband, it is so. I fear he is not to be reclaimed; there is
\par scarcely a hope that anything in his character or fortunes is reparable
\par now. But, I am sure that he is capable of good things, gentle things,
\par even magnanimous things."
\par 
\par She looked so beautiful in the purity of her faith in this lost man,
\par that her husband could have looked at her as she was for hours.
\par 
\par "And, O my dearest Love!" she urged, clinging nearer to him, laying her
\par head upon his breast, and raising her eyes to his, "remember how strong
\par we are in our happiness, and how weak he is in his misery!"
\par 
\par The supplication touched him home. "I will always remember it, dear
\par Heart! I will remember it as long as I live."
\par 
\par He bent over the golden head, and put the rosy lips to his, and folded
\par her in his arms. If one forlorn wanderer then pacing the dark streets,
\par could have heard her innocent disclosure, and could have seen the drops
\par of pity kissed away by her husband from the soft blue eyes so loving of
\par that husband, he might have cried to the night--and the words would not
\par have parted from his lips for the first time--
\par 
\par "God bless her for her sweet compassion!"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XXI. Echoing Footsteps
\par 
\par 
\par A wonderful corner for echoes, it has been remarked, that corner where
\par the Doctor lived. Ever busily winding the golden thread which bound
\par her husband, and her father, and herself, and her old directress and
\par companion, in a life of quiet bliss, Lucie sat in the still house in
\par the tranquilly resounding corner, listening to the echoing footsteps of
\par years.
\par 
\par At first, there were times, though she was a perfectly happy young wife,
\par when her work would slowly fall from her hands, and her eyes would be
\par dimmed. For, there was something coming in the echoes, something light,
\par afar off, and scarcely audible yet, that stirred her heart too much.
\par Fluttering hopes and doubts--hopes, of a love as yet unknown to her:
\par doubts, of her remaining upon earth, to enjoy that new delight--divided
\par her breast. Among the echoes then, there would arise the sound of
\par footsteps at her own early grave; and thoughts of the husband who would
\par be left so desolate, and who would mourn for her so much, swelled to her
\par eyes, and broke like waves.
\par 
\par That time passed, and her little Lucie lay on her bosom. Then, among the
\par advancing echoes, there was the tread of her tiny feet and the sound of
\par her prattling words. Let greater echoes resound as they would, the young
\par mother at the cradle side could always hear those coming. They came, and
\par the shady house was sunny with a child's laugh, and the Divine friend of
\par children, to whom in her trouble she had confided hers, seemed to take
\par her child in his arms, as He took the child of old, and made it a sacred
\par joy to her.
\par 
\par Ever busily winding the golden thread that bound them all together,
\par weaving the service of her happy influence through the tissue of all
\par their lives, and making it predominate nowhere, Lucie heard in the
\par echoes of years none but friendly and soothing sounds. Her husband's
\par step was strong and prosperous among them; her father's firm and equal.
\par Lo, Miss Pross, in harness of string, awakening the echoes, as an
\par unruly charger, whip-corrected, snorting and pawing the earth under the
\par plane-tree in the garden!
\par 
\par Even when there were sounds of sorrow among the rest, they were not
\par harsh nor cruel. Even when golden hair, like her own, lay in a halo on a
\par pillow round the worn face of a little boy, and he said, with a radiant
\par smile, "Dear papa and mamma, I am very sorry to leave you both, and to
\par leave my pretty sister; but I am called, and I must go!" those were not
\par tears all of agony that wetted his young mother's cheek, as the spirit
\par departed from her embrace that had been entrusted to it. Suffer them and
\par forbid them not. They see my Father's face. O Father, blessed words!
\par 
\par Thus, the rustling of an Angel's wings got blended with the other
\par echoes, and they were not wholly of earth, but had in them that breath
\par of Heaven. Sighs of the winds that blew over a little garden-tomb were
\par mingled with them also, and both were audible to Lucie, in a hushed
\par murmur--like the breathing of a summer sea asleep upon a sandy shore--as
\par the little Lucie, comically studious at the task of the morning, or
\par dressing a doll at her mother's footstool, chattered in the tongues of
\par the Two Cities that were blended in her life.
\par 
\par The Echoes rarely answered to the actual tread of Sydney Carton. Some
\par half-dozen times a year, at most, he claimed his privilege of coming in
\par uninvited, and would sit among them through the evening, as he had once
\par done often. He never came there heated with wine. And one other thing
\par regarding him was whispered in the echoes, which has been whispered by
\par all true echoes for ages and ages.
\par 
\par No man ever really loved a woman, lost her, and knew her with a
\par blameless though an unchanged mind, when she was a wife and a mother,
\par but her children had a strange sympathy with him--an instinctive
\par delicacy of pity for him. What fine hidden sensibilities are touched in
\par such a case, no echoes tell; but it is so, and it was so here. Carton
\par was the first stranger to whom little Lucie held out her chubby arms,
\par and he kept his place with her as she grew. The little boy had spoken of
\par him, almost at the last. "Poor Carton! Kiss him for me!"
\par 
\par Mr. Stryver shouldered his way through the law, like some great engine
\par forcing itself through turbid water, and dragged his useful friend in
\par his wake, like a boat towed astern. As the boat so favoured is usually
\par in a rough plight, and mostly under water, so, Sydney had a swamped
\par life of it. But, easy and strong custom, unhappily so much easier and
\par stronger in him than any stimulating sense of desert or disgrace, made
\par it the life he was to lead; and he no more thought of emerging from his
\par state of lion's jackal, than any real jackal may be supposed to think of
\par rising to be a lion. Stryver was rich; had married a florid widow with
\par property and three boys, who had nothing particularly shining about them
\par but the straight hair of their dumpling heads.
\par 
\par These three young gentlemen, Mr. Stryver, exuding patronage of the most
\par offensive quality from every pore, had walked before him like three
\par sheep to the quiet corner in Soho, and had offered as pupils to
\par Lucie's husband: delicately saying "Halloa! here are three lumps of
\par bread-and-cheese towards your matrimonial picnic, Darnay!" The polite
\par rejection of the three lumps of bread-and-cheese had quite bloated Mr.
\par Stryver with indignation, which he afterwards turned to account in the
\par training of the young gentlemen, by directing them to beware of the
\par pride of Beggars, like that tutor-fellow. He was also in the habit of
\par declaiming to Mrs. Stryver, over his full-bodied wine, on the arts
\par Mrs. Darnay had once put in practice to "catch" him, and on the
\par diamond-cut-diamond arts in himself, madam, which had rendered him "not
\par to be caught." Some of his King's Bench familiars, who were occasionally
\par parties to the full-bodied wine and the lie, excused him for the
\par latter by saying that he had told it so often, that he believed
\par it himself--which is surely such an incorrigible aggravation of an
\par originally bad offence, as to justify any such offender's being carried
\par off to some suitably retired spot, and there hanged out of the way.
\par 
\par These were among the echoes to which Lucie, sometimes pensive, sometimes
\par amused and laughing, listened in the echoing corner, until her little
\par daughter was six years old. How near to her heart the echoes of her
\par child's tread came, and those of her own dear father's, always active
\par and self-possessed, and those of her dear husband's, need not be told.
\par Nor, how the lightest echo of their united home, directed by herself
\par with such a wise and elegant thrift that it was more abundant than any
\par waste, was music to her. Nor, how there were echoes all about her, sweet
\par in her ears, of the many times her father had told her that he found her
\par more devoted to him married (if that could be) than single, and of the
\par many times her husband had said to her that no cares and duties seemed
\par to divide her love for him or her help to him, and asked her "What is
\par the magic secret, my darling, of your being everything to all of us,
\par as if there were only one of us, yet never seeming to be hurried, or to
\par have too much to do?"
\par 
\par But, there were other echoes, from a distance, that rumbled menacingly
\par in the corner all through this space of time. And it was now, about
\par little Lucie's sixth birthday, that they began to have an awful sound,
\par as of a great storm in France with a dreadful sea rising.
\par 
\par On a night in mid-July, one thousand seven hundred and eighty-nine, Mr.
\par Lorry came in late, from Tellson's, and sat himself down by Lucie and
\par her husband in the dark window. It was a hot, wild night, and they were
\par all three reminded of the old Sunday night when they had looked at the
\par lightning from the same place.
\par 
\par "I began to think," said Mr. Lorry, pushing his brown wig back, "that
\par I should have to pass the night at Tellson's. We have been so full of
\par business all day, that we have not known what to do first, or which way
\par to turn. There is such an uneasiness in Paris, that we have actually a
\par run of confidence upon us! Our customers over there, seem not to be able
\par to confide their property to us fast enough. There is positively a mania
\par among some of them for sending it to England."
\par 
\par "That has a bad look," said Darnay--
\par 
\par "A bad look, you say, my dear Darnay? Yes, but we don't know what reason
\par there is in it. People are so unreasonable! Some of us at Tellson's are
\par getting old, and we really can't be troubled out of the ordinary course
\par without due occasion."
\par 
\par "Still," said Darnay, "you know how gloomy and threatening the sky is."
\par 
\par "I know that, to be sure," assented Mr. Lorry, trying to persuade
\par himself that his sweet temper was soured, and that he grumbled, "but I
\par am determined to be peevish after my long day's botheration. Where is
\par Manette?"
\par 
\par "Here he is," said the Doctor, entering the dark room at the moment.
\par 
\par "I am quite glad you are at home; for these hurries and forebodings by
\par which I have been surrounded all day long, have made me nervous without
\par reason. You are not going out, I hope?"
\par 
\par "No; I am going to play backgammon with you, if you like," said the
\par Doctor.
\par 
\par "I don't think I do like, if I may speak my mind. I am not fit to be
\par pitted against you to-night. Is the teaboard still there, Lucie? I can't
\par see."
\par 
\par "Of course, it has been kept for you."
\par 
\par "Thank ye, my dear. The precious child is safe in bed?"
\par 
\par "And sleeping soundly."
\par 
\par "That's right; all safe and well! I don't know why anything should be
\par otherwise than safe and well here, thank God; but I have been so put out
\par all day, and I am not as young as I was! My tea, my dear! Thank ye. Now,
\par come and take your place in the circle, and let us sit quiet, and hear
\par the echoes about which you have your theory."
\par 
\par "Not a theory; it was a fancy."
\par 
\par "A fancy, then, my wise pet," said Mr. Lorry, patting her hand. "They
\par are very numerous and very loud, though, are they not? Only hear them!"
\par 
\par Headlong, mad, and dangerous footsteps to force their way into anybody's
\par life, footsteps not easily made clean again if once stained red, the
\par footsteps raging in Saint Antoine afar off, as the little circle sat in
\par the dark London window.
\par 
\par Saint Antoine had been, that morning, a vast dusky mass of scarecrows
\par heaving to and fro, with frequent gleams of light above the billowy
\par heads, where steel blades and bayonets shone in the sun. A tremendous
\par roar arose from the throat of Saint Antoine, and a forest of naked arms
\par struggled in the air like shrivelled branches of trees in a winter wind:
\par all the fingers convulsively clutching at every weapon or semblance of a
\par weapon that was thrown up from the depths below, no matter how far off.
\par 
\par Who gave them out, whence they last came, where they began, through what
\par agency they crookedly quivered and jerked, scores at a time, over the
\par heads of the crowd, like a kind of lightning, no eye in the throng could
\par have told; but, muskets were being distributed--so were cartridges,
\par powder, and ball, bars of iron and wood, knives, axes, pikes, every
\par weapon that distracted ingenuity could discover or devise. People who
\par could lay hold of nothing else, set themselves with bleeding hands to
\par force stones and bricks out of their places in walls. Every pulse and
\par heart in Saint Antoine was on high-fever strain and at high-fever heat.
\par Every living creature there held life as of no account, and was demented
\par with a passionate readiness to sacrifice it.
\par 
\par As a whirlpool of boiling waters has a centre point, so, all this raging
\par circled round Defarge's wine-shop, and every human drop in the caldron
\par had a tendency to be sucked towards the vortex where Defarge himself,
\par already begrimed with gunpowder and sweat, issued orders, issued arms,
\par thrust this man back, dragged this man forward, disarmed one to arm
\par another, laboured and strove in the thickest of the uproar.
\par 
\par "Keep near to me, Jacques Three," cried Defarge; "and do you, Jacques
\par One and Two, separate and put yourselves at the head of as many of these
\par patriots as you can. Where is my wife?"
\par 
\par "Eh, well! Here you see me!" said madame, composed as ever, but not
\par knitting to-day. Madame's resolute right hand was occupied with an axe,
\par in place of the usual softer implements, and in her girdle were a pistol
\par and a cruel knife.
\par 
\par "Where do you go, my wife?"
\par 
\par "I go," said madame, "with you at present. You shall see me at the head
\par of women, by-and-bye."
\par 
\par "Come, then!" cried Defarge, in a resounding voice. "Patriots and
\par friends, we are ready! The Bastille!"
\par 
\par With a roar that sounded as if all the breath in France had been shaped
\par into the detested word, the living sea rose, wave on wave, depth on
\par depth, and overflowed the city to that point. Alarm-bells ringing, drums
\par beating, the sea raging and thundering on its new beach, the attack
\par began.
\par 
\par Deep ditches, double drawbridge, massive stone walls, eight great
\par towers, cannon, muskets, fire and smoke. Through the fire and through
\par the smoke--in the fire and in the smoke, for the sea cast him up against
\par a cannon, and on the instant he became a cannonier--Defarge of the
\par wine-shop worked like a manful soldier, Two fierce hours.
\par 
\par Deep ditch, single drawbridge, massive stone walls, eight great towers,
\par cannon, muskets, fire and smoke. One drawbridge down! "Work, comrades
\par all, work! Work, Jacques One, Jacques Two, Jacques One Thousand, Jacques
\par Two Thousand, Jacques Five-and-Twenty Thousand; in the name of all
\par the Angels or the Devils--which you prefer--work!" Thus Defarge of the
\par wine-shop, still at his gun, which had long grown hot.
\par 
\par "To me, women!" cried madame his wife. "What! We can kill as well as
\par the men when the place is taken!" And to her, with a shrill thirsty
\par cry, trooping women variously armed, but all armed alike in hunger and
\par revenge.
\par 
\par Cannon, muskets, fire and smoke; but, still the deep ditch, the single
\par drawbridge, the massive stone walls, and the eight great towers. Slight
\par displacements of the raging sea, made by the falling wounded. Flashing
\par weapons, blazing torches, smoking waggonloads of wet straw, hard work
\par at neighbouring barricades in all directions, shrieks, volleys,
\par execrations, bravery without stint, boom smash and rattle, and the
\par furious sounding of the living sea; but, still the deep ditch, and the
\par single drawbridge, and the massive stone walls, and the eight great
\par towers, and still Defarge of the wine-shop at his gun, grown doubly hot
\par by the service of Four fierce hours.
\par 
\par A white flag from within the fortress, and a parley--this dimly
\par perceptible through the raging storm, nothing audible in it--suddenly
\par the sea rose immeasurably wider and higher, and swept Defarge of the
\par wine-shop over the lowered drawbridge, past the massive stone outer
\par walls, in among the eight great towers surrendered!
\par 
\par So resistless was the force of the ocean bearing him on, that even to
\par draw his breath or turn his head was as impracticable as if he had been
\par struggling in the surf at the South Sea, until he was landed in the
\par outer courtyard of the Bastille. There, against an angle of a wall, he
\par made a struggle to look about him. Jacques Three was nearly at his side;
\par Madame Defarge, still heading some of her women, was visible in the
\par inner distance, and her knife was in her hand. Everywhere was tumult,
\par exultation, deafening and maniacal bewilderment, astounding noise, yet
\par furious dumb-show.
\par 
\par "The Prisoners!"
\par 
\par "The Records!"
\par 
\par "The secret cells!"
\par 
\par "The instruments of torture!"
\par 
\par "The Prisoners!"
\par 
\par Of all these cries, and ten thousand incoherences, "The Prisoners!" was
\par the cry most taken up by the sea that rushed in, as if there were an
\par eternity of people, as well as of time and space. When the foremost
\par billows rolled past, bearing the prison officers with them, and
\par threatening them all with instant death if any secret nook remained
\par undisclosed, Defarge laid his strong hand on the breast of one of
\par these men--a man with a grey head, who had a lighted torch in his
\par hand--separated him from the rest, and got him between himself and the
\par wall.
\par 
\par "Show me the North Tower!" said Defarge. "Quick!"
\par 
\par "I will faithfully," replied the man, "if you will come with me. But
\par there is no one there."
\par 
\par "What is the meaning of One Hundred and Five, North Tower?" asked
\par Defarge. "Quick!"
\par 
\par "The meaning, monsieur?"
\par 
\par "Does it mean a captive, or a place of captivity? Or do you mean that I
\par shall strike you dead?"
\par 
\par "Kill him!" croaked Jacques Three, who had come close up.
\par 
\par "Monsieur, it is a cell."
\par 
\par "Show it me!"
\par 
\par "Pass this way, then."
\par 
\par Jacques Three, with his usual craving on him, and evidently disappointed
\par by the dialogue taking a turn that did not seem to promise bloodshed,
\par held by Defarge's arm as he held by the turnkey's. Their three heads had
\par been close together during this brief discourse, and it had been as much
\par as they could do to hear one another, even then: so tremendous was the
\par noise of the living ocean, in its irruption into the Fortress, and
\par its inundation of the courts and passages and staircases. All around
\par outside, too, it beat the walls with a deep, hoarse roar, from which,
\par occasionally, some partial shouts of tumult broke and leaped into the
\par air like spray.
\par 
\par Through gloomy vaults where the light of day had never shone, past
\par hideous doors of dark dens and cages, down cavernous flights of steps,
\par and again up steep rugged ascents of stone and brick, more like dry
\par waterfalls than staircases, Defarge, the turnkey, and Jacques Three,
\par linked hand and arm, went with all the speed they could make. Here and
\par there, especially at first, the inundation started on them and swept by;
\par but when they had done descending, and were winding and climbing up a
\par tower, they were alone. Hemmed in here by the massive thickness of walls
\par and arches, the storm within the fortress and without was only audible
\par to them in a dull, subdued way, as if the noise out of which they had
\par come had almost destroyed their sense of hearing.
\par 
\par The turnkey stopped at a low door, put a key in a clashing lock, swung
\par the door slowly open, and said, as they all bent their heads and passed
\par in:
\par 
\par "One hundred and five, North Tower!"
\par 
\par There was a small, heavily-grated, unglazed window high in the wall,
\par with a stone screen before it, so that the sky could be only seen by
\par stooping low and looking up. There was a small chimney, heavily barred
\par across, a few feet within. There was a heap of old feathery wood-ashes
\par on the hearth. There was a stool, and table, and a straw bed. There were
\par the four blackened walls, and a rusted iron ring in one of them.
\par 
\par "Pass that torch slowly along these walls, that I may see them," said
\par Defarge to the turnkey.
\par 
\par The man obeyed, and Defarge followed the light closely with his eyes.
\par 
\par "Stop!--Look here, Jacques!"
\par 
\par "A. M.!" croaked Jacques Three, as he read greedily.
\par 
\par "Alexandre Manette," said Defarge in his ear, following the letters
\par with his swart forefinger, deeply engrained with gunpowder. "And here he
\par wrote 'a poor physician.' And it was he, without doubt, who scratched
\par a calendar on this stone. What is that in your hand? A crowbar? Give it
\par me!"
\par 
\par He had still the linstock of his gun in his own hand. He made a sudden
\par exchange of the two instruments, and turning on the worm-eaten stool and
\par table, beat them to pieces in a few blows.
\par 
\par "Hold the light higher!" he said, wrathfully, to the turnkey. "Look
\par among those fragments with care, Jacques. And see! Here is my knife,"
\par throwing it to him; "rip open that bed, and search the straw. Hold the
\par light higher, you!"
\par 
\par With a menacing look at the turnkey he crawled upon the hearth, and,
\par peering up the chimney, struck and prised at its sides with the crowbar,
\par and worked at the iron grating across it. In a few minutes, some mortar
\par and dust came dropping down, which he averted his face to avoid; and
\par in it, and in the old wood-ashes, and in a crevice in the chimney
\par into which his weapon had slipped or wrought itself, he groped with a
\par cautious touch.
\par 
\par "Nothing in the wood, and nothing in the straw, Jacques?"
\par 
\par "Nothing."
\par 
\par "Let us collect them together, in the middle of the cell. So! Light
\par them, you!"
\par 
\par The turnkey fired the little pile, which blazed high and hot. Stooping
\par again to come out at the low-arched door, they left it burning, and
\par retraced their way to the courtyard; seeming to recover their sense
\par of hearing as they came down, until they were in the raging flood once
\par more.
\par 
\par They found it surging and tossing, in quest of Defarge himself. Saint
\par Antoine was clamorous to have its wine-shop keeper foremost in the guard
\par upon the governor who had defended the Bastille and shot the people.
\par Otherwise, the governor would not be marched to the Hotel de Ville for
\par judgment. Otherwise, the governor would escape, and the people's
\par blood (suddenly of some value, after many years of worthlessness) be
\par unavenged.
\par 
\par In the howling universe of passion and contention that seemed to
\par encompass this grim old officer conspicuous in his grey coat and red
\par decoration, there was but one quite steady figure, and that was a
\par woman's. "See, there is my husband!" she cried, pointing him out.
\par "See Defarge!" She stood immovable close to the grim old officer, and
\par remained immovable close to him; remained immovable close to him through
\par the streets, as Defarge and the rest bore him along; remained immovable
\par close to him when he was got near his destination, and began to
\par be struck at from behind; remained immovable close to him when the
\par long-gathering rain of stabs and blows fell heavy; was so close to him
\par when he dropped dead under it, that, suddenly animated, she put her foot
\par upon his neck, and with her cruel knife--long ready--hewed off his head.
\par 
\par The hour was come, when Saint Antoine was to execute his horrible idea
\par of hoisting up men for lamps to show what he could be and do. Saint
\par Antoine's blood was up, and the blood of tyranny and domination by the
\par iron hand was down--down on the steps of the Hotel de Ville where the
\par governor's body lay--down on the sole of the shoe of Madame Defarge
\par where she had trodden on the body to steady it for mutilation. "Lower
\par the lamp yonder!" cried Saint Antoine, after glaring round for a new
\par means of death; "here is one of his soldiers to be left on guard!" The
\par swinging sentinel was posted, and the sea rushed on.
\par 
\par The sea of black and threatening waters, and of destructive upheaving
\par of wave against wave, whose depths were yet unfathomed and whose forces
\par were yet unknown. The remorseless sea of turbulently swaying shapes,
\par voices of vengeance, and faces hardened in the furnaces of suffering
\par until the touch of pity could make no mark on them.
\par 
\par But, in the ocean of faces where every fierce and furious expression was
\par in vivid life, there were two groups of faces--each seven in number--so
\par fixedly contrasting with the rest, that never did sea roll which bore
\par more memorable wrecks with it. Seven faces of prisoners, suddenly
\par released by the storm that had burst their tomb, were carried high
\par overhead: all scared, all lost, all wondering and amazed, as if the Last
\par Day were come, and those who rejoiced around them were lost spirits.
\par Other seven faces there were, carried higher, seven dead faces, whose
\par drooping eyelids and half-seen eyes awaited the Last Day. Impassive
\par faces, yet with a suspended--not an abolished--expression on them;
\par faces, rather, in a fearful pause, as having yet to raise the dropped
\par lids of the eyes, and bear witness with the bloodless lips, "THOU DIDST
\par IT!"
\par 
\par Seven prisoners released, seven gory heads on pikes, the keys of the
\par accursed fortress of the eight strong towers, some discovered letters
\par and other memorials of prisoners of old time, long dead of broken
\par hearts,--such, and such--like, the loudly echoing footsteps of Saint
\par Antoine escort through the Paris streets in mid-July, one thousand seven
\par hundred and eighty-nine. Now, Heaven defeat the fancy of Lucie Darnay,
\par and keep these feet far out of her life! For, they are headlong, mad,
\par and dangerous; and in the years so long after the breaking of the cask
\par at Defarge's wine-shop door, they are not easily purified when once
\par stained red.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XXII. The Sea Still Rises
\par 
\par 
\par Haggard Saint Antoine had had only one exultant week, in which to soften
\par his modicum of hard and bitter bread to such extent as he could, with
\par the relish of fraternal embraces and congratulations, when Madame
\par Defarge sat at her counter, as usual, presiding over the customers.
\par Madame Defarge wore no rose in her head, for the great brotherhood of
\par Spies had become, even in one short week, extremely chary of trusting
\par themselves to the saint's mercies. The lamps across his streets had a
\par portentously elastic swing with them.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge, with her arms folded, sat in the morning light and heat,
\par contemplating the wine-shop and the street. In both, there were several
\par knots of loungers, squalid and miserable, but now with a manifest sense
\par of power enthroned on their distress. The raggedest nightcap, awry on
\par the wretchedest head, had this crooked significance in it: "I know how
\par hard it has grown for me, the wearer of this, to support life in myself;
\par but do you know how easy it has grown for me, the wearer of this, to
\par destroy life in you?" Every lean bare arm, that had been without work
\par before, had this work always ready for it now, that it could strike.
\par The fingers of the knitting women were vicious, with the experience that
\par they could tear. There was a change in the appearance of Saint Antoine;
\par the image had been hammering into this for hundreds of years, and the
\par last finishing blows had told mightily on the expression.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge sat observing it, with such suppressed approval as was
\par to be desired in the leader of the Saint Antoine women. One of her
\par sisterhood knitted beside her. The short, rather plump wife of a starved
\par grocer, and the mother of two children withal, this lieutenant had
\par already earned the complimentary name of The Vengeance.
\par 
\par "Hark!" said The Vengeance. "Listen, then! Who comes?"
\par 
\par As if a train of powder laid from the outermost bound of Saint Antoine
\par Quarter to the wine-shop door, had been suddenly fired, a fast-spreading
\par murmur came rushing along.
\par 
\par "It is Defarge," said madame. "Silence, patriots!"
\par 
\par Defarge came in breathless, pulled off a red cap he wore, and looked
\par around him! "Listen, everywhere!" said madame again. "Listen to him!"
\par Defarge stood, panting, against a background of eager eyes and open
\par mouths, formed outside the door; all those within the wine-shop had
\par sprung to their feet.
\par 
\par "Say then, my husband. What is it?"
\par 
\par "News from the other world!"
\par 
\par "How, then?" cried madame, contemptuously. "The other world?"
\par 
\par "Does everybody here recall old Foulon, who told the famished people
\par that they might eat grass, and who died, and went to Hell?"
\par 
\par "Everybody!" from all throats.
\par 
\par "The news is of him. He is among us!"
\par 
\par "Among us!" from the universal throat again. "And dead?"
\par 
\par "Not dead! He feared us so much--and with reason--that he caused himself
\par to be represented as dead, and had a grand mock-funeral. But they have
\par found him alive, hiding in the country, and have brought him in. I have
\par seen him but now, on his way to the Hotel de Ville, a prisoner. I have
\par said that he had reason to fear us. Say all! _Had_ he reason?"
\par 
\par Wretched old sinner of more than threescore years and ten, if he had
\par never known it yet, he would have known it in his heart of hearts if he
\par could have heard the answering cry.
\par 
\par A moment of profound silence followed. Defarge and his wife looked
\par steadfastly at one another. The Vengeance stooped, and the jar of a drum
\par was heard as she moved it at her feet behind the counter.
\par 
\par "Patriots!" said Defarge, in a determined voice, "are we ready?"
\par 
\par Instantly Madame Defarge's knife was in her girdle; the drum was beating
\par in the streets, as if it and a drummer had flown together by magic; and
\par The Vengeance, uttering terrific shrieks, and flinging her arms about
\par her head like all the forty Furies at once, was tearing from house to
\par house, rousing the women.
\par 
\par The men were terrible, in the bloody-minded anger with which they looked
\par from windows, caught up what arms they had, and came pouring down into
\par the streets; but, the women were a sight to chill the boldest. From
\par such household occupations as their bare poverty yielded, from their
\par children, from their aged and their sick crouching on the bare ground
\par famished and naked, they ran out with streaming hair, urging one
\par another, and themselves, to madness with the wildest cries and actions.
\par Villain Foulon taken, my sister! Old Foulon taken, my mother! Miscreant
\par Foulon taken, my daughter! Then, a score of others ran into the midst of
\par these, beating their breasts, tearing their hair, and screaming, Foulon
\par alive! Foulon who told the starving people they might eat grass! Foulon
\par who told my old father that he might eat grass, when I had no bread
\par to give him! Foulon who told my baby it might suck grass, when these
\par breasts were dry with want! O mother of God, this Foulon! O Heaven our
\par suffering! Hear me, my dead baby and my withered father: I swear on my
\par knees, on these stones, to avenge you on Foulon! Husbands, and brothers,
\par and young men, Give us the blood of Foulon, Give us the head of Foulon,
\par Give us the heart of Foulon, Give us the body and soul of Foulon, Rend
\par Foulon to pieces, and dig him into the ground, that grass may grow from
\par him! With these cries, numbers of the women, lashed into blind frenzy,
\par whirled about, striking and tearing at their own friends until they
\par dropped into a passionate swoon, and were only saved by the men
\par belonging to them from being trampled under foot.
\par 
\par Nevertheless, not a moment was lost; not a moment! This Foulon was at
\par the Hotel de Ville, and might be loosed. Never, if Saint Antoine knew
\par his own sufferings, insults, and wrongs! Armed men and women flocked out
\par of the Quarter so fast, and drew even these last dregs after them with
\par such a force of suction, that within a quarter of an hour there was not
\par a human creature in Saint Antoine's bosom but a few old crones and the
\par wailing children.
\par 
\par No. They were all by that time choking the Hall of Examination where
\par this old man, ugly and wicked, was, and overflowing into the adjacent
\par open space and streets. The Defarges, husband and wife, The Vengeance,
\par and Jacques Three, were in the first press, and at no great distance
\par from him in the Hall.
\par 
\par "See!" cried madame, pointing with her knife. "See the old villain bound
\par with ropes. That was well done to tie a bunch of grass upon his back.
\par Ha, ha! That was well done. Let him eat it now!" Madame put her knife
\par under her arm, and clapped her hands as at a play.
\par 
\par The people immediately behind Madame Defarge, explaining the cause of
\par her satisfaction to those behind them, and those again explaining to
\par others, and those to others, the neighbouring streets resounded with the
\par clapping of hands. Similarly, during two or three hours of drawl,
\par and the winnowing of many bushels of words, Madame Defarge's frequent
\par expressions of impatience were taken up, with marvellous quickness, at
\par a distance: the more readily, because certain men who had by some
\par wonderful exercise of agility climbed up the external architecture
\par to look in from the windows, knew Madame Defarge well, and acted as a
\par telegraph between her and the crowd outside the building.
\par 
\par At length the sun rose so high that it struck a kindly ray as of hope or
\par protection, directly down upon the old prisoner's head. The favour was
\par too much to bear; in an instant the barrier of dust and chaff that had
\par stood surprisingly long, went to the winds, and Saint Antoine had got
\par him!
\par 
\par It was known directly, to the furthest confines of the crowd. Defarge
\par had but sprung over a railing and a table, and folded the miserable
\par wretch in a deadly embrace--Madame Defarge had but followed and turned
\par her hand in one of the ropes with which he was tied--The Vengeance and
\par Jacques Three were not yet up with them, and the men at the windows
\par had not yet swooped into the Hall, like birds of prey from their high
\par perches--when the cry seemed to go up, all over the city, "Bring him
\par out! Bring him to the lamp!"
\par 
\par Down, and up, and head foremost on the steps of the building; now, on
\par his knees; now, on his feet; now, on his back; dragged, and struck at,
\par and stifled by the bunches of grass and straw that were thrust into his
\par face by hundreds of hands; torn, bruised, panting, bleeding, yet always
\par entreating and beseeching for mercy; now full of vehement agony of
\par action, with a small clear space about him as the people drew one
\par another back that they might see; now, a log of dead wood drawn through
\par a forest of legs; he was hauled to the nearest street corner where one
\par of the fatal lamps swung, and there Madame Defarge let him go--as a cat
\par might have done to a mouse--and silently and composedly looked at him
\par while they made ready, and while he besought her: the women passionately
\par screeching at him all the time, and the men sternly calling out to have
\par him killed with grass in his mouth. Once, he went aloft, and the rope
\par broke, and they caught him shrieking; twice, he went aloft, and the rope
\par broke, and they caught him shrieking; then, the rope was merciful, and
\par held him, and his head was soon upon a pike, with grass enough in the
\par mouth for all Saint Antoine to dance at the sight of.
\par 
\par Nor was this the end of the day's bad work, for Saint Antoine so shouted
\par and danced his angry blood up, that it boiled again, on hearing when
\par the day closed in that the son-in-law of the despatched, another of the
\par people's enemies and insulters, was coming into Paris under a guard
\par five hundred strong, in cavalry alone. Saint Antoine wrote his crimes
\par on flaring sheets of paper, seized him--would have torn him out of the
\par breast of an army to bear Foulon company--set his head and heart on
\par pikes, and carried the three spoils of the day, in Wolf-procession
\par through the streets.
\par 
\par Not before dark night did the men and women come back to the children,
\par wailing and breadless. Then, the miserable bakers' shops were beset by
\par long files of them, patiently waiting to buy bad bread; and while
\par they waited with stomachs faint and empty, they beguiled the time by
\par embracing one another on the triumphs of the day, and achieving them
\par again in gossip. Gradually, these strings of ragged people shortened and
\par frayed away; and then poor lights began to shine in high windows, and
\par slender fires were made in the streets, at which neighbours cooked in
\par common, afterwards supping at their doors.
\par 
\par Scanty and insufficient suppers those, and innocent of meat, as of
\par most other sauce to wretched bread. Yet, human fellowship infused
\par some nourishment into the flinty viands, and struck some sparks of
\par cheerfulness out of them. Fathers and mothers who had had their full
\par share in the worst of the day, played gently with their meagre children;
\par and lovers, with such a world around them and before them, loved and
\par hoped.
\par 
\par It was almost morning, when Defarge's wine-shop parted with its last
\par knot of customers, and Monsieur Defarge said to madame his wife, in
\par husky tones, while fastening the door:
\par 
\par "At last it is come, my dear!"
\par 
\par "Eh well!" returned madame. "Almost."
\par 
\par Saint Antoine slept, the Defarges slept: even The Vengeance slept with
\par her starved grocer, and the drum was at rest. The drum's was the
\par only voice in Saint Antoine that blood and hurry had not changed. The
\par Vengeance, as custodian of the drum, could have wakened him up and had
\par the same speech out of him as before the Bastille fell, or old Foulon
\par was seized; not so with the hoarse tones of the men and women in Saint
\par Antoine's bosom.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XXIII. Fire Rises
\par 
\par 
\par There was a change on the village where the fountain fell, and where
\par the mender of roads went forth daily to hammer out of the stones on the
\par highway such morsels of bread as might serve for patches to hold his
\par poor ignorant soul and his poor reduced body together. The prison on the
\par crag was not so dominant as of yore; there were soldiers to guard it,
\par but not many; there were officers to guard the soldiers, but not one of
\par them knew what his men would do--beyond this: that it would probably not
\par be what he was ordered.
\par 
\par Far and wide lay a ruined country, yielding nothing but desolation.
\par Every green leaf, every blade of grass and blade of grain, was as
\par shrivelled and poor as the miserable people. Everything was bowed down,
\par dejected, oppressed, and broken. Habitations, fences, domesticated
\par animals, men, women, children, and the soil that bore them--all worn
\par out.
\par 
\par Monseigneur (often a most worthy individual gentleman) was a national
\par blessing, gave a chivalrous tone to things, was a polite example of
\par luxurious and shining life, and a great deal more to equal purpose;
\par nevertheless, Monseigneur as a class had, somehow or other, brought
\par things to this. Strange that Creation, designed expressly for
\par Monseigneur, should be so soon wrung dry and squeezed out! There must
\par be something short-sighted in the eternal arrangements, surely! Thus it
\par was, however; and the last drop of blood having been extracted from the
\par flints, and the last screw of the rack having been turned so often that
\par its purchase crumbled, and it now turned and turned with nothing
\par to bite, Monseigneur began to run away from a phenomenon so low and
\par unaccountable.
\par 
\par But, this was not the change on the village, and on many a village like
\par it. For scores of years gone by, Monseigneur had squeezed it and wrung
\par it, and had seldom graced it with his presence except for the pleasures
\par of the chase--now, found in hunting the people; now, found in hunting
\par the beasts, for whose preservation Monseigneur made edifying spaces
\par of barbarous and barren wilderness. No. The change consisted in
\par the appearance of strange faces of low caste, rather than in the
\par disappearance of the high caste, chiselled, and otherwise beautified and
\par beautifying features of Monseigneur.
\par 
\par For, in these times, as the mender of roads worked, solitary, in the
\par dust, not often troubling himself to reflect that dust he was and
\par to dust he must return, being for the most part too much occupied in
\par thinking how little he had for supper and how much more he would eat if
\par he had it--in these times, as he raised his eyes from his lonely labour,
\par and viewed the prospect, he would see some rough figure approaching on
\par foot, the like of which was once a rarity in those parts, but was now
\par a frequent presence. As it advanced, the mender of roads would discern
\par without surprise, that it was a shaggy-haired man, of almost barbarian
\par aspect, tall, in wooden shoes that were clumsy even to the eyes of a
\par mender of roads, grim, rough, swart, steeped in the mud and dust of many
\par highways, dank with the marshy moisture of many low grounds, sprinkled
\par with the thorns and leaves and moss of many byways through woods.
\par 
\par Such a man came upon him, like a ghost, at noon in the July weather,
\par as he sat on his heap of stones under a bank, taking such shelter as he
\par could get from a shower of hail.
\par 
\par The man looked at him, looked at the village in the hollow, at the mill,
\par and at the prison on the crag. When he had identified these objects
\par in what benighted mind he had, he said, in a dialect that was just
\par intelligible:
\par 
\par "How goes it, Jacques?"
\par 
\par "All well, Jacques."
\par 
\par "Touch then!"
\par 
\par They joined hands, and the man sat down on the heap of stones.
\par 
\par "No dinner?"
\par 
\par "Nothing but supper now," said the mender of roads, with a hungry face.
\par 
\par "It is the fashion," growled the man. "I meet no dinner anywhere."
\par 
\par He took out a blackened pipe, filled it, lighted it with flint and
\par steel, pulled at it until it was in a bright glow: then, suddenly held
\par it from him and dropped something into it from between his finger and
\par thumb, that blazed and went out in a puff of smoke.
\par 
\par "Touch then." It was the turn of the mender of roads to say it this
\par time, after observing these operations. They again joined hands.
\par 
\par "To-night?" said the mender of roads.
\par 
\par "To-night," said the man, putting the pipe in his mouth.
\par 
\par "Where?"
\par 
\par "Here."
\par 
\par He and the mender of roads sat on the heap of stones looking silently at
\par one another, with the hail driving in between them like a pigmy charge
\par of bayonets, until the sky began to clear over the village.
\par 
\par "Show me!" said the traveller then, moving to the brow of the hill.
\par 
\par "See!" returned the mender of roads, with extended finger. "You go down
\par here, and straight through the street, and past the fountain--"
\par 
\par "To the Devil with all that!" interrupted the other, rolling his eye
\par over the landscape. "_I_ go through no streets and past no fountains.
\par Well?"
\par 
\par "Well! About two leagues beyond the summit of that hill above the
\par village."
\par 
\par "Good. When do you cease to work?"
\par 
\par "At sunset."
\par 
\par "Will you wake me, before departing? I have walked two nights without
\par resting. Let me finish my pipe, and I shall sleep like a child. Will you
\par wake me?"
\par 
\par "Surely."
\par 
\par The wayfarer smoked his pipe out, put it in his breast, slipped off his
\par great wooden shoes, and lay down on his back on the heap of stones. He
\par was fast asleep directly.
\par 
\par As the road-mender plied his dusty labour, and the hail-clouds, rolling
\par away, revealed bright bars and streaks of sky which were responded to
\par by silver gleams upon the landscape, the little man (who wore a red cap
\par now, in place of his blue one) seemed fascinated by the figure on the
\par heap of stones. His eyes were so often turned towards it, that he used
\par his tools mechanically, and, one would have said, to very poor account.
\par The bronze face, the shaggy black hair and beard, the coarse woollen
\par red cap, the rough medley dress of home-spun stuff and hairy skins of
\par beasts, the powerful frame attenuated by spare living, and the sullen
\par and desperate compression of the lips in sleep, inspired the mender
\par of roads with awe. The traveller had travelled far, and his feet were
\par footsore, and his ankles chafed and bleeding; his great shoes, stuffed
\par with leaves and grass, had been heavy to drag over the many long
\par leagues, and his clothes were chafed into holes, as he himself was into
\par sores. Stooping down beside him, the road-mender tried to get a peep at
\par secret weapons in his breast or where not; but, in vain, for he slept
\par with his arms crossed upon him, and set as resolutely as his lips.
\par Fortified towns with their stockades, guard-houses, gates, trenches, and
\par drawbridges, seemed to the mender of roads, to be so much air as against
\par this figure. And when he lifted his eyes from it to the horizon and
\par looked around, he saw in his small fancy similar figures, stopped by no
\par obstacle, tending to centres all over France.
\par 
\par The man slept on, indifferent to showers of hail and intervals of
\par brightness, to sunshine on his face and shadow, to the paltering lumps
\par of dull ice on his body and the diamonds into which the sun changed
\par them, until the sun was low in the west, and the sky was glowing. Then,
\par the mender of roads having got his tools together and all things ready
\par to go down into the village, roused him.
\par 
\par "Good!" said the sleeper, rising on his elbow. "Two leagues beyond the
\par summit of the hill?"
\par 
\par "About."
\par 
\par "About. Good!"
\par 
\par The mender of roads went home, with the dust going on before him
\par according to the set of the wind, and was soon at the fountain,
\par squeezing himself in among the lean kine brought there to drink, and
\par appearing even to whisper to them in his whispering to all the village.
\par When the village had taken its poor supper, it did not creep to bed,
\par as it usually did, but came out of doors again, and remained there. A
\par curious contagion of whispering was upon it, and also, when it gathered
\par together at the fountain in the dark, another curious contagion of
\par looking expectantly at the sky in one direction only. Monsieur Gabelle,
\par chief functionary of the place, became uneasy; went out on his house-top
\par alone, and looked in that direction too; glanced down from behind his
\par chimneys at the darkening faces by the fountain below, and sent word to
\par the sacristan who kept the keys of the church, that there might be need
\par to ring the tocsin by-and-bye.
\par 
\par The night deepened. The trees environing the old chateau, keeping its
\par solitary state apart, moved in a rising wind, as though they threatened
\par the pile of building massive and dark in the gloom. Up the two terrace
\par flights of steps the rain ran wildly, and beat at the great door, like a
\par swift messenger rousing those within; uneasy rushes of wind went through
\par the hall, among the old spears and knives, and passed lamenting up the
\par stairs, and shook the curtains of the bed where the last Marquis
\par had slept. East, West, North, and South, through the woods, four
\par heavy-treading, unkempt figures crushed the high grass and cracked the
\par branches, striding on cautiously to come together in the courtyard. Four
\par lights broke out there, and moved away in different directions, and all
\par was black again.
\par 
\par But, not for long. Presently, the chateau began to make itself strangely
\par visible by some light of its own, as though it were growing luminous.
\par Then, a flickering streak played behind the architecture of the front,
\par picking out transparent places, and showing where balustrades, arches,
\par and windows were. Then it soared higher, and grew broader and brighter.
\par Soon, from a score of the great windows, flames burst forth, and the
\par stone faces awakened, stared out of fire.
\par 
\par A faint murmur arose about the house from the few people who were left
\par there, and there was a saddling of a horse and riding away. There was
\par spurring and splashing through the darkness, and bridle was drawn in the
\par space by the village fountain, and the horse in a foam stood at Monsieur
\par Gabelle's door. "Help, Gabelle! Help, every one!" The tocsin rang
\par impatiently, but other help (if that were any) there was none. The
\par mender of roads, and two hundred and fifty particular friends, stood
\par with folded arms at the fountain, looking at the pillar of fire in the
\par sky. "It must be forty feet high," said they, grimly; and never moved.
\par 
\par The rider from the chateau, and the horse in a foam, clattered away
\par through the village, and galloped up the stony steep, to the prison on
\par the crag. At the gate, a group of officers were looking at the fire;
\par removed from them, a group of soldiers. "Help, gentlemen--officers! The
\par chateau is on fire; valuable objects may be saved from the flames by
\par timely aid! Help, help!" The officers looked towards the soldiers who
\par looked at the fire; gave no orders; and answered, with shrugs and biting
\par of lips, "It must burn."
\par 
\par As the rider rattled down the hill again and through the street, the
\par village was illuminating. The mender of roads, and the two hundred and
\par fifty particular friends, inspired as one man and woman by the idea of
\par lighting up, had darted into their houses, and were putting candles in
\par every dull little pane of glass. The general scarcity of everything,
\par occasioned candles to be borrowed in a rather peremptory manner of
\par Monsieur Gabelle; and in a moment of reluctance and hesitation on
\par that functionary's part, the mender of roads, once so submissive to
\par authority, had remarked that carriages were good to make bonfires with,
\par and that post-horses would roast.
\par 
\par The chateau was left to itself to flame and burn. In the roaring and
\par raging of the conflagration, a red-hot wind, driving straight from the
\par infernal regions, seemed to be blowing the edifice away. With the rising
\par and falling of the blaze, the stone faces showed as if they were in
\par torment. When great masses of stone and timber fell, the face with the
\par two dints in the nose became obscured: anon struggled out of the smoke
\par again, as if it were the face of the cruel Marquis, burning at the stake
\par and contending with the fire.
\par 
\par The chateau burned; the nearest trees, laid hold of by the fire,
\par scorched and shrivelled; trees at a distance, fired by the four fierce
\par figures, begirt the blazing edifice with a new forest of smoke. Molten
\par lead and iron boiled in the marble basin of the fountain; the water ran
\par dry; the extinguisher tops of the towers vanished like ice before the
\par heat, and trickled down into four rugged wells of flame. Great rents and
\par splits branched out in the solid walls, like crystallisation; stupefied
\par birds wheeled about and dropped into the furnace; four fierce figures
\par trudged away, East, West, North, and South, along the night-enshrouded
\par roads, guided by the beacon they had lighted, towards their next
\par destination. The illuminated village had seized hold of the tocsin, and,
\par abolishing the lawful ringer, rang for joy.
\par 
\par Not only that; but the village, light-headed with famine, fire, and
\par bell-ringing, and bethinking itself that Monsieur Gabelle had to do with
\par the collection of rent and taxes--though it was but a small instalment
\par of taxes, and no rent at all, that Gabelle had got in those latter
\par days--became impatient for an interview with him, and, surrounding his
\par house, summoned him to come forth for personal conference. Whereupon,
\par Monsieur Gabelle did heavily bar his door, and retire to hold counsel
\par with himself. The result of that conference was, that Gabelle again
\par withdrew himself to his housetop behind his stack of chimneys; this time
\par resolved, if his door were broken in (he was a small Southern man
\par of retaliative temperament), to pitch himself head foremost over the
\par parapet, and crush a man or two below.
\par 
\par Probably, Monsieur Gabelle passed a long night up there, with the
\par distant chateau for fire and candle, and the beating at his door,
\par combined with the joy-ringing, for music; not to mention his having an
\par ill-omened lamp slung across the road before his posting-house gate,
\par which the village showed a lively inclination to displace in his favour.
\par A trying suspense, to be passing a whole summer night on the brink of
\par the black ocean, ready to take that plunge into it upon which Monsieur
\par Gabelle had resolved! But, the friendly dawn appearing at last, and the
\par rush-candles of the village guttering out, the people happily dispersed,
\par and Monsieur Gabelle came down bringing his life with him for that
\par while.
\par 
\par Within a hundred miles, and in the light of other fires, there were
\par other functionaries less fortunate, that night and other nights, whom
\par the rising sun found hanging across once-peaceful streets, where they
\par had been born and bred; also, there were other villagers and townspeople
\par less fortunate than the mender of roads and his fellows, upon whom the
\par functionaries and soldiery turned with success, and whom they strung up
\par in their turn. But, the fierce figures were steadily wending East, West,
\par North, and South, be that as it would; and whosoever hung, fire burned.
\par The altitude of the gallows that would turn to water and quench it,
\par no functionary, by any stretch of mathematics, was able to calculate
\par successfully.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XXIV. Drawn to the Loadstone Rock
\par 
\par 
\par In such risings of fire and risings of sea--the firm earth shaken by
\par the rushes of an angry ocean which had now no ebb, but was always on the
\par flow, higher and higher, to the terror and wonder of the beholders on
\par the shore--three years of tempest were consumed. Three more birthdays
\par of little Lucie had been woven by the golden thread into the peaceful
\par tissue of the life of her home.
\par 
\par Many a night and many a day had its inmates listened to the echoes in
\par the corner, with hearts that failed them when they heard the thronging
\par feet. For, the footsteps had become to their minds as the footsteps of
\par a people, tumultuous under a red flag and with their country declared in
\par danger, changed into wild beasts, by terrible enchantment long persisted
\par in.
\par 
\par Monseigneur, as a class, had dissociated himself from the phenomenon of
\par his not being appreciated: of his being so little wanted in France, as
\par to incur considerable danger of receiving his dismissal from it, and
\par this life together. Like the fabled rustic who raised the Devil with
\par infinite pains, and was so terrified at the sight of him that he could
\par ask the Enemy no question, but immediately fled; so, Monseigneur, after
\par boldly reading the Lord's Prayer backwards for a great number of years,
\par and performing many other potent spells for compelling the Evil One, no
\par sooner beheld him in his terrors than he took to his noble heels.
\par 
\par The shining Bull's Eye of the Court was gone, or it would have been the
\par mark for a hurricane of national bullets. It had never been a good
\par eye to see with--had long had the mote in it of Lucifer's pride,
\par Sardanapalus's luxury, and a mole's blindness--but it had dropped
\par out and was gone. The Court, from that exclusive inner circle to its
\par outermost rotten ring of intrigue, corruption, and dissimulation, was
\par all gone together. Royalty was gone; had been besieged in its Palace and
\par "suspended," when the last tidings came over.
\par 
\par The August of the year one thousand seven hundred and ninety-two was
\par come, and Monseigneur was by this time scattered far and wide.
\par 
\par As was natural, the head-quarters and great gathering-place of
\par Monseigneur, in London, was Tellson's Bank. Spirits are supposed to
\par haunt the places where their bodies most resorted, and Monseigneur
\par without a guinea haunted the spot where his guineas used to be.
\par Moreover, it was the spot to which such French intelligence as was most
\par to be relied upon, came quickest. Again: Tellson's was a munificent
\par house, and extended great liberality to old customers who had fallen
\par from their high estate. Again: those nobles who had seen the coming
\par storm in time, and anticipating plunder or confiscation, had made
\par provident remittances to Tellson's, were always to be heard of there
\par by their needy brethren. To which it must be added that every new-comer
\par from France reported himself and his tidings at Tellson's, almost as
\par a matter of course. For such variety of reasons, Tellson's was at that
\par time, as to French intelligence, a kind of High Exchange; and this
\par was so well known to the public, and the inquiries made there were in
\par consequence so numerous, that Tellson's sometimes wrote the latest news
\par out in a line or so and posted it in the Bank windows, for all who ran
\par through Temple Bar to read.
\par 
\par On a steaming, misty afternoon, Mr. Lorry sat at his desk, and Charles
\par Darnay stood leaning on it, talking with him in a low voice. The
\par penitential den once set apart for interviews with the House, was now
\par the news-Exchange, and was filled to overflowing. It was within half an
\par hour or so of the time of closing.
\par 
\par "But, although you are the youngest man that ever lived," said Charles
\par Darnay, rather hesitating, "I must still suggest to you--"
\par 
\par "I understand. That I am too old?" said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "Unsettled weather, a long journey, uncertain means of travelling, a
\par disorganised country, a city that may not be even safe for you."
\par 
\par "My dear Charles," said Mr. Lorry, with cheerful confidence, "you touch
\par some of the reasons for my going: not for my staying away. It is safe
\par enough for me; nobody will care to interfere with an old fellow of hard
\par upon fourscore when there are so many people there much better worth
\par interfering with. As to its being a disorganised city, if it were not a
\par disorganised city there would be no occasion to send somebody from our
\par House here to our House there, who knows the city and the business, of
\par old, and is in Tellson's confidence. As to the uncertain travelling, the
\par long journey, and the winter weather, if I were not prepared to submit
\par myself to a few inconveniences for the sake of Tellson's, after all
\par these years, who ought to be?"
\par 
\par "I wish I were going myself," said Charles Darnay, somewhat restlessly,
\par and like one thinking aloud.
\par 
\par "Indeed! You are a pretty fellow to object and advise!" exclaimed Mr.
\par Lorry. "You wish you were going yourself? And you a Frenchman born? You
\par are a wise counsellor."
\par 
\par "My dear Mr. Lorry, it is because I am a Frenchman born, that the
\par thought (which I did not mean to utter here, however) has passed through
\par my mind often. One cannot help thinking, having had some sympathy for
\par the miserable people, and having abandoned something to them," he spoke
\par here in his former thoughtful manner, "that one might be listened to,
\par and might have the power to persuade to some restraint. Only last night,
\par after you had left us, when I was talking to Lucie--"
\par 
\par "When you were talking to Lucie," Mr. Lorry repeated. "Yes. I wonder you
\par are not ashamed to mention the name of Lucie! Wishing you were going to
\par France at this time of day!"
\par 
\par "However, I am not going," said Charles Darnay, with a smile. "It is
\par more to the purpose that you say you are."
\par 
\par "And I am, in plain reality. The truth is, my dear Charles," Mr. Lorry
\par glanced at the distant House, and lowered his voice, "you can have no
\par conception of the difficulty with which our business is transacted, and
\par of the peril in which our books and papers over yonder are involved. The
\par Lord above knows what the compromising consequences would be to numbers
\par of people, if some of our documents were seized or destroyed; and they
\par might be, at any time, you know, for who can say that Paris is not set
\par afire to-day, or sacked to-morrow! Now, a judicious selection from these
\par with the least possible delay, and the burying of them, or otherwise
\par getting of them out of harm's way, is within the power (without loss of
\par precious time) of scarcely any one but myself, if any one. And shall
\par I hang back, when Tellson's knows this and says this--Tellson's, whose
\par bread I have eaten these sixty years--because I am a little stiff about
\par the joints? Why, I am a boy, sir, to half a dozen old codgers here!"
\par 
\par "How I admire the gallantry of your youthful spirit, Mr. Lorry."
\par 
\par "Tut! Nonsense, sir!--And, my dear Charles," said Mr. Lorry, glancing at
\par the House again, "you are to remember, that getting things out of
\par Paris at this present time, no matter what things, is next to an
\par impossibility. Papers and precious matters were this very day brought
\par to us here (I speak in strict confidence; it is not business-like to
\par whisper it, even to you), by the strangest bearers you can imagine,
\par every one of whom had his head hanging on by a single hair as he passed
\par the Barriers. At another time, our parcels would come and go, as easily
\par as in business-like Old England; but now, everything is stopped."
\par 
\par "And do you really go to-night?"
\par 
\par "I really go to-night, for the case has become too pressing to admit of
\par delay."
\par 
\par "And do you take no one with you?"
\par 
\par "All sorts of people have been proposed to me, but I will have nothing
\par to say to any of them. I intend to take Jerry. Jerry has been my
\par bodyguard on Sunday nights for a long time past and I am used to him.
\par Nobody will suspect Jerry of being anything but an English bull-dog, or
\par of having any design in his head but to fly at anybody who touches his
\par master."
\par 
\par "I must say again that I heartily admire your gallantry and
\par youthfulness."
\par 
\par "I must say again, nonsense, nonsense! When I have executed this little
\par commission, I shall, perhaps, accept Tellson's proposal to retire and
\par live at my ease. Time enough, then, to think about growing old."
\par 
\par This dialogue had taken place at Mr. Lorry's usual desk, with
\par Monseigneur swarming within a yard or two of it, boastful of what he
\par would do to avenge himself on the rascal-people before long. It was too
\par much the way of Monseigneur under his reverses as a refugee, and it
\par was much too much the way of native British orthodoxy, to talk of this
\par terrible Revolution as if it were the only harvest ever known under
\par the skies that had not been sown--as if nothing had ever been done, or
\par omitted to be done, that had led to it--as if observers of the wretched
\par millions in France, and of the misused and perverted resources that
\par should have made them prosperous, had not seen it inevitably coming,
\par years before, and had not in plain words recorded what they saw. Such
\par vapouring, combined with the extravagant plots of Monseigneur for the
\par restoration of a state of things that had utterly exhausted itself,
\par and worn out Heaven and earth as well as itself, was hard to be endured
\par without some remonstrance by any sane man who knew the truth. And it was
\par such vapouring all about his ears, like a troublesome confusion of blood
\par in his own head, added to a latent uneasiness in his mind, which had
\par already made Charles Darnay restless, and which still kept him so.
\par 
\par Among the talkers, was Stryver, of the King's Bench Bar, far on his
\par way to state promotion, and, therefore, loud on the theme: broaching
\par to Monseigneur, his devices for blowing the people up and exterminating
\par them from the face of the earth, and doing without them: and for
\par accomplishing many similar objects akin in their nature to the abolition
\par of eagles by sprinkling salt on the tails of the race. Him, Darnay heard
\par with a particular feeling of objection; and Darnay stood divided between
\par going away that he might hear no more, and remaining to interpose his
\par word, when the thing that was to be, went on to shape itself out.
\par 
\par The House approached Mr. Lorry, and laying a soiled and unopened letter
\par before him, asked if he had yet discovered any traces of the person to
\par whom it was addressed? The House laid the letter down so close to Darnay
\par that he saw the direction--the more quickly because it was his own right
\par name. The address, turned into English, ran:
\par 
\par "Very pressing. To Monsieur heretofore the Marquis St. Evremonde, of
\par France. Confided to the cares of Messrs. Tellson and Co., Bankers,
\par London, England."
\par 
\par On the marriage morning, Doctor Manette had made it his one urgent and
\par express request to Charles Darnay, that the secret of this name should
\par be--unless he, the Doctor, dissolved the obligation--kept inviolate
\par between them. Nobody else knew it to be his name; his own wife had no
\par suspicion of the fact; Mr. Lorry could have none.
\par 
\par "No," said Mr. Lorry, in reply to the House; "I have referred it,
\par I think, to everybody now here, and no one can tell me where this
\par gentleman is to be found."
\par 
\par The hands of the clock verging upon the hour of closing the Bank, there
\par was a general set of the current of talkers past Mr. Lorry's desk. He
\par held the letter out inquiringly; and Monseigneur looked at it, in the
\par person of this plotting and indignant refugee; and Monseigneur looked at
\par it in the person of that plotting and indignant refugee; and This, That,
\par and The Other, all had something disparaging to say, in French or in
\par English, concerning the Marquis who was not to be found.
\par 
\par "Nephew, I believe--but in any case degenerate successor--of the
\par polished Marquis who was murdered," said one. "Happy to say, I never
\par knew him."
\par 
\par "A craven who abandoned his post," said another--this Monseigneur had
\par been got out of Paris, legs uppermost and half suffocated, in a load of
\par hay--"some years ago."
\par 
\par "Infected with the new doctrines," said a third, eyeing the direction
\par through his glass in passing; "set himself in opposition to the last
\par Marquis, abandoned the estates when he inherited them, and left them to
\par the ruffian herd. They will recompense him now, I hope, as he deserves."
\par 
\par "Hey?" cried the blatant Stryver. "Did he though? Is that the sort of
\par fellow? Let us look at his infamous name. D--n the fellow!"
\par 
\par Darnay, unable to restrain himself any longer, touched Mr. Stryver on
\par the shoulder, and said:
\par 
\par "I know the fellow."
\par 
\par "Do you, by Jupiter?" said Stryver. "I am sorry for it."
\par 
\par "Why?"
\par 
\par "Why, Mr. Darnay? D'ye hear what he did? Don't ask, why, in these
\par times."
\par 
\par "But I do ask why?"
\par 
\par "Then I tell you again, Mr. Darnay, I am sorry for it. I am sorry to
\par hear you putting any such extraordinary questions. Here is a fellow,
\par who, infected by the most pestilent and blasphemous code of devilry that
\par ever was known, abandoned his property to the vilest scum of the earth
\par that ever did murder by wholesale, and you ask me why I am sorry that a
\par man who instructs youth knows him? Well, but I'll answer you. I am sorry
\par because I believe there is contamination in such a scoundrel. That's
\par why."
\par 
\par Mindful of the secret, Darnay with great difficulty checked himself, and
\par said: "You may not understand the gentleman."
\par 
\par "I understand how to put _you_ in a corner, Mr. Darnay," said Bully
\par Stryver, "and I'll do it. If this fellow is a gentleman, I _don't_
\par understand him. You may tell him so, with my compliments. You may also
\par tell him, from me, that after abandoning his worldly goods and position
\par to this butcherly mob, I wonder he is not at the head of them. But, no,
\par gentlemen," said Stryver, looking all round, and snapping his fingers,
\par "I know something of human nature, and I tell you that you'll never
\par find a fellow like this fellow, trusting himself to the mercies of such
\par precious _proteges_. No, gentlemen; he'll always show 'em a clean pair
\par of heels very early in the scuffle, and sneak away."
\par 
\par With those words, and a final snap of his fingers, Mr. Stryver
\par shouldered himself into Fleet-street, amidst the general approbation of
\par his hearers. Mr. Lorry and Charles Darnay were left alone at the desk,
\par in the general departure from the Bank.
\par 
\par "Will you take charge of the letter?" said Mr. Lorry. "You know where to
\par deliver it?"
\par 
\par "I do."
\par 
\par "Will you undertake to explain, that we suppose it to have been
\par addressed here, on the chance of our knowing where to forward it, and
\par that it has been here some time?"
\par 
\par "I will do so. Do you start for Paris from here?"
\par 
\par "From here, at eight."
\par 
\par "I will come back, to see you off."
\par 
\par Very ill at ease with himself, and with Stryver and most other men,
\par Darnay made the best of his way into the quiet of the Temple, opened the
\par letter, and read it. These were its contents:
\par 
\par 
\par "Prison of the Abbaye, Paris.
\par 
\par "June 21, 1792. "MONSIEUR HERETOFORE THE MARQUIS.
\par 
\par "After having long been in danger of my life at the hands of the
\par village, I have been seized, with great violence and indignity, and
\par brought a long journey on foot to Paris. On the road I have suffered a
\par great deal. Nor is that all; my house has been destroyed--razed to the
\par ground.
\par 
\par "The crime for which I am imprisoned, Monsieur heretofore the Marquis,
\par and for which I shall be summoned before the tribunal, and shall lose my
\par life (without your so generous help), is, they tell me, treason against
\par the majesty of the people, in that I have acted against them for an
\par emigrant. It is in vain I represent that I have acted for them, and not
\par against, according to your commands. It is in vain I represent that,
\par before the sequestration of emigrant property, I had remitted the
\par imposts they had ceased to pay; that I had collected no rent; that I had
\par had recourse to no process. The only response is, that I have acted for
\par an emigrant, and where is that emigrant?
\par 
\par "Ah! most gracious Monsieur heretofore the Marquis, where is that
\par emigrant? I cry in my sleep where is he? I demand of Heaven, will he
\par not come to deliver me? No answer. Ah Monsieur heretofore the Marquis,
\par I send my desolate cry across the sea, hoping it may perhaps reach your
\par ears through the great bank of Tilson known at Paris!
\par 
\par "For the love of Heaven, of justice, of generosity, of the honour of
\par your noble name, I supplicate you, Monsieur heretofore the Marquis, to
\par succour and release me. My fault is, that I have been true to you. Oh
\par Monsieur heretofore the Marquis, I pray you be you true to me!
\par 
\par "From this prison here of horror, whence I every hour tend nearer and
\par nearer to destruction, I send you, Monsieur heretofore the Marquis, the
\par assurance of my dolorous and unhappy service.
\par 
\par "Your afflicted,
\par 
\par "Gabelle."
\par 
\par 
\par The latent uneasiness in Darnay's mind was roused to vigourous life
\par by this letter. The peril of an old servant and a good one, whose
\par only crime was fidelity to himself and his family, stared him so
\par reproachfully in the face, that, as he walked to and fro in the Temple
\par considering what to do, he almost hid his face from the passersby.
\par 
\par He knew very well, that in his horror of the deed which had culminated
\par the bad deeds and bad reputation of the old family house, in his
\par resentful suspicions of his uncle, and in the aversion with which his
\par conscience regarded the crumbling fabric that he was supposed to uphold,
\par he had acted imperfectly. He knew very well, that in his love for Lucie,
\par his renunciation of his social place, though by no means new to his own
\par mind, had been hurried and incomplete. He knew that he ought to have
\par systematically worked it out and supervised it, and that he had meant to
\par do it, and that it had never been done.
\par 
\par The happiness of his own chosen English home, the necessity of being
\par always actively employed, the swift changes and troubles of the time
\par which had followed on one another so fast, that the events of this week
\par annihilated the immature plans of last week, and the events of the week
\par following made all new again; he knew very well, that to the force of
\par these circumstances he had yielded:--not without disquiet, but still
\par without continuous and accumulating resistance. That he had watched
\par the times for a time of action, and that they had shifted and struggled
\par until the time had gone by, and the nobility were trooping from
\par France by every highway and byway, and their property was in course of
\par confiscation and destruction, and their very names were blotting out,
\par was as well known to himself as it could be to any new authority in
\par France that might impeach him for it.
\par 
\par But, he had oppressed no man, he had imprisoned no man; he was so
\par far from having harshly exacted payment of his dues, that he had
\par relinquished them of his own will, thrown himself on a world with no
\par favour in it, won his own private place there, and earned his own
\par bread. Monsieur Gabelle had held the impoverished and involved estate
\par on written instructions, to spare the people, to give them what little
\par there was to give--such fuel as the heavy creditors would let them have
\par in the winter, and such produce as could be saved from the same grip in
\par the summer--and no doubt he had put the fact in plea and proof, for his
\par own safety, so that it could not but appear now.
\par 
\par This favoured the desperate resolution Charles Darnay had begun to make,
\par that he would go to Paris.
\par 
\par Yes. Like the mariner in the old story, the winds and streams had driven
\par him within the influence of the Loadstone Rock, and it was drawing him
\par to itself, and he must go. Everything that arose before his mind drifted
\par him on, faster and faster, more and more steadily, to the terrible
\par attraction. His latent uneasiness had been, that bad aims were being
\par worked out in his own unhappy land by bad instruments, and that he who
\par could not fail to know that he was better than they, was not there,
\par trying to do something to stay bloodshed, and assert the claims of mercy
\par and humanity. With this uneasiness half stifled, and half reproaching
\par him, he had been brought to the pointed comparison of himself with the
\par brave old gentleman in whom duty was so strong; upon that comparison
\par (injurious to himself) had instantly followed the sneers of Monseigneur,
\par which had stung him bitterly, and those of Stryver, which above all were
\par coarse and galling, for old reasons. Upon those, had followed Gabelle's
\par letter: the appeal of an innocent prisoner, in danger of death, to his
\par justice, honour, and good name.
\par 
\par His resolution was made. He must go to Paris.
\par 
\par Yes. The Loadstone Rock was drawing him, and he must sail on, until he
\par struck. He knew of no rock; he saw hardly any danger. The intention
\par with which he had done what he had done, even although he had left
\par it incomplete, presented it before him in an aspect that would be
\par gratefully acknowledged in France on his presenting himself to assert
\par it. Then, that glorious vision of doing good, which is so often the
\par sanguine mirage of so many good minds, arose before him, and he even
\par saw himself in the illusion with some influence to guide this raging
\par Revolution that was running so fearfully wild.
\par 
\par As he walked to and fro with his resolution made, he considered that
\par neither Lucie nor her father must know of it until he was gone.
\par Lucie should be spared the pain of separation; and her father, always
\par reluctant to turn his thoughts towards the dangerous ground of old,
\par should come to the knowledge of the step, as a step taken, and not in
\par the balance of suspense and doubt. How much of the incompleteness of his
\par situation was referable to her father, through the painful anxiety
\par to avoid reviving old associations of France in his mind, he did not
\par discuss with himself. But, that circumstance too, had had its influence
\par in his course.
\par 
\par He walked to and fro, with thoughts very busy, until it was time to
\par return to Tellson's and take leave of Mr. Lorry. As soon as he arrived
\par in Paris he would present himself to this old friend, but he must say
\par nothing of his intention now.
\par 
\par A carriage with post-horses was ready at the Bank door, and Jerry was
\par booted and equipped.
\par 
\par "I have delivered that letter," said Charles Darnay to Mr. Lorry. "I
\par would not consent to your being charged with any written answer, but
\par perhaps you will take a verbal one?"
\par 
\par "That I will, and readily," said Mr. Lorry, "if it is not dangerous."
\par 
\par "Not at all. Though it is to a prisoner in the Abbaye."
\par 
\par "What is his name?" said Mr. Lorry, with his open pocket-book in his
\par hand.
\par 
\par "Gabelle."
\par 
\par "Gabelle. And what is the message to the unfortunate Gabelle in prison?"
\par 
\par "Simply, 'that he has received the letter, and will come.'"
\par 
\par "Any time mentioned?"
\par 
\par "He will start upon his journey to-morrow night."
\par 
\par "Any person mentioned?"
\par 
\par "No."
\par 
\par He helped Mr. Lorry to wrap himself in a number of coats and cloaks,
\par and went out with him from the warm atmosphere of the old Bank, into the
\par misty air of Fleet-street. "My love to Lucie, and to little Lucie," said
\par Mr. Lorry at parting, "and take precious care of them till I come back."
\par Charles Darnay shook his head and doubtfully smiled, as the carriage
\par rolled away.
\par 
\par That night--it was the fourteenth of August--he sat up late, and wrote
\par two fervent letters; one was to Lucie, explaining the strong obligation
\par he was under to go to Paris, and showing her, at length, the reasons
\par that he had, for feeling confident that he could become involved in no
\par personal danger there; the other was to the Doctor, confiding Lucie and
\par their dear child to his care, and dwelling on the same topics with the
\par strongest assurances. To both, he wrote that he would despatch letters
\par in proof of his safety, immediately after his arrival.
\par 
\par It was a hard day, that day of being among them, with the first
\par reservation of their joint lives on his mind. It was a hard matter to
\par preserve the innocent deceit of which they were profoundly unsuspicious.
\par But, an affectionate glance at his wife, so happy and busy, made him
\par resolute not to tell her what impended (he had been half moved to do it,
\par so strange it was to him to act in anything without her quiet aid), and
\par the day passed quickly. Early in the evening he embraced her, and her
\par scarcely less dear namesake, pretending that he would return by-and-bye
\par (an imaginary engagement took him out, and he had secreted a valise
\par of clothes ready), and so he emerged into the heavy mist of the heavy
\par streets, with a heavier heart.
\par 
\par The unseen force was drawing him fast to itself, now, and all the tides
\par and winds were setting straight and strong towards it. He left his
\par two letters with a trusty porter, to be delivered half an hour before
\par midnight, and no sooner; took horse for Dover; and began his journey.
\par "For the love of Heaven, of justice, of generosity, of the honour of
\par your noble name!" was the poor prisoner's cry with which he strengthened
\par his sinking heart, as he left all that was dear on earth behind him, and
\par floated away for the Loadstone Rock.
\par 
\par 
\par The end of the second book.
\par 
