\par 
\par Book the Third--the Track of a Storm
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par I. In Secret
\par 
\par 
\par The traveller fared slowly on his way, who fared towards Paris from
\par England in the autumn of the year one thousand seven hundred and
\par ninety-two. More than enough of bad roads, bad equipages, and bad
\par horses, he would have encountered to delay him, though the fallen and
\par unfortunate King of France had been upon his throne in all his glory;
\par but, the changed times were fraught with other obstacles than
\par these. Every town-gate and village taxing-house had its band of
\par citizen-patriots, with their national muskets in a most explosive state
\par of readiness, who stopped all comers and goers, cross-questioned them,
\par inspected their papers, looked for their names in lists of their own,
\par turned them back, or sent them on, or stopped them and laid them in
\par hold, as their capricious judgment or fancy deemed best for the dawning
\par Republic One and Indivisible, of Liberty, Equality, Fraternity, or
\par Death.
\par 
\par A very few French leagues of his journey were accomplished, when Charles
\par Darnay began to perceive that for him along these country roads there
\par was no hope of return until he should have been declared a good citizen
\par at Paris. Whatever might befall now, he must on to his journey's end.
\par Not a mean village closed upon him, not a common barrier dropped across
\par the road behind him, but he knew it to be another iron door in
\par the series that was barred between him and England. The universal
\par watchfulness so encompassed him, that if he had been taken in a net,
\par or were being forwarded to his destination in a cage, he could not have
\par felt his freedom more completely gone.
\par 
\par This universal watchfulness not only stopped him on the highway twenty
\par times in a stage, but retarded his progress twenty times in a day, by
\par riding after him and taking him back, riding before him and stopping him
\par by anticipation, riding with him and keeping him in charge. He had been
\par days upon his journey in France alone, when he went to bed tired out, in
\par a little town on the high road, still a long way from Paris.
\par 
\par Nothing but the production of the afflicted Gabelle's letter from his
\par prison of the Abbaye would have got him on so far. His difficulty at the
\par guard-house in this small place had been such, that he felt his journey
\par to have come to a crisis. And he was, therefore, as little surprised as
\par a man could be, to find himself awakened at the small inn to which he
\par had been remitted until morning, in the middle of the night.
\par 
\par Awakened by a timid local functionary and three armed patriots in rough
\par red caps and with pipes in their mouths, who sat down on the bed.
\par 
\par "Emigrant," said the functionary, "I am going to send you on to Paris,
\par under an escort."
\par 
\par "Citizen, I desire nothing more than to get to Paris, though I could
\par dispense with the escort."
\par 
\par "Silence!" growled a red-cap, striking at the coverlet with the butt-end
\par of his musket. "Peace, aristocrat!"
\par 
\par "It is as the good patriot says," observed the timid functionary. "You
\par are an aristocrat, and must have an escort--and must pay for it."
\par 
\par "I have no choice," said Charles Darnay.
\par 
\par "Choice! Listen to him!" cried the same scowling red-cap. "As if it was
\par not a favour to be protected from the lamp-iron!"
\par 
\par "It is always as the good patriot says," observed the functionary. "Rise
\par and dress yourself, emigrant."
\par 
\par Darnay complied, and was taken back to the guard-house, where other
\par patriots in rough red caps were smoking, drinking, and sleeping, by
\par a watch-fire. Here he paid a heavy price for his escort, and hence he
\par started with it on the wet, wet roads at three o'clock in the morning.
\par 
\par The escort were two mounted patriots in red caps and tri-coloured
\par cockades, armed with national muskets and sabres, who rode one on either
\par side of him.
\par 
\par The escorted governed his own horse, but a loose line was attached to
\par his bridle, the end of which one of the patriots kept girded round his
\par wrist. In this state they set forth with the sharp rain driving in their
\par faces: clattering at a heavy dragoon trot over the uneven town pavement,
\par and out upon the mire-deep roads. In this state they traversed without
\par change, except of horses and pace, all the mire-deep leagues that lay
\par between them and the capital.
\par 
\par They travelled in the night, halting an hour or two after daybreak, and
\par lying by until the twilight fell. The escort were so wretchedly clothed,
\par that they twisted straw round their bare legs, and thatched their ragged
\par shoulders to keep the wet off. Apart from the personal discomfort of
\par being so attended, and apart from such considerations of present danger
\par as arose from one of the patriots being chronically drunk, and carrying
\par his musket very recklessly, Charles Darnay did not allow the restraint
\par that was laid upon him to awaken any serious fears in his breast; for,
\par he reasoned with himself that it could have no reference to the merits
\par of an individual case that was not yet stated, and of representations,
\par confirmable by the prisoner in the Abbaye, that were not yet made.
\par 
\par But when they came to the town of Beauvais--which they did at eventide,
\par when the streets were filled with people--he could not conceal from
\par himself that the aspect of affairs was very alarming. An ominous crowd
\par gathered to see him dismount of the posting-yard, and many voices called
\par out loudly, "Down with the emigrant!"
\par 
\par He stopped in the act of swinging himself out of his saddle, and,
\par resuming it as his safest place, said:
\par 
\par "Emigrant, my friends! Do you not see me here, in France, of my own
\par will?"
\par 
\par "You are a cursed emigrant," cried a farrier, making at him in a
\par furious manner through the press, hammer in hand; "and you are a cursed
\par aristocrat!"
\par 
\par The postmaster interposed himself between this man and the rider's
\par bridle (at which he was evidently making), and soothingly said, "Let him
\par be; let him be! He will be judged at Paris."
\par 
\par "Judged!" repeated the farrier, swinging his hammer. "Ay! and condemned
\par as a traitor." At this the crowd roared approval.
\par 
\par Checking the postmaster, who was for turning his horse's head to the
\par yard (the drunken patriot sat composedly in his saddle looking on, with
\par the line round his wrist), Darnay said, as soon as he could make his
\par voice heard:
\par 
\par "Friends, you deceive yourselves, or you are deceived. I am not a
\par traitor."
\par 
\par "He lies!" cried the smith. "He is a traitor since the decree. His life
\par is forfeit to the people. His cursed life is not his own!"
\par 
\par At the instant when Darnay saw a rush in the eyes of the crowd, which
\par another instant would have brought upon him, the postmaster turned his
\par horse into the yard, the escort rode in close upon his horse's flanks,
\par and the postmaster shut and barred the crazy double gates. The farrier
\par struck a blow upon them with his hammer, and the crowd groaned; but, no
\par more was done.
\par 
\par "What is this decree that the smith spoke of?" Darnay asked the
\par postmaster, when he had thanked him, and stood beside him in the yard.
\par 
\par "Truly, a decree for selling the property of emigrants."
\par 
\par "When passed?"
\par 
\par "On the fourteenth."
\par 
\par "The day I left England!"
\par 
\par "Everybody says it is but one of several, and that there will be
\par others--if there are not already--banishing all emigrants, and
\par condemning all to death who return. That is what he meant when he said
\par your life was not your own."
\par 
\par "But there are no such decrees yet?"
\par 
\par "What do I know!" said the postmaster, shrugging his shoulders; "there
\par may be, or there will be. It is all the same. What would you have?"
\par 
\par They rested on some straw in a loft until the middle of the night, and
\par then rode forward again when all the town was asleep. Among the many
\par wild changes observable on familiar things which made this wild ride
\par unreal, not the least was the seeming rarity of sleep. After long and
\par lonely spurring over dreary roads, they would come to a cluster of poor
\par cottages, not steeped in darkness, but all glittering with lights, and
\par would find the people, in a ghostly manner in the dead of the night,
\par circling hand in hand round a shrivelled tree of Liberty, or all drawn
\par up together singing a Liberty song. Happily, however, there was sleep in
\par Beauvais that night to help them out of it and they passed on once more
\par into solitude and loneliness: jingling through the untimely cold and
\par wet, among impoverished fields that had yielded no fruits of the earth
\par that year, diversified by the blackened remains of burnt houses, and by
\par the sudden emergence from ambuscade, and sharp reining up across their
\par way, of patriot patrols on the watch on all the roads.
\par 
\par Daylight at last found them before the wall of Paris. The barrier was
\par closed and strongly guarded when they rode up to it.
\par 
\par "Where are the papers of this prisoner?" demanded a resolute-looking man
\par in authority, who was summoned out by the guard.
\par 
\par Naturally struck by the disagreeable word, Charles Darnay requested the
\par speaker to take notice that he was a free traveller and French citizen,
\par in charge of an escort which the disturbed state of the country had
\par imposed upon him, and which he had paid for.
\par 
\par "Where," repeated the same personage, without taking any heed of him
\par whatever, "are the papers of this prisoner?"
\par 
\par The drunken patriot had them in his cap, and produced them. Casting his
\par eyes over Gabelle's letter, the same personage in authority showed some
\par disorder and surprise, and looked at Darnay with a close attention.
\par 
\par He left escort and escorted without saying a word, however, and went
\par into the guard-room; meanwhile, they sat upon their horses outside the
\par gate. Looking about him while in this state of suspense, Charles
\par Darnay observed that the gate was held by a mixed guard of soldiers and
\par patriots, the latter far outnumbering the former; and that while ingress
\par into the city for peasants' carts bringing in supplies, and for similar
\par traffic and traffickers, was easy enough, egress, even for the homeliest
\par people, was very difficult. A numerous medley of men and women, not
\par to mention beasts and vehicles of various sorts, was waiting to issue
\par forth; but, the previous identification was so strict, that they
\par filtered through the barrier very slowly. Some of these people knew
\par their turn for examination to be so far off, that they lay down on the
\par ground to sleep or smoke, while others talked together, or loitered
\par about. The red cap and tri-colour cockade were universal, both among men
\par and women.
\par 
\par When he had sat in his saddle some half-hour, taking note of these
\par things, Darnay found himself confronted by the same man in authority,
\par who directed the guard to open the barrier. Then he delivered to the
\par escort, drunk and sober, a receipt for the escorted, and requested him
\par to dismount. He did so, and the two patriots, leading his tired horse,
\par turned and rode away without entering the city.
\par 
\par He accompanied his conductor into a guard-room, smelling of common wine
\par and tobacco, where certain soldiers and patriots, asleep and awake,
\par drunk and sober, and in various neutral states between sleeping and
\par waking, drunkenness and sobriety, were standing and lying about. The
\par light in the guard-house, half derived from the waning oil-lamps of
\par the night, and half from the overcast day, was in a correspondingly
\par uncertain condition. Some registers were lying open on a desk, and an
\par officer of a coarse, dark aspect, presided over these.
\par 
\par "Citizen Defarge," said he to Darnay's conductor, as he took a slip of
\par paper to write on. "Is this the emigrant Evremonde?"
\par 
\par "This is the man."
\par 
\par "Your age, Evremonde?"
\par 
\par "Thirty-seven."
\par 
\par "Married, Evremonde?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "Where married?"
\par 
\par "In England."
\par 
\par "Without doubt. Where is your wife, Evremonde?"
\par 
\par "In England."
\par 
\par "Without doubt. You are consigned, Evremonde, to the prison of La
\par Force."
\par 
\par "Just Heaven!" exclaimed Darnay. "Under what law, and for what offence?"
\par 
\par The officer looked up from his slip of paper for a moment.
\par 
\par "We have new laws, Evremonde, and new offences, since you were here." He
\par said it with a hard smile, and went on writing.
\par 
\par "I entreat you to observe that I have come here voluntarily, in response
\par to that written appeal of a fellow-countryman which lies before you. I
\par demand no more than the opportunity to do so without delay. Is not that
\par my right?"
\par 
\par "Emigrants have no rights, Evremonde," was the stolid reply. The officer
\par wrote until he had finished, read over to himself what he had written,
\par sanded it, and handed it to Defarge, with the words "In secret."
\par 
\par Defarge motioned with the paper to the prisoner that he must accompany
\par him. The prisoner obeyed, and a guard of two armed patriots attended
\par them.
\par 
\par "Is it you," said Defarge, in a low voice, as they went down the
\par guardhouse steps and turned into Paris, "who married the daughter of
\par Doctor Manette, once a prisoner in the Bastille that is no more?"
\par 
\par "Yes," replied Darnay, looking at him with surprise.
\par 
\par "My name is Defarge, and I keep a wine-shop in the Quarter Saint
\par Antoine. Possibly you have heard of me."
\par 
\par "My wife came to your house to reclaim her father? Yes!"
\par 
\par The word "wife" seemed to serve as a gloomy reminder to Defarge, to say
\par with sudden impatience, "In the name of that sharp female newly-born,
\par and called La Guillotine, why did you come to France?"
\par 
\par "You heard me say why, a minute ago. Do you not believe it is the
\par truth?"
\par 
\par "A bad truth for you," said Defarge, speaking with knitted brows, and
\par looking straight before him.
\par 
\par "Indeed I am lost here. All here is so unprecedented, so changed, so
\par sudden and unfair, that I am absolutely lost. Will you render me a
\par little help?"
\par 
\par "None." Defarge spoke, always looking straight before him.
\par 
\par "Will you answer me a single question?"
\par 
\par "Perhaps. According to its nature. You can say what it is."
\par 
\par "In this prison that I am going to so unjustly, shall I have some free
\par communication with the world outside?"
\par 
\par "You will see."
\par 
\par "I am not to be buried there, prejudged, and without any means of
\par presenting my case?"
\par 
\par "You will see. But, what then? Other people have been similarly buried
\par in worse prisons, before now."
\par 
\par "But never by me, Citizen Defarge."
\par 
\par Defarge glanced darkly at him for answer, and walked on in a steady
\par and set silence. The deeper he sank into this silence, the fainter hope
\par there was--or so Darnay thought--of his softening in any slight degree.
\par He, therefore, made haste to say:
\par 
\par "It is of the utmost importance to me (you know, Citizen, even better
\par than I, of how much importance), that I should be able to communicate to
\par Mr. Lorry of Tellson's Bank, an English gentleman who is now in Paris,
\par the simple fact, without comment, that I have been thrown into the
\par prison of La Force. Will you cause that to be done for me?"
\par 
\par "I will do," Defarge doggedly rejoined, "nothing for you. My duty is to
\par my country and the People. I am the sworn servant of both, against you.
\par I will do nothing for you."
\par 
\par Charles Darnay felt it hopeless to entreat him further, and his pride
\par was touched besides. As they walked on in silence, he could not but see
\par how used the people were to the spectacle of prisoners passing along the
\par streets. The very children scarcely noticed him. A few passers turned
\par their heads, and a few shook their fingers at him as an aristocrat;
\par otherwise, that a man in good clothes should be going to prison, was no
\par more remarkable than that a labourer in working clothes should be
\par going to work. In one narrow, dark, and dirty street through which they
\par passed, an excited orator, mounted on a stool, was addressing an excited
\par audience on the crimes against the people, of the king and the royal
\par family. The few words that he caught from this man's lips, first made
\par it known to Charles Darnay that the king was in prison, and that the
\par foreign ambassadors had one and all left Paris. On the road (except at
\par Beauvais) he had heard absolutely nothing. The escort and the universal
\par watchfulness had completely isolated him.
\par 
\par That he had fallen among far greater dangers than those which had
\par developed themselves when he left England, he of course knew now. That
\par perils had thickened about him fast, and might thicken faster and faster
\par yet, he of course knew now. He could not but admit to himself that he
\par might not have made this journey, if he could have foreseen the events
\par of a few days. And yet his misgivings were not so dark as, imagined by
\par the light of this later time, they would appear. Troubled as the future
\par was, it was the unknown future, and in its obscurity there was ignorant
\par hope. The horrible massacre, days and nights long, which, within a few
\par rounds of the clock, was to set a great mark of blood upon the blessed
\par garnering time of harvest, was as far out of his knowledge as if it had
\par been a hundred thousand years away. The "sharp female newly-born, and
\par called La Guillotine," was hardly known to him, or to the generality
\par of people, by name. The frightful deeds that were to be soon done, were
\par probably unimagined at that time in the brains of the doers. How could
\par they have a place in the shadowy conceptions of a gentle mind?
\par 
\par Of unjust treatment in detention and hardship, and in cruel separation
\par from his wife and child, he foreshadowed the likelihood, or the
\par certainty; but, beyond this, he dreaded nothing distinctly. With this on
\par his mind, which was enough to carry into a dreary prison courtyard, he
\par arrived at the prison of La Force.
\par 
\par A man with a bloated face opened the strong wicket, to whom Defarge
\par presented "The Emigrant Evremonde."
\par 
\par "What the Devil! How many more of them!" exclaimed the man with the
\par bloated face.
\par 
\par Defarge took his receipt without noticing the exclamation, and withdrew,
\par with his two fellow-patriots.
\par 
\par "What the Devil, I say again!" exclaimed the gaoler, left with his wife.
\par "How many more!"
\par 
\par The gaoler's wife, being provided with no answer to the question, merely
\par replied, "One must have patience, my dear!" Three turnkeys who entered
\par responsive to a bell she rang, echoed the sentiment, and one added, "For
\par the love of Liberty;" which sounded in that place like an inappropriate
\par conclusion.
\par 
\par The prison of La Force was a gloomy prison, dark and filthy, and with a
\par horrible smell of foul sleep in it. Extraordinary how soon the noisome
\par flavour of imprisoned sleep, becomes manifest in all such places that
\par are ill cared for!
\par 
\par "In secret, too," grumbled the gaoler, looking at the written paper. "As
\par if I was not already full to bursting!"
\par 
\par He stuck the paper on a file, in an ill-humour, and Charles Darnay
\par awaited his further pleasure for half an hour: sometimes, pacing to and
\par fro in the strong arched room: sometimes, resting on a stone seat: in
\par either case detained to be imprinted on the memory of the chief and his
\par subordinates.
\par 
\par "Come!" said the chief, at length taking up his keys, "come with me,
\par emigrant."
\par 
\par Through the dismal prison twilight, his new charge accompanied him by
\par corridor and staircase, many doors clanging and locking behind them,
\par until they came into a large, low, vaulted chamber, crowded with
\par prisoners of both sexes. The women were seated at a long table, reading
\par and writing, knitting, sewing, and embroidering; the men were for the
\par most part standing behind their chairs, or lingering up and down the
\par room.
\par 
\par In the instinctive association of prisoners with shameful crime and
\par disgrace, the new-comer recoiled from this company. But the crowning
\par unreality of his long unreal ride, was, their all at once rising to
\par receive him, with every refinement of manner known to the time, and with
\par all the engaging graces and courtesies of life.
\par 
\par So strangely clouded were these refinements by the prison manners and
\par gloom, so spectral did they become in the inappropriate squalor and
\par misery through which they were seen, that Charles Darnay seemed to stand
\par in a company of the dead. Ghosts all! The ghost of beauty, the ghost
\par of stateliness, the ghost of elegance, the ghost of pride, the ghost of
\par frivolity, the ghost of wit, the ghost of youth, the ghost of age, all
\par waiting their dismissal from the desolate shore, all turning on him eyes
\par that were changed by the death they had died in coming there.
\par 
\par It struck him motionless. The gaoler standing at his side, and the other
\par gaolers moving about, who would have been well enough as to appearance
\par in the ordinary exercise of their functions, looked so extravagantly
\par coarse contrasted with sorrowing mothers and blooming daughters who were
\par there--with the apparitions of the coquette, the young beauty, and the
\par mature woman delicately bred--that the inversion of all experience and
\par likelihood which the scene of shadows presented, was heightened to its
\par utmost. Surely, ghosts all. Surely, the long unreal ride some progress
\par of disease that had brought him to these gloomy shades!
\par 
\par "In the name of the assembled companions in misfortune," said a
\par gentleman of courtly appearance and address, coming forward, "I have the
\par honour of giving you welcome to La Force, and of condoling with you
\par on the calamity that has brought you among us. May it soon terminate
\par happily! It would be an impertinence elsewhere, but it is not so here,
\par to ask your name and condition?"
\par 
\par Charles Darnay roused himself, and gave the required information, in
\par words as suitable as he could find.
\par 
\par "But I hope," said the gentleman, following the chief gaoler with his
\par eyes, who moved across the room, "that you are not in secret?"
\par 
\par "I do not understand the meaning of the term, but I have heard them say
\par so."
\par 
\par "Ah, what a pity! We so much regret it! But take courage; several
\par members of our society have been in secret, at first, and it has lasted
\par but a short time." Then he added, raising his voice, "I grieve to inform
\par the society--in secret."
\par 
\par There was a murmur of commiseration as Charles Darnay crossed the room
\par to a grated door where the gaoler awaited him, and many voices--among
\par which, the soft and compassionate voices of women were conspicuous--gave
\par him good wishes and encouragement. He turned at the grated door, to
\par render the thanks of his heart; it closed under the gaoler's hand; and
\par the apparitions vanished from his sight forever.
\par 
\par The wicket opened on a stone staircase, leading upward. When they had
\par ascended forty steps (the prisoner of half an hour already counted
\par them), the gaoler opened a low black door, and they passed into a
\par solitary cell. It struck cold and damp, but was not dark.
\par 
\par "Yours," said the gaoler.
\par 
\par "Why am I confined alone?"
\par 
\par "How do I know!"
\par 
\par "I can buy pen, ink, and paper?"
\par 
\par "Such are not my orders. You will be visited, and can ask then. At
\par present, you may buy your food, and nothing more."
\par 
\par There were in the cell, a chair, a table, and a straw mattress. As
\par the gaoler made a general inspection of these objects, and of the four
\par walls, before going out, a wandering fancy wandered through the mind of
\par the prisoner leaning against the wall opposite to him, that this gaoler
\par was so unwholesomely bloated, both in face and person, as to look like
\par a man who had been drowned and filled with water. When the gaoler was
\par gone, he thought in the same wandering way, "Now am I left, as if I were
\par dead." Stopping then, to look down at the mattress, he turned from it
\par with a sick feeling, and thought, "And here in these crawling creatures
\par is the first condition of the body after death."
\par 
\par "Five paces by four and a half, five paces by four and a half, five
\par paces by four and a half." The prisoner walked to and fro in his cell,
\par counting its measurement, and the roar of the city arose like muffled
\par drums with a wild swell of voices added to them. "He made shoes, he made
\par shoes, he made shoes." The prisoner counted the measurement again, and
\par paced faster, to draw his mind with him from that latter repetition.
\par "The ghosts that vanished when the wicket closed. There was one among
\par them, the appearance of a lady dressed in black, who was leaning in the
\par embrasure of a window, and she had a light shining upon her golden
\par hair, and she looked like * * * * Let us ride on again, for God's sake,
\par through the illuminated villages with the people all awake! * * * * He
\par made shoes, he made shoes, he made shoes. * * * * Five paces by four and
\par a half." With such scraps tossing and rolling upward from the depths of
\par his mind, the prisoner walked faster and faster, obstinately counting
\par and counting; and the roar of the city changed to this extent--that it
\par still rolled in like muffled drums, but with the wail of voices that he
\par knew, in the swell that rose above them.
\par 
