\par 
\par 
\par II. The Grindstone
\par 
\par 
\par Tellson's Bank, established in the Saint Germain Quarter of Paris, was
\par in a wing of a large house, approached by a courtyard and shut off from
\par the street by a high wall and a strong gate. The house belonged to
\par a great nobleman who had lived in it until he made a flight from the
\par troubles, in his own cook's dress, and got across the borders. A
\par mere beast of the chase flying from hunters, he was still in his
\par metempsychosis no other than the same Monseigneur, the preparation
\par of whose chocolate for whose lips had once occupied three strong men
\par besides the cook in question.
\par 
\par Monseigneur gone, and the three strong men absolving themselves from the
\par sin of having drawn his high wages, by being more than ready and
\par willing to cut his throat on the altar of the dawning Republic one and
\par indivisible of Liberty, Equality, Fraternity, or Death, Monseigneur's
\par house had been first sequestrated, and then confiscated. For, all
\par things moved so fast, and decree followed decree with that fierce
\par precipitation, that now upon the third night of the autumn month
\par of September, patriot emissaries of the law were in possession of
\par Monseigneur's house, and had marked it with the tri-colour, and were
\par drinking brandy in its state apartments.
\par 
\par A place of business in London like Tellson's place of business in Paris,
\par would soon have driven the House out of its mind and into the Gazette.
\par For, what would staid British responsibility and respectability have
\par said to orange-trees in boxes in a Bank courtyard, and even to a Cupid
\par over the counter? Yet such things were. Tellson's had whitewashed the
\par Cupid, but he was still to be seen on the ceiling, in the coolest
\par linen, aiming (as he very often does) at money from morning to
\par night. Bankruptcy must inevitably have come of this young Pagan, in
\par Lombard-street, London, and also of a curtained alcove in the rear of
\par the immortal boy, and also of a looking-glass let into the wall, and
\par also of clerks not at all old, who danced in public on the slightest
\par provocation. Yet, a French Tellson's could get on with these things
\par exceedingly well, and, as long as the times held together, no man had
\par taken fright at them, and drawn out his money.
\par 
\par What money would be drawn out of Tellson's henceforth, and what would
\par lie there, lost and forgotten; what plate and jewels would tarnish in
\par Tellson's hiding-places, while the depositors rusted in prisons,
\par and when they should have violently perished; how many accounts with
\par Tellson's never to be balanced in this world, must be carried over into
\par the next; no man could have said, that night, any more than Mr. Jarvis
\par Lorry could, though he thought heavily of these questions. He sat by
\par a newly-lighted wood fire (the blighted and unfruitful year was
\par prematurely cold), and on his honest and courageous face there was a
\par deeper shade than the pendent lamp could throw, or any object in the
\par room distortedly reflect--a shade of horror.
\par 
\par He occupied rooms in the Bank, in his fidelity to the House of which
\par he had grown to be a part, like strong root-ivy. It chanced that they
\par derived a kind of security from the patriotic occupation of the main
\par building, but the true-hearted old gentleman never calculated about
\par that. All such circumstances were indifferent to him, so that he did
\par his duty. On the opposite side of the courtyard, under a colonnade,
\par was extensive standing--for carriages--where, indeed, some carriages
\par of Monseigneur yet stood. Against two of the pillars were fastened two
\par great flaring flambeaux, and in the light of these, standing out in the
\par open air, was a large grindstone: a roughly mounted thing which appeared
\par to have hurriedly been brought there from some neighbouring smithy,
\par or other workshop. Rising and looking out of window at these harmless
\par objects, Mr. Lorry shivered, and retired to his seat by the fire. He had
\par opened, not only the glass window, but the lattice blind outside it, and
\par he had closed both again, and he shivered through his frame.
\par 
\par From the streets beyond the high wall and the strong gate, there came
\par the usual night hum of the city, with now and then an indescribable ring
\par in it, weird and unearthly, as if some unwonted sounds of a terrible
\par nature were going up to Heaven.
\par 
\par "Thank God," said Mr. Lorry, clasping his hands, "that no one near and
\par dear to me is in this dreadful town to-night. May He have mercy on all
\par who are in danger!"
\par 
\par Soon afterwards, the bell at the great gate sounded, and he thought,
\par "They have come back!" and sat listening. But, there was no loud
\par irruption into the courtyard, as he had expected, and he heard the gate
\par clash again, and all was quiet.
\par 
\par The nervousness and dread that were upon him inspired that vague
\par uneasiness respecting the Bank, which a great change would naturally
\par awaken, with such feelings roused. It was well guarded, and he got up to
\par go among the trusty people who were watching it, when his door suddenly
\par opened, and two figures rushed in, at sight of which he fell back in
\par amazement.
\par 
\par Lucie and her father! Lucie with her arms stretched out to him, and with
\par that old look of earnestness so concentrated and intensified, that it
\par seemed as though it had been stamped upon her face expressly to give
\par force and power to it in this one passage of her life.
\par 
\par "What is this?" cried Mr. Lorry, breathless and confused. "What is the
\par matter? Lucie! Manette! What has happened? What has brought you here?
\par What is it?"
\par 
\par With the look fixed upon him, in her paleness and wildness, she panted
\par out in his arms, imploringly, "O my dear friend! My husband!"
\par 
\par "Your husband, Lucie?"
\par 
\par "Charles."
\par 
\par "What of Charles?"
\par 
\par "Here.
\par 
\par "Here, in Paris?"
\par 
\par "Has been here some days--three or four--I don't know how many--I can't
\par collect my thoughts. An errand of generosity brought him here unknown to
\par us; he was stopped at the barrier, and sent to prison."
\par 
\par The old man uttered an irrepressible cry. Almost at the same moment, the
\par bell of the great gate rang again, and a loud noise of feet and voices
\par came pouring into the courtyard.
\par 
\par "What is that noise?" said the Doctor, turning towards the window.
\par 
\par "Don't look!" cried Mr. Lorry. "Don't look out! Manette, for your life,
\par don't touch the blind!"
\par 
\par The Doctor turned, with his hand upon the fastening of the window, and
\par said, with a cool, bold smile:
\par 
\par "My dear friend, I have a charmed life in this city. I have been
\par a Bastille prisoner. There is no patriot in Paris--in Paris? In
\par France--who, knowing me to have been a prisoner in the Bastille, would
\par touch me, except to overwhelm me with embraces, or carry me in triumph.
\par My old pain has given me a power that has brought us through the
\par barrier, and gained us news of Charles there, and brought us here. I
\par knew it would be so; I knew I could help Charles out of all danger; I
\par told Lucie so.--What is that noise?" His hand was again upon the window.
\par 
\par "Don't look!" cried Mr. Lorry, absolutely desperate. "No, Lucie, my
\par dear, nor you!" He got his arm round her, and held her. "Don't be so
\par terrified, my love. I solemnly swear to you that I know of no harm
\par having happened to Charles; that I had no suspicion even of his being in
\par this fatal place. What prison is he in?"
\par 
\par "La Force!"
\par 
\par "La Force! Lucie, my child, if ever you were brave and serviceable in
\par your life--and you were always both--you will compose yourself now, to
\par do exactly as I bid you; for more depends upon it than you can think, or
\par I can say. There is no help for you in any action on your part to-night;
\par you cannot possibly stir out. I say this, because what I must bid you
\par to do for Charles's sake, is the hardest thing to do of all. You must
\par instantly be obedient, still, and quiet. You must let me put you in a
\par room at the back here. You must leave your father and me alone for
\par two minutes, and as there are Life and Death in the world you must not
\par delay."
\par 
\par "I will be submissive to you. I see in your face that you know I can do
\par nothing else than this. I know you are true."
\par 
\par The old man kissed her, and hurried her into his room, and turned the
\par key; then, came hurrying back to the Doctor, and opened the window and
\par partly opened the blind, and put his hand upon the Doctor's arm, and
\par looked out with him into the courtyard.
\par 
\par Looked out upon a throng of men and women: not enough in number, or near
\par enough, to fill the courtyard: not more than forty or fifty in all. The
\par people in possession of the house had let them in at the gate, and they
\par had rushed in to work at the grindstone; it had evidently been set up
\par there for their purpose, as in a convenient and retired spot.
\par 
\par But, such awful workers, and such awful work!
\par 
\par The grindstone had a double handle, and, turning at it madly were two
\par men, whose faces, as their long hair flapped back when the whirlings of
\par the grindstone brought their faces up, were more horrible and cruel than
\par the visages of the wildest savages in their most barbarous disguise.
\par False eyebrows and false moustaches were stuck upon them, and their
\par hideous countenances were all bloody and sweaty, and all awry with
\par howling, and all staring and glaring with beastly excitement and want of
\par sleep. As these ruffians turned and turned, their matted locks now flung
\par forward over their eyes, now flung backward over their necks, some women
\par held wine to their mouths that they might drink; and what with dropping
\par blood, and what with dropping wine, and what with the stream of sparks
\par struck out of the stone, all their wicked atmosphere seemed gore and
\par fire. The eye could not detect one creature in the group free from
\par the smear of blood. Shouldering one another to get next at the
\par sharpening-stone, were men stripped to the waist, with the stain all
\par over their limbs and bodies; men in all sorts of rags, with the stain
\par upon those rags; men devilishly set off with spoils of women's lace
\par and silk and ribbon, with the stain dyeing those trifles through
\par and through. Hatchets, knives, bayonets, swords, all brought to be
\par sharpened, were all red with it. Some of the hacked swords were tied to
\par the wrists of those who carried them, with strips of linen and fragments
\par of dress: ligatures various in kind, but all deep of the one colour. And
\par as the frantic wielders of these weapons snatched them from the stream
\par of sparks and tore away into the streets, the same red hue was red in
\par their frenzied eyes;--eyes which any unbrutalised beholder would have
\par given twenty years of life, to petrify with a well-directed gun.
\par 
\par All this was seen in a moment, as the vision of a drowning man, or of
\par any human creature at any very great pass, could see a world if it
\par were there. They drew back from the window, and the Doctor looked for
\par explanation in his friend's ashy face.
\par 
\par "They are," Mr. Lorry whispered the words, glancing fearfully round at
\par the locked room, "murdering the prisoners. If you are sure of what you
\par say; if you really have the power you think you have--as I believe you
\par have--make yourself known to these devils, and get taken to La Force. It
\par may be too late, I don't know, but let it not be a minute later!"
\par 
\par Doctor Manette pressed his hand, hastened bareheaded out of the room,
\par and was in the courtyard when Mr. Lorry regained the blind.
\par 
\par His streaming white hair, his remarkable face, and the impetuous
\par confidence of his manner, as he put the weapons aside like water,
\par carried him in an instant to the heart of the concourse at the stone.
\par For a few moments there was a pause, and a hurry, and a murmur, and
\par the unintelligible sound of his voice; and then Mr. Lorry saw him,
\par surrounded by all, and in the midst of a line of twenty men long, all
\par linked shoulder to shoulder, and hand to shoulder, hurried out with
\par cries of--"Live the Bastille prisoner! Help for the Bastille prisoner's
\par kindred in La Force! Room for the Bastille prisoner in front there! Save
\par the prisoner Evremonde at La Force!" and a thousand answering shouts.
\par 
\par He closed the lattice again with a fluttering heart, closed the window
\par and the curtain, hastened to Lucie, and told her that her father was
\par assisted by the people, and gone in search of her husband. He found
\par her child and Miss Pross with her; but, it never occurred to him to be
\par surprised by their appearance until a long time afterwards, when he sat
\par watching them in such quiet as the night knew.
\par 
\par Lucie had, by that time, fallen into a stupor on the floor at his feet,
\par clinging to his hand. Miss Pross had laid the child down on his own
\par bed, and her head had gradually fallen on the pillow beside her pretty
\par charge. O the long, long night, with the moans of the poor wife! And O
\par the long, long night, with no return of her father and no tidings!
\par 
\par Twice more in the darkness the bell at the great gate sounded, and the
\par irruption was repeated, and the grindstone whirled and spluttered.
\par "What is it?" cried Lucie, affrighted. "Hush! The soldiers' swords are
\par sharpened there," said Mr. Lorry. "The place is national property now,
\par and used as a kind of armoury, my love."
\par 
\par Twice more in all; but, the last spell of work was feeble and fitful.
\par Soon afterwards the day began to dawn, and he softly detached himself
\par from the clasping hand, and cautiously looked out again. A man, so
\par besmeared that he might have been a sorely wounded soldier creeping back
\par to consciousness on a field of slain, was rising from the pavement by
\par the side of the grindstone, and looking about him with a vacant air.
\par Shortly, this worn-out murderer descried in the imperfect light one of
\par the carriages of Monseigneur, and, staggering to that gorgeous vehicle,
\par climbed in at the door, and shut himself up to take his rest on its
\par dainty cushions.
\par 
\par The great grindstone, Earth, had turned when Mr. Lorry looked out again,
\par and the sun was red on the courtyard. But, the lesser grindstone stood
\par alone there in the calm morning air, with a red upon it that the sun had
\par never given, and would never take away.
\par 
