\par 
\par III. The Shadow
\par 
\par 
\par One of the first considerations which arose in the business mind of Mr.
\par Lorry when business hours came round, was this:--that he had no right to
\par imperil Tellson's by sheltering the wife of an emigrant prisoner under
\par the Bank roof. His own possessions, safety, life, he would have hazarded
\par for Lucie and her child, without a moment's demur; but the great trust
\par he held was not his own, and as to that business charge he was a strict
\par man of business.
\par 
\par At first, his mind reverted to Defarge, and he thought of finding out
\par the wine-shop again and taking counsel with its master in reference to
\par the safest dwelling-place in the distracted state of the city. But, the
\par same consideration that suggested him, repudiated him; he lived in the
\par most violent Quarter, and doubtless was influential there, and deep in
\par its dangerous workings.
\par 
\par Noon coming, and the Doctor not returning, and every minute's delay
\par tending to compromise Tellson's, Mr. Lorry advised with Lucie. She said
\par that her father had spoken of hiring a lodging for a short term, in that
\par Quarter, near the Banking-house. As there was no business objection to
\par this, and as he foresaw that even if it were all well with Charles, and
\par he were to be released, he could not hope to leave the city, Mr. Lorry
\par went out in quest of such a lodging, and found a suitable one, high up
\par in a removed by-street where the closed blinds in all the other windows
\par of a high melancholy square of buildings marked deserted homes.
\par 
\par To this lodging he at once removed Lucie and her child, and Miss Pross:
\par giving them what comfort he could, and much more than he had himself.
\par He left Jerry with them, as a figure to fill a doorway that would bear
\par considerable knocking on the head, and returned to his own occupations.
\par A disturbed and doleful mind he brought to bear upon them, and slowly
\par and heavily the day lagged on with him.
\par 
\par It wore itself out, and wore him out with it, until the Bank closed. He
\par was again alone in his room of the previous night, considering what to
\par do next, when he heard a foot upon the stair. In a few moments, a
\par man stood in his presence, who, with a keenly observant look at him,
\par addressed him by his name.
\par 
\par "Your servant," said Mr. Lorry. "Do you know me?"
\par 
\par He was a strongly made man with dark curling hair, from forty-five
\par to fifty years of age. For answer he repeated, without any change of
\par emphasis, the words:
\par 
\par "Do you know me?"
\par 
\par "I have seen you somewhere."
\par 
\par "Perhaps at my wine-shop?"
\par 
\par Much interested and agitated, Mr. Lorry said: "You come from Doctor
\par Manette?"
\par 
\par "Yes. I come from Doctor Manette."
\par 
\par "And what says he? What does he send me?"
\par 
\par Defarge gave into his anxious hand, an open scrap of paper. It bore the
\par words in the Doctor's writing:
\par 
\par     "Charles is safe, but I cannot safely leave this place yet.
\par      I have obtained the favour that the bearer has a short note
\par      from Charles to his wife.  Let the bearer see his wife."
\par 
\par It was dated from La Force, within an hour.
\par 
\par "Will you accompany me," said Mr. Lorry, joyfully relieved after reading
\par this note aloud, "to where his wife resides?"
\par 
\par "Yes," returned Defarge.
\par 
\par Scarcely noticing as yet, in what a curiously reserved and mechanical
\par way Defarge spoke, Mr. Lorry put on his hat and they went down into the
\par courtyard. There, they found two women; one, knitting.
\par 
\par "Madame Defarge, surely!" said Mr. Lorry, who had left her in exactly
\par the same attitude some seventeen years ago.
\par 
\par "It is she," observed her husband.
\par 
\par "Does Madame go with us?" inquired Mr. Lorry, seeing that she moved as
\par they moved.
\par 
\par "Yes. That she may be able to recognise the faces and know the persons.
\par It is for their safety."
\par 
\par Beginning to be struck by Defarge's manner, Mr. Lorry looked dubiously
\par at him, and led the way. Both the women followed; the second woman being
\par The Vengeance.
\par 
\par They passed through the intervening streets as quickly as they might,
\par ascended the staircase of the new domicile, were admitted by Jerry,
\par and found Lucie weeping, alone. She was thrown into a transport by the
\par tidings Mr. Lorry gave her of her husband, and clasped the hand that
\par delivered his note--little thinking what it had been doing near him in
\par the night, and might, but for a chance, have done to him.
\par 
\par      "DEAREST,--Take courage.  I am well, and your father has
\par       influence around me.  You cannot answer this.
\par       Kiss our child for me."
\par 
\par That was all the writing. It was so much, however, to her who received
\par it, that she turned from Defarge to his wife, and kissed one of the
\par hands that knitted. It was a passionate, loving, thankful, womanly
\par action, but the hand made no response--dropped cold and heavy, and took
\par to its knitting again.
\par 
\par There was something in its touch that gave Lucie a check. She stopped in
\par the act of putting the note in her bosom, and, with her hands yet at her
\par neck, looked terrified at Madame Defarge. Madame Defarge met the lifted
\par eyebrows and forehead with a cold, impassive stare.
\par 
\par "My dear," said Mr. Lorry, striking in to explain; "there are frequent
\par risings in the streets; and, although it is not likely they will ever
\par trouble you, Madame Defarge wishes to see those whom she has the power
\par to protect at such times, to the end that she may know them--that she
\par may identify them. I believe," said Mr. Lorry, rather halting in his
\par reassuring words, as the stony manner of all the three impressed itself
\par upon him more and more, "I state the case, Citizen Defarge?"
\par 
\par Defarge looked gloomily at his wife, and gave no other answer than a
\par gruff sound of acquiescence.
\par 
\par "You had better, Lucie," said Mr. Lorry, doing all he could to
\par propitiate, by tone and manner, "have the dear child here, and our
\par good Pross. Our good Pross, Defarge, is an English lady, and knows no
\par French."
\par 
\par The lady in question, whose rooted conviction that she was more than a
\par match for any foreigner, was not to be shaken by distress and, danger,
\par appeared with folded arms, and observed in English to The Vengeance,
\par whom her eyes first encountered, "Well, I am sure, Boldface! I hope
\par _you_ are pretty well!" She also bestowed a British cough on Madame
\par Defarge; but, neither of the two took much heed of her.
\par 
\par "Is that his child?" said Madame Defarge, stopping in her work for the
\par first time, and pointing her knitting-needle at little Lucie as if it
\par were the finger of Fate.
\par 
\par "Yes, madame," answered Mr. Lorry; "this is our poor prisoner's darling
\par daughter, and only child."
\par 
\par The shadow attendant on Madame Defarge and her party seemed to fall so
\par threatening and dark on the child, that her mother instinctively
\par kneeled on the ground beside her, and held her to her breast. The
\par shadow attendant on Madame Defarge and her party seemed then to fall,
\par threatening and dark, on both the mother and the child.
\par 
\par "It is enough, my husband," said Madame Defarge. "I have seen them. We
\par may go."
\par 
\par But, the suppressed manner had enough of menace in it--not visible and
\par presented, but indistinct and withheld--to alarm Lucie into saying, as
\par she laid her appealing hand on Madame Defarge's dress:
\par 
\par "You will be good to my poor husband. You will do him no harm. You will
\par help me to see him if you can?"
\par 
\par "Your husband is not my business here," returned Madame Defarge, looking
\par down at her with perfect composure. "It is the daughter of your father
\par who is my business here."
\par 
\par "For my sake, then, be merciful to my husband. For my child's sake! She
\par will put her hands together and pray you to be merciful. We are more
\par afraid of you than of these others."
\par 
\par Madame Defarge received it as a compliment, and looked at her husband.
\par Defarge, who had been uneasily biting his thumb-nail and looking at her,
\par collected his face into a sterner expression.
\par 
\par "What is it that your husband says in that little letter?" asked Madame
\par Defarge, with a lowering smile. "Influence; he says something touching
\par influence?"
\par 
\par "That my father," said Lucie, hurriedly taking the paper from her
\par breast, but with her alarmed eyes on her questioner and not on it, "has
\par much influence around him."
\par 
\par "Surely it will release him!" said Madame Defarge. "Let it do so."
\par 
\par "As a wife and mother," cried Lucie, most earnestly, "I implore you to
\par have pity on me and not to exercise any power that you possess, against
\par my innocent husband, but to use it in his behalf. O sister-woman, think
\par of me. As a wife and mother!"
\par 
\par Madame Defarge looked, coldly as ever, at the suppliant, and said,
\par turning to her friend The Vengeance:
\par 
\par "The wives and mothers we have been used to see, since we were as little
\par as this child, and much less, have not been greatly considered? We have
\par known _their_ husbands and fathers laid in prison and kept from them,
\par often enough? All our lives, we have seen our sister-women suffer, in
\par themselves and in their children, poverty, nakedness, hunger, thirst,
\par sickness, misery, oppression and neglect of all kinds?"
\par 
\par "We have seen nothing else," returned The Vengeance.
\par 
\par "We have borne this a long time," said Madame Defarge, turning her eyes
\par again upon Lucie. "Judge you! Is it likely that the trouble of one wife
\par and mother would be much to us now?"
\par 
\par She resumed her knitting and went out. The Vengeance followed. Defarge
\par went last, and closed the door.
\par 
\par "Courage, my dear Lucie," said Mr. Lorry, as he raised her. "Courage,
\par courage! So far all goes well with us--much, much better than it has of
\par late gone with many poor souls. Cheer up, and have a thankful heart."
\par 
\par "I am not thankless, I hope, but that dreadful woman seems to throw a
\par shadow on me and on all my hopes."
\par 
\par "Tut, tut!" said Mr. Lorry; "what is this despondency in the brave
\par little breast? A shadow indeed! No substance in it, Lucie."
\par 
\par But the shadow of the manner of these Defarges was dark upon himself,
\par for all that, and in his secret mind it troubled him greatly.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par IV. Calm in Storm
\par 
\par 
\par Doctor Manette did not return until the morning of the fourth day of his
\par absence. So much of what had happened in that dreadful time as could be
\par kept from the knowledge of Lucie was so well concealed from her, that
\par not until long afterwards, when France and she were far apart, did she
\par know that eleven hundred defenceless prisoners of both sexes and all
\par ages had been killed by the populace; that four days and nights had been
\par darkened by this deed of horror; and that the air around her had been
\par tainted by the slain. She only knew that there had been an attack upon
\par the prisons, that all political prisoners had been in danger, and that
\par some had been dragged out by the crowd and murdered.
\par 
\par To Mr. Lorry, the Doctor communicated under an injunction of secrecy on
\par which he had no need to dwell, that the crowd had taken him through a
\par scene of carnage to the prison of La Force. That, in the prison he had
\par found a self-appointed Tribunal sitting, before which the prisoners were
\par brought singly, and by which they were rapidly ordered to be put forth
\par to be massacred, or to be released, or (in a few cases) to be sent back
\par to their cells. That, presented by his conductors to this Tribunal, he
\par had announced himself by name and profession as having been for eighteen
\par years a secret and unaccused prisoner in the Bastille; that, one of the
\par body so sitting in judgment had risen and identified him, and that this
\par man was Defarge.
\par 
\par That, hereupon he had ascertained, through the registers on the table,
\par that his son-in-law was among the living prisoners, and had pleaded hard
\par to the Tribunal--of whom some members were asleep and some awake, some
\par dirty with murder and some clean, some sober and some not--for his life
\par and liberty. That, in the first frantic greetings lavished on himself as
\par a notable sufferer under the overthrown system, it had been accorded
\par to him to have Charles Darnay brought before the lawless Court, and
\par examined. That, he seemed on the point of being at once released, when
\par the tide in his favour met with some unexplained check (not intelligible
\par to the Doctor), which led to a few words of secret conference. That,
\par the man sitting as President had then informed Doctor Manette that
\par the prisoner must remain in custody, but should, for his sake, be held
\par inviolate in safe custody. That, immediately, on a signal, the prisoner
\par was removed to the interior of the prison again; but, that he, the
\par Doctor, had then so strongly pleaded for permission to remain and
\par assure himself that his son-in-law was, through no malice or mischance,
\par delivered to the concourse whose murderous yells outside the gate had
\par often drowned the proceedings, that he had obtained the permission, and
\par had remained in that Hall of Blood until the danger was over.
\par 
\par The sights he had seen there, with brief snatches of food and sleep by
\par intervals, shall remain untold. The mad joy over the prisoners who were
\par saved, had astounded him scarcely less than the mad ferocity against
\par those who were cut to pieces. One prisoner there was, he said, who had
\par been discharged into the street free, but at whom a mistaken savage had
\par thrust a pike as he passed out. Being besought to go to him and dress
\par the wound, the Doctor had passed out at the same gate, and had found him
\par in the arms of a company of Samaritans, who were seated on the bodies
\par of their victims. With an inconsistency as monstrous as anything in this
\par awful nightmare, they had helped the healer, and tended the wounded man
\par with the gentlest solicitude--had made a litter for him and escorted him
\par carefully from the spot--had then caught up their weapons and plunged
\par anew into a butchery so dreadful, that the Doctor had covered his eyes
\par with his hands, and swooned away in the midst of it.
\par 
\par As Mr. Lorry received these confidences, and as he watched the face of
\par his friend now sixty-two years of age, a misgiving arose within him that
\par such dread experiences would revive the old danger.
\par 
\par But, he had never seen his friend in his present aspect: he had never
\par at all known him in his present character. For the first time the Doctor
\par felt, now, that his suffering was strength and power. For the first time
\par he felt that in that sharp fire, he had slowly forged the iron which
\par could break the prison door of his daughter's husband, and deliver him.
\par "It all tended to a good end, my friend; it was not mere waste and ruin.
\par As my beloved child was helpful in restoring me to myself, I will be
\par helpful now in restoring the dearest part of herself to her; by the aid
\par of Heaven I will do it!" Thus, Doctor Manette. And when Jarvis Lorry saw
\par the kindled eyes, the resolute face, the calm strong look and bearing
\par of the man whose life always seemed to him to have been stopped, like a
\par clock, for so many years, and then set going again with an energy which
\par had lain dormant during the cessation of its usefulness, he believed.
\par 
\par Greater things than the Doctor had at that time to contend with, would
\par have yielded before his persevering purpose. While he kept himself
\par in his place, as a physician, whose business was with all degrees
\par of mankind, bond and free, rich and poor, bad and good, he used his
\par personal influence so wisely, that he was soon the inspecting physician
\par of three prisons, and among them of La Force. He could now assure Lucie
\par that her husband was no longer confined alone, but was mixed with the
\par general body of prisoners; he saw her husband weekly, and brought sweet
\par messages to her, straight from his lips; sometimes her husband himself
\par sent a letter to her (though never by the Doctor's hand), but she was
\par not permitted to write to him: for, among the many wild suspicions of
\par plots in the prisons, the wildest of all pointed at emigrants who were
\par known to have made friends or permanent connections abroad.
\par 
\par This new life of the Doctor's was an anxious life, no doubt; still, the
\par sagacious Mr. Lorry saw that there was a new sustaining pride in it.
\par Nothing unbecoming tinged the pride; it was a natural and worthy one;
\par but he observed it as a curiosity. The Doctor knew, that up to that
\par time, his imprisonment had been associated in the minds of his daughter
\par and his friend, with his personal affliction, deprivation, and weakness.
\par Now that this was changed, and he knew himself to be invested through
\par that old trial with forces to which they both looked for Charles's
\par ultimate safety and deliverance, he became so far exalted by the change,
\par that he took the lead and direction, and required them as the weak, to
\par trust to him as the strong. The preceding relative positions of himself
\par and Lucie were reversed, yet only as the liveliest gratitude and
\par affection could reverse them, for he could have had no pride but in
\par rendering some service to her who had rendered so much to him. "All
\par curious to see," thought Mr. Lorry, in his amiably shrewd way, "but all
\par natural and right; so, take the lead, my dear friend, and keep it; it
\par couldn't be in better hands."
\par 
\par But, though the Doctor tried hard, and never ceased trying, to get
\par Charles Darnay set at liberty, or at least to get him brought to trial,
\par the public current of the time set too strong and fast for him. The new
\par era began; the king was tried, doomed, and beheaded; the Republic of
\par Liberty, Equality, Fraternity, or Death, declared for victory or death
\par against the world in arms; the black flag waved night and day from the
\par great towers of Notre Dame; three hundred thousand men, summoned to rise
\par against the tyrants of the earth, rose from all the varying soils
\par of France, as if the dragon's teeth had been sown broadcast, and
\par had yielded fruit equally on hill and plain, on rock, in gravel, and
\par alluvial mud, under the bright sky of the South and under the clouds of
\par the North, in fell and forest, in the vineyards and the olive-grounds
\par and among the cropped grass and the stubble of the corn, along the
\par fruitful banks of the broad rivers, and in the sand of the sea-shore.
\par What private solicitude could rear itself against the deluge of the Year
\par One of Liberty--the deluge rising from below, not falling from above,
\par and with the windows of Heaven shut, not opened!
\par 
\par There was no pause, no pity, no peace, no interval of relenting rest, no
\par measurement of time. Though days and nights circled as regularly as when
\par time was young, and the evening and morning were the first day, other
\par count of time there was none. Hold of it was lost in the raging fever
\par of a nation, as it is in the fever of one patient. Now, breaking the
\par unnatural silence of a whole city, the executioner showed the people the
\par head of the king--and now, it seemed almost in the same breath, the
\par head of his fair wife which had had eight weary months of imprisoned
\par widowhood and misery, to turn it grey.
\par 
\par And yet, observing the strange law of contradiction which obtains in
\par all such cases, the time was long, while it flamed by so fast. A
\par revolutionary tribunal in the capital, and forty or fifty thousand
\par revolutionary committees all over the land; a law of the Suspected,
\par which struck away all security for liberty or life, and delivered over
\par any good and innocent person to any bad and guilty one; prisons gorged
\par with people who had committed no offence, and could obtain no hearing;
\par these things became the established order and nature of appointed
\par things, and seemed to be ancient usage before they were many weeks old.
\par Above all, one hideous figure grew as familiar as if it had been before
\par the general gaze from the foundations of the world--the figure of the
\par sharp female called La Guillotine.
\par 
\par It was the popular theme for jests; it was the best cure for headache,
\par it infallibly prevented the hair from turning grey, it imparted a
\par peculiar delicacy to the complexion, it was the National Razor which
\par shaved close: who kissed La Guillotine, looked through the little window
\par and sneezed into the sack. It was the sign of the regeneration of the
\par human race. It superseded the Cross. Models of it were worn on breasts
\par from which the Cross was discarded, and it was bowed down to and
\par believed in where the Cross was denied.
\par 
\par It sheared off heads so many, that it, and the ground it most polluted,
\par were a rotten red. It was taken to pieces, like a toy-puzzle for a young
\par Devil, and was put together again when the occasion wanted it. It hushed
\par the eloquent, struck down the powerful, abolished the beautiful and
\par good. Twenty-two friends of high public mark, twenty-one living and one
\par dead, it had lopped the heads off, in one morning, in as many minutes.
\par The name of the strong man of Old Scripture had descended to the chief
\par functionary who worked it; but, so armed, he was stronger than his
\par namesake, and blinder, and tore away the gates of God's own Temple every
\par day.
\par 
\par Among these terrors, and the brood belonging to them, the Doctor walked
\par with a steady head: confident in his power, cautiously persistent in his
\par end, never doubting that he would save Lucie's husband at last. Yet the
\par current of the time swept by, so strong and deep, and carried the time
\par away so fiercely, that Charles had lain in prison one year and three
\par months when the Doctor was thus steady and confident. So much more
\par wicked and distracted had the Revolution grown in that December month,
\par that the rivers of the South were encumbered with the bodies of the
\par violently drowned by night, and prisoners were shot in lines and squares
\par under the southern wintry sun. Still, the Doctor walked among the
\par terrors with a steady head. No man better known than he, in Paris at
\par that day; no man in a stranger situation. Silent, humane, indispensable
\par in hospital and prison, using his art equally among assassins and
\par victims, he was a man apart. In the exercise of his skill, the
\par appearance and the story of the Bastille Captive removed him from all
\par other men. He was not suspected or brought in question, any more than if
\par he had indeed been recalled to life some eighteen years before, or were
\par a Spirit moving among mortals.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par V. The Wood-Sawyer
\par 
\par 
\par One year and three months. During all that time Lucie was never
\par sure, from hour to hour, but that the Guillotine would strike off her
\par husband's head next day. Every day, through the stony streets, the
\par tumbrils now jolted heavily, filled with Condemned. Lovely girls; bright
\par women, brown-haired, black-haired, and grey; youths; stalwart men and
\par old; gentle born and peasant born; all red wine for La Guillotine, all
\par daily brought into light from the dark cellars of the loathsome prisons,
\par and carried to her through the streets to slake her devouring thirst.
\par Liberty, equality, fraternity, or death;--the last, much the easiest to
\par bestow, O Guillotine!
\par 
\par If the suddenness of her calamity, and the whirling wheels of the time,
\par had stunned the Doctor's daughter into awaiting the result in idle
\par despair, it would but have been with her as it was with many. But, from
\par the hour when she had taken the white head to her fresh young bosom in
\par the garret of Saint Antoine, she had been true to her duties. She was
\par truest to them in the season of trial, as all the quietly loyal and good
\par will always be.
\par 
\par As soon as they were established in their new residence, and her father
\par had entered on the routine of his avocations, she arranged the little
\par household as exactly as if her husband had been there. Everything had
\par its appointed place and its appointed time. Little Lucie she taught,
\par as regularly, as if they had all been united in their English home. The
\par slight devices with which she cheated herself into the show of a belief
\par that they would soon be reunited--the little preparations for his speedy
\par return, the setting aside of his chair and his books--these, and the
\par solemn prayer at night for one dear prisoner especially, among the many
\par unhappy souls in prison and the shadow of death--were almost the only
\par outspoken reliefs of her heavy mind.
\par 
\par She did not greatly alter in appearance. The plain dark dresses, akin to
\par mourning dresses, which she and her child wore, were as neat and as well
\par attended to as the brighter clothes of happy days. She lost her colour,
\par and the old and intent expression was a constant, not an occasional,
\par thing; otherwise, she remained very pretty and comely. Sometimes, at
\par night on kissing her father, she would burst into the grief she had
\par repressed all day, and would say that her sole reliance, under Heaven,
\par was on him. He always resolutely answered: "Nothing can happen to him
\par without my knowledge, and I know that I can save him, Lucie."
\par 
\par They had not made the round of their changed life many weeks, when her
\par father said to her, on coming home one evening:
\par 
\par "My dear, there is an upper window in the prison, to which Charles can
\par sometimes gain access at three in the afternoon. When he can get to
\par it--which depends on many uncertainties and incidents--he might see you
\par in the street, he thinks, if you stood in a certain place that I can
\par show you. But you will not be able to see him, my poor child, and even
\par if you could, it would be unsafe for you to make a sign of recognition."
\par 
\par "O show me the place, my father, and I will go there every day."
\par 
\par From that time, in all weathers, she waited there two hours. As the
\par clock struck two, she was there, and at four she turned resignedly away.
\par When it was not too wet or inclement for her child to be with her, they
\par went together; at other times she was alone; but, she never missed a
\par single day.
\par 
\par It was the dark and dirty corner of a small winding street. The hovel
\par of a cutter of wood into lengths for burning, was the only house at that
\par end; all else was wall. On the third day of her being there, he noticed
\par her.
\par 
\par "Good day, citizeness."
\par 
\par "Good day, citizen."
\par 
\par This mode of address was now prescribed by decree. It had been
\par established voluntarily some time ago, among the more thorough patriots;
\par but, was now law for everybody.
\par 
\par "Walking here again, citizeness?"
\par 
\par "You see me, citizen!"
\par 
\par The wood-sawyer, who was a little man with a redundancy of gesture (he
\par had once been a mender of roads), cast a glance at the prison, pointed
\par at the prison, and putting his ten fingers before his face to represent
\par bars, peeped through them jocosely.
\par 
\par "But it's not my business," said he. And went on sawing his wood.
\par 
\par Next day he was looking out for her, and accosted her the moment she
\par appeared.
\par 
\par "What? Walking here again, citizeness?"
\par 
\par "Yes, citizen."
\par 
\par "Ah! A child too! Your mother, is it not, my little citizeness?"
\par 
\par "Do I say yes, mamma?" whispered little Lucie, drawing close to her.
\par 
\par "Yes, dearest."
\par 
\par "Yes, citizen."
\par 
\par "Ah! But it's not my business. My work is my business. See my saw! I
\par call it my Little Guillotine. La, la, la; La, la, la! And off his head
\par comes!"
\par 
\par The billet fell as he spoke, and he threw it into a basket.
\par 
\par "I call myself the Samson of the firewood guillotine. See here again!
\par Loo, loo, loo; Loo, loo, loo! And off _her_ head comes! Now, a child.
\par Tickle, tickle; Pickle, pickle! And off _its_ head comes. All the
\par family!"
\par 
\par Lucie shuddered as he threw two more billets into his basket, but it was
\par impossible to be there while the wood-sawyer was at work, and not be in
\par his sight. Thenceforth, to secure his good will, she always spoke to him
\par first, and often gave him drink-money, which he readily received.
\par 
\par He was an inquisitive fellow, and sometimes when she had quite forgotten
\par him in gazing at the prison roof and grates, and in lifting her heart
\par up to her husband, she would come to herself to find him looking at her,
\par with his knee on his bench and his saw stopped in its work. "But it's
\par not my business!" he would generally say at those times, and would
\par briskly fall to his sawing again.
\par 
\par In all weathers, in the snow and frost of winter, in the bitter winds of
\par spring, in the hot sunshine of summer, in the rains of autumn, and again
\par in the snow and frost of winter, Lucie passed two hours of every day at
\par this place; and every day on leaving it, she kissed the prison wall.
\par Her husband saw her (so she learned from her father) it might be once in
\par five or six times: it might be twice or thrice running: it might be, not
\par for a week or a fortnight together. It was enough that he could and did
\par see her when the chances served, and on that possibility she would have
\par waited out the day, seven days a week.
\par 
\par These occupations brought her round to the December month, wherein her
\par father walked among the terrors with a steady head. On a lightly-snowing
\par afternoon she arrived at the usual corner. It was a day of some wild
\par rejoicing, and a festival. She had seen the houses, as she came along,
\par decorated with little pikes, and with little red caps stuck upon them;
\par also, with tricoloured ribbons; also, with the standard inscription
\par (tricoloured letters were the favourite), Republic One and Indivisible.
\par Liberty, Equality, Fraternity, or Death!
\par 
\par The miserable shop of the wood-sawyer was so small, that its whole
\par surface furnished very indifferent space for this legend. He had got
\par somebody to scrawl it up for him, however, who had squeezed Death in
\par with most inappropriate difficulty. On his house-top, he displayed pike
\par and cap, as a good citizen must, and in a window he had stationed his
\par saw inscribed as his "Little Sainte Guillotine"--for the great sharp
\par female was by that time popularly canonised. His shop was shut and he
\par was not there, which was a relief to Lucie, and left her quite alone.
\par 
\par But, he was not far off, for presently she heard a troubled movement
\par and a shouting coming along, which filled her with fear. A moment
\par afterwards, and a throng of people came pouring round the corner by the
\par prison wall, in the midst of whom was the wood-sawyer hand in hand with
\par The Vengeance. There could not be fewer than five hundred people, and
\par they were dancing like five thousand demons. There was no other music
\par than their own singing. They danced to the popular Revolution song,
\par keeping a ferocious time that was like a gnashing of teeth in unison.
\par Men and women danced together, women danced together, men danced
\par together, as hazard had brought them together. At first, they were a
\par mere storm of coarse red caps and coarse woollen rags; but, as they
\par filled the place, and stopped to dance about Lucie, some ghastly
\par apparition of a dance-figure gone raving mad arose among them. They
\par advanced, retreated, struck at one another's hands, clutched at one
\par another's heads, spun round alone, caught one another and spun round
\par in pairs, until many of them dropped. While those were down, the rest
\par linked hand in hand, and all spun round together: then the ring broke,
\par and in separate rings of two and four they turned and turned until they
\par all stopped at once, began again, struck, clutched, and tore, and then
\par reversed the spin, and all spun round another way. Suddenly they stopped
\par again, paused, struck out the time afresh, formed into lines the width
\par of the public way, and, with their heads low down and their hands high
\par up, swooped screaming off. No fight could have been half so terrible
\par as this dance. It was so emphatically a fallen sport--a something, once
\par innocent, delivered over to all devilry--a healthy pastime changed into
\par a means of angering the blood, bewildering the senses, and steeling the
\par heart. Such grace as was visible in it, made it the uglier, showing how
\par warped and perverted all things good by nature were become. The maidenly
\par bosom bared to this, the pretty almost-child's head thus distracted, the
\par delicate foot mincing in this slough of blood and dirt, were types of
\par the disjointed time.
\par 
\par This was the Carmagnole. As it passed, leaving Lucie frightened and
\par bewildered in the doorway of the wood-sawyer's house, the feathery snow
\par fell as quietly and lay as white and soft, as if it had never been.
\par 
\par "O my father!" for he stood before her when she lifted up the eyes she
\par had momentarily darkened with her hand; "such a cruel, bad sight."
\par 
\par "I know, my dear, I know. I have seen it many times. Don't be
\par frightened! Not one of them would harm you."
\par 
\par "I am not frightened for myself, my father. But when I think of my
\par husband, and the mercies of these people--"
\par 
\par "We will set him above their mercies very soon. I left him climbing to
\par the window, and I came to tell you. There is no one here to see. You may
\par kiss your hand towards that highest shelving roof."
\par 
\par "I do so, father, and I send him my Soul with it!"
\par 
\par "You cannot see him, my poor dear?"
\par 
\par "No, father," said Lucie, yearning and weeping as she kissed her hand,
\par "no."
\par 
\par A footstep in the snow. Madame Defarge. "I salute you, citizeness,"
\par from the Doctor. "I salute you, citizen." This in passing. Nothing more.
\par Madame Defarge gone, like a shadow over the white road.
\par 
\par "Give me your arm, my love. Pass from here with an air of cheerfulness
\par and courage, for his sake. That was well done;" they had left the spot;
\par "it shall not be in vain. Charles is summoned for to-morrow."
\par 
\par "For to-morrow!"
\par 
\par "There is no time to lose. I am well prepared, but there are precautions
\par to be taken, that could not be taken until he was actually summoned
\par before the Tribunal. He has not received the notice yet, but I know
\par that he will presently be summoned for to-morrow, and removed to the
\par Conciergerie; I have timely information. You are not afraid?"
\par 
\par She could scarcely answer, "I trust in you."
\par 
\par "Do so, implicitly. Your suspense is nearly ended, my darling; he shall
\par be restored to you within a few hours; I have encompassed him with every
\par protection. I must see Lorry."
\par 
\par He stopped. There was a heavy lumbering of wheels within hearing. They
\par both knew too well what it meant. One. Two. Three. Three tumbrils faring
\par away with their dread loads over the hushing snow.
\par 
\par "I must see Lorry," the Doctor repeated, turning her another way.
\par 
\par The staunch old gentleman was still in his trust; had never left it. He
\par and his books were in frequent requisition as to property confiscated
\par and made national. What he could save for the owners, he saved. No
\par better man living to hold fast by what Tellson's had in keeping, and to
\par hold his peace.
\par 
\par A murky red and yellow sky, and a rising mist from the Seine, denoted
\par the approach of darkness. It was almost dark when they arrived at the
\par Bank. The stately residence of Monseigneur was altogether blighted and
\par deserted. Above a heap of dust and ashes in the court, ran the letters:
\par National Property. Republic One and Indivisible. Liberty, Equality,
\par Fraternity, or Death!
\par 
\par Who could that be with Mr. Lorry--the owner of the riding-coat upon the
\par chair--who must not be seen? From whom newly arrived, did he come out,
\par agitated and surprised, to take his favourite in his arms? To whom did
\par he appear to repeat her faltering words, when, raising his voice and
\par turning his head towards the door of the room from which he had issued,
\par he said: "Removed to the Conciergerie, and summoned for to-morrow?"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VI. Triumph
\par 
\par 
\par The dread tribunal of five Judges, Public Prosecutor, and determined
\par Jury, sat every day. Their lists went forth every evening, and were
\par read out by the gaolers of the various prisons to their prisoners. The
\par standard gaoler-joke was, "Come out and listen to the Evening Paper, you
\par inside there!"
\par 
\par "Charles Evremonde, called Darnay!"
\par 
\par So at last began the Evening Paper at La Force.
\par 
\par When a name was called, its owner stepped apart into a spot reserved
\par for those who were announced as being thus fatally recorded. Charles
\par Evremonde, called Darnay, had reason to know the usage; he had seen
\par hundreds pass away so.
\par 
\par His bloated gaoler, who wore spectacles to read with, glanced over them
\par to assure himself that he had taken his place, and went through the
\par list, making a similar short pause at each name. There were twenty-three
\par names, but only twenty were responded to; for one of the prisoners so
\par summoned had died in gaol and been forgotten, and two had already been
\par guillotined and forgotten. The list was read, in the vaulted chamber
\par where Darnay had seen the associated prisoners on the night of his
\par arrival. Every one of those had perished in the massacre; every human
\par creature he had since cared for and parted with, had died on the
\par scaffold.
\par 
\par There were hurried words of farewell and kindness, but the parting was
\par soon over. It was the incident of every day, and the society of La Force
\par were engaged in the preparation of some games of forfeits and a little
\par concert, for that evening. They crowded to the grates and shed tears
\par there; but, twenty places in the projected entertainments had to be
\par refilled, and the time was, at best, short to the lock-up hour, when the
\par common rooms and corridors would be delivered over to the great dogs
\par who kept watch there through the night. The prisoners were far from
\par insensible or unfeeling; their ways arose out of the condition of the
\par time. Similarly, though with a subtle difference, a species of fervour
\par or intoxication, known, without doubt, to have led some persons to
\par brave the guillotine unnecessarily, and to die by it, was not mere
\par boastfulness, but a wild infection of the wildly shaken public mind. In
\par seasons of pestilence, some of us will have a secret attraction to the
\par disease--a terrible passing inclination to die of it. And all of us have
\par like wonders hidden in our breasts, only needing circumstances to evoke
\par them.
\par 
\par The passage to the Conciergerie was short and dark; the night in its
\par vermin-haunted cells was long and cold. Next day, fifteen prisoners were
\par put to the bar before Charles Darnay's name was called. All the fifteen
\par were condemned, and the trials of the whole occupied an hour and a half.
\par 
\par "Charles Evremonde, called Darnay," was at length arraigned.
\par 
\par His judges sat upon the Bench in feathered hats; but the rough red cap
\par and tricoloured cockade was the head-dress otherwise prevailing. Looking
\par at the Jury and the turbulent audience, he might have thought that the
\par usual order of things was reversed, and that the felons were trying the
\par honest men. The lowest, cruelest, and worst populace of a city, never
\par without its quantity of low, cruel, and bad, were the directing
\par spirits of the scene: noisily commenting, applauding, disapproving,
\par anticipating, and precipitating the result, without a check. Of the men,
\par the greater part were armed in various ways; of the women, some wore
\par knives, some daggers, some ate and drank as they looked on, many
\par knitted. Among these last, was one, with a spare piece of knitting under
\par her arm as she worked. She was in a front row, by the side of a man whom
\par he had never seen since his arrival at the Barrier, but whom he directly
\par remembered as Defarge. He noticed that she once or twice whispered in
\par his ear, and that she seemed to be his wife; but, what he most noticed
\par in the two figures was, that although they were posted as close to
\par himself as they could be, they never looked towards him. They seemed to
\par be waiting for something with a dogged determination, and they looked at
\par the Jury, but at nothing else. Under the President sat Doctor Manette,
\par in his usual quiet dress. As well as the prisoner could see, he and Mr.
\par Lorry were the only men there, unconnected with the Tribunal, who
\par wore their usual clothes, and had not assumed the coarse garb of the
\par Carmagnole.
\par 
\par Charles Evremonde, called Darnay, was accused by the public prosecutor
\par as an emigrant, whose life was forfeit to the Republic, under the decree
\par which banished all emigrants on pain of Death. It was nothing that the
\par decree bore date since his return to France. There he was, and there was
\par the decree; he had been taken in France, and his head was demanded.
\par 
\par "Take off his head!" cried the audience. "An enemy to the Republic!"
\par 
\par The President rang his bell to silence those cries, and asked the
\par prisoner whether it was not true that he had lived many years in
\par England?
\par 
\par Undoubtedly it was.
\par 
\par Was he not an emigrant then? What did he call himself?
\par 
\par Not an emigrant, he hoped, within the sense and spirit of the law.
\par 
\par Why not? the President desired to know.
\par 
\par Because he had voluntarily relinquished a title that was distasteful
\par to him, and a station that was distasteful to him, and had left
\par his country--he submitted before the word emigrant in the present
\par acceptation by the Tribunal was in use--to live by his own industry in
\par England, rather than on the industry of the overladen people of France.
\par 
\par What proof had he of this?
\par 
\par He handed in the names of two witnesses; Theophile Gabelle, and
\par Alexandre Manette.
\par 
\par But he had married in England? the President reminded him.
\par 
\par True, but not an English woman.
\par 
\par A citizeness of France?
\par 
\par Yes. By birth.
\par 
\par Her name and family?
\par 
\par "Lucie Manette, only daughter of Doctor Manette, the good physician who
\par sits there."
\par 
\par This answer had a happy effect upon the audience. Cries in exaltation
\par of the well-known good physician rent the hall. So capriciously were
\par the people moved, that tears immediately rolled down several ferocious
\par countenances which had been glaring at the prisoner a moment before, as
\par if with impatience to pluck him out into the streets and kill him.
\par 
\par On these few steps of his dangerous way, Charles Darnay had set his foot
\par according to Doctor Manette's reiterated instructions. The same cautious
\par counsel directed every step that lay before him, and had prepared every
\par inch of his road.
\par 
\par The President asked, why had he returned to France when he did, and not
\par sooner?
\par 
\par He had not returned sooner, he replied, simply because he had no means
\par of living in France, save those he had resigned; whereas, in England,
\par he lived by giving instruction in the French language and literature.
\par He had returned when he did, on the pressing and written entreaty of
\par a French citizen, who represented that his life was endangered by his
\par absence. He had come back, to save a citizen's life, and to bear his
\par testimony, at whatever personal hazard, to the truth. Was that criminal
\par in the eyes of the Republic?
\par 
\par The populace cried enthusiastically, "No!" and the President rang his
\par bell to quiet them. Which it did not, for they continued to cry "No!"
\par until they left off, of their own will.
\par 
\par The President required the name of that citizen. The accused explained
\par that the citizen was his first witness. He also referred with confidence
\par to the citizen's letter, which had been taken from him at the Barrier,
\par but which he did not doubt would be found among the papers then before
\par the President.
\par 
\par The Doctor had taken care that it should be there--had assured him that
\par it would be there--and at this stage of the proceedings it was produced
\par and read. Citizen Gabelle was called to confirm it, and did so. Citizen
\par Gabelle hinted, with infinite delicacy and politeness, that in the
\par pressure of business imposed on the Tribunal by the multitude of
\par enemies of the Republic with which it had to deal, he had been slightly
\par overlooked in his prison of the Abbaye--in fact, had rather passed out
\par of the Tribunal's patriotic remembrance--until three days ago; when he
\par had been summoned before it, and had been set at liberty on the Jury's
\par declaring themselves satisfied that the accusation against him was
\par answered, as to himself, by the surrender of the citizen Evremonde,
\par called Darnay.
\par 
\par Doctor Manette was next questioned. His high personal popularity,
\par and the clearness of his answers, made a great impression; but, as he
\par proceeded, as he showed that the Accused was his first friend on his
\par release from his long imprisonment; that, the accused had remained in
\par England, always faithful and devoted to his daughter and himself in
\par their exile; that, so far from being in favour with the Aristocrat
\par government there, he had actually been tried for his life by it, as
\par the foe of England and friend of the United States--as he brought these
\par circumstances into view, with the greatest discretion and with the
\par straightforward force of truth and earnestness, the Jury and the
\par populace became one. At last, when he appealed by name to Monsieur
\par Lorry, an English gentleman then and there present, who, like himself,
\par had been a witness on that English trial and could corroborate his
\par account of it, the Jury declared that they had heard enough, and that
\par they were ready with their votes if the President were content to
\par receive them.
\par 
\par At every vote (the Jurymen voted aloud and individually), the populace
\par set up a shout of applause. All the voices were in the prisoner's
\par favour, and the President declared him free.
\par 
\par Then, began one of those extraordinary scenes with which the populace
\par sometimes gratified their fickleness, or their better impulses towards
\par generosity and mercy, or which they regarded as some set-off against
\par their swollen account of cruel rage. No man can decide now to which of
\par these motives such extraordinary scenes were referable; it is probable,
\par to a blending of all the three, with the second predominating. No sooner
\par was the acquittal pronounced, than tears were shed as freely as blood
\par at another time, and such fraternal embraces were bestowed upon the
\par prisoner by as many of both sexes as could rush at him, that after
\par his long and unwholesome confinement he was in danger of fainting from
\par exhaustion; none the less because he knew very well, that the very same
\par people, carried by another current, would have rushed at him with
\par the very same intensity, to rend him to pieces and strew him over the
\par streets.
\par 
\par His removal, to make way for other accused persons who were to be tried,
\par rescued him from these caresses for the moment. Five were to be tried
\par together, next, as enemies of the Republic, forasmuch as they had not
\par assisted it by word or deed. So quick was the Tribunal to compensate
\par itself and the nation for a chance lost, that these five came down to
\par him before he left the place, condemned to die within twenty-four
\par hours. The first of them told him so, with the customary prison sign
\par of Death--a raised finger--and they all added in words, "Long live the
\par Republic!"
\par 
\par The five had had, it is true, no audience to lengthen their proceedings,
\par for when he and Doctor Manette emerged from the gate, there was a great
\par crowd about it, in which there seemed to be every face he had seen in
\par Court--except two, for which he looked in vain. On his coming out, the
\par concourse made at him anew, weeping, embracing, and shouting, all by
\par turns and all together, until the very tide of the river on the bank of
\par which the mad scene was acted, seemed to run mad, like the people on the
\par shore.
\par 
\par They put him into a great chair they had among them, and which they had
\par taken either out of the Court itself, or one of its rooms or passages.
\par Over the chair they had thrown a red flag, and to the back of it they
\par had bound a pike with a red cap on its top. In this car of triumph, not
\par even the Doctor's entreaties could prevent his being carried to his home
\par on men's shoulders, with a confused sea of red caps heaving about him,
\par and casting up to sight from the stormy deep such wrecks of faces, that
\par he more than once misdoubted his mind being in confusion, and that he
\par was in the tumbril on his way to the Guillotine.
\par 
\par In wild dreamlike procession, embracing whom they met and pointing
\par him out, they carried him on. Reddening the snowy streets with the
\par prevailing Republican colour, in winding and tramping through them, as
\par they had reddened them below the snow with a deeper dye, they carried
\par him thus into the courtyard of the building where he lived. Her father
\par had gone on before, to prepare her, and when her husband stood upon his
\par feet, she dropped insensible in his arms.
\par 
\par As he held her to his heart and turned her beautiful head between his
\par face and the brawling crowd, so that his tears and her lips might come
\par together unseen, a few of the people fell to dancing. Instantly, all the
\par rest fell to dancing, and the courtyard overflowed with the Carmagnole.
\par Then, they elevated into the vacant chair a young woman from the
\par crowd to be carried as the Goddess of Liberty, and then swelling and
\par overflowing out into the adjacent streets, and along the river's bank,
\par and over the bridge, the Carmagnole absorbed them every one and whirled
\par them away.
\par 
\par After grasping the Doctor's hand, as he stood victorious and proud
\par before him; after grasping the hand of Mr. Lorry, who came panting in
\par breathless from his struggle against the waterspout of the Carmagnole;
\par after kissing little Lucie, who was lifted up to clasp her arms round
\par his neck; and after embracing the ever zealous and faithful Pross who
\par lifted her; he took his wife in his arms, and carried her up to their
\par rooms.
\par 
\par "Lucie! My own! I am safe."
\par 
\par "O dearest Charles, let me thank God for this on my knees as I have
\par prayed to Him."
\par 
\par They all reverently bowed their heads and hearts. When she was again in
\par his arms, he said to her:
\par 
\par "And now speak to your father, dearest. No other man in all this France
\par could have done what he has done for me."
\par 
\par She laid her head upon her father's breast, as she had laid his poor
\par head on her own breast, long, long ago. He was happy in the return he
\par had made her, he was recompensed for his suffering, he was proud of his
\par strength. "You must not be weak, my darling," he remonstrated; "don't
\par tremble so. I have saved him."
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VII. A Knock at the Door
\par 
\par 
\par "I have saved him." It was not another of the dreams in which he had
\par often come back; he was really here. And yet his wife trembled, and a
\par vague but heavy fear was upon her.
\par 
\par All the air round was so thick and dark, the people were so passionately
\par revengeful and fitful, the innocent were so constantly put to death on
\par vague suspicion and black malice, it was so impossible to forget that
\par many as blameless as her husband and as dear to others as he was to
\par her, every day shared the fate from which he had been clutched, that her
\par heart could not be as lightened of its load as she felt it ought to be.
\par The shadows of the wintry afternoon were beginning to fall, and even now
\par the dreadful carts were rolling through the streets. Her mind pursued
\par them, looking for him among the Condemned; and then she clung closer to
\par his real presence and trembled more.
\par 
\par Her father, cheering her, showed a compassionate superiority to this
\par woman's weakness, which was wonderful to see. No garret, no shoemaking,
\par no One Hundred and Five, North Tower, now! He had accomplished the task
\par he had set himself, his promise was redeemed, he had saved Charles. Let
\par them all lean upon him.
\par 
\par Their housekeeping was of a very frugal kind: not only because that was
\par the safest way of life, involving the least offence to the people, but
\par because they were not rich, and Charles, throughout his imprisonment,
\par had had to pay heavily for his bad food, and for his guard, and towards
\par the living of the poorer prisoners. Partly on this account, and
\par partly to avoid a domestic spy, they kept no servant; the citizen and
\par citizeness who acted as porters at the courtyard gate, rendered them
\par occasional service; and Jerry (almost wholly transferred to them by
\par Mr. Lorry) had become their daily retainer, and had his bed there every
\par night.
\par 
\par It was an ordinance of the Republic One and Indivisible of Liberty,
\par Equality, Fraternity, or Death, that on the door or doorpost of every
\par house, the name of every inmate must be legibly inscribed in letters
\par of a certain size, at a certain convenient height from the ground. Mr.
\par Jerry Cruncher's name, therefore, duly embellished the doorpost down
\par below; and, as the afternoon shadows deepened, the owner of that name
\par himself appeared, from overlooking a painter whom Doctor Manette had
\par employed to add to the list the name of Charles Evremonde, called
\par Darnay.
\par 
\par In the universal fear and distrust that darkened the time, all the usual
\par harmless ways of life were changed. In the Doctor's little household, as
\par in very many others, the articles of daily consumption that were wanted
\par were purchased every evening, in small quantities and at various small
\par shops. To avoid attracting notice, and to give as little occasion as
\par possible for talk and envy, was the general desire.
\par 
\par For some months past, Miss Pross and Mr. Cruncher had discharged the
\par office of purveyors; the former carrying the money; the latter, the
\par basket. Every afternoon at about the time when the public lamps were
\par lighted, they fared forth on this duty, and made and brought home
\par such purchases as were needful. Although Miss Pross, through her long
\par association with a French family, might have known as much of their
\par language as of her own, if she had had a mind, she had no mind in that
\par direction; consequently she knew no more of that "nonsense" (as she was
\par pleased to call it) than Mr. Cruncher did. So her manner of marketing
\par was to plump a noun-substantive at the head of a shopkeeper without any
\par introduction in the nature of an article, and, if it happened not to be
\par the name of the thing she wanted, to look round for that thing, lay hold
\par of it, and hold on by it until the bargain was concluded. She always
\par made a bargain for it, by holding up, as a statement of its just price,
\par one finger less than the merchant held up, whatever his number might be.
\par 
\par "Now, Mr. Cruncher," said Miss Pross, whose eyes were red with felicity;
\par "if you are ready, I am."
\par 
\par Jerry hoarsely professed himself at Miss Pross's service. He had worn
\par all his rust off long ago, but nothing would file his spiky head down.
\par 
\par "There's all manner of things wanted," said Miss Pross, "and we shall
\par have a precious time of it. We want wine, among the rest. Nice toasts
\par these Redheads will be drinking, wherever we buy it."
\par 
\par "It will be much the same to your knowledge, miss, I should think,"
\par retorted Jerry, "whether they drink your health or the Old Un's."
\par 
\par "Who's he?" said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher, with some diffidence, explained himself as meaning "Old
\par Nick's."
\par 
\par "Ha!" said Miss Pross, "it doesn't need an interpreter to explain the
\par meaning of these creatures. They have but one, and it's Midnight Murder,
\par and Mischief."
\par 
\par "Hush, dear! Pray, pray, be cautious!" cried Lucie.
\par 
\par "Yes, yes, yes, I'll be cautious," said Miss Pross; "but I may say
\par among ourselves, that I do hope there will be no oniony and tobaccoey
\par smotherings in the form of embracings all round, going on in the
\par streets. Now, Ladybird, never you stir from that fire till I come back!
\par Take care of the dear husband you have recovered, and don't move your
\par pretty head from his shoulder as you have it now, till you see me again!
\par May I ask a question, Doctor Manette, before I go?"
\par 
\par "I think you may take that liberty," the Doctor answered, smiling.
\par 
\par "For gracious sake, don't talk about Liberty; we have quite enough of
\par that," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par "Hush, dear! Again?" Lucie remonstrated.
\par 
\par "Well, my sweet," said Miss Pross, nodding her head emphatically, "the
\par short and the long of it is, that I am a subject of His Most Gracious
\par Majesty King George the Third;" Miss Pross curtseyed at the name; "and
\par as such, my maxim is, Confound their politics, Frustrate their knavish
\par tricks, On him our hopes we fix, God save the King!"
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher, in an access of loyalty, growlingly repeated the words
\par after Miss Pross, like somebody at church.
\par 
\par "I am glad you have so much of the Englishman in you, though I wish you
\par had never taken that cold in your voice," said Miss Pross, approvingly.
\par "But the question, Doctor Manette. Is there"--it was the good creature's
\par way to affect to make light of anything that was a great anxiety
\par with them all, and to come at it in this chance manner--"is there any
\par prospect yet, of our getting out of this place?"
\par 
\par "I fear not yet. It would be dangerous for Charles yet."
\par 
\par "Heigh-ho-hum!" said Miss Pross, cheerfully repressing a sigh as she
\par glanced at her darling's golden hair in the light of the fire, "then we
\par must have patience and wait: that's all. We must hold up our heads and
\par fight low, as my brother Solomon used to say. Now, Mr. Cruncher!--Don't
\par you move, Ladybird!"
\par 
\par They went out, leaving Lucie, and her husband, her father, and the
\par child, by a bright fire. Mr. Lorry was expected back presently from the
\par Banking House. Miss Pross had lighted the lamp, but had put it aside in
\par a corner, that they might enjoy the fire-light undisturbed. Little Lucie
\par sat by her grandfather with her hands clasped through his arm: and he,
\par in a tone not rising much above a whisper, began to tell her a story of
\par a great and powerful Fairy who had opened a prison-wall and let out
\par a captive who had once done the Fairy a service. All was subdued and
\par quiet, and Lucie was more at ease than she had been.
\par 
\par "What is that?" she cried, all at once.
\par 
\par "My dear!" said her father, stopping in his story, and laying his hand
\par on hers, "command yourself. What a disordered state you are in! The
\par least thing--nothing--startles you! _You_, your father's daughter!"
\par 
\par "I thought, my father," said Lucie, excusing herself, with a pale face
\par and in a faltering voice, "that I heard strange feet upon the stairs."
\par 
\par "My love, the staircase is as still as Death."
\par 
\par As he said the word, a blow was struck upon the door.
\par 
\par "Oh father, father. What can this be! Hide Charles. Save him!"
\par 
\par "My child," said the Doctor, rising, and laying his hand upon her
\par shoulder, "I _have_ saved him. What weakness is this, my dear! Let me go
\par to the door."
\par 
\par He took the lamp in his hand, crossed the two intervening outer rooms,
\par and opened it. A rude clattering of feet over the floor, and four rough
\par men in red caps, armed with sabres and pistols, entered the room.
\par 
\par "The Citizen Evremonde, called Darnay," said the first.
\par 
\par "Who seeks him?" answered Darnay.
\par 
\par "I seek him. We seek him. I know you, Evremonde; I saw you before the
\par Tribunal to-day. You are again the prisoner of the Republic."
\par 
\par The four surrounded him, where he stood with his wife and child clinging
\par to him.
\par 
\par "Tell me how and why am I again a prisoner?"
\par 
\par "It is enough that you return straight to the Conciergerie, and will
\par know to-morrow. You are summoned for to-morrow."
\par 
\par Doctor Manette, whom this visitation had so turned into stone, that he
\par stood with the lamp in his hand, as if he were a statue made to hold it,
\par moved after these words were spoken, put the lamp down, and confronting
\par the speaker, and taking him, not ungently, by the loose front of his red
\par woollen shirt, said:
\par 
\par "You know him, you have said. Do you know me?"
\par 
\par "Yes, I know you, Citizen Doctor."
\par 
\par "We all know you, Citizen Doctor," said the other three.
\par 
\par He looked abstractedly from one to another, and said, in a lower voice,
\par after a pause:
\par 
\par "Will you answer his question to me then? How does this happen?"
\par 
\par "Citizen Doctor," said the first, reluctantly, "he has been denounced to
\par the Section of Saint Antoine. This citizen," pointing out the second who
\par had entered, "is from Saint Antoine."
\par 
\par The citizen here indicated nodded his head, and added:
\par 
\par "He is accused by Saint Antoine."
\par 
\par "Of what?" asked the Doctor.
\par 
\par "Citizen Doctor," said the first, with his former reluctance, "ask no
\par more. If the Republic demands sacrifices from you, without doubt you as
\par a good patriot will be happy to make them. The Republic goes before all.
\par The People is supreme. Evremonde, we are pressed."
\par 
\par "One word," the Doctor entreated. "Will you tell me who denounced him?"
\par 
\par "It is against rule," answered the first; "but you can ask Him of Saint
\par Antoine here."
\par 
\par The Doctor turned his eyes upon that man. Who moved uneasily on his
\par feet, rubbed his beard a little, and at length said:
\par 
\par "Well! Truly it is against rule. But he is denounced--and gravely--by
\par the Citizen and Citizeness Defarge. And by one other."
\par 
\par "What other?"
\par 
\par "Do _you_ ask, Citizen Doctor?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par "Then," said he of Saint Antoine, with a strange look, "you will be
\par answered to-morrow. Now, I am dumb!"
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par VIII. A Hand at Cards
\par 
\par 
\par Happily unconscious of the new calamity at home, Miss Pross threaded her
\par way along the narrow streets and crossed the river by the bridge of the
\par Pont-Neuf, reckoning in her mind the number of indispensable purchases
\par she had to make. Mr. Cruncher, with the basket, walked at her side. They
\par both looked to the right and to the left into most of the shops they
\par passed, had a wary eye for all gregarious assemblages of people, and
\par turned out of their road to avoid any very excited group of talkers. It
\par was a raw evening, and the misty river, blurred to the eye with blazing
\par lights and to the ear with harsh noises, showed where the barges were
\par stationed in which the smiths worked, making guns for the Army of the
\par Republic. Woe to the man who played tricks with _that_ Army, or got
\par undeserved promotion in it! Better for him that his beard had never
\par grown, for the National Razor shaved him close.
\par 
\par Having purchased a few small articles of grocery, and a measure of oil
\par for the lamp, Miss Pross bethought herself of the wine they wanted.
\par After peeping into several wine-shops, she stopped at the sign of the
\par Good Republican Brutus of Antiquity, not far from the National Palace,
\par once (and twice) the Tuileries, where the aspect of things rather
\par took her fancy. It had a quieter look than any other place of the same
\par description they had passed, and, though red with patriotic caps, was
\par not so red as the rest. Sounding Mr. Cruncher, and finding him of her
\par opinion, Miss Pross resorted to the Good Republican Brutus of Antiquity,
\par attended by her cavalier.
\par 
\par Slightly observant of the smoky lights; of the people, pipe in mouth,
\par playing with limp cards and yellow dominoes; of the one bare-breasted,
\par bare-armed, soot-begrimed workman reading a journal aloud, and of
\par the others listening to him; of the weapons worn, or laid aside to be
\par resumed; of the two or three customers fallen forward asleep, who in the
\par popular high-shouldered shaggy black spencer looked, in that attitude,
\par like slumbering bears or dogs; the two outlandish customers approached
\par the counter, and showed what they wanted.
\par 
\par As their wine was measuring out, a man parted from another man in a
\par corner, and rose to depart. In going, he had to face Miss Pross. No
\par sooner did he face her, than Miss Pross uttered a scream, and clapped
\par her hands.
\par 
\par In a moment, the whole company were on their feet. That somebody was
\par assassinated by somebody vindicating a difference of opinion was the
\par likeliest occurrence. Everybody looked to see somebody fall, but only
\par saw a man and a woman standing staring at each other; the man with all
\par the outward aspect of a Frenchman and a thorough Republican; the woman,
\par evidently English.
\par 
\par What was said in this disappointing anti-climax, by the disciples of the
\par Good Republican Brutus of Antiquity, except that it was something very
\par voluble and loud, would have been as so much Hebrew or Chaldean to Miss
\par Pross and her protector, though they had been all ears. But, they had no
\par ears for anything in their surprise. For, it must be recorded, that
\par not only was Miss Pross lost in amazement and agitation, but,
\par Mr. Cruncher--though it seemed on his own separate and individual
\par account--was in a state of the greatest wonder.
\par 
\par "What is the matter?" said the man who had caused Miss Pross to scream;
\par speaking in a vexed, abrupt voice (though in a low tone), and in
\par English.
\par 
\par "Oh, Solomon, dear Solomon!" cried Miss Pross, clapping her hands again.
\par "After not setting eyes upon you or hearing of you for so long a time,
\par do I find you here!"
\par 
\par "Don't call me Solomon. Do you want to be the death of me?" asked the
\par man, in a furtive, frightened way.
\par 
\par "Brother, brother!" cried Miss Pross, bursting into tears. "Have I ever
\par been so hard with you that you ask me such a cruel question?"
\par 
\par "Then hold your meddlesome tongue," said Solomon, "and come out, if you
\par want to speak to me. Pay for your wine, and come out. Who's this man?"
\par 
\par Miss Pross, shaking her loving and dejected head at her by no means
\par affectionate brother, said through her tears, "Mr. Cruncher."
\par 
\par "Let him come out too," said Solomon. "Does he think me a ghost?"
\par 
\par Apparently, Mr. Cruncher did, to judge from his looks. He said not a
\par word, however, and Miss Pross, exploring the depths of her reticule
\par through her tears with great difficulty paid for her wine. As she did
\par so, Solomon turned to the followers of the Good Republican Brutus
\par of Antiquity, and offered a few words of explanation in the French
\par language, which caused them all to relapse into their former places and
\par pursuits.
\par 
\par "Now," said Solomon, stopping at the dark street corner, "what do you
\par want?"
\par 
\par "How dreadfully unkind in a brother nothing has ever turned my love away
\par from!" cried Miss Pross, "to give me such a greeting, and show me no
\par affection."
\par 
\par "There. Confound it! There," said Solomon, making a dab at Miss Pross's
\par lips with his own. "Now are you content?"
\par 
\par Miss Pross only shook her head and wept in silence.
\par 
\par "If you expect me to be surprised," said her brother Solomon, "I am not
\par surprised; I knew you were here; I know of most people who are here. If
\par you really don't want to endanger my existence--which I half believe you
\par do--go your ways as soon as possible, and let me go mine. I am busy. I
\par am an official."
\par 
\par "My English brother Solomon," mourned Miss Pross, casting up her
\par tear-fraught eyes, "that had the makings in him of one of the best and
\par greatest of men in his native country, an official among foreigners, and
\par such foreigners! I would almost sooner have seen the dear boy lying in
\par his--"
\par 
\par "I said so!" cried her brother, interrupting. "I knew it. You want to be
\par the death of me. I shall be rendered Suspected, by my own sister. Just
\par as I am getting on!"
\par 
\par "The gracious and merciful Heavens forbid!" cried Miss Pross. "Far
\par rather would I never see you again, dear Solomon, though I have ever
\par loved you truly, and ever shall. Say but one affectionate word to me,
\par and tell me there is nothing angry or estranged between us, and I will
\par detain you no longer."
\par 
\par Good Miss Pross! As if the estrangement between them had come of any
\par culpability of hers. As if Mr. Lorry had not known it for a fact, years
\par ago, in the quiet corner in Soho, that this precious brother had spent
\par her money and left her!
\par 
\par He was saying the affectionate word, however, with a far more grudging
\par condescension and patronage than he could have shown if their relative
\par merits and positions had been reversed (which is invariably the case,
\par all the world over), when Mr. Cruncher, touching him on the shoulder,
\par hoarsely and unexpectedly interposed with the following singular
\par question:
\par 
\par "I say! Might I ask the favour? As to whether your name is John Solomon,
\par or Solomon John?"
\par 
\par The official turned towards him with sudden distrust. He had not
\par previously uttered a word.
\par 
\par "Come!" said Mr. Cruncher. "Speak out, you know." (Which, by the way,
\par was more than he could do himself.) "John Solomon, or Solomon John? She
\par calls you Solomon, and she must know, being your sister. And _I_ know
\par you're John, you know. Which of the two goes first? And regarding that
\par name of Pross, likewise. That warn't your name over the water."
\par 
\par "What do you mean?"
\par 
\par "Well, I don't know all I mean, for I can't call to mind what your name
\par was, over the water."
\par 
\par "No?"
\par 
\par "No. But I'll swear it was a name of two syllables."
\par 
\par "Indeed?"
\par 
\par "Yes. T'other one's was one syllable. I know you. You was a spy--witness
\par at the Bailey. What, in the name of the Father of Lies, own father to
\par yourself, was you called at that time?"
\par 
\par "Barsad," said another voice, striking in.
\par 
\par "That's the name for a thousand pound!" cried Jerry.
\par 
\par The speaker who struck in, was Sydney Carton. He had his hands behind
\par him under the skirts of his riding-coat, and he stood at Mr. Cruncher's
\par elbow as negligently as he might have stood at the Old Bailey itself.
\par 
\par "Don't be alarmed, my dear Miss Pross. I arrived at Mr. Lorry's, to his
\par surprise, yesterday evening; we agreed that I would not present myself
\par elsewhere until all was well, or unless I could be useful; I present
\par myself here, to beg a little talk with your brother. I wish you had a
\par better employed brother than Mr. Barsad. I wish for your sake Mr. Barsad
\par was not a Sheep of the Prisons."
\par 
\par Sheep was a cant word of the time for a spy, under the gaolers. The spy,
\par who was pale, turned paler, and asked him how he dared--
\par 
\par "I'll tell you," said Sydney. "I lighted on you, Mr. Barsad, coming out
\par of the prison of the Conciergerie while I was contemplating the walls,
\par an hour or more ago. You have a face to be remembered, and I remember
\par faces well. Made curious by seeing you in that connection, and having
\par a reason, to which you are no stranger, for associating you with
\par the misfortunes of a friend now very unfortunate, I walked in your
\par direction. I walked into the wine-shop here, close after you, and
\par sat near you. I had no difficulty in deducing from your unreserved
\par conversation, and the rumour openly going about among your admirers, the
\par nature of your calling. And gradually, what I had done at random, seemed
\par to shape itself into a purpose, Mr. Barsad."
\par 
\par "What purpose?" the spy asked.
\par 
\par "It would be troublesome, and might be dangerous, to explain in the
\par street. Could you favour me, in confidence, with some minutes of your
\par company--at the office of Tellson's Bank, for instance?"
\par 
\par "Under a threat?"
\par 
\par "Oh! Did I say that?"
\par 
\par "Then, why should I go there?"
\par 
\par "Really, Mr. Barsad, I can't say, if you can't."
\par 
\par "Do you mean that you won't say, sir?" the spy irresolutely asked.
\par 
\par "You apprehend me very clearly, Mr. Barsad. I won't."
\par 
\par Carton's negligent recklessness of manner came powerfully in aid of his
\par quickness and skill, in such a business as he had in his secret mind,
\par and with such a man as he had to do with. His practised eye saw it, and
\par made the most of it.
\par 
\par "Now, I told you so," said the spy, casting a reproachful look at his
\par sister; "if any trouble comes of this, it's your doing."
\par 
\par "Come, come, Mr. Barsad!" exclaimed Sydney. "Don't be ungrateful.
\par But for my great respect for your sister, I might not have led up so
\par pleasantly to a little proposal that I wish to make for our mutual
\par satisfaction. Do you go with me to the Bank?"
\par 
\par "I'll hear what you have got to say. Yes, I'll go with you."
\par 
\par "I propose that we first conduct your sister safely to the corner of her
\par own street. Let me take your arm, Miss Pross. This is not a good city,
\par at this time, for you to be out in, unprotected; and as your escort
\par knows Mr. Barsad, I will invite him to Mr. Lorry's with us. Are we
\par ready? Come then!"
\par 
\par Miss Pross recalled soon afterwards, and to the end of her life
\par remembered, that as she pressed her hands on Sydney's arm and looked up
\par in his face, imploring him to do no hurt to Solomon, there was a braced
\par purpose in the arm and a kind of inspiration in the eyes, which not only
\par contradicted his light manner, but changed and raised the man. She was
\par too much occupied then with fears for the brother who so little deserved
\par her affection, and with Sydney's friendly reassurances, adequately to
\par heed what she observed.
\par 
\par They left her at the corner of the street, and Carton led the way to Mr.
\par Lorry's, which was within a few minutes' walk. John Barsad, or Solomon
\par Pross, walked at his side.
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry had just finished his dinner, and was sitting before a cheery
\par little log or two of fire--perhaps looking into their blaze for the
\par picture of that younger elderly gentleman from Tellson's, who had looked
\par into the red coals at the Royal George at Dover, now a good many years
\par ago. He turned his head as they entered, and showed the surprise with
\par which he saw a stranger.
\par 
\par "Miss Pross's brother, sir," said Sydney. "Mr. Barsad."
\par 
\par "Barsad?" repeated the old gentleman, "Barsad? I have an association
\par with the name--and with the face."
\par 
\par "I told you you had a remarkable face, Mr. Barsad," observed Carton,
\par coolly. "Pray sit down."
\par 
\par As he took a chair himself, he supplied the link that Mr. Lorry wanted,
\par by saying to him with a frown, "Witness at that trial." Mr. Lorry
\par immediately remembered, and regarded his new visitor with an undisguised
\par look of abhorrence.
\par 
\par "Mr. Barsad has been recognised by Miss Pross as the affectionate
\par brother you have heard of," said Sydney, "and has acknowledged the
\par relationship. I pass to worse news. Darnay has been arrested again."
\par 
\par Struck with consternation, the old gentleman exclaimed, "What do you
\par tell me! I left him safe and free within these two hours, and am about
\par to return to him!"
\par 
\par "Arrested for all that. When was it done, Mr. Barsad?"
\par 
\par "Just now, if at all."
\par 
\par "Mr. Barsad is the best authority possible, sir," said Sydney, "and I
\par have it from Mr. Barsad's communication to a friend and brother Sheep
\par over a bottle of wine, that the arrest has taken place. He left the
\par messengers at the gate, and saw them admitted by the porter. There is no
\par earthly doubt that he is retaken."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry's business eye read in the speaker's face that it was loss
\par of time to dwell upon the point. Confused, but sensible that something
\par might depend on his presence of mind, he commanded himself, and was
\par silently attentive.
\par 
\par "Now, I trust," said Sydney to him, "that the name and influence of
\par Doctor Manette may stand him in as good stead to-morrow--you said he
\par would be before the Tribunal again to-morrow, Mr. Barsad?--"
\par 
\par "Yes; I believe so."
\par 
\par "--In as good stead to-morrow as to-day. But it may not be so. I own
\par to you, I am shaken, Mr. Lorry, by Doctor Manette's not having had the
\par power to prevent this arrest."
\par 
\par "He may not have known of it beforehand," said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "But that very circumstance would be alarming, when we remember how
\par identified he is with his son-in-law."
\par 
\par "That's true," Mr. Lorry acknowledged, with his troubled hand at his
\par chin, and his troubled eyes on Carton.
\par 
\par "In short," said Sydney, "this is a desperate time, when desperate games
\par are played for desperate stakes. Let the Doctor play the winning game; I
\par will play the losing one. No man's life here is worth purchase. Any one
\par carried home by the people to-day, may be condemned tomorrow. Now, the
\par stake I have resolved to play for, in case of the worst, is a friend
\par in the Conciergerie. And the friend I purpose to myself to win, is Mr.
\par Barsad."
\par 
\par "You need have good cards, sir," said the spy.
\par 
\par "I'll run them over. I'll see what I hold,--Mr. Lorry, you know what a
\par brute I am; I wish you'd give me a little brandy."
\par 
\par It was put before him, and he drank off a glassful--drank off another
\par glassful--pushed the bottle thoughtfully away.
\par 
\par "Mr. Barsad," he went on, in the tone of one who really was looking
\par over a hand at cards: "Sheep of the prisons, emissary of Republican
\par committees, now turnkey, now prisoner, always spy and secret informer,
\par so much the more valuable here for being English that an Englishman
\par is less open to suspicion of subornation in those characters than a
\par Frenchman, represents himself to his employers under a false name.
\par That's a very good card. Mr. Barsad, now in the employ of the republican
\par French government, was formerly in the employ of the aristocratic
\par English government, the enemy of France and freedom. That's an excellent
\par card. Inference clear as day in this region of suspicion, that Mr.
\par Barsad, still in the pay of the aristocratic English government, is the
\par spy of Pitt, the treacherous foe of the Republic crouching in its bosom,
\par the English traitor and agent of all mischief so much spoken of and so
\par difficult to find. That's a card not to be beaten. Have you followed my
\par hand, Mr. Barsad?"
\par 
\par "Not to understand your play," returned the spy, somewhat uneasily.
\par 
\par "I play my Ace, Denunciation of Mr. Barsad to the nearest Section
\par Committee. Look over your hand, Mr. Barsad, and see what you have. Don't
\par hurry."
\par 
\par He drew the bottle near, poured out another glassful of brandy, and
\par drank it off. He saw that the spy was fearful of his drinking himself
\par into a fit state for the immediate denunciation of him. Seeing it, he
\par poured out and drank another glassful.
\par 
\par "Look over your hand carefully, Mr. Barsad. Take time."
\par 
\par It was a poorer hand than he suspected. Mr. Barsad saw losing cards
\par in it that Sydney Carton knew nothing of. Thrown out of his honourable
\par employment in England, through too much unsuccessful hard swearing
\par there--not because he was not wanted there; our English reasons for
\par vaunting our superiority to secrecy and spies are of very modern
\par date--he knew that he had crossed the Channel, and accepted service in
\par France: first, as a tempter and an eavesdropper among his own countrymen
\par there: gradually, as a tempter and an eavesdropper among the natives. He
\par knew that under the overthrown government he had been a spy upon Saint
\par Antoine and Defarge's wine-shop; had received from the watchful police
\par such heads of information concerning Doctor Manette's imprisonment,
\par release, and history, as should serve him for an introduction to
\par familiar conversation with the Defarges; and tried them on Madame
\par Defarge, and had broken down with them signally. He always remembered
\par with fear and trembling, that that terrible woman had knitted when he
\par talked with her, and had looked ominously at him as her fingers moved.
\par He had since seen her, in the Section of Saint Antoine, over and over
\par again produce her knitted registers, and denounce people whose lives the
\par guillotine then surely swallowed up. He knew, as every one employed as
\par he was did, that he was never safe; that flight was impossible; that
\par he was tied fast under the shadow of the axe; and that in spite of
\par his utmost tergiversation and treachery in furtherance of the reigning
\par terror, a word might bring it down upon him. Once denounced, and on such
\par grave grounds as had just now been suggested to his mind, he foresaw
\par that the dreadful woman of whose unrelenting character he had seen many
\par proofs, would produce against him that fatal register, and would quash
\par his last chance of life. Besides that all secret men are men soon
\par terrified, here were surely cards enough of one black suit, to justify
\par the holder in growing rather livid as he turned them over.
\par 
\par "You scarcely seem to like your hand," said Sydney, with the greatest
\par composure. "Do you play?"
\par 
\par "I think, sir," said the spy, in the meanest manner, as he turned to Mr.
\par Lorry, "I may appeal to a gentleman of your years and benevolence, to
\par put it to this other gentleman, so much your junior, whether he can
\par under any circumstances reconcile it to his station to play that Ace
\par of which he has spoken. I admit that _I_ am a spy, and that it is
\par considered a discreditable station--though it must be filled by
\par somebody; but this gentleman is no spy, and why should he so demean
\par himself as to make himself one?"
\par 
\par "I play my Ace, Mr. Barsad," said Carton, taking the answer on himself,
\par and looking at his watch, "without any scruple, in a very few minutes."
\par 
\par "I should have hoped, gentlemen both," said the spy, always striving to
\par hook Mr. Lorry into the discussion, "that your respect for my sister--"
\par 
\par "I could not better testify my respect for your sister than by finally
\par relieving her of her brother," said Sydney Carton.
\par 
\par "You think not, sir?"
\par 
\par "I have thoroughly made up my mind about it."
\par 
\par The smooth manner of the spy, curiously in dissonance with his
\par ostentatiously rough dress, and probably with his usual demeanour,
\par received such a check from the inscrutability of Carton,--who was a
\par mystery to wiser and honester men than he,--that it faltered here and
\par failed him. While he was at a loss, Carton said, resuming his former air
\par of contemplating cards:
\par 
\par "And indeed, now I think again, I have a strong impression that I
\par have another good card here, not yet enumerated. That friend and
\par fellow-Sheep, who spoke of himself as pasturing in the country prisons;
\par who was he?"
\par 
\par "French. You don't know him," said the spy, quickly.
\par 
\par "French, eh?" repeated Carton, musing, and not appearing to notice him
\par at all, though he echoed his word. "Well; he may be."
\par 
\par "Is, I assure you," said the spy; "though it's not important."
\par 
\par "Though it's not important," repeated Carton, in the same mechanical
\par way--"though it's not important--No, it's not important. No. Yet I know
\par the face."
\par 
\par "I think not. I am sure not. It can't be," said the spy.
\par 
\par "It-can't-be," muttered Sydney Carton, retrospectively, and idling his
\par glass (which fortunately was a small one) again. "Can't-be. Spoke good
\par French. Yet like a foreigner, I thought?"
\par 
\par "Provincial," said the spy.
\par 
\par "No. Foreign!" cried Carton, striking his open hand on the table, as a
\par light broke clearly on his mind. "Cly! Disguised, but the same man. We
\par had that man before us at the Old Bailey."
\par 
\par "Now, there you are hasty, sir," said Barsad, with a smile that gave his
\par aquiline nose an extra inclination to one side; "there you really give
\par me an advantage over you. Cly (who I will unreservedly admit, at this
\par distance of time, was a partner of mine) has been dead several years. I
\par attended him in his last illness. He was buried in London, at the church
\par of Saint Pancras-in-the-Fields. His unpopularity with the blackguard
\par multitude at the moment prevented my following his remains, but I helped
\par to lay him in his coffin."
\par 
\par Here, Mr. Lorry became aware, from where he sat, of a most remarkable
\par goblin shadow on the wall. Tracing it to its source, he discovered it
\par to be caused by a sudden extraordinary rising and stiffening of all the
\par risen and stiff hair on Mr. Cruncher's head.
\par 
\par "Let us be reasonable," said the spy, "and let us be fair. To show you
\par how mistaken you are, and what an unfounded assumption yours is, I will
\par lay before you a certificate of Cly's burial, which I happened to have
\par carried in my pocket-book," with a hurried hand he produced and opened
\par it, "ever since. There it is. Oh, look at it, look at it! You may take
\par it in your hand; it's no forgery."
\par 
\par Here, Mr. Lorry perceived the reflection on the wall to elongate, and
\par Mr. Cruncher rose and stepped forward. His hair could not have been more
\par violently on end, if it had been that moment dressed by the Cow with the
\par crumpled horn in the house that Jack built.
\par 
\par Unseen by the spy, Mr. Cruncher stood at his side, and touched him on
\par the shoulder like a ghostly bailiff.
\par 
\par "That there Roger Cly, master," said Mr. Cruncher, with a taciturn and
\par iron-bound visage. "So _you_ put him in his coffin?"
\par 
\par "I did."
\par 
\par "Who took him out of it?"
\par 
\par Barsad leaned back in his chair, and stammered, "What do you mean?"
\par 
\par "I mean," said Mr. Cruncher, "that he warn't never in it. No! Not he!
\par I'll have my head took off, if he was ever in it."
\par 
\par The spy looked round at the two gentlemen; they both looked in
\par unspeakable astonishment at Jerry.
\par 
\par "I tell you," said Jerry, "that you buried paving-stones and earth in
\par that there coffin. Don't go and tell me that you buried Cly. It was a
\par take in. Me and two more knows it."
\par 
\par "How do you know it?"
\par 
\par "What's that to you? Ecod!" growled Mr. Cruncher, "it's you I have got a
\par old grudge again, is it, with your shameful impositions upon tradesmen!
\par I'd catch hold of your throat and choke you for half a guinea."
\par 
\par Sydney Carton, who, with Mr. Lorry, had been lost in amazement at
\par this turn of the business, here requested Mr. Cruncher to moderate and
\par explain himself.
\par 
\par "At another time, sir," he returned, evasively, "the present time is
\par ill-conwenient for explainin'. What I stand to, is, that he knows well
\par wot that there Cly was never in that there coffin. Let him say he was,
\par in so much as a word of one syllable, and I'll either catch hold of his
\par throat and choke him for half a guinea;" Mr. Cruncher dwelt upon this as
\par quite a liberal offer; "or I'll out and announce him."
\par 
\par "Humph! I see one thing," said Carton. "I hold another card, Mr. Barsad.
\par Impossible, here in raging Paris, with Suspicion filling the air, for
\par you to outlive denunciation, when you are in communication with another
\par aristocratic spy of the same antecedents as yourself, who, moreover, has
\par the mystery about him of having feigned death and come to life again!
\par A plot in the prisons, of the foreigner against the Republic. A strong
\par card--a certain Guillotine card! Do you play?"
\par 
\par "No!" returned the spy. "I throw up. I confess that we were so unpopular
\par with the outrageous mob, that I only got away from England at the risk
\par of being ducked to death, and that Cly was so ferreted up and down, that
\par he never would have got away at all but for that sham. Though how this
\par man knows it was a sham, is a wonder of wonders to me."
\par 
\par "Never you trouble your head about this man," retorted the contentious
\par Mr. Cruncher; "you'll have trouble enough with giving your attention to
\par that gentleman. And look here! Once more!"--Mr. Cruncher could not
\par be restrained from making rather an ostentatious parade of his
\par liberality--"I'd catch hold of your throat and choke you for half a
\par guinea."
\par 
\par The Sheep of the prisons turned from him to Sydney Carton, and said,
\par with more decision, "It has come to a point. I go on duty soon, and
\par can't overstay my time. You told me you had a proposal; what is it?
\par Now, it is of no use asking too much of me. Ask me to do anything in my
\par office, putting my head in great extra danger, and I had better trust my
\par life to the chances of a refusal than the chances of consent. In short,
\par I should make that choice. You talk of desperation. We are all desperate
\par here. Remember! I may denounce you if I think proper, and I can swear my
\par way through stone walls, and so can others. Now, what do you want with
\par me?"
\par 
\par "Not very much. You are a turnkey at the Conciergerie?"
\par 
\par "I tell you once for all, there is no such thing as an escape possible,"
\par said the spy, firmly.
\par 
\par "Why need you tell me what I have not asked? You are a turnkey at the
\par Conciergerie?"
\par 
\par "I am sometimes."
\par 
\par "You can be when you choose?"
\par 
\par "I can pass in and out when I choose."
\par 
\par Sydney Carton filled another glass with brandy, poured it slowly out
\par upon the hearth, and watched it as it dropped. It being all spent, he
\par said, rising:
\par 
\par "So far, we have spoken before these two, because it was as well that
\par the merits of the cards should not rest solely between you and me. Come
\par into the dark room here, and let us have one final word alone."
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par IX. The Game Made
\par 
\par 
\par While Sydney Carton and the Sheep of the prisons were in the adjoining
\par dark room, speaking so low that not a sound was heard, Mr. Lorry looked
\par at Jerry in considerable doubt and mistrust. That honest tradesman's
\par manner of receiving the look, did not inspire confidence; he changed the
\par leg on which he rested, as often as if he had fifty of those limbs,
\par and were trying them all; he examined his finger-nails with a very
\par questionable closeness of attention; and whenever Mr. Lorry's eye caught
\par his, he was taken with that peculiar kind of short cough requiring the
\par hollow of a hand before it, which is seldom, if ever, known to be an
\par infirmity attendant on perfect openness of character.
\par 
\par "Jerry," said Mr. Lorry. "Come here."
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher came forward sideways, with one of his shoulders in advance
\par of him.
\par 
\par "What have you been, besides a messenger?"
\par 
\par After some cogitation, accompanied with an intent look at his patron,
\par Mr. Cruncher conceived the luminous idea of replying, "Agicultooral
\par character."
\par 
\par "My mind misgives me much," said Mr. Lorry, angrily shaking a forefinger
\par at him, "that you have used the respectable and great house of Tellson's
\par as a blind, and that you have had an unlawful occupation of an infamous
\par description. If you have, don't expect me to befriend you when you
\par get back to England. If you have, don't expect me to keep your secret.
\par Tellson's shall not be imposed upon."
\par 
\par "I hope, sir," pleaded the abashed Mr. Cruncher, "that a gentleman like
\par yourself wot I've had the honour of odd jobbing till I'm grey at it,
\par would think twice about harming of me, even if it wos so--I don't say it
\par is, but even if it wos. And which it is to be took into account that if
\par it wos, it wouldn't, even then, be all o' one side. There'd be two sides
\par to it. There might be medical doctors at the present hour, a picking
\par up their guineas where a honest tradesman don't pick up his
\par fardens--fardens! no, nor yet his half fardens--half fardens! no, nor
\par yet his quarter--a banking away like smoke at Tellson's, and a cocking
\par their medical eyes at that tradesman on the sly, a going in and going
\par out to their own carriages--ah! equally like smoke, if not more so.
\par Well, that 'ud be imposing, too, on Tellson's. For you cannot sarse the
\par goose and not the gander. And here's Mrs. Cruncher, or leastways wos
\par in the Old England times, and would be to-morrow, if cause given,
\par a floppin' again the business to that degree as is ruinating--stark
\par ruinating! Whereas them medical doctors' wives don't flop--catch 'em at
\par it! Or, if they flop, their floppings goes in favour of more patients,
\par and how can you rightly have one without t'other? Then, wot with
\par undertakers, and wot with parish clerks, and wot with sextons, and wot
\par with private watchmen (all awaricious and all in it), a man wouldn't get
\par much by it, even if it wos so. And wot little a man did get, would never
\par prosper with him, Mr. Lorry. He'd never have no good of it; he'd want
\par all along to be out of the line, if he, could see his way out, being
\par once in--even if it wos so."
\par 
\par "Ugh!" cried Mr. Lorry, rather relenting, nevertheless, "I am shocked at
\par the sight of you."
\par 
\par "Now, what I would humbly offer to you, sir," pursued Mr. Cruncher,
\par "even if it wos so, which I don't say it is--"
\par 
\par "Don't prevaricate," said Mr. Lorry.
\par 
\par "No, I will _not_, sir," returned Mr. Crunches as if nothing were
\par further from his thoughts or practice--"which I don't say it is--wot I
\par would humbly offer to you, sir, would be this. Upon that there stool, at
\par that there Bar, sets that there boy of mine, brought up and growed up to
\par be a man, wot will errand you, message you, general-light-job you, till
\par your heels is where your head is, if such should be your wishes. If it
\par wos so, which I still don't say it is (for I will not prewaricate to
\par you, sir), let that there boy keep his father's place, and take care of
\par his mother; don't blow upon that boy's father--do not do it, sir--and
\par let that father go into the line of the reg'lar diggin', and make amends
\par for what he would have undug--if it wos so--by diggin' of 'em in with
\par a will, and with conwictions respectin' the futur' keepin' of 'em safe.
\par That, Mr. Lorry," said Mr. Cruncher, wiping his forehead with his
\par arm, as an announcement that he had arrived at the peroration of his
\par discourse, "is wot I would respectfully offer to you, sir. A man don't
\par see all this here a goin' on dreadful round him, in the way of Subjects
\par without heads, dear me, plentiful enough fur to bring the price down
\par to porterage and hardly that, without havin' his serious thoughts of
\par things. And these here would be mine, if it wos so, entreatin' of you
\par fur to bear in mind that wot I said just now, I up and said in the good
\par cause when I might have kep' it back."
\par 
\par "That at least is true," said Mr. Lorry. "Say no more now. It may be
\par that I shall yet stand your friend, if you deserve it, and repent in
\par action--not in words. I want no more words."
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher knuckled his forehead, as Sydney Carton and the spy
\par returned from the dark room. "Adieu, Mr. Barsad," said the former; "our
\par arrangement thus made, you have nothing to fear from me."
\par 
\par He sat down in a chair on the hearth, over against Mr. Lorry. When they
\par were alone, Mr. Lorry asked him what he had done?
\par 
\par "Not much. If it should go ill with the prisoner, I have ensured access
\par to him, once."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry's countenance fell.
\par 
\par "It is all I could do," said Carton. "To propose too much, would be
\par to put this man's head under the axe, and, as he himself said, nothing
\par worse could happen to him if he were denounced. It was obviously the
\par weakness of the position. There is no help for it."
\par 
\par "But access to him," said Mr. Lorry, "if it should go ill before the
\par Tribunal, will not save him."
\par 
\par "I never said it would."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry's eyes gradually sought the fire; his sympathy with his
\par darling, and the heavy disappointment of his second arrest, gradually
\par weakened them; he was an old man now, overborne with anxiety of late,
\par and his tears fell.
\par 
\par "You are a good man and a true friend," said Carton, in an altered
\par voice. "Forgive me if I notice that you are affected. I could not see my
\par father weep, and sit by, careless. And I could not respect your
\par sorrow more, if you were my father. You are free from that misfortune,
\par however."
\par 
\par Though he said the last words, with a slip into his usual manner, there
\par was a true feeling and respect both in his tone and in his touch,
\par that Mr. Lorry, who had never seen the better side of him, was wholly
\par unprepared for. He gave him his hand, and Carton gently pressed it.
\par 
\par "To return to poor Darnay," said Carton. "Don't tell Her of this
\par interview, or this arrangement. It would not enable Her to go to see
\par him. She might think it was contrived, in case of the worse, to convey
\par to him the means of anticipating the sentence."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry had not thought of that, and he looked quickly at Carton to
\par see if it were in his mind. It seemed to be; he returned the look, and
\par evidently understood it.
\par 
\par "She might think a thousand things," Carton said, "and any of them would
\par only add to her trouble. Don't speak of me to her. As I said to you when
\par I first came, I had better not see her. I can put my hand out, to do any
\par little helpful work for her that my hand can find to do, without that.
\par You are going to her, I hope? She must be very desolate to-night."
\par 
\par "I am going now, directly."
\par 
\par "I am glad of that. She has such a strong attachment to you and reliance
\par on you. How does she look?"
\par 
\par "Anxious and unhappy, but very beautiful."
\par 
\par "Ah!"
\par 
\par It was a long, grieving sound, like a sigh--almost like a sob. It
\par attracted Mr. Lorry's eyes to Carton's face, which was turned to the
\par fire. A light, or a shade (the old gentleman could not have said which),
\par passed from it as swiftly as a change will sweep over a hill-side on a
\par wild bright day, and he lifted his foot to put back one of the little
\par flaming logs, which was tumbling forward. He wore the white riding-coat
\par and top-boots, then in vogue, and the light of the fire touching their
\par light surfaces made him look very pale, with his long brown hair,
\par all untrimmed, hanging loose about him. His indifference to fire was
\par sufficiently remarkable to elicit a word of remonstrance from Mr. Lorry;
\par his boot was still upon the hot embers of the flaming log, when it had
\par broken under the weight of his foot.
\par 
\par "I forgot it," he said.
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry's eyes were again attracted to his face. Taking note of the
\par wasted air which clouded the naturally handsome features, and having
\par the expression of prisoners' faces fresh in his mind, he was strongly
\par reminded of that expression.
\par 
\par "And your duties here have drawn to an end, sir?" said Carton, turning
\par to him.
\par 
\par "Yes. As I was telling you last night when Lucie came in so
\par unexpectedly, I have at length done all that I can do here. I hoped to
\par have left them in perfect safety, and then to have quitted Paris. I have
\par my Leave to Pass. I was ready to go."
\par 
\par They were both silent.
\par 
\par "Yours is a long life to look back upon, sir?" said Carton, wistfully.
\par 
\par "I am in my seventy-eighth year."
\par 
\par "You have been useful all your life; steadily and constantly occupied;
\par trusted, respected, and looked up to?"
\par 
\par "I have been a man of business, ever since I have been a man. Indeed, I
\par may say that I was a man of business when a boy."
\par 
\par "See what a place you fill at seventy-eight. How many people will miss
\par you when you leave it empty!"
\par 
\par "A solitary old bachelor," answered Mr. Lorry, shaking his head. "There
\par is nobody to weep for me."
\par 
\par "How can you say that? Wouldn't She weep for you? Wouldn't her child?"
\par 
\par "Yes, yes, thank God. I didn't quite mean what I said."
\par 
\par "It _is_ a thing to thank God for; is it not?"
\par 
\par "Surely, surely."
\par 
\par "If you could say, with truth, to your own solitary heart, to-night,
\par 'I have secured to myself the love and attachment, the gratitude or
\par respect, of no human creature; I have won myself a tender place in no
\par regard; I have done nothing good or serviceable to be remembered by!'
\par your seventy-eight years would be seventy-eight heavy curses; would they
\par not?"
\par 
\par "You say truly, Mr. Carton; I think they would be."
\par 
\par Sydney turned his eyes again upon the fire, and, after a silence of a
\par few moments, said:
\par 
\par "I should like to ask you:--Does your childhood seem far off? Do the
\par days when you sat at your mother's knee, seem days of very long ago?"
\par 
\par Responding to his softened manner, Mr. Lorry answered:
\par 
\par "Twenty years back, yes; at this time of my life, no. For, as I draw
\par closer and closer to the end, I travel in the circle, nearer and
\par nearer to the beginning. It seems to be one of the kind smoothings and
\par preparings of the way. My heart is touched now, by many remembrances
\par that had long fallen asleep, of my pretty young mother (and I so old!),
\par and by many associations of the days when what we call the World was not
\par so real with me, and my faults were not confirmed in me."
\par 
\par "I understand the feeling!" exclaimed Carton, with a bright flush. "And
\par you are the better for it?"
\par 
\par "I hope so."
\par 
\par Carton terminated the conversation here, by rising to help him on with
\par his outer coat; "But you," said Mr. Lorry, reverting to the theme, "you
\par are young."
\par 
\par "Yes," said Carton. "I am not old, but my young way was never the way to
\par age. Enough of me."
\par 
\par "And of me, I am sure," said Mr. Lorry. "Are you going out?"
\par 
\par "I'll walk with you to her gate. You know my vagabond and restless
\par habits. If I should prowl about the streets a long time, don't be
\par uneasy; I shall reappear in the morning. You go to the Court to-morrow?"
\par 
\par "Yes, unhappily."
\par 
\par "I shall be there, but only as one of the crowd. My Spy will find a
\par place for me. Take my arm, sir."
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry did so, and they went down-stairs and out in the streets. A
\par few minutes brought them to Mr. Lorry's destination. Carton left him
\par there; but lingered at a little distance, and turned back to the gate
\par again when it was shut, and touched it. He had heard of her going to
\par the prison every day. "She came out here," he said, looking about him,
\par "turned this way, must have trod on these stones often. Let me follow in
\par her steps."
\par 
\par It was ten o'clock at night when he stood before the prison of La Force,
\par where she had stood hundreds of times. A little wood-sawyer, having
\par closed his shop, was smoking his pipe at his shop-door.
\par 
\par "Good night, citizen," said Sydney Carton, pausing in going by; for, the
\par man eyed him inquisitively.
\par 
\par "Good night, citizen."
\par 
\par "How goes the Republic?"
\par 
\par "You mean the Guillotine. Not ill. Sixty-three to-day. We shall mount
\par to a hundred soon. Samson and his men complain sometimes, of being
\par exhausted. Ha, ha, ha! He is so droll, that Samson. Such a Barber!"
\par 
\par "Do you often go to see him--"
\par 
\par "Shave? Always. Every day. What a barber! You have seen him at work?"
\par 
\par "Never."
\par 
\par "Go and see him when he has a good batch. Figure this to yourself,
\par citizen; he shaved the sixty-three to-day, in less than two pipes! Less
\par than two pipes. Word of honour!"
\par 
\par As the grinning little man held out the pipe he was smoking, to explain
\par how he timed the executioner, Carton was so sensible of a rising desire
\par to strike the life out of him, that he turned away.
\par 
\par "But you are not English," said the wood-sawyer, "though you wear
\par English dress?"
\par 
\par "Yes," said Carton, pausing again, and answering over his shoulder.
\par 
\par "You speak like a Frenchman."
\par 
\par "I am an old student here."
\par 
\par "Aha, a perfect Frenchman! Good night, Englishman."
\par 
\par "Good night, citizen."
\par 
\par "But go and see that droll dog," the little man persisted, calling after
\par him. "And take a pipe with you!"
\par 
\par Sydney had not gone far out of sight, when he stopped in the middle of
\par the street under a glimmering lamp, and wrote with his pencil on a scrap
\par of paper. Then, traversing with the decided step of one who remembered
\par the way well, several dark and dirty streets--much dirtier than usual,
\par for the best public thoroughfares remained uncleansed in those times of
\par terror--he stopped at a chemist's shop, which the owner was closing with
\par his own hands. A small, dim, crooked shop, kept in a tortuous, up-hill
\par thoroughfare, by a small, dim, crooked man.
\par 
\par Giving this citizen, too, good night, as he confronted him at his
\par counter, he laid the scrap of paper before him. "Whew!" the chemist
\par whistled softly, as he read it. "Hi! hi! hi!"
\par 
\par Sydney Carton took no heed, and the chemist said:
\par 
\par "For you, citizen?"
\par 
\par "For me."
\par 
\par "You will be careful to keep them separate, citizen? You know the
\par consequences of mixing them?"
\par 
\par "Perfectly."
\par 
\par Certain small packets were made and given to him. He put them, one by
\par one, in the breast of his inner coat, counted out the money for them,
\par and deliberately left the shop. "There is nothing more to do," said he,
\par glancing upward at the moon, "until to-morrow. I can't sleep."
\par 
\par It was not a reckless manner, the manner in which he said these words
\par aloud under the fast-sailing clouds, nor was it more expressive of
\par negligence than defiance. It was the settled manner of a tired man, who
\par had wandered and struggled and got lost, but who at length struck into
\par his road and saw its end.
\par 
\par Long ago, when he had been famous among his earliest competitors as a
\par youth of great promise, he had followed his father to the grave. His
\par mother had died, years before. These solemn words, which had been
\par read at his father's grave, arose in his mind as he went down the dark
\par streets, among the heavy shadows, with the moon and the clouds sailing
\par on high above him. "I am the resurrection and the life, saith the Lord:
\par he that believeth in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live: and
\par whosoever liveth and believeth in me, shall never die."
\par 
\par In a city dominated by the axe, alone at night, with natural sorrow
\par rising in him for the sixty-three who had been that day put to death,
\par and for to-morrow's victims then awaiting their doom in the prisons,
\par and still of to-morrow's and to-morrow's, the chain of association that
\par brought the words home, like a rusty old ship's anchor from the deep,
\par might have been easily found. He did not seek it, but repeated them and
\par went on.
\par 
\par With a solemn interest in the lighted windows where the people were
\par going to rest, forgetful through a few calm hours of the horrors
\par surrounding them; in the towers of the churches, where no prayers
\par were said, for the popular revulsion had even travelled that length
\par of self-destruction from years of priestly impostors, plunderers, and
\par profligates; in the distant burial-places, reserved, as they wrote upon
\par the gates, for Eternal Sleep; in the abounding gaols; and in the streets
\par along which the sixties rolled to a death which had become so common and
\par material, that no sorrowful story of a haunting Spirit ever arose among
