\par 
\par 
\par 
\par X. The Substance of the Shadow
\par 
\par 
\par "I, Alexandre Manette, unfortunate physician, native of Beauvais, and
\par afterwards resident in Paris, write this melancholy paper in my doleful
\par cell in the Bastille, during the last month of the year, 1767. I write
\par it at stolen intervals, under every difficulty. I design to secrete it
\par in the wall of the chimney, where I have slowly and laboriously made a
\par place of concealment for it. Some pitying hand may find it there, when I
\par and my sorrows are dust.
\par 
\par "These words are formed by the rusty iron point with which I write with
\par difficulty in scrapings of soot and charcoal from the chimney, mixed
\par with blood, in the last month of the tenth year of my captivity. Hope
\par has quite departed from my breast. I know from terrible warnings I have
\par noted in myself that my reason will not long remain unimpaired, but I
\par solemnly declare that I am at this time in the possession of my right
\par mind--that my memory is exact and circumstantial--and that I write the
\par truth as I shall answer for these my last recorded words, whether they
\par be ever read by men or not, at the Eternal Judgment-seat.
\par 
\par "One cloudy moonlight night, in the third week of December (I think the
\par twenty-second of the month) in the year 1757, I was walking on a retired
\par part of the quay by the Seine for the refreshment of the frosty air,
\par at an hour's distance from my place of residence in the Street of the
\par School of Medicine, when a carriage came along behind me, driven very
\par fast. As I stood aside to let that carriage pass, apprehensive that it
\par might otherwise run me down, a head was put out at the window, and a
\par voice called to the driver to stop.
\par 
\par "The carriage stopped as soon as the driver could rein in his horses,
\par and the same voice called to me by my name. I answered. The carriage
\par was then so far in advance of me that two gentlemen had time to open the
\par door and alight before I came up with it.
\par 
\par "I observed that they were both wrapped in cloaks, and appeared to
\par conceal themselves. As they stood side by side near the carriage door,
\par I also observed that they both looked of about my own age, or rather
\par younger, and that they were greatly alike, in stature, manner, voice,
\par and (as far as I could see) face too.
\par 
\par "'You are Doctor Manette?' said one.
\par 
\par "I am."
\par 
\par "'Doctor Manette, formerly of Beauvais,' said the other; 'the young
\par physician, originally an expert surgeon, who within the last year or two
\par has made a rising reputation in Paris?'
\par 
\par "'Gentlemen,' I returned, 'I am that Doctor Manette of whom you speak so
\par graciously.'
\par 
\par "'We have been to your residence,' said the first, 'and not being
\par so fortunate as to find you there, and being informed that you were
\par probably walking in this direction, we followed, in the hope of
\par overtaking you. Will you please to enter the carriage?'
\par 
\par "The manner of both was imperious, and they both moved, as these words
\par were spoken, so as to place me between themselves and the carriage door.
\par They were armed. I was not.
\par 
\par "'Gentlemen,' said I, 'pardon me; but I usually inquire who does me
\par the honour to seek my assistance, and what is the nature of the case to
\par which I am summoned.'
\par 
\par "The reply to this was made by him who had spoken second. 'Doctor,
\par your clients are people of condition. As to the nature of the case,
\par our confidence in your skill assures us that you will ascertain it for
\par yourself better than we can describe it. Enough. Will you please to
\par enter the carriage?'
\par 
\par "I could do nothing but comply, and I entered it in silence. They both
\par entered after me--the last springing in, after putting up the steps. The
\par carriage turned about, and drove on at its former speed.
\par 
\par "I repeat this conversation exactly as it occurred. I have no doubt that
\par it is, word for word, the same. I describe everything exactly as it took
\par place, constraining my mind not to wander from the task. Where I make
\par the broken marks that follow here, I leave off for the time, and put my
\par paper in its hiding-place.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "The carriage left the streets behind, passed the North Barrier, and
\par emerged upon the country road. At two-thirds of a league from the
\par Barrier--I did not estimate the distance at that time, but afterwards
\par when I traversed it--it struck out of the main avenue, and presently
\par stopped at a solitary house, We all three alighted, and walked, by
\par a damp soft footpath in a garden where a neglected fountain had
\par overflowed, to the door of the house. It was not opened immediately, in
\par answer to the ringing of the bell, and one of my two conductors struck
\par the man who opened it, with his heavy riding glove, across the face.
\par 
\par "There was nothing in this action to attract my particular attention,
\par for I had seen common people struck more commonly than dogs. But, the
\par other of the two, being angry likewise, struck the man in like manner
\par with his arm; the look and bearing of the brothers were then so exactly
\par alike, that I then first perceived them to be twin brothers.
\par 
\par "From the time of our alighting at the outer gate (which we found
\par locked, and which one of the brothers had opened to admit us, and had
\par relocked), I had heard cries proceeding from an upper chamber. I was
\par conducted to this chamber straight, the cries growing louder as we
\par ascended the stairs, and I found a patient in a high fever of the brain,
\par lying on a bed.
\par 
\par "The patient was a woman of great beauty, and young; assuredly not much
\par past twenty. Her hair was torn and ragged, and her arms were bound to
\par her sides with sashes and handkerchiefs. I noticed that these bonds were
\par all portions of a gentleman's dress. On one of them, which was a fringed
\par scarf for a dress of ceremony, I saw the armorial bearings of a Noble,
\par and the letter E.
\par 
\par "I saw this, within the first minute of my contemplation of the patient;
\par for, in her restless strivings she had turned over on her face on the
\par edge of the bed, had drawn the end of the scarf into her mouth, and was
\par in danger of suffocation. My first act was to put out my hand to relieve
\par her breathing; and in moving the scarf aside, the embroidery in the
\par corner caught my sight.
\par 
\par "I turned her gently over, placed my hands upon her breast to calm her
\par and keep her down, and looked into her face. Her eyes were dilated and
\par wild, and she constantly uttered piercing shrieks, and repeated the
\par words, 'My husband, my father, and my brother!' and then counted up to
\par twelve, and said, 'Hush!' For an instant, and no more, she would pause
\par to listen, and then the piercing shrieks would begin again, and she
\par would repeat the cry, 'My husband, my father, and my brother!' and
\par would count up to twelve, and say, 'Hush!' There was no variation in the
\par order, or the manner. There was no cessation, but the regular moment's
\par pause, in the utterance of these sounds.
\par 
\par "'How long,' I asked, 'has this lasted?'
\par 
\par "To distinguish the brothers, I will call them the elder and the
\par younger; by the elder, I mean him who exercised the most authority. It
\par was the elder who replied, 'Since about this hour last night.'
\par 
\par "'She has a husband, a father, and a brother?'
\par 
\par "'A brother.'
\par 
\par "'I do not address her brother?'
\par 
\par "He answered with great contempt, 'No.'
\par 
\par "'She has some recent association with the number twelve?'
\par 
\par "The younger brother impatiently rejoined, 'With twelve o'clock?'
\par 
\par "'See, gentlemen,' said I, still keeping my hands upon her breast, 'how
\par useless I am, as you have brought me! If I had known what I was coming
\par to see, I could have come provided. As it is, time must be lost. There
\par are no medicines to be obtained in this lonely place.'
\par 
\par "The elder brother looked to the younger, who said haughtily, 'There is
\par a case of medicines here;' and brought it from a closet, and put it on
\par the table.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "I opened some of the bottles, smelt them, and put the stoppers to my
\par lips. If I had wanted to use anything save narcotic medicines that were
\par poisons in themselves, I would not have administered any of those.
\par 
\par "'Do you doubt them?' asked the younger brother.
\par 
\par "'You see, monsieur, I am going to use them,' I replied, and said no
\par more.
\par 
\par "I made the patient swallow, with great difficulty, and after many
\par efforts, the dose that I desired to give. As I intended to repeat it
\par after a while, and as it was necessary to watch its influence, I then
\par sat down by the side of the bed. There was a timid and suppressed woman
\par in attendance (wife of the man down-stairs), who had retreated into
\par a corner. The house was damp and decayed, indifferently
\par furnished--evidently, recently occupied and temporarily used. Some thick
\par old hangings had been nailed up before the windows, to deaden the
\par sound of the shrieks. They continued to be uttered in their regular
