\par this my cell in the Bastille, near the close of the tenth year of my
\par captivity, as I saw them all that night.
\par 
\par "On some hay on the ground, with a cushion thrown under his head, lay a
\par handsome peasant boy--a boy of not more than seventeen at the most.
\par He lay on his back, with his teeth set, his right hand clenched on his
\par breast, and his glaring eyes looking straight upward. I could not see
\par where his wound was, as I kneeled on one knee over him; but, I could see
\par that he was dying of a wound from a sharp point.
\par 
