\par 
\par "'I do not want it examined,' he answered; 'let it be.'
\par 
\par "It was under his hand, and I soothed him to let me move his hand away.
\par The wound was a sword-thrust, received from twenty to twenty-four hours
\par before, but no skill could have saved him if it had been looked to
\par without delay. He was then dying fast. As I turned my eyes to the elder
\par brother, I saw him looking down at this handsome boy whose life was
\par ebbing out, as if he were a wounded bird, or hare, or rabbit; not at all
\par as if he were a fellow-creature.
\par 
\par "'How has this been done, monsieur?' said I.
\par 
\par "'A crazed young common dog! A serf! Forced my brother to draw upon him,
\par and has fallen by my brother's sword--like a gentleman.'
\par 
\par "There was no touch of pity, sorrow, or kindred humanity, in this
\par answer. The speaker seemed to acknowledge that it was inconvenient to
\par have that different order of creature dying there, and that it would
\par have been better if he had died in the usual obscure routine of his
\par vermin kind. He was quite incapable of any compassionate feeling about
\par the boy, or about his fate.
\par 
\par "The boy's eyes had slowly moved to him as he had spoken, and they now
\par slowly moved to me.
\par 
\par "'Doctor, they are very proud, these Nobles; but we common dogs are
\par proud too, sometimes. They plunder us, outrage us, beat us, kill us; but
\par we have a little pride left, sometimes. She--have you seen her, Doctor?'
\par 
\par "The shrieks and the cries were audible there, though subdued by the
\par distance. He referred to them, as if she were lying in our presence.
\par 
\par "I said, 'I have seen her.'
\par 
\par "'She is my sister, Doctor. They have had their shameful rights, these
\par Nobles, in the modesty and virtue of our sisters, many years, but we
\par have had good girls among us. I know it, and have heard my father say
\par so. She was a good girl. She was betrothed to a good young man, too: a
\par tenant of his. We were all tenants of his--that man's who stands there.
\par The other is his brother, the worst of a bad race.'
\par 
\par "It was with the greatest difficulty that the boy gathered bodily force
\par to speak; but, his spirit spoke with a dreadful emphasis.
\par 
\par "'We were so robbed by that man who stands there, as all we common dogs
\par are by those superior Beings--taxed by him without mercy, obliged to
\par work for him without pay, obliged to grind our corn at his mill, obliged
\par to feed scores of his tame birds on our wretched crops, and forbidden
\par for our lives to keep a single tame bird of our own, pillaged and
\par plundered to that degree that when we chanced to have a bit of meat, we
\par ate it in fear, with the door barred and the shutters closed, that his
\par people should not see it and take it from us--I say, we were so robbed,
\par and hunted, and were made so poor, that our father told us it was a
\par dreadful thing to bring a child into the world, and that what we should
\par most pray for, was, that our women might be barren and our miserable
\par race die out!'
\par 
\par "I had never before seen the sense of being oppressed, bursting forth
\par like a fire. I had supposed that it must be latent in the people
\par somewhere; but, I had never seen it break out, until I saw it in the
\par dying boy.
\par 
\par "'Nevertheless, Doctor, my sister married. He was ailing at that time,
\par poor fellow, and she married her lover, that she might tend and comfort
\par him in our cottage--our dog-hut, as that man would call it. She had not
\par been married many weeks, when that man's brother saw her and admired
\par her, and asked that man to lend her to him--for what are husbands among
\par us! He was willing enough, but my sister was good and virtuous, and
\par hated his brother with a hatred as strong as mine. What did the two
\par then, to persuade her husband to use his influence with her, to make her
\par willing?'
\par 
\par "The boy's eyes, which had been fixed on mine, slowly turned to the
\par looker-on, and I saw in the two faces that all he said was true. The two
\par opposing kinds of pride confronting one another, I can see, even in this
\par Bastille; the gentleman's, all negligent indifference; the peasant's, all
\par trodden-down sentiment, and passionate revenge.
\par 
\par "'You know, Doctor, that it is among the Rights of these Nobles to
\par harness us common dogs to carts, and drive us. They so harnessed him and
\par drove him. You know that it is among their Rights to keep us in their
\par grounds all night, quieting the frogs, in order that their noble sleep
\par may not be disturbed. They kept him out in the unwholesome mists at
\par night, and ordered him back into his harness in the day. But he was
\par not persuaded. No! Taken out of harness one day at noon, to feed--if he
\par could find food--he sobbed twelve times, once for every stroke of the
\par bell, and died on her bosom.'
\par 
\par "Nothing human could have held life in the boy but his determination to
\par tell all his wrong. He forced back the gathering shadows of death, as
\par he forced his clenched right hand to remain clenched, and to cover his
\par wound.
\par 
\par "'Then, with that man's permission and even with his aid, his
\par brother took her away; in spite of what I know she must have told his
\par brother--and what that is, will not be long unknown to you, Doctor, if
\par it is now--his brother took her away--for his pleasure and diversion,
\par for a little while. I saw her pass me on the road. When I took the
\par tidings home, our father's heart burst; he never spoke one of the words
\par that filled it. I took my young sister (for I have another) to a place
\par beyond the reach of this man, and where, at least, she will never be
\par _his_ vassal. Then, I tracked the brother here, and last night climbed
\par in--a common dog, but sword in hand.--Where is the loft window? It was
\par somewhere here?'
\par 
\par "The room was darkening to his sight; the world was narrowing around
\par him. I glanced about me, and saw that the hay and straw were trampled
\par over the floor, as if there had been a struggle.
\par 
\par "'She heard me, and ran in. I told her not to come near us till he was
\par dead. He came in and first tossed me some pieces of money; then struck
\par at me with a whip. But I, though a common dog, so struck at him as to
\par make him draw. Let him break into as many pieces as he will, the sword
\par that he stained with my common blood; he drew to defend himself--thrust
\par at me with all his skill for his life.'
\par 
\par "My glance had fallen, but a few moments before, on the fragments of
\par a broken sword, lying among the hay. That weapon was a gentleman's. In
\par another place, lay an old sword that seemed to have been a soldier's.
\par 
\par "'Now, lift me up, Doctor; lift me up. Where is he?'
\par 
\par "'He is not here,' I said, supporting the boy, and thinking that he
\par referred to the brother.
\par 
\par "'He! Proud as these nobles are, he is afraid to see me. Where is the
\par man who was here? Turn my face to him.'
\par 
\par "I did so, raising the boy's head against my knee. But, invested for the
\par moment with extraordinary power, he raised himself completely: obliging
\par me to rise too, or I could not have still supported him.
\par 
\par "'Marquis,' said the boy, turned to him with his eyes opened wide, and
\par his right hand raised, 'in the days when all these things are to be
\par answered for, I summon you and yours, to the last of your bad race, to
\par answer for them. I mark this cross of blood upon you, as a sign that
\par I do it. In the days when all these things are to be answered for,
\par I summon your brother, the worst of the bad race, to answer for them
\par separately. I mark this cross of blood upon him, as a sign that I do
\par it.'
\par 
\par "Twice, he put his hand to the wound in his breast, and with his
\par forefinger drew a cross in the air. He stood for an instant with the
\par finger yet raised, and as it dropped, he dropped with it, and I laid him
\par down dead.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "When I returned to the bedside of the young woman, I found her raving
\par in precisely the same order of continuity. I knew that this might last
\par for many hours, and that it would probably end in the silence of the
\par grave.
\par 
\par "I repeated the medicines I had given her, and I sat at the side of
\par the bed until the night was far advanced. She never abated the piercing
\par quality of her shrieks, never stumbled in the distinctness or the order
\par of her words. They were always 'My husband, my father, and my brother!
\par One, two, three, four, five, six, seven, eight, nine, ten, eleven,
\par twelve. Hush!'
\par 
\par "This lasted twenty-six hours from the time when I first saw her. I had
\par come and gone twice, and was again sitting by her, when she began to
\par falter. I did what little could be done to assist that opportunity, and
\par by-and-bye she sank into a lethargy, and lay like the dead.
\par 
\par "It was as if the wind and rain had lulled at last, after a long and
\par fearful storm. I released her arms, and called the woman to assist me to
\par compose her figure and the dress she had torn. It was then that I knew
\par her condition to be that of one in whom the first expectations of being
\par a mother have arisen; and it was then that I lost the little hope I had
\par had of her.
\par 
\par "'Is she dead?' asked the Marquis, whom I will still describe as the
\par elder brother, coming booted into the room from his horse.
\par 
\par "'Not dead,' said I; 'but like to die.'
\par 
\par "'What strength there is in these common bodies!' he said, looking down
\par at her with some curiosity.
\par 
\par "'There is prodigious strength,' I answered him, 'in sorrow and
\par despair.'
\par 
\par "He first laughed at my words, and then frowned at them. He moved a
\par chair with his foot near to mine, ordered the woman away, and said in a
\par subdued voice,
\par 
\par "'Doctor, finding my brother in this difficulty with these hinds, I
\par recommended that your aid should be invited. Your reputation is high,
\par and, as a young man with your fortune to make, you are probably mindful
\par of your interest. The things that you see here, are things to be seen,
\par and not spoken of.'
\par 
\par "I listened to the patient's breathing, and avoided answering.
\par 
\par "'Do you honour me with your attention, Doctor?'
\par 
\par "'Monsieur,' said I, 'in my profession, the communications of patients
\par are always received in confidence.' I was guarded in my answer, for I
\par was troubled in my mind with what I had heard and seen.
\par 
\par "Her breathing was so difficult to trace, that I carefully tried the
\par pulse and the heart. There was life, and no more. Looking round as I
\par resumed my seat, I found both the brothers intent upon me.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "I write with so much difficulty, the cold is so severe, I am so
\par fearful of being detected and consigned to an underground cell and total
\par darkness, that I must abridge this narrative. There is no confusion or
\par failure in my memory; it can recall, and could detail, every word that
\par was ever spoken between me and those brothers.
\par 
\par "She lingered for a week. Towards the last, I could understand some few
\par syllables that she said to me, by placing my ear close to her lips. She
\par asked me where she was, and I told her; who I was, and I told her. It
\par was in vain that I asked her for her family name. She faintly shook her
\par head upon the pillow, and kept her secret, as the boy had done.
\par 
\par "I had no opportunity of asking her any question, until I had told the
\par brothers she was sinking fast, and could not live another day. Until
\par then, though no one was ever presented to her consciousness save the
\par woman and myself, one or other of them had always jealously sat behind
\par the curtain at the head of the bed when I was there. But when it came to
\par that, they seemed careless what communication I might hold with her; as
\par if--the thought passed through my mind--I were dying too.
\par 
\par "I always observed that their pride bitterly resented the younger
\par brother's (as I call him) having crossed swords with a peasant, and that
\par peasant a boy. The only consideration that appeared to affect the mind
\par of either of them was the consideration that this was highly degrading
\par to the family, and was ridiculous. As often as I caught the younger
\par brother's eyes, their expression reminded me that he disliked me deeply,
\par for knowing what I knew from the boy. He was smoother and more polite to
\par me than the elder; but I saw this. I also saw that I was an incumbrance
\par in the mind of the elder, too.
\par 
\par "My patient died, two hours before midnight--at a time, by my watch,
\par answering almost to the minute when I had first seen her. I was alone
\par with her, when her forlorn young head drooped gently on one side, and
\par all her earthly wrongs and sorrows ended.
\par 
\par "The brothers were waiting in a room down-stairs, impatient to ride
\par away. I had heard them, alone at the bedside, striking their boots with
\par their riding-whips, and loitering up and down.
\par 
\par "'At last she is dead?' said the elder, when I went in.
\par 
\par "'She is dead,' said I.
\par 
\par "'I congratulate you, my brother,' were his words as he turned round.
\par 
\par "He had before offered me money, which I had postponed taking. He now
\par gave me a rouleau of gold. I took it from his hand, but laid it on
\par the table. I had considered the question, and had resolved to accept
\par nothing.
\par 
\par "'Pray excuse me,' said I. 'Under the circumstances, no.'
\par 
\par "They exchanged looks, but bent their heads to me as I bent mine to
\par them, and we parted without another word on either side.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "I am weary, weary, weary--worn down by misery. I cannot read what I
\par have written with this gaunt hand.
\par 
\par "Early in the morning, the rouleau of gold was left at my door in a
\par little box, with my name on the outside. From the first, I had anxiously
\par considered what I ought to do. I decided, that day, to write privately
\par to the Minister, stating the nature of the two cases to which I had been
\par summoned, and the place to which I had gone: in effect, stating all the
\par circumstances. I knew what Court influence was, and what the immunities
\par of the Nobles were, and I expected that the matter would never be
\par heard of; but, I wished to relieve my own mind. I had kept the matter a
\par profound secret, even from my wife; and this, too, I resolved to state
\par in my letter. I had no apprehension whatever of my real danger; but
\par I was conscious that there might be danger for others, if others were
\par compromised by possessing the knowledge that I possessed.
\par 
\par "I was much engaged that day, and could not complete my letter that
\par night. I rose long before my usual time next morning to finish it.
\par It was the last day of the year. The letter was lying before me just
\par completed, when I was told that a lady waited, who wished to see me.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "I am growing more and more unequal to the task I have set myself. It is
\par so cold, so dark, my senses are so benumbed, and the gloom upon me is so
\par dreadful.
\par 
\par "The lady was young, engaging, and handsome, but not marked for long
\par life. She was in great agitation. She presented herself to me as the
\par wife of the Marquis St. Evremonde. I connected the title by which the
\par boy had addressed the elder brother, with the initial letter embroidered
\par on the scarf, and had no difficulty in arriving at the conclusion that I
\par had seen that nobleman very lately.
\par 
\par "My memory is still accurate, but I cannot write the words of our
\par conversation. I suspect that I am watched more closely than I was, and I
\par know not at what times I may be watched. She had in part suspected, and
\par in part discovered, the main facts of the cruel story, of her husband's
\par share in it, and my being resorted to. She did not know that the girl
\par was dead. Her hope had been, she said in great distress, to show her,
\par in secret, a woman's sympathy. Her hope had been to avert the wrath of
\par Heaven from a House that had long been hateful to the suffering many.
\par 
\par "She had reasons for believing that there was a young sister living, and
\par her greatest desire was, to help that sister. I could tell her nothing
\par but that there was such a sister; beyond that, I knew nothing. Her
\par inducement to come to me, relying on my confidence, had been the hope
\par that I could tell her the name and place of abode. Whereas, to this
\par wretched hour I am ignorant of both.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par "These scraps of paper fail me. One was taken from me, with a warning,
\par yesterday. I must finish my record to-day.
\par 
\par "She was a good, compassionate lady, and not happy in her marriage. How
\par could she be! The brother distrusted and disliked her, and his influence
\par was all opposed to her; she stood in dread of him, and in dread of her
\par husband too. When I handed her down to the door, there was a child, a
\par pretty boy from two to three years old, in her carriage.
\par 
\par "'For his sake, Doctor,' she said, pointing to him in tears, 'I would do
\par all I can to make what poor amends I can. He will never prosper in his
\par inheritance otherwise. I have a presentiment that if no other innocent
\par atonement is made for this, it will one day be required of him. What
\par I have left to call my own--it is little beyond the worth of a few
\par jewels--I will make it the first charge of his life to bestow, with the
\par compassion and lamenting of his dead mother, on this injured family, if
\par the sister can be discovered.'
\par 
\par "She kissed the boy, and said, caressing him, 'It is for thine own dear
\par sake. Thou wilt be faithful, little Charles?' The child answered her
\par bravely, 'Yes!' I kissed her hand, and she took him in her arms, and
\par went away caressing him. I never saw her more.
\par 
\par "As she had mentioned her husband's name in the faith that I knew it,
\par I added no mention of it to my letter. I sealed my letter, and, not
\par trusting it out of my own hands, delivered it myself that day.
\par 
\par "That night, the last night of the year, towards nine o'clock, a man in
\par a black dress rang at my gate, demanded to see me, and softly followed
\par my servant, Ernest Defarge, a youth, up-stairs. When my servant came
\par into the room where I sat with my wife--O my wife, beloved of my heart!
\par My fair young English wife!--we saw the man, who was supposed to be at
\par the gate, standing silent behind him.
\par 
\par "An urgent case in the Rue St. Honore, he said. It would not detain me,
\par he had a coach in waiting.
\par 
\par "It brought me here, it brought me to my grave. When I was clear of the
\par house, a black muffler was drawn tightly over my mouth from behind, and
\par my arms were pinioned. The two brothers crossed the road from a dark
\par corner, and identified me with a single gesture. The Marquis took from
\par his pocket the letter I had written, showed it me, burnt it in the light
\par of a lantern that was held, and extinguished the ashes with his foot.
\par Not a word was spoken. I was brought here, I was brought to my living
\par grave.
\par 
\par "If it had pleased _God_ to put it in the hard heart of either of the
\par brothers, in all these frightful years, to grant me any tidings of
\par my dearest wife--so much as to let me know by a word whether alive or
\par dead--I might have thought that He had not quite abandoned them. But,
\par now I believe that the mark of the red cross is fatal to them, and that
\par they have no part in His mercies. And them and their descendants, to the
\par last of their race, I, Alexandre Manette, unhappy prisoner, do this last
\par night of the year 1767, in my unbearable agony, denounce to the times
\par when all these things shall be answered for. I denounce them to Heaven
\par and to earth."
\par 
\par A terrible sound arose when the reading of this document was done. A
\par sound of craving and eagerness that had nothing articulate in it but
\par blood. The narrative called up the most revengeful passions of the time,
\par and there was not a head in the nation but must have dropped before it.
\par 
\par Little need, in presence of that tribunal and that auditory, to show
\par how the Defarges had not made the paper public, with the other captured
\par Bastille memorials borne in procession, and had kept it, biding their
\par time. Little need to show that this detested family name had long been
\par anathematised by Saint Antoine, and was wrought into the fatal register.
\par The man never trod ground whose virtues and services would have
\par sustained him in that place that day, against such denunciation.
\par 
\par And all the worse for the doomed man, that the denouncer was a
\par well-known citizen, his own attached friend, the father of his wife. One
\par of the frenzied aspirations of the populace was, for imitations of
\par the questionable public virtues of antiquity, and for sacrifices and
\par self-immolations on the people's altar. Therefore when the President
\par said (else had his own head quivered on his shoulders), that the good
\par physician of the Republic would deserve better still of the Republic by
\par rooting out an obnoxious family of Aristocrats, and would doubtless feel
\par a sacred glow and joy in making his daughter a widow and her child an
\par orphan, there was wild excitement, patriotic fervour, not a touch of
\par human sympathy.
\par 
\par "Much influence around him, has that Doctor?" murmured Madame Defarge,
\par smiling to The Vengeance. "Save him now, my Doctor, save him!"
\par 
\par At every juryman's vote, there was a roar. Another and another. Roar and
\par roar.
\par 
\par Unanimously voted. At heart and by descent an Aristocrat, an enemy
\par of the Republic, a notorious oppressor of the People. Back to the
\par Conciergerie, and Death within four-and-twenty hours!
