\par 
\par 
\par XI. Dusk
\par 
\par 
\par The wretched wife of the innocent man thus doomed to die, fell under
\par the sentence, as if she had been mortally stricken. But, she uttered no
\par sound; and so strong was the voice within her, representing that it was
\par she of all the world who must uphold him in his misery and not augment
\par it, that it quickly raised her, even from that shock.
\par 
\par The Judges having to take part in a public demonstration out of doors,
\par the Tribunal adjourned. The quick noise and movement of the court's
\par emptying itself by many passages had not ceased, when Lucie stood
\par stretching out her arms towards her husband, with nothing in her face
\par but love and consolation.
\par 
\par "If I might touch him! If I might embrace him once! O, good citizens, if
\par you would have so much compassion for us!"
\par 
\par There was but a gaoler left, along with two of the four men who had
\par taken him last night, and Barsad. The people had all poured out to the
\par show in the streets. Barsad proposed to the rest, "Let her embrace
\par him then; it is but a moment." It was silently acquiesced in, and they
\par passed her over the seats in the hall to a raised place, where he, by
\par leaning over the dock, could fold her in his arms.
\par 
\par "Farewell, dear darling of my soul. My parting blessing on my love. We
\par shall meet again, where the weary are at rest!"
\par 
\par They were her husband's words, as he held her to his bosom.
\par 
\par "I can bear it, dear Charles. I am supported from above: don't suffer
\par for me. A parting blessing for our child."
\par 
\par "I send it to her by you. I kiss her by you. I say farewell to her by
\par you."
\par 
\par "My husband. No! A moment!" He was tearing himself apart from her.
\par "We shall not be separated long. I feel that this will break my heart
\par by-and-bye; but I will do my duty while I can, and when I leave her, God
\par will raise up friends for her, as He did for me."
\par 
\par Her father had followed her, and would have fallen on his knees to both
\par of them, but that Darnay put out a hand and seized him, crying:
\par 
\par "No, no! What have you done, what have you done, that you should kneel
\par to us! We know now, what a struggle you made of old. We know, now what
\par you underwent when you suspected my descent, and when you knew it. We
\par know now, the natural antipathy you strove against, and conquered, for
\par her dear sake. We thank you with all our hearts, and all our love and
\par duty. Heaven be with you!"
\par 
\par Her father's only answer was to draw his hands through his white hair,
\par and wring them with a shriek of anguish.
\par 
\par "It could not be otherwise," said the prisoner. "All things have worked
\par together as they have fallen out. It was the always-vain endeavour to
\par discharge my poor mother's trust that first brought my fatal presence
\par near you. Good could never come of such evil, a happier end was not in
\par nature to so unhappy a beginning. Be comforted, and forgive me. Heaven
\par bless you!"
\par 
\par As he was drawn away, his wife released him, and stood looking after him
\par with her hands touching one another in the attitude of prayer, and
\par with a radiant look upon her face, in which there was even a comforting
\par smile. As he went out at the prisoners' door, she turned, laid her head
\par lovingly on her father's breast, tried to speak to him, and fell at his
\par feet.
\par 
\par Then, issuing from the obscure corner from which he had never moved,
\par Sydney Carton came and took her up. Only her father and Mr. Lorry were
\par with her. His arm trembled as it raised her, and supported her head.
\par Yet, there was an air about him that was not all of pity--that had a
\par flush of pride in it.
\par 
\par "Shall I take her to a coach? I shall never feel her weight."
\par 
\par He carried her lightly to the door, and laid her tenderly down in a
\par coach. Her father and their old friend got into it, and he took his seat
\par beside the driver.
\par 
\par When they arrived at the gateway where he had paused in the dark not
\par many hours before, to picture to himself on which of the rough stones of
\par the street her feet had trodden, he lifted her again, and carried her up
\par the staircase to their rooms. There, he laid her down on a couch, where
\par her child and Miss Pross wept over her.
\par 
\par "Don't recall her to herself," he said, softly, to the latter, "she is
\par better so. Don't revive her to consciousness, while she only faints."
\par 
\par "Oh, Carton, Carton, dear Carton!" cried little Lucie, springing up and
\par throwing her arms passionately round him, in a burst of grief. "Now that
\par you have come, I think you will do something to help mamma, something to
\par save papa! O, look at her, dear Carton! Can you, of all the people who
\par love her, bear to see her so?"
\par 
\par He bent over the child, and laid her blooming cheek against his face. He
\par put her gently from him, and looked at her unconscious mother.
\par 
\par "Before I go," he said, and paused--"I may kiss her?"
\par 
\par It was remembered afterwards that when he bent down and touched her face
\par with his lips, he murmured some words. The child, who was nearest to
\par him, told them afterwards, and told her grandchildren when she was a
\par handsome old lady, that she heard him say, "A life you love."
\par 
