\par 
\par XII. Darkness
\par 
\par 
\par Sydney Carton paused in the street, not quite decided where to go. "At
\par Tellson's banking-house at nine," he said, with a musing face. "Shall I
\par do well, in the mean time, to show myself? I think so. It is best that
\par these people should know there is such a man as I here; it is a sound
\par precaution, and may be a necessary preparation. But care, care, care!
\par Let me think it out!"
\par 
\par Checking his steps which had begun to tend towards an object, he took a
\par turn or two in the already darkening street, and traced the thought
\par in his mind to its possible consequences. His first impression was
\par confirmed. "It is best," he said, finally resolved, "that these people
\par should know there is such a man as I here." And he turned his face
\par towards Saint Antoine.
\par 
\par Defarge had described himself, that day, as the keeper of a wine-shop in
\par the Saint Antoine suburb. It was not difficult for one who knew the city
\par well, to find his house without asking any question. Having ascertained
\par its situation, Carton came out of those closer streets again, and dined
\par at a place of refreshment and fell sound asleep after dinner. For the
\par first time in many years, he had no strong drink. Since last night he
\par had taken nothing but a little light thin wine, and last night he had
\par dropped the brandy slowly down on Mr. Lorry's hearth like a man who had
\par done with it.
\par 
\par It was as late as seven o'clock when he awoke refreshed, and went out
\par into the streets again. As he passed along towards Saint Antoine, he
\par stopped at a shop-window where there was a mirror, and slightly altered
\par the disordered arrangement of his loose cravat, and his coat-collar, and
\par his wild hair. This done, he went on direct to Defarge's, and went in.
\par 
\par There happened to be no customer in the shop but Jacques Three, of the
\par restless fingers and the croaking voice. This man, whom he had seen upon
\par the Jury, stood drinking at the little counter, in conversation with the
\par Defarges, man and wife. The Vengeance assisted in the conversation, like
\par a regular member of the establishment.
\par 
\par As Carton walked in, took his seat and asked (in very indifferent
\par French) for a small measure of wine, Madame Defarge cast a careless
\par glance at him, and then a keener, and then a keener, and then advanced
\par to him herself, and asked him what it was he had ordered.
\par 
\par He repeated what he had already said.
\par 
\par "English?" asked Madame Defarge, inquisitively raising her dark
\par eyebrows.
\par 
\par After looking at her, as if the sound of even a single French word were
\par slow to express itself to him, he answered, in his former strong foreign
\par accent. "Yes, madame, yes. I am English!"
\par 
\par Madame Defarge returned to her counter to get the wine, and, as he
\par took up a Jacobin journal and feigned to pore over it puzzling out its
\par meaning, he heard her say, "I swear to you, like Evremonde!"
\par 
\par Defarge brought him the wine, and gave him Good Evening.
\par 
\par "How?"
\par 
\par "Good evening."
\par 
\par "Oh! Good evening, citizen," filling his glass. "Ah! and good wine. I
\par drink to the Republic."
\par 
\par Defarge went back to the counter, and said, "Certainly, a little like."
\par Madame sternly retorted, "I tell you a good deal like." Jacques Three
\par pacifically remarked, "He is so much in your mind, see you, madame."
\par The amiable Vengeance added, with a laugh, "Yes, my faith! And you
\par are looking forward with so much pleasure to seeing him once more
\par to-morrow!"
\par 
\par Carton followed the lines and words of his paper, with a slow
\par forefinger, and with a studious and absorbed face. They were all leaning
\par their arms on the counter close together, speaking low. After a silence
\par of a few moments, during which they all looked towards him without
\par disturbing his outward attention from the Jacobin editor, they resumed
\par their conversation.
\par 
\par "It is true what madame says," observed Jacques Three. "Why stop? There
\par is great force in that. Why stop?"
\par 
\par "Well, well," reasoned Defarge, "but one must stop somewhere. After all,
\par the question is still where?"
\par 
\par "At extermination," said madame.
\par 
\par "Magnificent!" croaked Jacques Three. The Vengeance, also, highly
\par approved.
\par 
\par "Extermination is good doctrine, my wife," said Defarge, rather
\par troubled; "in general, I say nothing against it. But this Doctor has
\par suffered much; you have seen him to-day; you have observed his face when
\par the paper was read."
\par 
\par "I have observed his face!" repeated madame, contemptuously and angrily.
\par "Yes. I have observed his face. I have observed his face to be not the
\par face of a true friend of the Republic. Let him take care of his face!"
\par 
\par "And you have observed, my wife," said Defarge, in a deprecatory manner,
\par "the anguish of his daughter, which must be a dreadful anguish to him!"
\par 
\par "I have observed his daughter," repeated madame; "yes, I have observed
\par his daughter, more times than one. I have observed her to-day, and I
\par have observed her other days. I have observed her in the court, and
\par I have observed her in the street by the prison. Let me but lift my
\par finger--!" She seemed to raise it (the listener's eyes were always on
\par his paper), and to let it fall with a rattle on the ledge before her, as
\par if the axe had dropped.
\par 
\par "The citizeness is superb!" croaked the Juryman.
\par 
\par "She is an Angel!" said The Vengeance, and embraced her.
\par 
\par "As to thee," pursued madame, implacably, addressing her husband, "if it
\par depended on thee--which, happily, it does not--thou wouldst rescue this
\par man even now."
\par 
\par "No!" protested Defarge. "Not if to lift this glass would do it! But I
\par would leave the matter there. I say, stop there."
\par 
\par "See you then, Jacques," said Madame Defarge, wrathfully; "and see you,
\par too, my little Vengeance; see you both! Listen! For other crimes as
\par tyrants and oppressors, I have this race a long time on my register,
\par doomed to destruction and extermination. Ask my husband, is that so."
\par 
\par "It is so," assented Defarge, without being asked.
\par 
\par "In the beginning of the great days, when the Bastille falls, he finds
\par this paper of to-day, and he brings it home, and in the middle of the
\par night when this place is clear and shut, we read it, here on this spot,
\par by the light of this lamp. Ask him, is that so."
\par 
\par "It is so," assented Defarge.
\par 
\par "That night, I tell him, when the paper is read through, and the lamp is
\par burnt out, and the day is gleaming in above those shutters and between
\par those iron bars, that I have now a secret to communicate. Ask him, is
\par that so."
\par 
\par "It is so," assented Defarge again.
\par 
\par "I communicate to him that secret. I smite this bosom with these two
\par hands as I smite it now, and I tell him, 'Defarge, I was brought up
\par among the fishermen of the sea-shore, and that peasant family so injured
\par by the two Evremonde brothers, as that Bastille paper describes, is my
\par family. Defarge, that sister of the mortally wounded boy upon the ground
\par was my sister, that husband was my sister's husband, that unborn child
\par was their child, that brother was my brother, that father was my father,
\par those dead are my dead, and that summons to answer for those things
\par descends to me!' Ask him, is that so."
\par 
\par "It is so," assented Defarge once more.
\par 
\par "Then tell Wind and Fire where to stop," returned madame; "but don't
\par tell me."
\par 
\par Both her hearers derived a horrible enjoyment from the deadly nature
\par of her wrath--the listener could feel how white she was, without seeing
\par her--and both highly commended it. Defarge, a weak minority, interposed
\par a few words for the memory of the compassionate wife of the Marquis; but
\par only elicited from his own wife a repetition of her last reply. "Tell
\par the Wind and the Fire where to stop; not me!"
\par 
\par Customers entered, and the group was broken up. The English customer
\par paid for what he had had, perplexedly counted his change, and asked, as
\par a stranger, to be directed towards the National Palace. Madame Defarge
\par took him to the door, and put her arm on his, in pointing out the road.
\par The English customer was not without his reflections then, that it might
\par be a good deed to seize that arm, lift it, and strike under it sharp and
\par deep.
\par 
\par But, he went his way, and was soon swallowed up in the shadow of the
\par prison wall. At the appointed hour, he emerged from it to present
\par himself in Mr. Lorry's room again, where he found the old gentleman
\par walking to and fro in restless anxiety. He said he had been with Lucie
\par until just now, and had only left her for a few minutes, to come and
\par keep his appointment. Her father had not been seen, since he quitted the
\par banking-house towards four o'clock. She had some faint hopes that his
\par mediation might save Charles, but they were very slight. He had been
\par more than five hours gone: where could he be?
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry waited until ten; but, Doctor Manette not returning, and
\par he being unwilling to leave Lucie any longer, it was arranged that he
\par should go back to her, and come to the banking-house again at midnight.
\par In the meanwhile, Carton would wait alone by the fire for the Doctor.
\par 
\par He waited and waited, and the clock struck twelve; but Doctor Manette
\par did not come back. Mr. Lorry returned, and found no tidings of him, and
\par brought none. Where could he be?
\par 
\par They were discussing this question, and were almost building up some
\par weak structure of hope on his prolonged absence, when they heard him on
\par the stairs. The instant he entered the room, it was plain that all was
\par lost.
\par 
\par Whether he had really been to any one, or whether he had been all that
\par time traversing the streets, was never known. As he stood staring at
\par them, they asked him no question, for his face told them everything.
\par 
\par "I cannot find it," said he, "and I must have it. Where is it?"
\par 
\par His head and throat were bare, and, as he spoke with a helpless look
\par straying all around, he took his coat off, and let it drop on the floor.
\par 
\par "Where is my bench? I have been looking everywhere for my bench, and I
\par can't find it. What have they done with my work? Time presses: I must
\par finish those shoes."
\par 
\par They looked at one another, and their hearts died within them.
\par 
\par "Come, come!" said he, in a whimpering miserable way; "let me get to
\par work. Give me my work."
\par 
\par Receiving no answer, he tore his hair, and beat his feet upon the
\par ground, like a distracted child.
\par 
\par "Don't torture a poor forlorn wretch," he implored them, with a dreadful
\par cry; "but give me my work! What is to become of us, if those shoes are
\par not done to-night?"
\par 
\par Lost, utterly lost!
\par 
\par It was so clearly beyond hope to reason with him, or try to restore him,
\par that--as if by agreement--they each put a hand upon his shoulder, and
\par soothed him to sit down before the fire, with a promise that he should
\par have his work presently. He sank into the chair, and brooded over the
\par embers, and shed tears. As if all that had happened since the garret
\par time were a momentary fancy, or a dream, Mr. Lorry saw him shrink into
\par the exact figure that Defarge had had in keeping.
\par 
\par Affected, and impressed with terror as they both were, by this spectacle
\par of ruin, it was not a time to yield to such emotions. His lonely
\par daughter, bereft of her final hope and reliance, appealed to them both
\par too strongly. Again, as if by agreement, they looked at one another with
\par one meaning in their faces. Carton was the first to speak:
\par 
\par "The last chance is gone: it was not much. Yes; he had better be taken
\par to her. But, before you go, will you, for a moment, steadily attend to
\par me? Don't ask me why I make the stipulations I am going to make, and
\par exact the promise I am going to exact; I have a reason--a good one."
\par 
\par "I do not doubt it," answered Mr. Lorry. "Say on."
\par 
\par The figure in the chair between them, was all the time monotonously
\par rocking itself to and fro, and moaning. They spoke in such a tone as
\par they would have used if they had been watching by a sick-bed in the
\par night.
\par 
\par Carton stooped to pick up the coat, which lay almost entangling his
\par feet. As he did so, a small case in which the Doctor was accustomed to
\par carry the lists of his day's duties, fell lightly on the floor. Carton
\par took it up, and there was a folded paper in it. "We should look
\par at this!" he said. Mr. Lorry nodded his consent. He opened it, and
\par exclaimed, "Thank _God!_"
\par 
\par "What is it?" asked Mr. Lorry, eagerly.
\par 
\par "A moment! Let me speak of it in its place. First," he put his hand in
\par his coat, and took another paper from it, "that is the certificate which
\par enables me to pass out of this city. Look at it. You see--Sydney Carton,
\par an Englishman?"
\par 
\par Mr. Lorry held it open in his hand, gazing in his earnest face.
\par 
\par "Keep it for me until to-morrow. I shall see him to-morrow, you
\par remember, and I had better not take it into the prison."
\par 
\par "Why not?"
\par 
\par "I don't know; I prefer not to do so. Now, take this paper that Doctor
\par Manette has carried about him. It is a similar certificate, enabling him
\par and his daughter and her child, at any time, to pass the barrier and the
\par frontier! You see?"
\par 
\par "Yes!"
\par 
\par "Perhaps he obtained it as his last and utmost precaution against evil,
\par yesterday. When is it dated? But no matter; don't stay to look; put it
\par up carefully with mine and your own. Now, observe! I never doubted until
\par within this hour or two, that he had, or could have such a paper. It is
\par good, until recalled. But it may be soon recalled, and, I have reason to
\par think, will be."
\par 
\par "They are not in danger?"
\par 
\par "They are in great danger. They are in danger of denunciation by Madame
\par Defarge. I know it from her own lips. I have overheard words of that
\par woman's, to-night, which have presented their danger to me in strong
\par colours. I have lost no time, and since then, I have seen the spy. He
\par confirms me. He knows that a wood-sawyer, living by the prison wall,
\par is under the control of the Defarges, and has been rehearsed by
\par Madame Defarge as to his having seen Her"--he never mentioned Lucie's
\par name--"making signs and signals to prisoners. It is easy to foresee that
\par the pretence will be the common one, a prison plot, and that it will
\par involve her life--and perhaps her child's--and perhaps her father's--for
\par both have been seen with her at that place. Don't look so horrified. You
\par will save them all."
\par 
\par "Heaven grant I may, Carton! But how?"
\par 
\par "I am going to tell you how. It will depend on you, and it could depend
\par on no better man. This new denunciation will certainly not take place
\par until after to-morrow; probably not until two or three days afterwards;
\par more probably a week afterwards. You know it is a capital crime, to
\par mourn for, or sympathise with, a victim of the Guillotine. She and her
\par father would unquestionably be guilty of this crime, and this woman (the
\par inveteracy of whose pursuit cannot be described) would wait to add that
\par strength to her case, and make herself doubly sure. You follow me?"
\par 
\par "So attentively, and with so much confidence in what you say, that for
\par the moment I lose sight," touching the back of the Doctor's chair, "even
\par of this distress."
\par 
\par "You have money, and can buy the means of travelling to the seacoast
\par as quickly as the journey can be made. Your preparations have been
\par completed for some days, to return to England. Early to-morrow have your
\par horses ready, so that they may be in starting trim at two o'clock in the
\par afternoon."
\par 
\par "It shall be done!"
\par 
\par His manner was so fervent and inspiring, that Mr. Lorry caught the
\par flame, and was as quick as youth.
\par 
\par "You are a noble heart. Did I say we could depend upon no better man?
\par Tell her, to-night, what you know of her danger as involving her child
\par and her father. Dwell upon that, for she would lay her own fair head
\par beside her husband's cheerfully." He faltered for an instant; then went
\par on as before. "For the sake of her child and her father, press upon her
\par the necessity of leaving Paris, with them and you, at that hour. Tell
\par her that it was her husband's last arrangement. Tell her that more
\par depends upon it than she dare believe, or hope. You think that her
\par father, even in this sad state, will submit himself to her; do you not?"
\par 
\par "I am sure of it."
\par 
\par "I thought so. Quietly and steadily have all these arrangements made in
\par the courtyard here, even to the taking of your own seat in the carriage.
\par The moment I come to you, take me in, and drive away."
\par 
\par "I understand that I wait for you under all circumstances?"
\par 
\par "You have my certificate in your hand with the rest, you know, and will
\par reserve my place. Wait for nothing but to have my place occupied, and
\par then for England!"
\par 
\par "Why, then," said Mr. Lorry, grasping his eager but so firm and steady
\par hand, "it does not all depend on one old man, but I shall have a young
\par and ardent man at my side."
\par 
\par "By the help of Heaven you shall! Promise me solemnly that nothing will
\par influence you to alter the course on which we now stand pledged to one
\par another."
\par 
\par "Nothing, Carton."
\par 
\par "Remember these words to-morrow: change the course, or delay in it--for
\par any reason--and no life can possibly be saved, and many lives must
\par inevitably be sacrificed."
\par 
\par "I will remember them. I hope to do my part faithfully."
\par 
\par "And I hope to do mine. Now, good bye!"
\par 
\par Though he said it with a grave smile of earnestness, and though he even
\par put the old man's hand to his lips, he did not part from him then. He
\par helped him so far to arouse the rocking figure before the dying embers,
\par as to get a cloak and hat put upon it, and to tempt it forth to find
\par where the bench and work were hidden that it still moaningly besought
\par to have. He walked on the other side of it and protected it to the
\par courtyard of the house where the afflicted heart--so happy in
\par the memorable time when he had revealed his own desolate heart to
\par it--outwatched the awful night. He entered the courtyard and remained
\par there for a few moments alone, looking up at the light in the window of
\par her room. Before he went away, he breathed a blessing towards it, and a
\par Farewell.
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par 
\par XIII. Fifty-two
\par 
\par 
\par In the black prison of the Conciergerie, the doomed of the day awaited
\par their fate. They were in number as the weeks of the year. Fifty-two were
\par to roll that afternoon on the life-tide of the city to the boundless
\par everlasting sea. Before their cells were quit of them, new occupants
\par were appointed; before their blood ran into the blood spilled yesterday,
\par the blood that was to mingle with theirs to-morrow was already set
\par apart.
\par 
\par Two score and twelve were told off. From the farmer-general of seventy,
\par whose riches could not buy his life, to the seamstress of twenty, whose
\par poverty and obscurity could not save her. Physical diseases, engendered
\par in the vices and neglects of men, will seize on victims of all degrees;
\par and the frightful moral disorder, born of unspeakable suffering,
\par intolerable oppression, and heartless indifference, smote equally
\par without distinction.
\par 
\par Charles Darnay, alone in a cell, had sustained himself with no
\par flattering delusion since he came to it from the Tribunal. In every line
\par of the narrative he had heard, he had heard his condemnation. He had
\par fully comprehended that no personal influence could possibly save him,
\par that he was virtually sentenced by the millions, and that units could
\par avail him nothing.
\par 
\par Nevertheless, it was not easy, with the face of his beloved wife fresh
\par before him, to compose his mind to what it must bear. His hold on life
\par was strong, and it was very, very hard, to loosen; by gradual efforts
\par and degrees unclosed a little here, it clenched the tighter there; and
\par when he brought his strength to bear on that hand and it yielded,
\par this was closed again. There was a hurry, too, in all his thoughts,
\par a turbulent and heated working of his heart, that contended against
\par resignation. If, for a moment, he did feel resigned, then his wife and
\par child who had to live after him, seemed to protest and to make it a
\par selfish thing.
\par 
\par But, all this was at first. Before long, the consideration that there
\par was no disgrace in the fate he must meet, and that numbers went the same
\par road wrongfully, and trod it firmly every day, sprang up to stimulate
\par him. Next followed the thought that much of the future peace of mind
\par enjoyable by the dear ones, depended on his quiet fortitude. So,
\par by degrees he calmed into the better state, when he could raise his
\par thoughts much higher, and draw comfort down.
\par 
\par Before it had set in dark on the night of his condemnation, he had
\par travelled thus far on his last way. Being allowed to purchase the means
\par of writing, and a light, he sat down to write until such time as the
\par prison lamps should be extinguished.
\par 
\par He wrote a long letter to Lucie, showing her that he had known nothing
\par of her father's imprisonment, until he had heard of it from herself,
\par and that he had been as ignorant as she of his father's and uncle's
\par responsibility for that misery, until the paper had been read. He had
\par already explained to her that his concealment from herself of the name
\par he had relinquished, was the one condition--fully intelligible now--that
\par her father had attached to their betrothal, and was the one promise he
\par had still exacted on the morning of their marriage. He entreated her,
\par for her father's sake, never to seek to know whether her father had
\par become oblivious of the existence of the paper, or had had it recalled
\par to him (for the moment, or for good), by the story of the Tower, on
\par that old Sunday under the dear old plane-tree in the garden. If he had
\par preserved any definite remembrance of it, there could be no doubt that
\par he had supposed it destroyed with the Bastille, when he had found no
\par mention of it among the relics of prisoners which the populace had
\par discovered there, and which had been described to all the world. He
\par besought her--though he added that he knew it was needless--to console
\par her father, by impressing him through every tender means she could think
\par of, with the truth that he had done nothing for which he could justly
\par reproach himself, but had uniformly forgotten himself for their joint
\par sakes. Next to her preservation of his own last grateful love and
\par blessing, and her overcoming of her sorrow, to devote herself to their
\par dear child, he adjured her, as they would meet in Heaven, to comfort her
\par father.
\par 
\par To her father himself, he wrote in the same strain; but, he told her
\par father that he expressly confided his wife and child to his care. And
\par he told him this, very strongly, with the hope of rousing him from any
\par despondency or dangerous retrospect towards which he foresaw he might be
\par tending.
\par 
\par To Mr. Lorry, he commended them all, and explained his worldly affairs.
\par That done, with many added sentences of grateful friendship and warm
\par attachment, all was done. He never thought of Carton. His mind was so
\par full of the others, that he never once thought of him.
\par 
\par He had time to finish these letters before the lights were put out. When
\par he lay down on his straw bed, he thought he had done with this world.
\par 
\par But, it beckoned him back in his sleep, and showed itself in shining
\par forms. Free and happy, back in the old house in Soho (though it had
\par nothing in it like the real house), unaccountably released and light of
\par heart, he was with Lucie again, and she told him it was all a dream, and
\par he had never gone away. A pause of forgetfulness, and then he had even
\par suffered, and had come back to her, dead and at peace, and yet there
\par was no difference in him. Another pause of oblivion, and he awoke in the
\par sombre morning, unconscious where he was or what had happened, until it
\par flashed upon his mind, "this is the day of my death!"
\par 
\par Thus, had he come through the hours, to the day when the fifty-two heads
\par were to fall. And now, while he was composed, and hoped that he could
\par meet the end with quiet heroism, a new action began in his waking
\par thoughts, which was very difficult to master.
\par 
\par He had never seen the instrument that was to terminate his life. How
\par high it was from the ground, how many steps it had, where he would be
\par stood, how he would be touched, whether the touching hands would be dyed
\par red, which way his face would be turned, whether he would be the first,
\par or might be the last: these and many similar questions, in nowise
\par directed by his will, obtruded themselves over and over again, countless
\par times. Neither were they connected with fear: he was conscious of no
\par fear. Rather, they originated in a strange besetting desire to know what
\par to do when the time came; a desire gigantically disproportionate to the
\par few swift moments to which it referred; a wondering that was more like
\par the wondering of some other spirit within his, than his own.
\par 
\par The hours went on as he walked to and fro, and the clocks struck the
\par numbers he would never hear again. Nine gone for ever, ten gone for
\par ever, eleven gone for ever, twelve coming on to pass away. After a hard
\par contest with that eccentric action of thought which had last perplexed
\par him, he had got the better of it. He walked up and down, softly
\par repeating their names to himself. The worst of the strife was over.
\par He could walk up and down, free from distracting fancies, praying for
\par himself and for them.
\par 
\par Twelve gone for ever.
\par 
\par He had been apprised that the final hour was Three, and he knew he would
\par be summoned some time earlier, inasmuch as the tumbrils jolted heavily
\par and slowly through the streets. Therefore, he resolved to keep Two
\par before his mind, as the hour, and so to strengthen himself in the
\par interval that he might be able, after that time, to strengthen others.
\par 
\par Walking regularly to and fro with his arms folded on his breast, a very
\par different man from the prisoner, who had walked to and fro at La Force,
\par he heard One struck away from him, without surprise. The hour had
\par measured like most other hours. Devoutly thankful to Heaven for his
\par recovered self-possession, he thought, "There is but another now," and
\par turned to walk again.
\par 
\par Footsteps in the stone passage outside the door. He stopped.
\par 
\par The key was put in the lock, and turned. Before the door was opened, or
\par as it opened, a man said in a low voice, in English: "He has never seen
\par me here; I have kept out of his way. Go you in alone; I wait near. Lose
\par no time!"
\par 
\par The door was quickly opened and closed, and there stood before him
\par face to face, quiet, intent upon him, with the light of a smile on his
\par features, and a cautionary finger on his lip, Sydney Carton.
\par 
\par There was something so bright and remarkable in his look, that, for the
\par first moment, the prisoner misdoubted him to be an apparition of his own
\par imagining. But, he spoke, and it was his voice; he took the prisoner's
\par hand, and it was his real grasp.
\par 
\par "Of all the people upon earth, you least expected to see me?" he said.
\par 
\par "I could not believe it to be you. I can scarcely believe it now. You
\par are not"--the apprehension came suddenly into his mind--"a prisoner?"
\par 
\par "No. I am accidentally possessed of a power over one of the keepers
\par here, and in virtue of it I stand before you. I come from her--your
\par wife, dear Darnay."
\par 
\par The prisoner wrung his hand.
\par 
\par "I bring you a request from her."
\par 
\par "What is it?"
\par 
\par "A most earnest, pressing, and emphatic entreaty, addressed to you
\par in the most pathetic tones of the voice so dear to you, that you well
\par remember."
\par 
\par The prisoner turned his face partly aside.
\par 
\par "You have no time to ask me why I bring it, or what it means; I have
\par no time to tell you. You must comply with it--take off those boots you
\par wear, and draw on these of mine."
\par 
\par There was a chair against the wall of the cell, behind the prisoner.
\par Carton, pressing forward, had already, with the speed of lightning, got
\par him down into it, and stood over him, barefoot.
\par 
\par "Draw on these boots of mine. Put your hands to them; put your will to
\par them. Quick!"
\par 
\par "Carton, there is no escaping from this place; it never can be done. You
\par will only die with me. It is madness."
\par 
\par "It would be madness if I asked you to escape; but do I? When I ask you
\par to pass out at that door, tell me it is madness and remain here. Change
\par that cravat for this of mine, that coat for this of mine. While you do
\par it, let me take this ribbon from your hair, and shake out your hair like
\par this of mine!"
\par 
\par With wonderful quickness, and with a strength both of will and action,
\par that appeared quite supernatural, he forced all these changes upon him.
\par The prisoner was like a young child in his hands.
\par 
