\par 
\par 
\par In that same juncture of time when the Fifty-Two awaited their fate
\par Madame Defarge held darkly ominous council with The Vengeance and
\par Jacques Three of the Revolutionary Jury. Not in the wine-shop did Madame
\par Defarge confer with these ministers, but in the shed of the wood-sawyer,
\par erst a mender of roads. The sawyer himself did not participate in the
\par conference, but abided at a little distance, like an outer satellite who
\par was not to speak until required, or to offer an opinion until invited.
\par 
\par "But our Defarge," said Jacques Three, "is undoubtedly a good
\par Republican? Eh?"
\par 
\par "There is no better," the voluble Vengeance protested in her shrill
\par notes, "in France."
\par 
\par "Peace, little Vengeance," said Madame Defarge, laying her hand with
\par a slight frown on her lieutenant's lips, "hear me speak. My husband,
\par fellow-citizen, is a good Republican and a bold man; he has deserved
\par well of the Republic, and possesses its confidence. But my husband has
\par his weaknesses, and he is so weak as to relent towards this Doctor."
\par 
\par "It is a great pity," croaked Jacques Three, dubiously shaking his head,
\par with his cruel fingers at his hungry mouth; "it is not quite like a good
\par citizen; it is a thing to regret."
\par 
\par "See you," said madame, "I care nothing for this Doctor, I. He may wear
\par his head or lose it, for any interest I have in him; it is all one to
\par me. But, the Evremonde people are to be exterminated, and the wife and
\par child must follow the husband and father."
\par 
\par "She has a fine head for it," croaked Jacques Three. "I have seen blue
\par eyes and golden hair there, and they looked charming when Samson held
\par them up." Ogre that he was, he spoke like an epicure.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge cast down her eyes, and reflected a little.
\par 
\par "The child also," observed Jacques Three, with a meditative enjoyment
\par of his words, "has golden hair and blue eyes. And we seldom have a child
\par there. It is a pretty sight!"
\par 
\par "In a word," said Madame Defarge, coming out of her short abstraction,
\par "I cannot trust my husband in this matter. Not only do I feel, since
\par last night, that I dare not confide to him the details of my projects;
\par but also I feel that if I delay, there is danger of his giving warning,
\par and then they might escape."
