\par Seeing in this arrangement the hope of rendering real service in that
\par pressing emergency, Miss Pross hailed it with joy. She and Jerry had
\par beheld the coach start, had known who it was that Solomon brought, had
\par passed some ten minutes in tortures of suspense, and were now concluding
\par their arrangements to follow the coach, even as Madame Defarge,
\par taking her way through the streets, now drew nearer and nearer to the
\par else-deserted lodging in which they held their consultation.
\par 
\par "Now what do you think, Mr. Cruncher," said Miss Pross, whose agitation
\par was so great that she could hardly speak, or stand, or move, or live:
\par "what do you think of our not starting from this courtyard? Another
\par carriage having already gone from here to-day, it might awaken
\par suspicion."
\par 
\par "My opinion, miss," returned Mr. Cruncher, "is as you're right. Likewise
\par wot I'll stand by you, right or wrong."
\par 
\par "I am so distracted with fear and hope for our precious creatures," said
\par Miss Pross, wildly crying, "that I am incapable of forming any plan. Are
\par _you_ capable of forming any plan, my dear good Mr. Cruncher?"
\par 
\par "Respectin' a future spear o' life, miss," returned Mr. Cruncher, "I
\par hope so. Respectin' any present use o' this here blessed old head o'
\par mine, I think not. Would you do me the favour, miss, to take notice o'
\par two promises and wows wot it is my wishes fur to record in this here
\par crisis?"
\par 
\par "Oh, for gracious sake!" cried Miss Pross, still wildly crying, "record
\par them at once, and get them out of the way, like an excellent man."
\par 
\par "First," said Mr. Cruncher, who was all in a tremble, and who spoke with
\par an ashy and solemn visage, "them poor things well out o' this, never no
\par more will I do it, never no more!"
\par 
\par "I am quite sure, Mr. Cruncher," returned Miss Pross, "that you
\par never will do it again, whatever it is, and I beg you not to think it
\par necessary to mention more particularly what it is."
\par 
\par "No, miss," returned Jerry, "it shall not be named to you. Second: them
\par poor things well out o' this, and never no more will I interfere with
\par Mrs. Cruncher's flopping, never no more!"
\par 
\par "Whatever housekeeping arrangement that may be," said Miss Pross,
\par striving to dry her eyes and compose herself, "I have no doubt it
\par is best that Mrs. Cruncher should have it entirely under her own
\par superintendence.--O my poor darlings!"
\par 
\par "I go so far as to say, miss, moreover," proceeded Mr. Cruncher, with a
\par most alarming tendency to hold forth as from a pulpit--"and let my words
\par be took down and took to Mrs. Cruncher through yourself--that wot my
\par opinions respectin' flopping has undergone a change, and that wot I only
\par hope with all my heart as Mrs. Cruncher may be a flopping at the present
\par time."
\par 
\par "There, there, there! I hope she is, my dear man," cried the distracted
\par Miss Pross, "and I hope she finds it answering her expectations."
\par 
\par "Forbid it," proceeded Mr. Cruncher, with additional solemnity,
\par additional slowness, and additional tendency to hold forth and hold
\par out, "as anything wot I have ever said or done should be wisited on my
\par earnest wishes for them poor creeturs now! Forbid it as we shouldn't all
\par flop (if it was anyways conwenient) to get 'em out o' this here dismal
\par risk! Forbid it, miss! Wot I say, for-_bid_ it!" This was Mr. Cruncher's
\par conclusion after a protracted but vain endeavour to find a better one.
\par 
\par And still Madame Defarge, pursuing her way along the streets, came
\par nearer and nearer.
\par 
\par "If we ever get back to our native land," said Miss Pross, "you may rely
\par upon my telling Mrs. Cruncher as much as I may be able to remember and
\par understand of what you have so impressively said; and at all events
\par you may be sure that I shall bear witness to your being thoroughly in
\par earnest at this dreadful time. Now, pray let us think! My esteemed Mr.
\par Cruncher, let us think!"
\par 
\par Still, Madame Defarge, pursuing her way along the streets, came nearer
\par and nearer.
\par 
\par "If you were to go before," said Miss Pross, "and stop the vehicle and
\par horses from coming here, and were to wait somewhere for me; wouldn't
\par that be best?"
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher thought it might be best.
\par 
\par "Where could you wait for me?" asked Miss Pross.
\par 
\par Mr. Cruncher was so bewildered that he could think of no locality but
\par Temple Bar. Alas! Temple Bar was hundreds of miles away, and Madame
\par Defarge was drawing very near indeed.
\par 
\par "By the cathedral door," said Miss Pross. "Would it be much out of
\par the way, to take me in, near the great cathedral door between the two
\par towers?"
\par 
\par "No, miss," answered Mr. Cruncher.
\par 
\par "Then, like the best of men," said Miss Pross, "go to the posting-house
\par straight, and make that change."
\par 
\par "I am doubtful," said Mr. Cruncher, hesitating and shaking his head,
\par "about leaving of you, you see. We don't know what may happen."
\par 
\par "Heaven knows we don't," returned Miss Pross, "but have no fear for me.
\par Take me in at the cathedral, at Three o'Clock, or as near it as you can,
\par and I am sure it will be better than our going from here. I feel certain
\par of it. There! Bless you, Mr. Cruncher! Think-not of me, but of the lives
\par that may depend on both of us!"
\par 
\par This exordium, and Miss Pross's two hands in quite agonised entreaty
\par clasping his, decided Mr. Cruncher. With an encouraging nod or two, he
\par immediately went out to alter the arrangements, and left her by herself
\par to follow as she had proposed.
\par 
\par The having originated a precaution which was already in course of
\par execution, was a great relief to Miss Pross. The necessity of composing
\par her appearance so that it should attract no special notice in the
\par streets, was another relief. She looked at her watch, and it was twenty
\par minutes past two. She had no time to lose, but must get ready at once.
\par 
\par Afraid, in her extreme perturbation, of the loneliness of the deserted
\par rooms, and of half-imagined faces peeping from behind every open door
\par in them, Miss Pross got a basin of cold water and began laving her eyes,
\par which were swollen and red. Haunted by her feverish apprehensions, she
\par could not bear to have her sight obscured for a minute at a time by the
\par dripping water, but constantly paused and looked round to see that there
\par was no one watching her. In one of those pauses she recoiled and cried
\par out, for she saw a figure standing in the room.
\par 
\par The basin fell to the ground broken, and the water flowed to the feet of
\par Madame Defarge. By strange stern ways, and through much staining blood,
\par those feet had come to meet that water.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge looked coldly at her, and said, "The wife of Evremonde;
\par where is she?"
\par 
\par It flashed upon Miss Pross's mind that the doors were all standing open,
\par and would suggest the flight. Her first act was to shut them. There were
\par four in the room, and she shut them all. She then placed herself before
\par the door of the chamber which Lucie had occupied.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge's dark eyes followed her through this rapid movement,
\par and rested on her when it was finished. Miss Pross had nothing beautiful
\par about her; years had not tamed the wildness, or softened the grimness,
\par of her appearance; but, she too was a determined woman in her different
\par way, and she measured Madame Defarge with her eyes, every inch.
\par 
\par "You might, from your appearance, be the wife of Lucifer," said Miss
\par Pross, in her breathing. "Nevertheless, you shall not get the better of
\par me. I am an Englishwoman."
\par 
\par Madame Defarge looked at her scornfully, but still with something of
\par Miss Pross's own perception that they two were at bay. She saw a tight,
\par hard, wiry woman before her, as Mr. Lorry had seen in the same figure a
\par woman with a strong hand, in the years gone by. She knew full well that
\par Miss Pross was the family's devoted friend; Miss Pross knew full well
\par that Madame Defarge was the family's malevolent enemy.
\par 
\par "On my way yonder," said Madame Defarge, with a slight movement of
\par her hand towards the fatal spot, "where they reserve my chair and my
\par knitting for me, I am come to make my compliments to her in passing. I
\par wish to see her."
\par 
\par "I know that your intentions are evil," said Miss Pross, "and you may
\par depend upon it, I'll hold my own against them."
\par 
\par Each spoke in her own language; neither understood the other's words;
\par both were very watchful, and intent to deduce from look and manner, what
\par the unintelligible words meant.
\par 
\par "It will do her no good to keep herself concealed from me at this
\par moment," said Madame Defarge. "Good patriots will know what that means.
\par Let me see her. Go tell her that I wish to see her. Do you hear?"
\par 
\par "If those eyes of yours were bed-winches," returned Miss Pross, "and I
\par was an English four-poster, they shouldn't loose a splinter of me. No,
\par you wicked foreign woman; I am your match."
\par 
\par Madame Defarge was not likely to follow these idiomatic remarks in
\par detail; but, she so far understood them as to perceive that she was set
\par at naught.
\par 
\par "Woman imbecile and pig-like!" said Madame Defarge, frowning. "I take no
\par answer from you. I demand to see her. Either tell her that I demand
\par to see her, or stand out of the way of the door and let me go to her!"
\par This, with an angry explanatory wave of her right arm.
\par 
\par "I little thought," said Miss Pross, "that I should ever want to
\par understand your nonsensical language; but I would give all I have,
\par except the clothes I wear, to know whether you suspect the truth, or any
\par part of it."
\par 
\par Neither of them for a single moment released the other's eyes. Madame
\par Defarge had not moved from the spot where she stood when Miss Pross
\par first became aware of her; but, she now advanced one step.
\par 
\par "I am a Briton," said Miss Pross, "I am desperate. I don't care an
\par English Twopence for myself. I know that the longer I keep you here, the
\par greater hope there is for my Ladybird. I'll not leave a handful of that
\par dark hair upon your head, if you lay a finger on me!"
\par 
\par Thus Miss Pross, with a shake of her head and a flash of her eyes
\par between every rapid sentence, and every rapid sentence a whole breath.
\par Thus Miss Pross, who had never struck a blow in her life.
\par 
\par But, her courage was of that emotional nature that it brought the
\par irrepressible tears into her eyes. This was a courage that Madame
\par Defarge so little comprehended as to mistake for weakness. "Ha, ha!" she
\par laughed, "you poor wretch! What are you worth! I address myself to that
\par Doctor." Then she raised her voice and called out, "Citizen Doctor! Wife
\par of Evremonde! Child of Evremonde! Any person but this miserable fool,
\par answer the Citizeness Defarge!"
\par 
\par Perhaps the following silence, perhaps some latent disclosure in the
\par expression of Miss Pross's face, perhaps a sudden misgiving apart from
\par either suggestion, whispered to Madame Defarge that they were gone.
\par Three of the doors she opened swiftly, and looked in.
\par 
\par "Those rooms are all in disorder, there has been hurried packing, there
\par are odds and ends upon the ground. There is no one in that room behind
\par you! Let me look."
\par 
\par "Never!" said Miss Pross, who understood the request as perfectly as
\par Madame Defarge understood the answer.
\par 
\par "If they are not in that room, they are gone, and can be pursued and
\par brought back," said Madame Defarge to herself.
\par 
\par "As long as you don't know whether they are in that room or not, you are
\par uncertain what to do," said Miss Pross to herself; "and you shall not
\par know that, if I can prevent your knowing it; and know that, or not know
\par that, you shall not leave here while I can hold you."
\par 
\par "I have been in the streets from the first, nothing has stopped me,
\par I will tear you to pieces, but I will have you from that door," said
\par Madame Defarge.
\par 
\par "We are alone at the top of a high house in a solitary courtyard, we are
\par not likely to be heard, and I pray for bodily strength to keep you here,
\par while every minute you are here is worth a hundred thousand guineas to
\par my darling," said Miss Pross.
\par 
\par Madame Defarge made at the door. Miss Pross, on the instinct of the
\par moment, seized her round the waist in both her arms, and held her tight.
\par It was in vain for Madame Defarge to struggle and to strike; Miss Pross,
\par with the vigorous tenacity of love, always so much stronger than hate,
\par clasped her tight, and even lifted her from the floor in the struggle
\par that they had. The two hands of Madame Defarge buffeted and tore her
\par face; but, Miss Pross, with her head down, held her round the waist, and
\par clung to her with more than the hold of a drowning woman.
\par 
\par Soon, Madame Defarge's hands ceased to strike, and felt at her encircled
\par waist. "It is under my arm," said Miss Pross, in smothered tones, "you
\par shall not draw it. I am stronger than you, I bless Heaven for it. I hold
\par you till one or other of us faints or dies!"
\par 
\par Madame Defarge's hands were at her bosom. Miss Pross looked up, saw
\par what it was, struck at it, struck out a flash and a crash, and stood
\par alone--blinded with smoke.
\par 
\par All this was in a second. As the smoke cleared, leaving an awful
\par stillness, it passed out on the air, like the soul of the furious woman
\par whose body lay lifeless on the ground.
\par 
\par In the first fright and horror of her situation, Miss Pross passed the
\par body as far from it as she could, and ran down the stairs to call for
\par fruitless help. Happily, she bethought herself of the consequences of
\par what she did, in time to check herself and go back. It was dreadful to
\par go in at the door again; but, she did go in, and even went near it, to
\par get the bonnet and other things that she must wear. These she put on,
\par out on the staircase, first shutting and locking the door and taking
\par away the key. She then sat down on the stairs a few moments to breathe
\par and to cry, and then got up and hurried away.
\par 
\par By good fortune she had a veil on her bonnet, or she could hardly have
\par gone along the streets without being stopped. By good fortune, too, she
\par was naturally so peculiar in appearance as not to show disfigurement
\par like any other woman. She needed both advantages, for the marks of
\par gripping fingers were deep in her face, and her hair was torn, and her
\par dress (hastily composed with unsteady hands) was clutched and dragged a
\par hundred ways.
\par 
\par In crossing the bridge, she dropped the door key in the river. Arriving
\par at the cathedral some few minutes before her escort, and waiting there,
\par she thought, what if the key were already taken in a net, what if
\par it were identified, what if the door were opened and the remains
\par discovered, what if she were stopped at the gate, sent to prison, and
\par charged with murder! In the midst of these fluttering thoughts, the
\par escort appeared, took her in, and took her away.
\par 
\par "Is there any noise in the streets?" she asked him.
\par 
\par "The usual noises," Mr. Cruncher replied; and looked surprised by the
\par question and by her aspect.
\par 
\par "I don't hear you," said Miss Pross. "What do you say?"
\par 
\par It was in vain for Mr. Cruncher to repeat what he said; Miss Pross could
\par not hear him. "So I'll nod my head," thought Mr. Cruncher, amazed, "at
\par all events she'll see that." And she did.
\par 
\par "Is there any noise in the streets now?" asked Miss Pross again,
\par presently.
\par 
\par Again Mr. Cruncher nodded his head.
\par 
\par "I don't hear it."
\par 
\par "Gone deaf in an hour?" said Mr. Cruncher, ruminating, with his mind
\par much disturbed; "wot's come to her?"
\par 
\par "I feel," said Miss Pross, "as if there had been a flash and a crash,
\par and that crash was the last thing I should ever hear in this life."
\par 
\par "Blest if she ain't in a queer condition!" said Mr. Cruncher, more and
\par more disturbed. "Wot can she have been a takin', to keep her courage up?
\par Hark! There's the roll of them dreadful carts! You can hear that, miss?"
\par 
\par "I can hear," said Miss Pross, seeing that he spoke to her, "nothing. O,
\par my good man, there was first a great crash, and then a great stillness,
\par and that stillness seems to be fixed and unchangeable, never to be
\par broken any more as long as my life lasts."
\par 
\par "If she don't hear the roll of those dreadful carts, now very nigh their
\par journey's end," said Mr. Cruncher, glancing over his shoulder, "it's my
\par opinion that indeed she never will hear anything else in this world."
\par 
\par And indeed she never did.
\par 
