\par 
\par 
\par XV. The Footsteps Die Out For Ever
\par 
\par 
\par Along the Paris streets, the death-carts rumble, hollow and harsh. Six
\par tumbrils carry the day's wine to La Guillotine. All the devouring and
\par insatiate Monsters imagined since imagination could record itself,
\par are fused in the one realisation, Guillotine. And yet there is not in
\par France, with its rich variety of soil and climate, a blade, a leaf,
\par a root, a sprig, a peppercorn, which will grow to maturity under
\par conditions more certain than those that have produced this horror. Crush
\par humanity out of shape once more, under similar hammers, and it will
\par twist itself into the same tortured forms. Sow the same seed of
\par rapacious license and oppression over again, and it will surely yield
\par the same fruit according to its kind.
\par 
\par Six tumbrils roll along the streets. Change these back again to what
\par they were, thou powerful enchanter, Time, and they shall be seen to be
\par the carriages of absolute monarchs, the equipages of feudal nobles, the
\par toilettes of flaring Jezebels, the churches that are not my father's
\par house but dens of thieves, the huts of millions of starving peasants!
\par No; the great magician who majestically works out the appointed order
\par of the Creator, never reverses his transformations. "If thou be changed
\par into this shape by the will of God," say the seers to the enchanted, in
\par the wise Arabian stories, "then remain so! But, if thou wear this
\par form through mere passing conjuration, then resume thy former aspect!"
\par Changeless and hopeless, the tumbrils roll along.
\par 
\par As the sombre wheels of the six carts go round, they seem to plough up
\par a long crooked furrow among the populace in the streets. Ridges of faces
\par are thrown to this side and to that, and the ploughs go steadily onward.
\par So used are the regular inhabitants of the houses to the spectacle, that
\par in many windows there are no people, and in some the occupation of the
\par hands is not so much as suspended, while the eyes survey the faces in
\par the tumbrils. Here and there, the inmate has visitors to see the sight;
\par then he points his finger, with something of the complacency of a
\par curator or authorised exponent, to this cart and to this, and seems to
\par tell who sat here yesterday, and who there the day before.
\par 
\par Of the riders in the tumbrils, some observe these things, and all
\par things on their last roadside, with an impassive stare; others, with
\par a lingering interest in the ways of life and men. Some, seated with
\par drooping heads, are sunk in silent despair; again, there are some so
\par heedful of their looks that they cast upon the multitude such glances as
\par they have seen in theatres, and in pictures. Several close their eyes,
\par and think, or try to get their straying thoughts together. Only one, and
\par he a miserable creature, of a crazed aspect, is so shattered and made
\par drunk by horror, that he sings, and tries to dance. Not one of the whole
\par number appeals by look or gesture, to the pity of the people.
\par 
\par There is a guard of sundry horsemen riding abreast of the tumbrils,
\par and faces are often turned up to some of them, and they are asked some
\par question. It would seem to be always the same question, for, it is
\par always followed by a press of people towards the third cart. The
\par horsemen abreast of that cart, frequently point out one man in it with
\par their swords. The leading curiosity is, to know which is he; he stands
\par at the back of the tumbril with his head bent down, to converse with a
\par mere girl who sits on the side of the cart, and holds his hand. He has
\par no curiosity or care for the scene about him, and always speaks to the
\par girl. Here and there in the long street of St. Honore, cries are raised
\par against him. If they move him at all, it is only to a quiet smile, as he
\par shakes his hair a little more loosely about his face. He cannot easily
\par touch his face, his arms being bound.
\par 
\par On the steps of a church, awaiting the coming-up of the tumbrils, stands
\par the Spy and prison-sheep. He looks into the first of them: not there.
\par He looks into the second: not there. He already asks himself, "Has he
\par sacrificed me?" when his face clears, as he looks into the third.
\par 
\par "Which is Evremonde?" says a man behind him.
\par 
\par "That. At the back there."
\par 
\par "With his hand in the girl's?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par The man cries, "Down, Evremonde! To the Guillotine all aristocrats!
\par Down, Evremonde!"
\par 
\par "Hush, hush!" the Spy entreats him, timidly.
\par 
\par "And why not, citizen?"
\par 
\par "He is going to pay the forfeit: it will be paid in five minutes more.
\par Let him be at peace."
\par 
\par But the man continuing to exclaim, "Down, Evremonde!" the face of
\par Evremonde is for a moment turned towards him. Evremonde then sees the
\par Spy, and looks attentively at him, and goes his way.
\par 
\par The clocks are on the stroke of three, and the furrow ploughed among the
\par populace is turning round, to come on into the place of execution, and
\par end. The ridges thrown to this side and to that, now crumble in and
\par close behind the last plough as it passes on, for all are following
\par to the Guillotine. In front of it, seated in chairs, as in a garden of
\par public diversion, are a number of women, busily knitting. On one of the
\par fore-most chairs, stands The Vengeance, looking about for her friend.
\par 
\par "Therese!" she cries, in her shrill tones. "Who has seen her? Therese
\par Defarge!"
\par 
\par "She never missed before," says a knitting-woman of the sisterhood.
\par 
\par "No; nor will she miss now," cries The Vengeance, petulantly. "Therese."
\par 
\par "Louder," the woman recommends.
\par 
\par Ay! Louder, Vengeance, much louder, and still she will scarcely hear
\par thee. Louder yet, Vengeance, with a little oath or so added, and yet
\par it will hardly bring her. Send other women up and down to seek her,
\par lingering somewhere; and yet, although the messengers have done dread
\par deeds, it is questionable whether of their own wills they will go far
\par enough to find her!
\par 
\par "Bad Fortune!" cries The Vengeance, stamping her foot in the chair, "and
\par here are the tumbrils! And Evremonde will be despatched in a wink, and
\par she not here! See her knitting in my hand, and her empty chair ready for
\par her. I cry with vexation and disappointment!"
\par 
\par As The Vengeance descends from her elevation to do it, the tumbrils
\par begin to discharge their loads. The ministers of Sainte Guillotine are
\par robed and ready. Crash!--A head is held up, and the knitting-women who
\par scarcely lifted their eyes to look at it a moment ago when it could
\par think and speak, count One.
\par 
\par The second tumbril empties and moves on; the third comes up. Crash!--And
\par the knitting-women, never faltering or pausing in their Work, count Two.
\par 
\par The supposed Evremonde descends, and the seamstress is lifted out next
\par after him. He has not relinquished her patient hand in getting out, but
\par still holds it as he promised. He gently places her with her back to the
\par crashing engine that constantly whirrs up and falls, and she looks into
\par his face and thanks him.
\par 
\par "But for you, dear stranger, I should not be so composed, for I am
\par naturally a poor little thing, faint of heart; nor should I have been
\par able to raise my thoughts to Him who was put to death, that we might
\par have hope and comfort here to-day. I think you were sent to me by
\par Heaven."
\par 
\par "Or you to me," says Sydney Carton. "Keep your eyes upon me, dear child,
\par and mind no other object."
\par 
\par "I mind nothing while I hold your hand. I shall mind nothing when I let
\par it go, if they are rapid."
\par 
\par "They will be rapid. Fear not!"
\par 
\par The two stand in the fast-thinning throng of victims, but they speak as
\par if they were alone. Eye to eye, voice to voice, hand to hand, heart to
\par heart, these two children of the Universal Mother, else so wide apart
\par and differing, have come together on the dark highway, to repair home
\par together, and to rest in her bosom.
\par 
\par "Brave and generous friend, will you let me ask you one last question? I
\par am very ignorant, and it troubles me--just a little."
\par 
\par "Tell me what it is."
\par 
\par "I have a cousin, an only relative and an orphan, like myself, whom I
\par love very dearly. She is five years younger than I, and she lives in a
\par farmer's house in the south country. Poverty parted us, and she knows
\par nothing of my fate--for I cannot write--and if I could, how should I
\par tell her! It is better as it is."
\par 
\par "Yes, yes: better as it is."
\par 
\par "What I have been thinking as we came along, and what I am still
\par thinking now, as I look into your kind strong face which gives me so
\par much support, is this:--If the Republic really does good to the poor,
\par and they come to be less hungry, and in all ways to suffer less, she may
\par live a long time: she may even live to be old."
\par 
\par "What then, my gentle sister?"
\par 
\par "Do you think:" the uncomplaining eyes in which there is so much
\par endurance, fill with tears, and the lips part a little more and tremble:
\par "that it will seem long to me, while I wait for her in the better land
\par where I trust both you and I will be mercifully sheltered?"
\par 
\par "It cannot be, my child; there is no Time there, and no trouble there."
\par 
\par "You comfort me so much! I am so ignorant. Am I to kiss you now? Is the
\par moment come?"
\par 
\par "Yes."
\par 
\par She kisses his lips; he kisses hers; they solemnly bless each other.
\par The spare hand does not tremble as he releases it; nothing worse than
\par a sweet, bright constancy is in the patient face. She goes next before
\par him--is gone; the knitting-women count Twenty-Two.
\par 
\par "I am the Resurrection and the Life, saith the Lord: he that believeth
\par in me, though he were dead, yet shall he live: and whosoever liveth and
\par believeth in me shall never die."
\par 
\par The murmuring of many voices, the upturning of many faces, the pressing
\par on of many footsteps in the outskirts of the crowd, so that it swells
\par forward in a mass, like one great heave of water, all flashes away.
\par Twenty-Three.
\par 
\par         *****
\par 
\par They said of him, about the city that night, that it was the
\par peacefullest man's face ever beheld there. Many added that he looked
\par sublime and prophetic.
\par 
\par One of the most remarkable sufferers by the same axe--a woman--had asked
\par at the foot of the same scaffold, not long before, to be allowed to
\par write down the thoughts that were inspiring her. If he had given any
\par utterance to his, and they were prophetic, they would have been these:
\par 
\par "I see Barsad, and Cly, Defarge, The Vengeance, the Juryman, the Judge,
\par long ranks of the new oppressors who have risen on the destruction of
\par the old, perishing by this retributive instrument, before it shall cease
\par out of its present use. I see a beautiful city and a brilliant people
\par rising from this abyss, and, in their struggles to be truly free, in
\par their triumphs and defeats, through long years to come, I see the evil
\par of this time and of the previous time of which this is the natural
\par birth, gradually making expiation for itself and wearing out.
\par 
\par "I see the lives for which I lay down my life, peaceful, useful,
\par prosperous and happy, in that England which I shall see no more. I see
\par Her with a child upon her bosom, who bears my name. I see her father,
\par aged and bent, but otherwise restored, and faithful to all men in his
\par healing office, and at peace. I see the good old man, so long their
\par friend, in ten years' time enriching them with all he has, and passing
\par tranquilly to his reward.
\par 
\par "I see that I hold a sanctuary in their hearts, and in the hearts of
\par their descendants, generations hence. I see her, an old woman, weeping
\par for me on the anniversary of this day. I see her and her husband, their
\par course done, lying side by side in their last earthly bed, and I know
\par that each was not more honoured and held sacred in the other's soul,
\par than I was in the souls of both.
\par 
\par "I see that child who lay upon her bosom and who bore my name, a man
\par winning his way up in that path of life which once was mine. I see him
\par winning it so well, that my name is made illustrious there by the
\par light of his. I see the blots I threw upon it, faded away. I see him,
\par fore-most of just judges and honoured men, bringing a boy of my name,
\par with a forehead that I know and golden hair, to this place--then fair to
\par look upon, with not a trace of this day's disfigurement--and I hear him
\par tell the child my story, with a tender and a faltering voice.
\par 
\par "It is a far, far better thing that I do, than I have ever done; it is a
\par far, far better rest that I go to than I have ever known."
